text: this is the first time i 've bought leinenkugel 's on my own and i 'm very delighted in the results . smell is bland and much less present than any other aspect .  pours very dark brown with a large very foamy light brown head that leaves tons of drippy lacing and holds a nice rocky island and cap .  somewhat thin but more close to medium .

the aroma was quite lax , nothing really going on in the nose , it smelled a little spicey and nutty , but that 's all i got ? the taste is solid ; nice mix of unique spices and a grea tmalt taste with a sweet tone as well , i found it hard to grasp what exactly was in here but it was dispersed throughout very well .  appearance & gt ; yellow , lively . lovely .  it is slightly watery on the palate .

a malty aroma with some notes of coffee and nuts greeted me before my first sip . this is a very good full flavored beer that hides it 's 10 % alcohol very well .  impressive looking beer .  m - some carbonation , not much to speak of .

aroma of toffee , caramel , and apple . tastes light and fruity with small amounts of caramel and a strong mineral presence followed up by respectable hopping .  a-pitch black , perfect darkness . burnt and bitter , with black licorice .  lowish carbonation and a light , smooth mouthfeel .

the aromas are relatively straight forward with caramelized sugars and a raisin smell in the background .  beautiful fucking color .  i had this beer at the great waters facility as we stop in often . i try to take notes on the beers i try but sometimes forget . the attack was very smooth and there was a sweet and smooth flavor with faint hops character at the finish . i do n't think i have had any cask beers at great waters that i did n't like .

the nose is initially a bit harsh with a faint scent that borders on nail polish , but might be coming from the alcohol .  in a tulip the beer was near black in color with a light brown head . the head lingered well , and left abundant lace .  m : gritty and more astringent than any brown ale i 've ever tasted , very porterish feel .

the aroma is absolutely wonderful ... full of freshly crushed green , leafy and sweet hops . nice . the carbonation is mild to moderate . pleasantly surprised by this one..i thought this was going to be another average pale ale , but this very enjoyable .  from tower liquor a - a deep reddish-copper pour , slightly hazy , with a great fluffy , off-white head with good retention and lacing .  too much carbonation for this style ( -1.0 ) .

d- not a huge fan of the aroma but other than that it is a really nice beer .  a - dark maroon with lots of capuccino colored head .  this beer was purchased at cyclone liquors , in ames , iowa . the beer was very dark in color and tasted very well . i drank the beer warm and i think it was a good beer . i would try this beer again if it was presented to me . it had a very nice sweet taste for a german dunkel , which i am not a huge fan of .

my poured stubby elicited little smell , but the initial flavour was a rounded coffee chocolate.the flavour fell away though , to a minimalist charcoal toast it felt smooth and soft , perhaps too soft in the mouth . this is a strongish brew at 6.8 % and the coffee chocolate predominance makes it an enjoyable stout but one for moderation  pours a dark reddish brown with a huge off white head with huge fat lacing .  m-explosive carbonation . tough to gauge the feel over the bubbles . a bit too carbonated for me .

the was not my favorite part of the experience , it has a strong urea scent to it which i did n't care for , but that was more than compensated by the taste . the taste is very rich and deep , with different hops tones throughout .  pours a cloudy yellow with amazing white head that stays through out the whole glass .  light copper color with a large head s. malty with a slight resiny hop smell t. more bitter than sweet but well balanced with roasted malt m. a little to acidic and carbonated for my tastes d. a good lighter amber ale that i can heartily recommend

pours golden with a very light floral aroma , pure white head .  a : pitch black , slightly viscous . excellent head formation and nice lacing . this is how an ais should look in the glass .  pretty weak mouthfeel , it 's a bit watery . i 'm enjoying the flavour and aroma quite a bit but the mouthfeel is a bit weak . but lacking in mouthfeel .

smell : really expected a bit more from this . chocolate and coffee aromas at the fore . also roasted malt .  pours with an outrageously massive head , a dense , simmering mass of eggshell brown rising over the rim of the goblet like a souffle . what a visual feast !  the feel had decent carbonation , if only it had n't been followed by a lingering metallic feel on the tongue .

aroma is right there with what i look for in a bsda : nice bouquet of caramel malts , dark fruits , belgian yeast , and maybe some candied sugar . i 'm suddenly pretty jazzed about this beer . if the sweetness was dialed back a bit this could be a great beer ... still very good , but imo just a bit too sweet .  $ 5.00 / 750ml bottle county market grocery store stevens point , wisconsin appearance - a haze of golden yellow to a pale orange with a lasting frothy white head . very much carbonated as a constant flow of tiny bubbles speed to the top if the beer from the side and bottom of the pint glass .  m. a bit acidic d. overall a nice iipa .

this is one hell of an opaque beer , with minimal carbonation to boot . it tastes a bit chocolate-ly , and it 's rich and smooth without the boozy effects . this drinks supremely easy , just wish it is available easily in ca so it would become my daily session beer .  the pour is beautiful . intense rich brown/black , with a two finger dark brown head .  m/d - a little sticky but the body is still thin and it feels appropriate for the style .

the smell is quite inviting . taste is slightly bitter .  had a gorgeous impenetrable chestnut coloration , massive amounts of creeping carbonation , and a thick , creamy off-white head that displayed amazing retention .  m & d - the brew is a tiny bit watery , the doughy character is a tiny bit too small , and so the mouthfeel is n't as full as i 'd expect .

this was by far , the worst `` beer '' i 've ever tasted . if this bottle was n't infected , and was supposed to taste like that , i 'm downright confused .  quite surprising ... not because it 's a great beer from dogfish head ( that 's certainly not surprising ) , but because i have never actually enjoyed a pumpkin ale . seriously ever . appearance & gt ; what a beauty . colour reads from dark honey to a pumpkin orange glow . extremely lively .  mouthfeel is a little too carbonated and light but i still enjoyed the beer in-spite of those tow minor complaints .

smell : sweet malt , floral hop , light brown sugar , light bread , light whiff of dark fruits . the nose was a little light and the beer itself is more hop forward then what i would consider perfect for a esb , but on the whole a very simple but good brew .  poured into a fluted pilsner glass , this czech pils showed an exceptional ability to form a stiff , meringue-like , rocky head of foam . retention was great , lasting for the duration of the glass , leaving irregular clumps of foam on the way down .  and this is a surprisingly warming , earthy-tasting beverage for a `` summer ale '' -- i would n't mind opening up one of these in midwinter either , except in that it lacks body . it 's in the mouthfeel that the summeriness stands out .

smell is slightly hoppy with a bread-like background . first class beer .  pours a hazy golden color , with a huge fluffy white head . what a sight , as the head rose easily above the rim of the glass , and held there like an ice cream cone for a lengthy period of time .  medium bodied and a bit sticky in the mouth .

roasty , malty aroma with some molasses and bread .  black as the deepest parts of the ocean with some overcast fluffy 1 inch mocha colored head that fades at a good pace .  the first time i had this beer , i distinctly remember it being among the worst i had ever had . apparently my ba colleagues disagree , so i 'm giving it another try . there is some faint grassy hops , but this beer is mostly about the malt character . overall , this is way better than i remember . i might have to make this a regular part of my beer fridge ! or perhaps they had n't figured things out when the brewery was just getting started . glad that there 's another quality beer in e-town .

light straw golden color with an airy white head . light and sweet nose , with a bit of corn/cereal grains .  tasted june 22nd 2011 ( from notes ) poured into a la chouffe tulip a - a clear blood red , one finger tan head and some lacing s - alcohol , wine barrels , sweet dried fruits , earth , oak , french vanilla and more sweet and alcohol t - alcohol , lots of sugar , sweet malts , tons of sweet dried fruit , black cherries , wine barrels , raisins , charred oak , molasses , carmelised brown sugar and vanilla .  more carbonation would go a long way .

the smell is pleasant , overall light and grassy , but not that potent .  looks perfect . mounds of off white maybe pretty much light tan head , and has a clear dark copper colored body .  s - some grassy hops paired with caramel malt t - slight hop bitterness resolving into some serious roasty malt , but then it 's all gone fairly quickly with just a hint of woody bitterness m - quite light with just a hint of carbonation on the back of the tongue ; the slight bitterness endures for a whlie d - quick drinkable , though the excessive roasty malt will probably get in the way ; little to no alcohol warmth nice drink ; did n't expect it to be as dark as it is - listed as an american porter , but it 's almost a supercharged brown ale .

aroma was a bit lacking .  this is hands down the most beautiful looking beer i have ever seen . the head retention is pretty amazing and the lacing extensive .  m : very smooth , but seems pretty thin in terms of the body of the beer .

i didnt get too much from the smell other than , what i assume , is pumpkin spice . no alcohol burn and delicious taste makes this an extremely drinkable beer .  pours a nice bright yellow orange with a massive , almost overflowing white head . head sticks around indefinitely as bubbles continually rise in an energetic fashion .  mouthfeel was average .
subtle . t/m : great malt flavor .  pours out a beautiful amber color with a wonderful fluffy white head .  mouthfeel : a bit thin and watery .

pours a hazy straw yellow with a healthy tan head . smell of grass , pilsen malt , sweetness and hay . there seems to be more flavor and it is extremely smooth with very few flaws . very drinkable ; even sessionable at this high abv .  a- caramel amber beer , nice dark coloration , super huge head with sticky lacing .  i first had this beer a year ago and fell in love . so i was excited to see it appear once again this fall . i find it a very easy beer to drink even for the inexperienced beer drinker . flavorful and rich with malts , a slight hint of hops towards the end . the aroma is sweet but not overpowering , you can definitely smell the sweet malt that went into this brew . i highly recommend this beer . unfortunately its not around year round but it definitely will give you something to look forward to come fall .

s - roasted malt - not a ton going on here t - toasted malt , some underlying hoppy bitterness to balance it out the taste .  bomber bought at total wine a - dark black , 2 fingered head , dissipates slow and leaves a nice lacing .  had to give it the maximum points for appearance , because even out of an imported bottle , it looks just right . comes in with an alcohol bite that 's almost like an imperial . pertty nice taste , though , and if you had some , i would n't refuse .

the aroma is out of this world . a very , very bready smell . heavy yeast and a cake-like aroma . immense . the taste is very strong carrot cake . pumpkin spice and brown sugar . hits the back of the tongue with authority . rich and bready , like a sugary cake .  a - beautiful amber body with intense white huge head and sheets of lacing remaining for an insane amount of time .  this is pretty good , but not up to the level of most other weihenstephaner beers in my book . the aroma is raisiny and alcoholic with grapes , dry grain , hint of bread , honeym , pine , herbs , and hay . the taste is bread , herbs , pine , faint hints of honey , apple and lemon , with a tingly pine-herb flavour and bitterness , along with a faintly rough , thin mineral-water quality . it goes pretty well with food and is fairly easily drinkable , but not great .

smell : very sweet aroma with a caramel note to it but really very weak in the nose . very impressive flavor for a beer with such a weak aroma . mouthfeel : smooth , clean on the palate with a nice roastiness that lasts on the palate even after the beer is gone . aside from the weak smell i was very impressed with this beer .  bottle into a pils glass pours a clear , deep copper orange with a one and a half inch off-white head which holds up well throughout from lots of carbonation release . it also leaves some nice looking sheets of lacing down the sides of the glass . ca n't ask for a better looking beer .  this is an excellent pilsner . number three on my list , only behind konig and pilsner urquell . just as crisp and refreshing as both of those , but a little lighter in taste and body . very clean , top quality .

draft beer in a bottle is as good as it gets with mgd . nothing fancy , this is a great bbq beer . throw some burgers on the grill , crack open an mgd and have a great day out in the sun . not the best beer made by miller , but a great cold filtered brew .  had this at a recent ba gathering at milly 's , and brought a growler home . this is a beautiful beer : as black as can be , with a thick coffee-colored head .  this is a great light summer ale from pike brewing . this could be a great crossover ale for the bmc drinkers . it is very light yellow and clear . head is white light and fluffy , overall a great light easy drinking als . this is a beer that everyone will like .

the first thing i noticed was the head , which was average.it had an average amber color , but the taste was quite different than others i have tasted so far.i tasted chocolate.i understand this to be from the malt flavor being intensified.i have read that the kolsch style of beer should have a stronger hops taste , so maybe this is put in the wrong catagory.i liked this beer , probably due to my chocolate affinity.it has a pleasant disposition and is unoffending to the palatte.it has a sticky taste , like chocolate.i liked it.i would buy again , probably with a piece of chocolate .  poured black , with clear mahogany highlights , with a large mostly lasting light brown frothy head with good lacing .  smell : uh oh , something is going wrong ... taste : blecchhh . my stomach is starting to turn . what happened to this beer ? simply put , the taste is sour and offensive . beef notes : horrible . what was the thought process when putting this beer out for sale ?

however , the nose is pretty muted overall .  a - black , inch and half of tawny head . leaves amazing lacing that should be in a museum as art .  the mouthfeel was a bit watery which could be due to the fact it is only 4.8 % and thus not alot of malt was apparently used , but i think it held up well over time , although i have not tried this fresh so i can not compare .

( s ) - a dry , yet floral-like citrus . a damp wood-like pine . ( t ) - a fresh & crisp floral citrus of lemon , pineapple , grapefruit , and lime . has everything you would expect from the style .  giant billowing white head . the dense creamy , soapy head leaves giant lacey patches and a tantalizing heavy layer for the duration . color is a thickly hazey amber red with a big old carbonation tornado at the center .  good carb , but feels a bit thin and watered down in general .

aroma is surprisingly mild with light roasted malt and espresso scents a hit of grassy hops mixed in too .  2009 vintage a- deep violet , crimson red just a beautiful awe-inspiring color and massive towering head that seems to be independent of the beer and an entity all onto itself .  the carbonation is surprisingly strong for the style .

s : very feint smell , chocolate note , but a bit of roasty malt as well .  appearance : pours a beautiful hazy dark amber color with a finger of foamy off white head that leaves a little bit of lacing and good retention .  m good medium body , with a lot of carbonation , either takes away from this beer .

first it poured a very clear medium amber , just beautiful and it 's clarity reminded me of many cask beers i have enjoyed in england . aroma was a bit of a surprise , i was expecting , or hoping maybe , for the citrusy hop character of bear republic racer 5 or el toro 's agressive interpretation . i found it very restrained and almost tea like .  pours a very dark reddish brown color with a very nice looking 2 finger slightly tan head that does n't seem to want to go down !  i think that the long trip from greece to williamsburg , va did n't treat this beer too kindly . pours and looks like the standard heine-clone . taste was rather flat .

s : a roasted nose with hop undertones . not a big nose on this beer .  appearance - jet black in color with a very nice one finger light tan head that lingers while drinking . perfect for keeping in the flavor and smell of the beer smell - very light on the malt smell , but somewhat heavy on the bitter hops .  the mouth was a bit oily but not unpleasantly so .

aroma is pretty subdued .  hazy blond in color with a steady stream of bubbles rising from the bottom of the glass to form a huge , thick , rocky white head that lasts for the entire glass .  smooth , nice , a little thin maybe . not a ton of carbonation at the end which leaves it a little watery .

moderate yeasts and slightly sweet on the nose , with a mix of fresh and dried fruit . rather light for the style yet obviously restrained by a copious surface cap , holding the volatile smells at bay . this beer looks better than it smells . all is good again in the flavor of this beer .  a-pours a slightly clear copper/amber color with lots of thick white head that leaves outstanding lacing .  mouf & gt ; average drinkability & gt ; great ! more beers to add to the breakfast menu at my house .

had an imperial pint at mac 's taproom , slighshot is a clear pale copper with a small off-white head that leaves moderate lace . smell is very muted , especially when first served a bit to cold , sweet soft cereals and grassy hops .  appearance : pitch black . very dark head .  good coffee and chocolate and malt ( ate a small piece of oreo birthday cake with this and it was damn near orgasmic ) mouthfeel is surprisingly thin .

mostly amber ale aroma with hint of spice .  pours nicely for a two finger thick tan head , and has a copper colored well filtered body .  smoky , malty and mildy coffee-like . deep black with a thumb thick mocha head . fore is hoppy bitter then roasted barley malt follows . very much in the fullers vein as opposed to the more roasty and coffee/chocolate flavored american porters . very nice brew .

i perceive an overall sanitizer/cleanser aroma overall though , pretty much hides the aroma of the brew .  appearance : poured a nice , thick dark tan head which persisted nicely . color is very dark brown -- pretty much opaque .  mouthfeel : thin yet flavorful .

aroma is a terrific perfumey blend of spruce and crushed flowers and an underlying malt sweetness . very inviting . soft malt up front is washed away too quickly by the surprisingly watery mouthfeel .  absolutley perfect looking beer .  a bit watery at the start , but , it gradually gains weight as it rolls to the back of the palate .
the nose had some malt , and a light note of candy .  pours an opaque black with a creamy tan head that retains well and laces the glass .  m - kind of watery , but good carbonation .

s - the rich caramel and malty nose is unleashed on the pour . a light kiss of hops compliments the very malty nose . smells almost like a dopplebock . very sweet .  a - scotch / almond color . beautiful head with great lace .  poured chilled in large ale glass ; bottle courtesy buzzlitebeer a : dark chocolate colored ; good frothy head ; decent carb action s : chicory and ( what ? ) tobacco predominates ; musty coffee t : wow , unusual ; the brown ale is a base for experimentation into coffee and tobacco ; bitter cacao serve this to friends and you 'll definitely have a talking point ; it 's very distinctive

nose is slight with hints of fruit , apple in particular . mouthfeel is very carbonated with a light citric tingle .  poured into a tall glass , pours a cloudy almost two tone fire red color . genuinely impressive , that i have never seen something like this before .  m : a little thin on the body , and surprisingly light and spiky with the carbonation .
the aroma is very weak though .  this brew pours a very large head of creamy fine light brown bubbles and opaque black brown body .  mouthfeel seemed a bit to lean to me .

s : weaker aroma than i expected but i might have hyped the wet hops in my mind . floral hops and citrus `` dominate '' but the nose is still weak .  appearance : great stout , dark brown color with a coffee colored head .  the body is on the thin side , with below-average carbonation .

smell is lightly malted and a bit sweet ... not unpleasant at all .  a nice amber color with a thick tan head . lace was thick and copious .  this beer has a flavor i really like m- pretty thin and bubbly , almost reminds me of a bmc feel o- one of my favorite tasting pale ales .

s - smell is very subtle . bready malts , musty notes .  absolutely pitch black from the middle of the fluted part down , with a gorgeous caramel brown cascading head up to the rim . excellent head retention and nice lacing . held directly in front of a bright bulb , no light passed through the pour .  the body of the beer is actually approaching medium and the carbonation is not overly fizzy as many macros are .

i smell chocolate and coffee and malt and even some hops . very nice and somewhat unique representation of the style .  as the beer was going down in the glass , it left an incredible , thick creamy lacing all over the glass . appearance was pretty cloudy , light copper color .  the only detraction i can fin is the below average body .

smell is subtle and surprisingly fruity . overall an outstanding example of the style .  a : forms a nice 1.5 finger frothy head in my sa perfect pint glass with very good retention . it 's a crystal clear beer with varying colors , being auburn orange at the thinner parts and ruby red at the thicker , and a good amount of bubbles floating up from the etch at the bottom . perfect appearance at least .  taste : sweet malt , raisins , a lot of sweet nutty flavors like pecans , sour/tart dark cherry flavor , ending with a nutty malt characters mouthfeel : really light body , low carbonation , pretty basic .

s : hints of breadyness mf : medium bodied , slick & very well balanced great drinkability , such a well crafted dubbel ! although the lack of nose is a let down .  poured a slightly cloudy , amber to copper color with . nice frothy two finger off white lasting head . ample lacing cling to the glass .  as readily available as bud , and a whole lot better . a great fall-back session brew , which is good with a meal , or having several at a baseball game .

s : toasted cereal grains , earthy and a bit nutty . very light sweetness with some light caramel and toffee notes . d : pretty drinkable and tasty . hits the spot if you 're looking for something malty but not toasty or heavy .  heading was awesome , big , white and fluffy , with many tiny air bubbles racing toward the head .  nice carbonation , but this comes off as a little thin . this should be more drinkable considering its thin body , but as this is a stout , the thin body is a bit of a turn off .

aroma is the only thing that falls a bit short here as the hops are in the back somewhere . the aroma does have a touch of burnt caramels which is coming through from the rye . nice job on this one , just missing a little on the aroma end for what i was expecting .  a : bright red with an even keel of carbonation rising to fluffy beige head . gorgeous head does n't waver for a moment .  the mouthfeel is a bit thin and the carbonation is quite sharp ; a bit fizzier than i 'd like .

smell is an excellently projected , and wonderfully layered and clean tangerine , apricot , pear and lemon .  this is the dead-on look for a pilsner ; pale straw color with steady streams of bubbles heading for the surface . the head is huge and sticky and clings to the side of the glass as if it were a life-or-death matter .  tastes pretty amazing really . watery on the tongue but ends dryish .

s : surprisingly light smell ; holds heavily roasted dark malts a bit smoked . strong black coffee . t : taste is stronger than smell ; sweet marzipan-like malt , heavy roast and smoked .  pours a lager-yellow , huge creamy white head that dissipates down to a film leaving very much lace . nice looking beer .  it was also a little to carbonated for me in the mouth feel category .

a fragrent nose brings about thoughts of raspberry chewy candy and a bit of candied malt . enters the mouth with a long creamy tart feel . notes of crisp apples , fresh raspberries , and even end a nice mellow malty sweetness is faint on the end of the palate . i speak a lot of the sour and tartness of this beer but it is not to harsh but well balanced with a touch of woodsy malt sweetness . enjoyable for the style but drinkability says i still need to share the bottle with a friend .  a bottle exceptionally beautiful . so , for large qualities , almost everything .  a little lighter and less sweet than many `` real '' belgian beers , and a little thinner in the mouthfeel department .

the smell is pretty light , but its of roasted malts .  ( a great place ) poured a wonderfully rich yellow color . it was cloudy with a half inch of creamy white head . nice lacing with this beer .  mouthfeel was a little thin , that 's my only complaint .

this was a wonderful helles , with the crisp maltiness one would expect from german lager . sparingly hopped , but enought to balance well . show this to a lover of the macros and they might convernt yet ! i wish however , that they were in brown bottles , because i got that slight skunkyness from uv reaction .  appearance : pours a crystal clear dark orange color with a huge 3 '' + fluffy head that lasts a long time .  the mouthfeel is a bit thin and harsh from the acidity and carbonation . also finishes quite dry with little to no bitter .

surprising aroma of the euro skunk , not heavy , but noticeable - along with some spicey malts .  visually stunning with a clear red-amber hue , plentiful off-white head and lace , and carbonation bubbles that seem to be in slow motion as they rise to the surface .  an e-mail from the brewery indicated that twins lager is not the same beer as hauenstein , just with a different label . schells tells me that the twins lager uses a different recipe and yeast than the hauenstein , but a side by side comparison leaves me wondering why they would go through the trouble . i have always liked `` cheap '' beers . the beer drinkers of olden days wanted it cold , crisp , and cheap . but for afternoon lazing back and swigging , there is certainly nothing wrong with a cold bottle of twins lager . twins lager might be `` twice as refreshing '' as the label purports , but , boy would it be a treat to drink an original recipe fitgers again !

smell is a little flat ... some burnt caramel and a little bit of orange citrus . taste is off the rocker , though ... this is basically dogfish head 90 minute without the bitterness .  pours a rich opaque sable with a fine-bubbled light tan head .  mouthfeel is somewhat disappointing . if we 're talking about banana bread here , then it should be thicker , like bread .

s : malty , bready , yeasty and a bit hoppy . t : caramel sweet malt with toffee flavors , great malt/hop balance .  hopefully since it appears to be bottle conditioned that the beer is still holding up a - poured into goblet an opaque black color . fluffy inch tall light brown head that disapates into a tinner covering that lasts until the end .  it is a bit thin , bordering on watery with adequate to slightly low carbonation .

a little one-dimensional but still pleasant . very light malt , coriander ( again ) , and a faint orange flavor on the palate .  pours up a beautiful grapefruit color with a very thin white head .  the mouthfeel was thin with a slightly dry aftertaste .

s - roasted malt and faint molasses and hot chocolate notes . t - roasted malts , bakers chocolate , coffee and a faint sour note that i ca n't place , but it 's not unpleasant .  a : poured perfectly . nice pinkish , beige head with a good retention and very good lacing for this style .  bittersweet finish . kind of think and syrupy on the palate .

aroma- not much aroma , lightly floral . taste- floral , not bitter enough for my taste mouthfeel- smooth drinkability- high , odd aftertaste , not sure if i want more herbs or less in this beer .  a-pours a pitch black color with a finger and a half tan head .  a surprisingly great beer from a brewing giant . it could have been a little less punishing when guzzled , but hey it 's a dark beer and we are not dealing with coors light here . i think the beer is buitiful to look at , and is rather smooth . but the lable and beer fit perfectly ph

just great . t : similar to the smell but with bit of smokiness .  the black body of this brew is topped by a medium thick , brown head with a good amount of lacing left behind .  m - a little water , but it goes down smoothly d - this is a really good beer .

this beer is n't bad , but it does n't stand out in any way to me . the color is good , but the taste is a bit carbonated and weak for a porter . not as rich as i like , but not too pungent either . i prefer the cream stout . not sam 's best .  poured a 355 ml bottle , dated 15 nov 2007 , into a tulip . a : poured a massive 1.5 fingered creamy head , in a tulip this appears huge . the color is a glorious tawny . the carbonation is rising nicely in the glass and it seems as if the head is hardly going anywhere .  a little too thick on the tongue , but nice .

nose is tangy wheat with a bit of a roasted flavor and a touch of herbal hops . good overall and interesting as this is my first dunkel .  black as the abyss with a dark sticky head .  m : upper light body with high carbonation .

the smell is really light but i get some sweet carmel and pine and citrus with no hint of the oak .  pours a deep , opaque blood red with a really pretty cotton candy , rosy head that settled into a soapy haze .  in my opinion , flying dog brewery has created a great seasonal , smooth-tasting beer with very little bite or after taste . i would definitely recommend it to any self-respecting beer drinker who might be having an end-of-summer party this or any october .

s : faintly nutty , with no alcohol detectable . overall very mild , not really noteworthy .  a : my antonia pours a lovely straw/amber hue and is marked by a monstrous head of the consistency of whipped egg whites . definitely appealing ... .  mouthfeel is sticky-sweet and dense .

smooth , creamy taste , easy to drink with mild to medium body . cloudy , yellow-amber color . compatible with multiple foods . the first i have had of this style .  a- pours dark black . one of the prettiest beers i 've seen .  m : mouthfeel is decent , goes down reasonable smooth even with the slight burning sensation .

as far as smell goes , uh ... .there was n't much to mention . i could smell some hop fragrance but it really did n't stand out as exceptional to me .  pours an absolutely gorgeous dark cola body that illuminates to a caramel-amber when held to the light . creamy , light tan bubbles form a sizable froth on top and slowly settle to a thick veil of foam , thanks in part to a vigorous carbonation level .  the mouthfeel is very fizzy due to the ample carbonation .

smell : prunes , first and foremost . underneath that , a thick , banana-bread-like malt quality ; or maybe cinnamon-raisin-muffin-like quality . very sweet , almost cloying , but enough tone shift to remain above average .  pours very dark brown color with a 2.5 finger dense tan head with incredible retention , with some very nice lacing on the glass .  4.5 m - lacks body . a bit thin but spritzy carbonation .

aroma is mild , too mild , but i pick up on dark roasted malts , cocoa , light caramels , ans very german-smelling hops . tastes better room temp , smells better too as it warms .  glass : chimay goblet temp : cellared @ approx 45 degrees bottling date : 04-23-08 pours an exceptional clear golden amber color . minimal head that retains a light lacing all the way down .  m : the body is not as thick as i was expecting . it on the thin side as far as stouts go , but drinks very smoothly . i would have liked a thicker body , but that 's just being picky .

s : dark roasted malts and coffee . kind of disappointing for the style and look .  perfect head retention & lacing s : slight hops aroma t : some fruittyness up front .  smell is of old corn/rice and skunk . pew . taste was horrendous . a skunky malt liquor flavor mixed with sweet rice/corn adjunct . maybe it went bad on it 's journey from the carib-bean ? looks like i should have gone for the sam light that was also in the fridge ...

s : nose is very subtle for a -bal aged beer . muted chocolate , cocoa powder , and roasted malt .  the brew itself is a spectacular amber-orange color that is crystal clear . the head dissipates to a constant quarter-finger thickness with excellent lacing all the way down . while it has a fantastic appearance , everything else is only slightly above average ( for microbrews ) .  the palate is average .

the nose is full of notes of raisiny notes as well as distinct hoppy character .  browning 's bourbon barrel imperial stout pours a very nice , pitch black into a snifter with a small , light tan head that leaves lots of lacing behing .  its perfectly balanced and not overly done . m very medium , which i find most all stone beers to be and i dont really complain about . the carbonation is present and isnt overly aggressive or submissive .

aroma was weak with only a bit of honey and mostly chocolate and wood .  a one finger , mocha colored head has supreme retention and some amazing lacing to go along with it . very nice looking .  m : starts off creamy , but i 'm pretty quickly struck by how watery this is . the carbonation is decent , but i find this surprisingly thin .

nose is pleasant , full of citrus and wheat , and an undefined spiciness .  a : pours a beautiful bronze with ruby highlights . this beer looks fantastic . s : smell is of juicy citrusy hops , with an abundant dose of pale and caramel malt .  m : a little bit thinner than expected , medium-light bodied with low carbonation , lightly creamy .

the aroma was very strange and not at all appetising for me . the aroma was disappointing but that is one of the nicest beers i have ever tasted .  bottle in 16oz.sierra nevada glass leaves a beautiful 3/4 inch head . a-tremendous color , nice floaties , great lacing on the glass .  like cheap malt liquor infused with citrus and nail polish remover .

citrus notes are bright and festive in the nose , enticing . t : the nose is somewhat deceiving , this is a bitter bomb .  very attractive beer . massive sticky foamy eggshell colored head rises to 2 fingers and holds there forever .  very well carbonated , but not alot of head . i am thinking its a unique hop that i have not experienced alot of . thoughts - this beer is one of my favs from shiner .

smell is rather subtle actually , for the hop taste i would would expect more however i would never hold it against this beer .  a - black is right . the head is a medium brown and standing about three-quarter inches tall before slowly fading to bumpy and frothy top .  ) my only qualm was the the body seemed a little thin .

yet anothe winner from rogue , pours a deep amber with a big head , aroma is faint , taste is bold spice and nice toasty malt , almost peppery , delicious . mouthfeel is pefect as seems to be the case with all rogue brews . a superb amber ale , right up there with red rocket ale in my opionion , a very enjoyable brew .  it pours a rust-colored brown with a roasted 2-3 finger head . this looks as good as any of the big ipas made by stone , smuttynose and company .  this beer poured a dirty blonde color , with a haziness that made me suspect that i would n't enjoy this beer too much . aroma was malty , and flavor was a sweet maltiness with only a hint of hops . this was n't what i was expecting from an american pale ale , and i really did n't enjoy it . i may have gotten an old beer , but there is no date code on this beer , so i have no way of knowing its age and it gets what it gets ... most of this one is going down the drain .

very easy drinking ale with nice dark copper color and good lacing . makes a good session ale or good beer to introduce to non craft beer drinkers who will occasionally drink guiness stout .  look is beautiful . perfect 1/2 inch head when poured carefully into a surly pint glass .  quenching , medium-light body , citrus-earthy character .

mickey 's is the malt liquor that makes the name worth it . granted the whole idea that you play the brown paper bag hiding game , not right way to enjoy this delicious beverage . if you 're going to `` roll '' with a malt liquor , this is the selection for that night .  bottle says bottled on 4/16/09 a - pours cloudy orange with huge 3 fingers of pillowy foam that takes forever to die down - lacing is all over the glass . this is one fine looking beer s - very hoppy with a strong grassy aroma - there are so many other aromas also - reminds me of a wine t - bitterness is subdued , bready yeast flavor is present , solid malt backbone m - great creamy mouthfeel - but i wish there was a little more lingering bitterness to this brew d - this is a very sneaky 9 % abv - deceptively drinkable .  mouthfeel is probably the most disappointing aspect of this otherwise excellent beer ; the carbonation promised by the head largely disappeared , leaving a slick , full bodied beer with very light carbonation . a nice , sharp bite of carbonation would have been welcome in this case , drying out the finish nicely , but that does n't happen here .

yummy ... pours a heady white-over-bronze trophy , some modest lacing which arches around delightfully un-predictable shapes ... i think i see a war-elephent trumpeting hannibal 's decent from the alps ... smell was somewhat subdued , i did n't have any good glassware handy , i used a big wine glass . smell was suggestive of good things to come , but nothing terribly fancy . this is where the fun really starts .  pours jet black with a thick , luscious brown head .  the overall feel is dry , like it should be , but unfortunately , it 's also a touch chaulky , which is pretty unfortunate .

s : orange zest , sweet malt notes , light . t : very sweet beer , the orange predominates , but it 's not overbearing .  poured out of a 16.9 oz bottle into a tulip style glass . i held it up to the sun on my patio and admired it for a few seconds . ( cue music ) there were two inches of white head that led to a nice white cap that never dissipated .  my only complaint with this beer is that it is a little thin .

the aroma , however , is a-one , outstanding , and really well captured in the wineglass : nice , fresh pumpkin accompanied by strong notes of cinnamon , nutmeg , clove , maybe some ginger ... wow , this is the smell i look for in my pumpkin ales - imo they nailed it . that said , i feel the flavor takes a step back ; maybe the nose raised expectations too high ... still very nice , with the pumpkin and spices pulling through , but perhaps not as robustly as the nose had led me to believe ; there 's also a not entirely pleasant though subtle bitterness to it , as well as a bit a boozy bite to the finish .  pours black , black black , with a big , dark , thick cloud of a head .  i 'd love to try this on cask , if only to taste it more directly without all the carbonation dancing across my tongue .

the smell is just awful , such that your head may recoil out of fear .  bottle , a : pours yellow-orange , with a very long-lasting white head , great lacing .  while the carbonation is nice , the overall feel is a bit thin .

smell is fairly muted with a noticeable amount of citrusy hops . the hops in the smell are much more present in the taste . a light body and pleasant flavor make this very drinkable . all around a very well executed ipa .  mbc 's big jamoke pours up with a modest carbonation that creates a very creamy beige-khaki brown head that encompasses the very dark brown-mahogany body .  good carbonation and medium bodied . flavor is spicy , yeasty , hints of sweetness that gets buried by the yeast . lingering yeasty aftertaste .

sidenote : waitress tells me this name of this beer was chosen because a song by the same name was being played while it was brewed . aroma is toasted malt and caramel .  into a pint glass , it poured a transparent straw/gold ; heavily carbonated , two fingers of bright white , and great head retention and lacing .  m - a little thinner than i thought and more carbonated than i would expect .

the nose is doughy soapy water and yeast . spicy hops hit first chased by metallic sweetness with a soft-baked quality .  black with a glorious creamy beige head with great retention and lacing .  body is ok , nothing special but not bad . very boozy finish .

s : apple skin , musty dried fruit , creamed corn , slightly metallic . t : sweet and fruity up front - apples , a bit of raisons , prunes , figs .  dark mahogany color with a 1 finger , light tan head with excellent retention and lacing .  m- somewhat thin , actually . smooth , clean , but a little more watery than i expected .
i really like it .  a : red-brown , fluffy off-white head , awesome retention and lace !  m : relatively light though not particularly carbonated .

s : not a big smell . yeasty . overall : the smell does n't set you up propery for how the taste hits you in the mouth .  very good lacing & head retention smell : slight malt hints taste : slight caramel followed by malt & fruiityness .  the mouthfeel was a bit unimpressive too light in my opinion .

s - very fresh but light aroma .  the appearance is outstanding ! s : expresso like smell with subtle malty aroma .  reminded me a bit of bmc with a bit of syrup added for sweetness . the taste is more of the same with a quick malty dryness at the end that seems to say , `` ha ! had you fooled..you thought there was about to be something pleasant here , did n't you ? in fact , this may get sacrificed to the kitchen sink . as i always say , in total fairness to the brewer and his ( or her ) intentions , this may have its fans , but it most assuredly is *not* for me ...

there is a little malt sweetness , caramel-like . if only the nose was a little bit better .  a : orangey amber cloudy beer with a huge 3 finger cappucino head that settles to peaks and valleys veery slowly , great lace throughout .  the mouthfeel is light bodied with a high level of biting carbonation ( the carbonation is the only part of this beer that i 'm not too fond of ) . quite dry due to the high level of carbonation .

smell : lots of grainy and bready malts in the nose . medium in strength and quite nice for the style . taste : not nearly as good as the nose . bready malts and some grassy hops through the middle , but honestly a little watery through and through .  a big fluffy ice cream scoop of a head , eventually smooths out to about a quarter inch . for a lager this is a very good looking beer .  a new contender for the worst beer i 've ever tasted . it tasted like a carbonated v8 with sweeteners added .

certainly has that belgain yeatiness to it as well as the smell of good old alcohol .  what a crazy story ... a - a tall pour creates totally huge cascading that ends in a three+ finger head with awesome retention .  m : medium to full body but needs more carbonation .

the nose is n't prominent at all . all i can pick up is some muted honey cream and some pale malt sweetness with perhaps some clove . despite the short list of adjectives i used to describe the flavors , it 's actually very , very good for the style . this is a very good belgian strong pale and worth trying .  looks fantastic ! the head leaves plenty of lace after a couple of minutes .  the mouth feel was hindered a bit , as the bottle had n't been sitting in my refrigerator long enough , the ale could have been a little more carbonated .

smell : the alcohol is very evident , a sweet syrupy smell and raisins are the only other aromas i pick out . taste : the flavor profile is dominated by raisins and syrup , with warming alcohol in the finish . overall : one dimensional , and cloyingly sweet .  amazingly slow head cascade action . clear from yeast or other floaties .  does smell a little like `` beer , '' as my wife would say . so sweet on the tongue . slight raspberry tartness but it is like drinking raspberry sorbet after it melts . it is still trying to recover from the sweetness . a good once in a while beer . sorbet beer , i tell ya .

s : not a lot going on here . some pear , green apple , very minor tangerine . ethereal young wheat adds a gently malt background .  great retention and generous lacing . lovely looking porter .  mouthfeel is effervescent , lighter bodied ( almost thin ) , medium carbonation and slightly dry .

as expected , strong aroma of sweet oats and roasted coffee .  appearance is beatiful dark dark black with a fluffy , pale yellow head that laces nicely .  it is a little bit sweet on the tongue . i could stand it to be a little bit more dry .

a- pale golden yellow , has about 1/2 in head laces beautifully with lovely activity s - really nothing there , watery slightly malty with just the faintest buttery sense t - wow super smooth with a lot going on .  pours a cloudy garnet hue with a thin but persistent head . leaves an incredible lacing on the glass .  mouthfeel : surprisingly thin body , full carbonation , fairly thick coat after the swallow .

appearance this had a nice , dark , cloudy orange body with a decent head that laced a bit on my glass . smell this one is wrapped kind of tight , but the rind hops came out after a while and a touch of sweetness . yep , thats an ipa .  bottle : poured a pitch-black color stout with a huge dark brown color ahead with good retention and great lacing .  it was barely palatable : very little carbonation - full of sour , gone-bad notes .

smell : almost nothing to say here , the smell is very weak , it seems . from what i *can* detect , there is a gentle grassiness coupled with moderate sweetness . it 's unoffensive , and get more flavorful as the beer warms .  1,000 review a- awesome copper red appearance , great foam and nice head when poured from a bottle .  i got this beer in the beers of the world gift box for christmas . immediate taste is a lil sharp and bready with a hint of citrus in the smell . it was not an out of this world experience , but it is a very light and enjoyable beer for everyday or get togethers .

the smell was n't all it should be , but average . the taste above average , in fact , very good , but no top shelf kind of beer taste .  beautiful red orange color . a tan head sits on top for a while . a very pretty beer . we tried it with some honey ham and then some apple pie and it was terrific with both .  the mouthfeel is medium to full bodied with no carbonation .

special cask for crockett 's public house in puyallup . smell is slightly fruity , slight pine , honey , and earthiness .  a-bronze and brilliantly clear . huge eggshell head .  m- low carbonation , medium-body .

overall the aromas seem slightly restrained .  wow , this beer really looks like it was poured from a bar tap ... great body . boddingtons is so unique for being a light-looking golden beer that pours like an irish stout ; those widget things work well .  the mouthfeel i found oddly watery ... but still fairly full bodied at the same time . carbonation was fairly mild - maybe that lended to the `` watery '' sensation .

s - herbal hops , sweet fruit and graininess ; feels a little light in the nose t & m - hop bitterness nicely balanced with malts .  a-dark ruby to light brown with a huge tan head . clear .  i 'm rather late with this review but i had this on tap at nicholson 's downtown and it reminded me of sierra nevada celebration . in fact at the time the original name was celebration ale . i 've since had a few growlers from jungle jim 's and though it 's a quailty brew i 've experienced some diacetyl like off-flavors when served from the growler . still it 's quite enjoyable and recommended . i wish the best to mike and his future brews !

12 oz . the nose is rather subdued , without much going on other than some faint piney/herbaceous hop notes and a little whiff of biscuit . wonderfully drinkable and overall an excellent apa .  a : vigorous pour yielded a creamy 2 finger light caramel colored head with great retention and outrageous frothy web-like lacing .  carbonation a little higher than i expect in the style but still manages to be exceptionally drinkable .

the appearance is dark and deep with small pillow of foam on top ( died off on the way over to my table ) . the taste begins very sweet - a blend of chocolates , malts and sweet nuts . the finish is a bit delayed and it arrives with soft notes of bitters and alcohol . i 'd drink this one again ... and again .  appearance- black ! ! ! creamy head .  apricots . hops undetectable above the jaw-clenching , eye-squinching , head-shaking sourness . awful . ugh . otherwise , it defintely seems to be beer , ( if in no way resembling any version of a contemporary pa ) , but with a sour and bitter fruitiness that pervades , annoys , and overwhelms . the originally enticing head cashed in early and diminished to virtual non-existence before i gave up trying to like this one ; very little lacing to wash out of the glass . wo n't drink the other two in the sampler , did n't finish this one , and opened a sn celebration ale to get the taste out of my mouth .

smells of ambient pines and a touch of birch bark with a pale , white toast base . rather bland .  a : yellow , straw hues , slightly hazy , enormous whipped meringue head , long lasting retention , nice lacing .  m - comes across a tad light on the carbonation , making it a bit watery for my liking .

s : hay , citrus zest with light fruits on the background . crackery malts come through more as it warms .  pours a two finger cream head that fades slowly leaving a good lace . nice crystal clear ruby/amber color .  mouthfeel is light and carbonation fades to almost flat .

s : this is an obvious german pilsener - pure malt together with nice bitter hops in balance with the slight fainter floral hops .  light copper with a thick , mousse-like , sticky-as-hell head .  the carbonation is ok ; small fresh bubbles at a decent strength .

dunkels ; pours a clear , deep copper-brown w/ a thin light tan head which dissipates quickly leaving a moderate lacing in my pils glass ; a subtle smell , cereal grain , toasted nuts , and hints of dark fruits and noble hops ; a crisp , malty flavor , nutty w/ a caramel-like undertone , faint fig/date-like notes as well , an excellent finish ; very dry and light bodied with plenty of co2 , this beer feels like it evaporates off your tongue ; a very drinkable beer , i 'm def .  great retention and great lacing .  m - body is a little thin , moderate carbonation .

there was n't much aroma to speak of , but what there was was sweet and just a bit spicy .  look : dark brown with a good solid 1 inch head with great retention and some spotty lacing smell : smoked pork comes to mind .  mouthfeel was ok ; about the same as urquell .
s : mildly sweet but kind of faint .  brilliant cloudy , fuzzy , bubbly orange appearance with a perfect 1/4 inch puffy head and a pleasant hoppy aroma .  mouthfeel is soft and a little heavy .

s : subtle is the word i would use . there are floral notes and spice notes , but only if you really work at concentrating the aroma from the glass . t : lemony and slightly spicy .  a - brilliant copper color with a finger of thick solid off white head .  the mouthfeel was light but a bit chewy .

dales ' has a mildly hoppy bite and leaves little aftertaste - due to storage , i think . all-in-all , an exceptional quaff , though i do prefer oskar blues scotch ale `` old chubb .  it pours a dark brown to almos black color with a huge fluffy tan to light brown head .  light to medium in body .

the aroma is malty and sweet with a decent amount of spice and just a hint of hops . fairly malty and somewhat uneventful but still pleasant . very sweet with more malt and lots of spice and fruit : orange and cinnamon , nutmeg , cardamom .  reviewed 11/1/2009 ( bottle coded 8899 ) : pours a clear brown color body , with a big tan foamy head , very lasting .  though this is a red ale of stormy garnet and the menu states it is `` brewed with 20 % honey malts for a touch of sourness '' ( honey = sourness ? it is not merely that this red ale tastes bad ; it is absolutely offensive . of the lowest evolutionary order . the entire beer is corrupted by spoilage and should n't be served publicly .

happily , though , if you give it a minute or two , the stench fades away some , to reveal a nice malty aroma underneath .  a- poured into an over-sized beer mug , this made for a super robust head . great sticky lacing , a steady stream of carbonation , and an amber/orange body sets this beer up as one of the prettiest looking ipas ive seen in a while . s- i think the full scent has a bit of a hard time breaking through this super dense head !  m- a bit thin for my taste .

appearance : golden , great clarity , thick layer of light tan foam w/ good head retention aroma : skunk !  bottled 10/31/11 a : pours jet black with a nice finger high layer of dark mocha head that laces the glass nicely .  m : medium mouthfeel with moderate carbonation .

what i do get is small whiffs of cocoa which smells pretty good .  pours vibrant pale gold with lively streams of carbonation sustaining an impressive large white head and leaivng lovely lacing .  mouthfeel : the carbonation is light , as is the body .

malty and aggressively hoppy . nice flavor . mouthfeel is full and round . finish is clean and crisp , slightly smooth . aftertaste is bitter .  wow , what a good looking beer . dark dark , dark body and small light brown head ontop .  a - black on the pour with no head whatsoever s - big burnt malt and bittersweet chocolate aroma along with some bourbon , some oak and vanilla in there as well , slight alcohol , as the beer warms up , smells almost like straight bourbon , maybe more like a bourbon and cola t - big bourbon flavor right up front , lots of oak as well , some bittersweet chocolate in the body , finish is more bourbon and oak along with some vanilla , alcohol notes , long finish m - a bit too flat for my taste , full-bodied but totally devoid of any carbonation action in the mouth d - i 'm glad port put this in a 375ml bottle , because this is a sipper , treated this almost like fine bourbon sipping for quite awhile , but i could sip on this all night very interesting beer .
the aroma is a bit of wheat and sweetness but not much .  the white head is huge and pillowy and leaves wonderful fuzzy navel lacing .  m - the feel is not terrible .

i did n't think it smelled much like a pilsener but then again i did notice the malt used ... .the hops were a little muted for the style i thought .  excellent look - copper color with a big slightly off-white head that leaves excellent lacing . looks as good as a rye beer can .  the carbonation does not give this beer a pleasant mouthfeel that i would like .

hard to get a decent aroma - i 'm brewing right now so i will give it a average . fruity , earthy , a bit smokey and roasty .  great white head that left a really nice lacing .  cons : the low carbonation level does hurt many factors of the beer , but it is such an exquisitely brewed offering , it 's only a minor issue .

served in a goblet at armsby abby in worcester 8/24 . the nose in this beer is all alcohol with sight sweet malt .  stellar appearance with this beer . it pours a really nice orange amber color with fine yeast particles suspended in it like stars . very attractive .  this was my first encounter with pumpkin ale . i must confess that i could not finish the bottle . i had the distinct impression that the beer was trying to taste like something and not quite getting there . fearing the latter , i tossed the bottle after about five sips .

smell was odd ... something seemed off ... unbelievable the difference between smell and taste ... the taste was great..sweet on the front , rounding into a tartness and a very nice overtone of alcohol . drinkability is very good for the high abv ... very easy to drink .  pours a very nice amber , just the slightest bit of haze . nice thick , dense , head . excellent lacings .  i always look forward like most do the annual stone anniversary brews.poured a rich deep amber with a tight and sticky one finger off white head , big hops in the nose with a mix pine and herbal/leaf , there is a gummy , fruity-like sweet note as well.the mouthfeel is a bit sharp i will say it crashes down the gullett at first , it does begin to smooth out after a few sips but still seems a bit harsh.no holds barred hops hit the palate up front with big pine and big herbalness , a healthy does of sweeter alcohol gives a slight burn along with a bit of dark fruit.very good but seems like it something that should sit for awhile , still another fine one from stone .

there is not much in the way of aroma , slightly sweet with no hop aroma . the beer is full bodied , smooth across the tongue .  poured from a bottle into a pint - exceptionally clear , copper colored with a one finger head that was almost latte colored , enough carbonation to keep plenty of lacing and a little bit of a head until the end .  drink this on tap at city beverage in durham . i like the color and mouthfeel , though a bit thin for a heavy beer aroma is slightly sweet and complex spices taste is toasted barley , spices , and slight caramel with little head . drinks easy for a heavy beer

rather subdued smells of hops and citrus and i 'm getting a bigger than expected malt .  the color is incredible . i 'm not sure how you give this appearance anything other than a 1 or 5 . excellent retention , settling to a thick film and rings of clumpy lacing .  mouf & gt ; meh . okay . average .

incredibly fresh hop aroma . absolutely unbelievable . must try these galaxy hops for my homebrew soon .  this settles very slowly to a thin , nearly complete cap and leaving behind amazing lacing . the beer itself is black as night . a small amount of sediment remains in the bottle and the last portion of the pour seemed a little cloudy .  m : medium body with low carb . dry finish . nothing special here .

the nose was lightly malty with a slight fruitiness accompanying the sweetness . the finish was bittersweet and extremely pleasant .  a- deep black with a giant tan head . retention is awsome and it laces down the entire glass .  a completely black beer with a thin mocha head . boris is a thick , almost to the point of sludgy beer with a roasted malt taste with a noticeable but background hop presences . the oatmeal comes into play as a slight cookie taste . overall it 's a great beer that worthy of a try .

smell : yeasty . maybe some very mellow goldings or fuggles .  the color of this beer i find just amazing . it 's so dark as it sits in a guinness glass , with it 's beautiful smooth head . are there bubbles finer than these ? in contrast to how heavy it looks , it 's goes down incredibly smooth and fast .  the only thing slightly disappointing about this beer for me was the mouthfeel seemed a bit watery .

smell was alcohol and burnt malt .  stunning ruby red/black beauty with superb head retention .  mf : the carbonation is n't quite as spritzy as i would hope to go along with the huge sourness , the body is light d : this is a great lambic .

the smell is not all that appealing . it is way earthy and at first it reminded me of an ashtray . the mouthfeel is excellent very `` wet '' and good finish . overall , a very nice beer .  served in a pint glass poured from a 12oz bottle a : pours a deep black color with thick foamy head reminiscent of chocolate milk .  light , decently carbonated , and quenching for the desert dweller .

a - pours a nice deep inky dark color befitting a proper russian imp stout . s - dry biting hops come through with a dark roasted malt earthiness and just a touch of currant or other earthy dried fruit . not too complex or strong of a smell , though . d - incredibly well-balanced beer whose hops and malt come together in unison .  huge rocky off-white head with good retention . carbonation bubbles rise to the top which makes the head more active than a tornado in a trailor park . fine looking beer !  a-garnet with small ring of foam s-raisin , pancake syrup , faint vinager t-assertive sour front , sour cherry , some malt sweetness , dates m-medium , with average carbonation d-very tasty !

smell is intense . lemon sour acidity , pepper , lots of sweat & musk . sweet florals . earthy funk . it just seems more then a tad empty when compared to what i smelled up front .  poured from a 750ml bottle into a champagne flute : appearance : pours a beautiful strawberry red/ lavander purple color . huge pink head that has great retention .  flavor is absolutely nothing like an oud bruin .

the beer 's predominant smell is malts , with some citrus in the form of lemons and orange coming through , too , kind of like the first hint of spring .  poured out of a bottle to a beautiful dark color . really a beautiful beer .  the body is surprisingly light with moderate carbonation , helping to make this very drinkable .

to me , boddingtons is the `` caramel '' version of the `` chocolate '' guinness if that makes sense . it 's a smooth and very drinkable beer that you can just put down without even realizing . not much of a nose , which would probably be its biggest problem . it 's a staple , not something that pushes the boundaries , and it should be appreciated as such . it 's best on draught and pairs well with many deserts .  absolutely beautiful long-lasting cascade and unbelievable merangue-like head .  nice dark brown color with fantnaztic lacing ! smells choclotly with coffee . tastes even and thick with cocoa sweet caramel flavors continuing thru . good for its class this porter represents well , its much better than its younger brother . would drink again .

faint roasted malt aroma , perhaps a hint of sweetness .  pours with a hefty amount of two finger thick light tan head , and has a clear copper colored body .  mouthfeel is a bit thinner than i would have expected .

poured flat and tasted blandish . thin feel and a real lack of substance or flavour . i 've had a few other trafalgar beers which were pretty decent , so i was surprised .  summit horizon red : a : appearance is exceptional , great amber-red color to it with exceptional clarity ! nice 1 '' head that develops yet depletes half-way through .  mouthfeel is way more thin than the head and lacing made me think it would be . very quaffable .

s - not bad , vinous with a touch of vinegar . some fruitiness there as well . t - fruit vinegar and a touch of funk there .  pours a bright orange color , slightly carbonated , with a thick pillowy off-white head .  mouthfeel : this was my one issue with this beer . it loses carbonation quickly , and with not that much to start with , it is kind of a bummer . a little sticky as well but the taste makes up for a bit of this .

sampled from a 12oz bottle at the falcon 's christmas in july tasting sharp citrusy aroma with a grapefruit rind approach with some dry toasty malt notes . it 's unfortunate , but i i 'm cerrtain this was a well travelled bottle of what feels like it should be an otherwise fine beer .  very bright , very glowing red body . cream-colored head is boisterous and rocky .  tingly in the nose which is common with sour ales but this is n't sour at all t. sweet with dried fruit , malty m. has a biting quality , a bit to carbonated .

s- only could smell sweet and smoke . the only off area was the smell which is usually the area that lacks in most of my reviews . overall this was a great beer .  a very good porter , poured dark ruby brown color with strong tan head that i impatiently dove into smelling its aroma of chocolate , burnt malt , sweet caramels and hops .  mouthfeel : a bit thin the only thing i can say i 'm disappointed about here just seems watery i even recall the original munich formula having more body but hey sturdy carbonation excellent o-fest .

smells are light too , and crisp . nothing sweet or piny to note .  this brew pours with a deep amber body topped by a medium thick head with lots of lacing .  thin mouthfeel , this is the achilles heel of the beer .

s - first impression is sweet malt and diacetyl .  hazy and dark copper-amber in color with a thick cream colored head of super tightly laced foam that left great lacing at it receded at a slow but steady rate ; the head reminds me of an improperly baked cake very slowly losing its leavening .  m : it 's a little thin , but i kind of like it . d : improved because of the thin mouthfeel .

this is a seriously complex nose , just tons going on ... fruits , mainly peach , some pineapple ? certainly lemon , white grape , sure , some white pepper , dry lemon rind , citrus , gosh ... it goes on and on and on ... certainly some funk and wildness , dry white wine ... yeah , this is hard to pin down and extremely academic , enjoyable , and all around good . t. follows , lots of dry white wine , peachy , semi-sweet , spicy , earthy , some tire , champagne , peach again , no real hop , dry , wild , funky , lemon-citric , seriously interesting , challenging , to be sure , but i am digging it . fun to try and get your palate around . d. not really , this is something to share and comment on , and take your time with .  the color is pretty cool to look at .  good carbonation , which i appreciate . minimal complexity to this beer .

smell : i 'm really not getting much aroma off this . perhaps a hint of grasses , but barely . taste : nice malt taste with a light bit of citrus ( lemon ) and grasses .  this beer looks great , clean and clear , good carbonation and head .  the mouthfeel is quite thin , verging on watery .

foam looks like insulation foam.. smells okay , not a whole lot going on , mostly dark malts .  pours a beautiful dark brown , nearly black , with a tan head of about one finger .  a soft , almost too light mouthfeel and a little weak carbonation , the only appearent downside of this brew in my opinion .

pleasant aroma of amarillo hops with notes of mandarin/tangerine .  very pretty in the glass , big foam head that would n't quit through the whole bottle . heavy orange color .  mouthfeel : it 's a bit heavy for the style .

somewhat light and delicate but still flavorful . very , very drinkable . hearsay is that the house yeast strain was not used in this beer which , in my opinion , is a good thing .  appearance - crystal clear gold body with a huge white head ( took three goblets to pour this ) . gorgeous .  m - medium to light body , low carbonation , smooth mouthfeel going down , perhaps a bit watery .

lacing consists of large swaths of bubbles clinging to the glass , which dry out over time . smells fairly bright for a porter . roasted dark malts are at an appreciable minimum . ah , the nose does n't do the taste justice .  what a shame ... pours a pretty golden-amber color topped by a huge , thick , creamy white head .  the feel is a little odd . it does n't seem to be too carbonated , but the bubbles sting like sprite against your lips .

the taste is pretty good , it 's leaps and bounds ahead of the smell . big sweet malts , chocolate , coffee , hops , some slight smokiness , and almost an artificial banana flavor .  a : beautiful clear rich copper color with creamy tan head . m : smooth o : a very aesthetically pleasing beer . really beautiful to look at and smell .  m - extremely light and watery , typical carbonation from a cask .

the smell has some peach aromas to it , but it 's much lighter than i expected .  appearance : slightly hazy , ruby-amber pour with a voluminous ( and tenacious ) , light-tan whipped-cream head . recedes to floating dollops ... lace everywhere !  mouthfeel : there is a lot of bitterness .

s : a little sour and yeasty , followed by fruit . pears , figs and banana . i can just see a abbey full of monks enjoying this out of chalices , and having a great time .  pours a sparkling orange tinged gold , topped with a huge four finger pillowy white head , constant streams of carbonation bubbles , leaves thick puffy webs of lacing .  is this someones idea of a joke ? rotten peaches with a kick of dirty feet is not something i prefer in my beer . sour an nasty , she be . i should have know by the pour , cider apple yellow fizzy white head . cripe , im glad i only got 2 bottles of this overpriced ( $ 2.50 a pop ) sour peach soda geez , only 4.5 % . i would have kicked myself in the sack for buying this , but im no longer that agile .

a little bit of fruit gone bad on the nose , this might be due to the aging , it is n't too strong but still noticeable . rich malts and still some hops in the bg .  a : thick and black , dark almond head ( more like a thin disk of residual bubbles ) s : strong note of alcohol , bitter dark chocolate , coffee m : very alcoholic feel ; initial taste of a dark stout followed by the heat of a liquor akin to scotch .  malts help to round it out a little , but that bitterness hangs around for quite a bit m : medium body with typical sa carbonation , slightly oily d/o : well , apparently zeus is known for that intense piney flavor , so it is highlighted well here .

looks fantastic in this erdinger weizen glass . smell the nose is of yeasty wheat and malt . drinkability this is a very drinkable beer .  exceptional head and lace . big , rough , chunky , substantial lace . impressive to look at and earns full points on that count .  m : sharp carbonation is pretty overpowering , and any refreshing aspects of the smell and taste are lost .
decent lacing of foam s - grains and floral notes t - sweet malts .  wow ... what a head !  mouthfeel is on the light end .

i can easily smell the blackberry but it 's kind of got an artificial sweetener smell . this kind of overshadows any other aroma . just sweet fake blackberries .  came out a murky amber-gold with a good inch 's worth of head on it . great retention , and perfect lacing rings after each sip . beautiful .  the mouthfeel starts off kind of watery since this seems to be a light to medium bodied brew and leaves a dry , but sticky feel to the lips .

s - light malt scent , and not much else .  beautiful box package , dated 2004 , opens to reveal a classy looking bottle , numbered 85352 . this pours into a tukip a dark amber/light brown , with a thin head .  a little thin .

i am a big ipa fan and had never heard of this beer , but when i saw it on tap at a local restaurant decided to give it a try . nice traditional amber color , slight citrus nose , decent malt to hop balance , very drinkable , and went great with my pizza .  it has a very deep black color and tan head that make it beautiful to pour .  i always drink my high life out of cans ! it looks like beer , smells like beer , and tastes like beer ... to keep it simple . this is my go-to macro , and will always be as long as miller keeps it the same ! prost !

to be honest , the aroma is the worst part of this beer , because i love the taste .  a - pours black with a nice light-tan head . looks great . sticks fairly well to the side , just about as good as a porter could .  mf- raw resinous and sticky , becoming oily , medium carbonation , slightly astringent , dry and grainy in the finish d- well rounded ipa , but not the best around .

mouthfeel and smell are nothing that stands out for the style but not at all bad either . amber but not as dark as others of this style , quite nice to look at , a few bubbles run from top to bottom .  a- gorgeous . deep gold with hints of orange .  m : medium body but the finish is not as crisp nor as clean as it could be .

smell : faint aroma with some piney hops , a little bit of malt , and a hint of iced tea . taste : rich biscuit malty taste with a fair bit of caramel as well . drinkability : easily drinkable and very sessionable . final notes : a very good amber ale - lots of biscuity , caramelly goodness but the hoppy back end is also a pleasant surprise .  pours a very nice looking dark ruby with a thick tan head which remains forever and leaves sticky lacing in my delirium glass . a beautiful beer , i wish they all looked like this .  m- average medium bodied beer o- great take on a saison style beer .

s : pretty muted , a little malt , some faint hop and a little toasty bread . t : big caramel malt , some crisp pine resin hop , and very toasty .  great looking beer !  the flavor is a bit harsh and a bit watery , but not too much .

the aroma is quite faint , i pick up some buttery caramel malt .  this looked wonderful ! ! !  mouthfeel & drinkability : lighter bodied and less bitter than most other ipas , which makes for quite easy drinking .

aroma , while nice , is on the more subtle side .  a - pours a gorgeous bright and translucent dark copper color with some nice golden and slight amber hints . very good retention . almost perfect looking beer .  m - a little harsh , not as smooth as other ipas .

smell : a hint of caramel candy sweetness is all the nose picks ups .  a- pretty beautiful . a reddish amber color , just glowing .  poured from bottle to tulip glass a : brilliantly clear pale yellow color with huge 3+ finger head that fades very slowly n : nose of a light belgian type wit with some light malts , touch of spices , toasted quality , touch of yeast t : starts with more malts and toasted quality , pretty light otherwise , a touch of light fruits and banana , slight earthy marzen quality , no spices m : very light and somewhat watery f : finishes dry and very crisp with a fading earthy marzen taste , would make a good session beer final thoughts : its a very light tasting oktoberfest/marzen .

s - very goodly smell of malts and some faint raspberry juice in the background , biscut qualities too .  pours an opaque darkness with a huge stiff dark brown head that decomposes like an ice cream sundae , massive 3d lacing present .  mouthfeel is a bit thin , but thats a minor complaint .

the nose is beautiful . i get the belgian yeastiness , and something akin to peaches served with a dash of allspice . so far it 's awesome .  ) pitch black colour , moderate brown head . the appearance is top notch , a very fine and lasting brown head .  the rye is evident , as is a tangy almost sour note along with the bread . a little over-carbonated ... i found it slightly distracting and that it may have affected my enjoyment of the beer 's complexity . light-bodied and very refreshing . while i have little to no experience with beers of this style , i enjoyed this one and i believe that its a great refresher during the summer months .

smell : barely any aroma as is usual with nitro beers .  a- pours orange-amber with a massive , foamy and creamy head that retains amazingly , gives duvel a run for its money . the cloud is as big as the head of others .  mouthfeel is poor due to the overdone carbonation .

it had a mild malty aroma with good lacing and a very smooth palate .  i absolutely loved this bottle .  medium bodied with carbonation that was a little too high and too coarse for my liking , but it did n't turn me off completely . my only issue was the carbonation .

smell is hops and very very little floral notes .  pours to a beautiful deep dark brown body with a hint of ruby red when held to light . hosts a decent 1 and a half inch rich tan head , leaving some lace as it fades .  m - surprisingly , its a bit thin and lacks carbonation .
has a light hop aroma . moderate carbonation , with a silky mouth .  a : one of the most gorgeous beer i 've ever seen . head is tan and very very strong .  medium bodied fairly low carbonation .

not too much aroma , but you can detect a sweet , double ipa smell through the cloudy yellow foam .  but not rahr and son 's w.w. from the get go the pour was great a beautiful reddish brown with a head that stuck around for awhile . and lacing that covered the glass throughout the few minutes it took for me to gobble this one down and lots of sediment in the bottle .  light bodied for what i was expecting , but then it does n't claim to be a porter or stout .

also a faint green apple smell that seemed misplaced .  pours with a beautiful amber body topped by a thick lasting head with a good amount of lace left on the glass .  mouthfeel : a little watery , but not terrible .

smell - rosey , very subdued , but a little too much so . just would have expected a bit more out of it , in terms of aroma . taste - this reminds me of a barleywine . there were lots of hops in this , but it was very smooth . you can taste the alcohol . not what i would have expected out of the winter warmer style , but enjoyable none the less . feel - extremely smooth with a nice mouthcovering .  appearance : black as the abyssal depths topped by a hearty dark brown head that 's thick , frothy and slightly rocky . it sticks around for quite some time before settling down to a smallish layer of foam and then finally a ring of bubbles .  m : lighter than it should be and very creamy and smooth , decent carbonation . f : long creamy chocolate vanilla smoothness .

such a teaser the nose- complex and swirling with sweet notes of cocoa powder , toffee , freshly ground coffee , raisin , prune , brown sugar , peach and apricot . ) with a low carbonation , a mild and poorly integrated sourness , and a bigtime cloying sweetness upfront- the unfortunate result of the beer 's sweet chocolate flavors clashing head on with the brown sugary fruitiness . like i said , the nose is nice , but it really ends there .  pours amberish black . nice pillowy head . retention and lacing are nice apples , chocolate in the nose .  heavy hops , but not totally unbalanced . very quenching .
