nice and citrus spicey sweet which balances itself . i 'm not a huge fan of the style , but i found this to be a tasty brew nontheless .  i thought i did n't like saisons until i tried this one . great head , fine bubbles that stuck to the glass the whole way down .  my first tripel style beer , i spit it on my counter . the flavors of fruit combined with a bitter aftertaste left one bottle down the drain , and three still sitting in their case . anyone near me is welcome to the other three . while i am confident in the quality of this product , this style is definitely not for me .

the smell actually has a nice deep roasted malt aroma that dominated the nose , much stronger than i would have though , slightly sweet with a cocoa presence .  makes an impressive appearance , a nice red amber color with a large foamy pale head that lingers in the chalice with some sticking .  the body is medium with decent carbonation .

extremely smooth for a light beer and very easy to drink . a very nice light beer , and its quite easy to drink 2 or 30 of them . woooooooooooooooooooooooooooo  a nearly perfect pour . smells and tastes of the usual hefe spicy , peppery yeast , clove and banana , with a touch of citrus ( maybe lemon ) sourness .  spritely carbonated and fairly aqueous . very good but i would like a little more body .

s - has an aroma of apple cider mixed with a heavy dose of cloves and a very mild hint of pumpkin . also some mild banana-like esters . enough said .  appearance - black with murky auburn brown edges . nice semi tan head with great retention and lacing . super sticky on the sides , just beautiful .  actually thought it might be bad but when i drank it there was plenty of carbonation . smell : a toasted malty smell with an almost cardboard smell . taste : very strong toasted smell but more of a bitterness then a sweetness . note : no date on the bottle but wondering if this beer had gone bad . will try another attempt at it but not really looking forward to it .

the aroma was nice , but nothing special .  poured a hazy straw colored hue with a fluffy three finger head . the retention was beyond excellent as was the very stick lacing . by the time i got to the bottom of my hefe glass , there was still nearly a finger of fluffy head remaining .  mouthfeel : light/ medium body with excessive carbonation that somewhat hinders the flavor .

possibly the best maltese shandy i 've ever had . a- pale yellow and a big big white head that rises quick . s- nose is very faint.. a bit of lime . like a limeade , some sweet slickness that builds in the finish . ugh , i know it 's a lime shandy , but still , it 's like chewing on tropical antacid tablets . o- still the best maltese shandy i 've ever had .  drank on-tap at hot tomato 's , new haven , ct poured a hazy amber with a two-finger , bubbly , white head that left huge ridges of lacing all the way down the glass .  the body is thin and slightly anemic . a little more carbonation and body would carry this really unique beer into the stratosphere .

the aroma is a variety of differnet malts with a very slight spicy scent that i could n't identufy .  incredible whipped retention and lacing everywhere . this is an awesome looking beer !  mouth- thin ? it 's a little thin , it lacks depth , and too much raisin for my taste .

poured into a some big ass glass ... appearance-amber body , very dark pale ale . some skunk , not sure what the date is on this bottle ... taste-tart granny smith apple along with some sweet caramel malts .  sediment floats about in a strange vapor-like form . just the head by itself is more complex than most beers , sits on top the whole time , slowly getting all awesome and chunky looking and leaving good lacing .  very low carbonation , strong , hoppy with lingering after taste , a very typical english bitter but not my cup of tea .

s- strong cherry and rasberry charachter . a pretty strong tartness is every step of the way as well t- very strong tart charachter , not as sour as i was thinking , nicely fruity at the start but it stays too sweet at the finish which is a little off-putting , however some of my friends realy liked it .  beautiful looking beer to be sure , dark , dark brown with a very attractive frothy tan head . just looks so good in the glass .  lightly bodied , perhaps overly so , with a passably dextrinous mouthfeel .

s : faint toasted grains and earthy heath . t : toasted malts much more pronounced that aroma ; chocolate , lightly burnt toffee and bitter coffee . disappointed in the nose , but a good stout past that .  the three-finger beige head displayed great retention as a fluffy cap . eventually the cap became rocky and left little islands of foam floating atop the liquid . the lacing was also excellent , in curtains ; top marks for appearance .  the mouthfeel is the only thing i think could be improved here and it very well may just be that i am having it from a growler .

what i could detect was rather wheat-beerish : some cloves and bananas , maybe some lemons . decent light-amber color , too . very nice taste , with spicy oranges and other citrus ambling arm-in-arm with light bananas and some hay . of the american bpas i 've had , this was by far the most drinkable : not overly bitter or ham-fistedly hopped , but nicely balanced and quite drinkable .  comes out of the tap a rich opaque warm sable with a thick , fine-bubbled , almost guinness-like light tan head that leaves some good lacing .  the palate is somewhat thin for the style but it 's still smooth .

sticking my nose into this thing there is a bit of pine , grass , earth tones , but not much else .  a : attractive drink on the pour , looks like a lighter , creamier guinness pint from a good tap . huge head and flowing bubbles .  mouthfeel was not particularly big , enough that you knew you were drinking something real but not a facefull .

the aroma is coffeeish , bitter . this beer is a pretty masterful beer of the style , but it 's not quite exceptional ( for a stout ) . considering the fact there was as much flavor left as there was , this would probably be a beautiful beer if drawn from a cask with a handpump .  tasted nov. 21rst 2011 ( from notes ) tulip a - very nice translucent blood red , 1/4 finger off white fizzy head and minimum lacing s - peat , smoke , nuts , alcohol , slight wine , lots of yeast and oak t - so much peat , wow ! sap , wood , lemon , citrus , alcohol , sauvignon blanc , more peat , some nice hops and the peat kind of peats ( haha ) out all the other flavors m - medium body , medium acidity , low complexity , not balanced and very long finish d - while at first few sips the peat is overwhelming and almost nasty , after a bit the peat is more in the background of a smokey , citrus , alcoholic ale .  the mouthfeel was about what i expected going in , but i thought it might a little over-carbonated . the aggressiveness of the carbonation was a little distracting .

s : not much going on hear , some toffee and yeast t : very malty , toffee sweetness , some spice .  thick brown head with moderate retention . excellent lacing throughout .  it was bland and the stout portion was overpowering . yet , for reason 's i do n't understand , the people i know from philadelphia all seem to love this beer .
malt scent with a feint fruitiness to it .  poured a beautiful amber color . wonderful lacing . just a beautiful beer .  m : thin , but with a bit of sparkle .

afraid the smell is horrid..brings back the old english hangovers yuk .  a - it 's impossible to score higher , beautiful beer ... thick fluffy white head that resembles the frothed milk of a latte , dark gold to light copper , carbonation rains towards the head ... such a beautiful looking beer .  body is fairly thin , but that is expected for the modest abv .

lightest and sweetest helles yet -- perhaps even paler than a us macro . i like jason 's grape skin description . sidenote : bit of a clinical , soapy scent in the glass .  pours a perfect cloudy gold with a big fluffy head .  wow this has to be one of the worst ideas in beer history . trying to cross a pale ale with a belgian and what you got is something that is a distant cousin to both . instead of leveraging the style 's strengths this beer doubles down on their worst attributes . a very hoppy tatse that fights like a strong ale . not a fun beer and a true shame that it might discredit weyerbacher 's other great beers .

s : not the best aspect of this beer -- smells a lot like balsamic vinegar without much of the underlying fruit coming through . t : quite tart with a bit of barnyard horse blanket .  appearance : darkest , thickest brown head i 've seen , even a notch above rogue 's shakespeare stout . pitch black even when directly on top of a 60w lamp . tall head , intense lacing .  flavour is better than expected- a little woody and slightly spicy , with a thick strong maltiness . i 'd like the hearty body on this one , were it not for the turbocharged carbonation .

there is a faint smell of malt , but it is n't strong .  pours a deep murky brown with a nice frothy light-tan head that lasts and leaves great lacing .  feel is thin bodied overall , but well bodied for the style .

either is the rye . i sought out rye as i chose it to pair with an herbed chicken . the smoke is light as well so i suppose i could call it a bock . the hops , as expected , were n't pronounced .  appearance- beer pours clear and golden with a half finger of creamy white head with ample lacing on the sides of the glass . carbonation rises from the bottom of the glass as if this were a pilsner . very nice on looks at least .  taste is weak but odd at the same time with a mild rice-sweetness . this is the kind of beer you can share with your friends because most do n't appreciate the imports anyway . i drank plenty of this is my younger days ... when you look up headache in the dictionary it reads `` drink 12 budweisers and take a nap .
smells mostly of citrus and light malt . floral notes . nothing too prominent .  exquisite in appearance !  the mouthfeel is light carbonation , somewhat on the watery side , but very drinkable .

nice grapefruit citrus taste . a nice malty front with the citrus and slight sweetness undertones .  a perfect pour into an oversized wine glass with rich deep amber body a tightly formed thick white head , i could not find any reason to not give a perfect score.tropical fruity hops in the nose with a little boozy and caramel sweetness , overripe mango and pineapple on the palate with again some sweetish booze , the malt base is quite dry underneath the hops and sweet booze.a nice dipa , one of the best pours for me ... ever .  i have had ipas that went down a bit smoother but this one is n't bad it still goes down good but with just a little more carbonation and bite .
the smell is hops , almost bitter , and faint malt .  this beer is absolutely stunning in appearance .  the mouthfeel however is slightly taut . body is clear red copper with sustained carbonation .

it smells of mild biscuit grain , light piney hops , a bit woody , and some funky floral hops .  first of all this is an amazing looking beer . a nice pale orange , hazy , with a huge rocky white head . great retention and that belgian lace that i love .  as with several anchor offerings , i feel the carbonation is a bit overdone , but is n't powerful enough to be overly distracting .

light aroma of malt and some hops , nothing earth-shattering . hurry , get some at the brewery before it 's all gone !  pours black with virtually no light around the edges . towering cap of light brown foam that grew on the pour like one of those ash-growing snake things from a fireworks stand . retention is great , as is the lacing .  very carbonated feel on the tongue .

the smell is a heavenly mix of chocolate and raspberrries and malty goodness .  the beer pours beautiful . great head and retention .  m - a little thin for my liking . the body is quite thin , almost watery .

lately i have had my share of coffee infused brews so this one should be another great experience . coming off of a cold so the smell is n't that strong to me right . but it smell decent from what can make out .  pours a clear dark brown with superior side lacing and a copious tan head with very good retention . appearance is exceptional .  the feel is the only drawback here . it was rather light in body , and thin feeling . carbonation was adequate , but it just lacked that `` near medium '' that i would expect from a dipa .

s- very sour and thick . smells nothing like it tastes . d- incredible summer beer . this beer is the best witbier i have had .  bottle holiday wine cellar escondido , ca black as can be with a thick , persistent light brown head . perfection !  ) i would like a little more bready/chewiness as the mouthful feels a tad more thin than what i 'd prefer for this style .

appearance - was excellent , as dark and opaque as any stout , very little head with no visible carbonation . smell - some mild sweetness from the malt with a hint of that coffee taste associated with dark beers .  this brew is quite hazy with a golden orange body . the head produced is massive and bright white .  the mouthfeel , i was not so impressed with .

i remember when i reviewed jw dundee 's pale ale as pretty decent too . very lively . smelled like malt , there was n't much else . it 's more of a craft lager , which makes genesee go up on my scale even more .  11.2 oz , 2007 bottle a : deep brown , not quite black under a nice sized tan head . excellent lace and retention .  mouthfeel if very alive and crisp at first sip . maybe a bit overpowering on the carbonation .

smell : i ca n't pick up much here . some yeast and maybe hints of vanilla ?  poured into a chalice a- huge huge huge frothy merangue like , sand colored head rises way above the rim of the glass . it has incredible stay with incredible lacing . the beer is a murky and clouded dark brown/umber .  m : average , nothing of note .

smell was okay . juicy fruit and later cola .  i 'm very impressed with this beers look .  the largest macro beer in the country is very disappointing . the feel of this beer is somewhat thin but i liked the bock feel that it had .

a deep brown color gives the initial stout impression but a light citrusy aroma is present leading one to believe it 's and ipa .  bourbon colored with an excellent 3 finger head that rises a good 1/4 inch above the glass . very foamy head that last a long , long time .  the beer feels light but not watery . there is a little prickle on the tongue at the swallow .

smell - light and hoppy with a moderate aroma of malt .  firstly , i dont know if the nitro can should be listed alongside the on-tap version , because they are completely different , as the on tap version is far superior than the widget-can . anyway , if kept well , the pour is the classic we have all come to know and love .  somewhat smooth feel , moderate-medium body for amber , but still feels a little thin .

aroma is a bit muted .  served in a pilsner glass a : pours a deep mahogany color that looks thick . pours with very thick white head and leaves considerable lacing s : very sweet smelling brew possibly of cherries .  m : crisp feel at first , mellows gradually before eventually becoming a little sticky/gummy . light-medium body .

s - strong citrus and pine/juniper nose on it . very fragrant making you expect a delicious taste to follow . m - lots of bitter tangy sensation at the back of the tongue following a few sips , but strangely lite and unsatisfying . d - decent drinkability , but not exceptional . it 's a strange beer : starts off great with an impressive hops-laden nose , but then does n't really delivery .  a - two fingers of off-white head slowly fade on top of a gorgeous translucent amber beer with bubbles rising steadily through it s - smell is a juicy blend of citrus and apricot , grapefruit is most prominent but plenty of orange zest comes through , apricot is muted and there 's a little bit of mint and pine in there too , do n't get too much aroma from the malts , a touch of toffee maybe t - flavor is far too muted considering that the beer is so appealing to the eyes and the nose , a touch of sweetness , a lot of hop bitterness , some grapefruit and orange , some apricot , but so subdued m - nice tongue coating from the hops but the carbonation is a little prickly , not as smooth as it could be o - not a bad ipa , not a great ipa .  mouthfeel is a little lacking ; like i said , this bottle had very little to no carbonation , so i might need to try again . overall , though , a very tasty sweet high abv winter seasonal that i wo n't mind drinking again to `` research the carbonation .

she loves scotch ales/scottish ales and when i ca n't turn up something new/local for her to enjoy i fall back on the classic imports . the nose is mildly malty .  a- damn sexy looking in my pilsner glass . it sits atop a slightly hazed , deep red almost apple cider colored body .  the mouthfeel was lowly carbonated .

smell : not much smell , the small amount i am getting has nice coffee and mocha notes . taste : this really shines in this category , like the smell suggests this has strong coffee flavor with a nice mocha after taste that really becomes apparent several seconds after tasting . the light mouthfeel and the carbonation make this very drinkable ; almost scary drinkable for an oatmeal stout !  beautiful pour . bits of sediment floating around . nice creamy tan head that remained throughout with gorgeous lacing .  mouthfeel : medium body and a finish that is a bit dry . this beer almost flat .

the beer 's scent was almost entirely hops for me . it seemed to be a one dimensional flavor profile to the scent . i did n't get very much matlyness in the smell . the flavor was really where this beer started to pick up .  dark chocolate brown with a nice , thick , creamy , khaki head atop .  m - the reason i dinged it on mouthfeel is because it actually left some of that nasty coffee-mouth feeling in my gullet .

there is the light smell of caramel along with a whiff of alcohol ( which is a surprise considering the abv is not terribly high ) .  this brew pours out a deep , hazy red amber color crested with a massive head that retains very well and leaves huge , sticky lacing .  lighter body than i thought it would be with with very low carbonation..the weakest point of the brew . easy drinker for the abv and ignoring the mouth feel , a nice brew .

s - mostly raspberry , which i found quite appealing . some caramel and roasted malt .  great amber apperance with thick ass head that will not stop clinging to the glass .  the mouthfeel is light with a decent amount of carbonation .

really though , the harshness is what you get from the start , which is obviously off-putting . better as it warms . however , the nose dings the score a bit .  glassware - imperial pint appearance - dark amber/red in color , which makes sense . nice two finger white head that leaves a lot of really great lacing on the glass .  brownish gold beer straight out of a 40 ounce bottle . sugary sweet flavors of corn and grain . it 's not something i 'll buy very often . milwaukee 's best 40s are cheaper and taste better , even if they do n't have that signature bottle shape .

smell : very , very faint smell of malt and floral hops . taste : very smooth , creamy , slightly sweet , with good balance and a nice hop finish . fairly hopped for this class .  poured - beautiful dark color .  it is astringent and medicicnal .

mild roasted malt aroma .  pours a beautiful slightly hazy amber color with a large two inch off white head . excellent retention and some great lacing .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied to me . could be a little thicker on the tongue .

aroma is faint , but of roasted malts and some nutty and fruitiness . for such a mild beer , this is very impressive . full of flavour .  a careful pour produces a robust , sandy colored , three-finger head with excellent retention and lacing .  m - a little on the thin side .

found this ipa in hillsboro oregon in the fred meyer two days before thanksgiving bought the whole 12 pack cause the parents in from out of town were paying , so why not . this beer was good , a good session ipa not too bitter more like a pale ale , good color and taste , although not hoppy enough for me .  but wow , this one looks amazing ! a gorgeous burgundy with beautiful creamy froth on top .  nice floral hops and malt starchiness in the finish . it 's a drinkable beer . heavy in the stomach .

i put my nose in the head nosing for the nose . a robust bitter hopped start with enduring bitterness throughout the flavor with roundness or body to the flavor supplied by a malt character . a nice long finish consisting of the same lingering bitterness that dominates the flavor . this beer really has a finish quality about it- memorable .  this looks absolutely beautiful .  the only complaint i have is that the texture left much to be offered . overall i great beer .

it had surprisingly little smell , which belied the very tarty flavour.the tartness was very nicely balance at the end with a citrus fruitiness which made the taste and refreshing .  this beer poured a black body with a thick dark tan/black head . a beautiful sight to see .  the taste was very light and highly carbonated . overall i 'm really surprised at all the negative reviews of this beer . maybe it 's just the fact i had it on tap , or that it was fresh .

smell is very mild , slightly musty and dry . sure sign of belgian yeast .  black with reddish tints if you look hard enough . looks really good . fluffy foam settles to a thick , dense mass .  mouthfeel is decent , this beer seems to foam up in your mouth .

solid macrobrew beer . sometimes you just need to kick back and enjoy something fresh , and heineken delivers . if you are cutting calories go light , they taste the same .  a toasted head has great retention and lace .  the beer seems to thin a bit in the mouthfeel . very clean beer for a triple , slightly thin in the mouthfeel , but that helps give this beer a nice clean dry finish .

s. herby ( marijuana/skunk ) essence on the nose . not much else .  perfect head retention and plenty of lacing left behind in the glass .  the middle is kind of hoppy , but somewhat thin . the finish is dry and quite hoppy . a decent light beer .

poured from bottle into chimay goblet . smell - all i can really smell is the alcohol , maybe a bit of oak , not sure . taste - exceptional for its abv .  hopback pours a beautiful cloudy dark copper with an ample beige head .  t - again , bicuit and nut . nice and malty , virtually no hop bite , but tasty none the less . d - i have had this a ton in the past , but i only just got around to getting another one for the purposes of reviewing .

i live in north carolina and love to get my hands on beer from my area back home . the smell is just fairly subtile but hinted of almost friuty . overall a very decent beer .  amazing looking beer .  a- blackness with a espresso colored head s- coffee beans ground soaked in licorice coffee and dark chocolate really bold t- straight up coffee and espresso with bitter chocolate and a slight tang finish m- medium carbonation and a bit watery for the style d- i drink 3 cup of coffee a day who am i to judge ?

smell is almost non-existant to me .  a- glourious golden yellow with a fluffy and foamy white head that retains well in the tulip glass . dies to a fluffy ring and nice cloud that leaves thick lace all along the glass .  body is perhaps the one less thanexcellent area , as its a little too light and i would have preferred something heavier and slicker ( more like the maui offering ) .

smell : not too much on the nose , i get a little toffee .  makes a great looking beer for sure .  it may not be for everyone but i think this is a beautiful product . flavor is far less sweet than the smell and look might hint , in fact this is gobs of sour black cherry . it 's an instant classic and one of only a handful of lambics i 've liked so far .

chocolate covered malt balls , roasted barley , brown bread , molasses , shoyu , and a touch of oxidation ( sweat , cardboard ) in the nose . letting it `` breath '' for a while seems to help dispense with some of the undesirable aromatics ... old coffee grounds , and an almost sour hop flavor greet the palate . pleasing spice-like astringency . reminds me of nitro-tap but in a good way ... a well balanced and enjoyable example of the style , though it does n't seem as robust as the label claims - i 'd be nervous to age this except at a very cool temperature - as it tastes just a hair past its peak already .  huge four fingers of bright white , soapy head .  the mouth is a tiny bit like flat soda which was the only off-putting part of this beer .

not much in the nose . coffee and maybe a hint of lactose .  poured black with a thick brown head . the retention was great . very creamy and capuccino like looking head .  mouthfeel : the body is oddly thin , and crisp .

on tap at de molen in bodegraven after the waitress walked the tap list board over to us after asking what was on tap . lovely . s - dark fruit malts obvious . bready with dark rye coming to mind . more mild than exprected . weak aroma but flavour is what counts for me , so this was good .  the beer poured a hazy golden color with a massive white head .  mouth feel was pretty average , smooth , not very complex so i expected a little more from it in that department .

hmm odd profile of aromas . but it is nice . ugh .  the appearence is exceptional . pours a stout lovers favorite color , motor oil black . less than a finger of head , but it is a very dark brown .  m : the thinnest , lightest imperial i can remember , but the intensity doesnt have to be overpowering .

smell is average , not a lot comes through other than coriander and other spices .  a - gigantic frothy head that is the color of latte foam . the head lingers for an eternity and leaves a mountain of foam in the middle after it has dissipated to constant level . top notch look for a red . looks good though .  more watery flavored than i expected from this ... very light mouthfeel .

is 23 % and you can smell it , almost like a whisky nose . not much on the nose exept alcohol and a little molasses .  a- looks perfect . ruby amber with a one inch head that only fades after drinking and leaves some nice lacing .  this is very malty at the opening with a twinge of caramel . upon downing it , the taste resembles a very dark beer . very malty with heavy caramel presence that makes it a bit sweet . it also gives a bitter character that mellows into a sweetened deal . i 'll have to try it from the mug in the near future . it may turn out differently due to more carbonization released , making it less bitter , dare i venture to say . but , straight from the bottle , it is easier to imbibe if you 're used to dark , bitter ales .

esbs are not stop traffic hot chicks , but they are the type of chick that can give good head ... so this is on par . nose ... surprisingly musty , tones of malt and caramel are lurking around the back of the joint but are n't quite in the door , nothing offensive , nothing aggressive ... not much to quaff here taste etc ... tastes a bit like the smell except the aftertaste really develops nicely , up front it is slightly bitter with that musty flavor that leeches into the fluggel type flavor and rounds out with a mild cascade floral/p [ ne hop character . this is perfect at cellar temp ... nothing too complex here but man this beer just is a pleasure to drink .  looks like a magazine beer ad . beautiful clear , light , orange-amber color .  taste was pretty balanced with a bit of malt sweetness . overall i liked this one . this is the first beer i have tried from boulder . based on this one , i 'll have to try some of the others that we can get in ct . the website says that a secret spice is added , but i can not really taste any spice . maybe i 'll figure it out by the time i finish the six . good brew .

even though this beer tasted great , the smell left much to be desired . to some up in one word , bland in comparison to the complex smells of other beers .  a - caramel-butterscotch gold with a thick off-white head , very nice looking .  m : slick mouthfeel with a medium amount of carbonation that can be prickly at times . body is medium and has a bit of resiny stickiness to it .

aroma - limited nose , a fairly standard pilsener aroma .  great `` belgian '' lacing & very good head retention smell : sourness & then woody , lactic notes .  it feels very thin in the mouth , close to water .

has a strong fruity citrus smell , i do n't really smell hops ... maybe slightly ... but not as much as other people say .  based on notes poured into a thistle glass with an effervescent amber with 4 fingers of rocky eggshell colored head . great lacing & head retention s : ever-so slight sweet berry smell t : malty , fruittyness , a hint of warming boozeyness up front .  it has little to no head on it with a soft pour . this beer has a good balance of spices that is not overpowering . the aftertaste is mellow . this is one of the darker ales that i have drank but all in all i would give it another try . especially on a snowy winter day .

smell & gt ; average . notes of grain and honey , but slightly metallic .  pouring a deep black with ruby tinting around the edges , out of bounds also has a creamy , tan head which gives way to an attractive , spotted lacing .  like chocolate carbonated corn syrup . body is light and watery ... good carbonation level helps it feel thicker than it is and hints at being creamy .

smells of some heavy brown malts , some toast , a bit of spiciness underlined with a hint of booze . overall , a fantastic and robust offering from a favorite producer . puts countless other pas to shame and raises the bar in an excellent way .  this alt looked fantastic ! has a rich , deep , clear chestnut color , with a very fine light tan head topping off at about 1 '' . the head dissipates at a very slow rate , and leaves top-shelf lacing .  the body was only medium , this was not unexpected as it is an ipa style , but i though it could have done with a bit extra .
no discernable aroma at all - kind of weird .  this beer pours exceptionally well for a three finger thick cranium in a light tan color .  the mouthfeel is medium , slightly watery .

it has a nice colour and can easily be consumed on mass while watching either the maple leafs of the blue jays . i find that creemore does not have the best aroma and infact it greatly detracts from the flavour .  a : nice brown body with a fluffy 1+ finger head that lasted forever .  incredibly light with cereal grains , very grainy taste , hops are nowhere in site . there are way better summer beers out there .

the beer has a golden color with a hint of orange and features a wonderful malty aroma that is crisp and rich . the flavor is also crisp with some malt highlights and a pretty bitter aftertaste , and overall is heavier than i expected ( i was expecting something like a brewpub blond from this since they also offer a pale ale ) . my last swigs still get that great malt aroma wonderful ! !  beautiful , beautiful honey color with a thick , but not creamy , head .  m : a touch thin .

the smell dropped off a bit , being dominated by a biscuit smell with bit of roastiness under it . nice , but nothing special .  huge sticky head alone has a personality all its own . gorgeous golden haze pour that has no room for improvement , while in a class all its own .  md-light body and sharp moderate carbonation . foamed pretty good going down the drain .

smell of alcohol and malts . color was bodacious . mouthfeel was like heavenly night blooming jasmine with a hint of mirliitons and cypress buds .  dissipates slowly and exhibits great retention with beautiful lacing .  ) it has very low carbonation witch makes the mouthfell very average with about that of a tap bud lite , only a little tingle from the carbonation .

s : quite vegetal , has a hint of agave syrup , fairly hoppy , not what you 'd expect .  frickin ' a beautiful . deep and black , medium head of nice and tight dark tan bubbles . no effort required to get it and even going vigorously on the pour it seems like there 's not a crazy amount of head . beautiful .  the mouthfeel is just a touch too syrupy , though it does n't detract much at all from the enjoyment of the beer .

smell : very weak smell overall- some sweet pale malts and grain hints .  the head poured out at 1.5 fingers and stays that way forever in a rocky , creamy form that just refuses to recede . gorgeous appearance .  smell was sweet , with a citrus hint and strong english ale smell . initial taste was interesting , and i was n't sure about whether i would like it . by the end of the bottle , it had become one of the best beers i 've tasted . i would n't recommend it for any parties , but in small groups of like minded people i would say good call . very drinkable beer . looking forward to trying more from the brewery ( if i can find it )

but what i can smell is a lot of malt with some caramel to it . ( please remember on this tasting that i do have a stuffed nose ; thank you ) taste : lighter malty ( spelling ) taste ; great body to the beer ; smooth going down , not noticing the high alcohol content mouthfeel : feels like a well balanced beer .  excellent lacing . great looking ipa .  taste is dominating by anis with some candi sugar . body was above average and alcohol was well hidden .

there was very little nose to speak of , just a bit of a sweetness , like caramel . it was very drinkable , and as with newcastle you can often find this when theres nothing else in the bar/restaurant worth drinking and it would certainly get the job done .  body was black as night with a tan head .  the beer is somewhat oxidized , but still highly drinkable very light bodied bitter , true to the the style . this is a prime candidate for a session beer . at 3.8 % abv , it 's alcohol content makes this a clear choice for something that could literally be consumed all day long , starting with your pancakes !

strong hoppy aroma with a floral hint .  poured from the bottle into a sam adams sensory glass . a : a beautiful pillowy head sits atop a clear , deep brownish copper , with great carbonation . perfect and appetizing .  nothing special here .

and now these famous waters are again being put to good use as the principle ingredient in local ales . spartesian is a soft , summer ale . it is exceptionally pale in a dramatic hue of sun-yellow . fortunately , my tastes stray far from `` timid '' and i was able to settle in to a satisfying appreciation of this very pale beer . it has low co2 , no smell , little forward hop flavor , and a vivid lemon color . but the smooth body makes it an easy drinker on a summer 's day and i was left wondering if that billowy mouthfeel was attributable to olympia 's famous artesian well water .  a - very nice lacing left by a frothy white head with strong stamina on top of a copper colored and translucent body . i even witnessed the bartender pouring some head away .  medium-bodied , maybe just a little bit thin .

the aroma is slight but hoppy , with some pine to it . the flavor is surprisingly light , with piny hops and a tinge of bready malt .  appearance : pitch black with a thick foamy lasting head that laces nicely .  mouthful : somewhat over-carbonated but generally decent mouthfeel .

leaves some real nice lacing on the way down . i smell the hops , but nothing too disctinct .  a : beautiful pour from this 440ml nitro can . bright copper with a thick , creamy white head . great lacing left behind .  drinks a little heavy because of all the sediment but feels watery and thin on the palate . adequate carbonation but not incredible lively .

the aroma was a simple citrus hints and some malts .  a beautiful site setting in the glass , this blackberry to almost brown elixir of life , the head gargantuan in size , creamy in texture , the color a light chocolate brown , the residual lace a thick clinging sheet .  boosting the carbonation would help .
aroma is basic , clean and crisp .  looks beautiful and inviting !  very light bodied , but carbonation seems too low to me .

s : i was a unprepared for the smell , as the malts had a big impact . if i was pressed for details ( i suppose that 's the point here ) i could pinpoint some caramel . t : i think the flavor of this beer is gorgeous . do n't let that push you away though , because it is n't a kriek by any means . kudos to the widmer brothers .  the appearance is amazing . it pours really really dark brown , safe to say black . it leaves a thick lacing around the glass that is very very intimidating .  m - a little thin , sickly-sweet finish .

s : aroma is reserved , with hints of dried fruit and spice . t : dried fruit , bananas , cloves , and ginger are well balanced .  into a tulip . pours the closest to motor oil i 've ever seen in a beer , dark crimson/brown head , dense retention and heavy legs .  mouthfeel : pretty heavy for a porter but very drinkable even in the heat .

s - roasted malts faint grassy hop and dark fruit smell . t - nice balance .  it has a gold cloudy body with a beautiful head and just the right amount of carbonation from an aesthetic point of view . it is a simply picture perfect beer .  the mouthfeel is a bit thin , spicy , moderately dry , and has a distinct saison flavor in the aftertaste .

it was quite amazing . nice bitter coffee notes , with more chocolate notes and sweet malts than with the aroma . this was smelling great , drinking good and going down easy .  pour was exceptional . the head rose faster than expected , and shot over the top of the mug - but it did n't overflow .  smooth and to the point , bit of a sweet aftertaste in the sweet sticky beer way .

nice lacing developed . the aroma was of some barely noticeable malt .  1-fingered extremely light tan head with very impressive retention , leaves rings of lace all the way down the glass .  mouthfeel - a little gritty , though a light body to it .

loads of burp from a very clean , light golden fizz and a nice hopped edge on the aftertaste . certainly wo n't stand up to serious beer for beer competition but this is the type of refreshing hot summer beer that 's best served very cold for thirst quenching . like i say this is the best choice for a breakfast bar beer - nothing else .  appearance : pours the color of a tripel ; that burnt golden orange appearance . head is gigantic and rocky which dissipates slowly into a thick rocky soapy lacing that clings to the glass tenaciously and refuses to let go . it even have yeast in the bottle which i found out on the last pour of my bomber . so really proper looking for an imperial ipa and the color of a tripel . i 'm giving this a 5 ! its a beautiful beer smell : this a very hoppy beer .  mouthfeel : a little slick , thinner on the palate than i expected drinkability : a fine porter , would definitely drink again .

very grassy on the nose with a touch of pine and skunk . also a bit of a musty smell , and a hint of smoky sweet malts .  drinking it in a pint glass poured from a 12 oz bottle ... huge , thick head . awesome . beer is opaque and black .  m : medium to light bodied . feels a touch watery .

aroma is of sweet malt , grain and corn , some tart sugar notes like an apricot .  appearance - pours dark enough to block out all light . a big bubbled mocha head springs up and i have to quell the pour a bit to calm things down . it caps off and forms a nice creamy cover with large spacious bubbles of foam below it .  mouthfeel : medium body , a bit chalky , tingly carbonation and a dry finish .

faint clean scent the malty base swiftly gives way to a spicy resin that lingers so long you can get lost in its subtle piney suggestions of cinnamon and nutmeg .  pours a ruby brown with a creamy beige head . excellent lacing and retention .  m - medium body , with moderate to high carbonation . a bit too carbonated for my liking . slightly thin , would like a bigger body from a stout . the mouthfeel is lacking , and sweet flavors of vanilla and chocolate make it too much like a dessert beer , one is all you need .

smell : it has the smell of wet low acidity hops , slight earthy/barnyard and almost a hint of malt . mouthfeel : balanced with a smooth medium body , medium carbonation and a nice nip on the tip of the tongue .  appearance - pours with a nice , clear golden head , some dark reddish hues provide a little tint . two fingers of whity rocky head with a crusty top and lots of good stick .  mouthfeel is a bit thin and resinous , this is really the only fault i can find .

nose is roasty coffee , caramel , roast chocolate , herbal hop , and fruity , spicy and nutty yeast products . crazy . the first thing that hits me is fruit bouquet , then herbal hop ushers in phenols . good if you do n't think of it as stout .  say what you will about guinness ; yes , i know they 're a bunch of gimmick happy corporate whores , but one thing is undeniable ... there is no other beer on the planet , that looks , smells , or tastes , like a guinness on tap . the cascading effect is awesome . for the first third of the glass it leaves a solid wall of lace all the way around without a break in it . held to the light it 's surprisingly clear and reveals a fiery red hue .  for the mouthfeel , i found this stout almost watery in consistency .

s - kind of muted actually . maybe some slight dark fruits and touches of rum soaked bread .  big firm plush head , one of the most impressive i have ever seen . opaque black hue as expected .  m : full bodied and creamy , the slightest touch of carbonation and a smooth , somewhat watery finish .

s : toasted bread and grain , not as much caramel as the appearance might suggest , with some faint tangerine citrus occasionally emerging .  a - pours nice black and huge heavy sticky head .  do not know if this was an aberation , but this caused a lower score in mouthfeel .

buttery , pure milk chocolate sweetness hits the nose at first , then is ceded by notes of carob and suggestions of chocolate covered candied orange peel along with coffeeish , borderline burnt roasted barley . real chocolate never wavers in aroma , remaining constant and assertive .  solid finger of brown , almost black head . incredibly dark body with nice lace . darkest head i 've seen .  i 've always liked this beer , and if they beefed up the abv and gave it a little more body , it would be the perfect porter . why grant 's beers share these characteristics i do n't know , but if they ever did beef 'em up a little , they could truly be a contender .
the smell was a bit bitter -- -the only part i did n't like too much . i was very pleasantly surprised .  dark brown pour with a solid tan head .  mouthfeel is rather thin and average .

aroma of burnt toffee - more like a brown ale to me . very tasty , hop flavor mixes well with the roasty , chewy grains . no yeast trub in this bottle .  a : what a great looking stout . deep brown color with an extremly silkey 1/2 '' head that slowly disipates into lacing s : roasted malt t : grain sweet ness and roasted malts m & d : mouth feel was medium and dry .  seems a bit thin , with very soft carbonation .

all are very light scents .  this one pours a dark muddy brown that shows some ruby highlights when held to light . the beer is topped by a nice frothy khaki head that lasts and leaves beautiful lacing .  m : thinner than i expected , pretty fair amount of carbonation , once again a little more reminiscent of a porter than a stout .

murphy 's stout on tap is one of my favorite dry irish stouts . this style of beer does not have much of a smell , but the taste is wonderfully sharp and smooth at the same time . murphy 's is perhaps a bit less bitter than guinness , but they are close . the mouthfeel is very smooth , and i personally find this to be an extremely drinkable beer , and i am happy to drink it all night .  great pour , huge amount of foam , thins out to lace the outer edge of the beer . dark brown in color , yet the beer itself is light , meaning not as thick as you would expect it .  body is a little thin .

smell is nearly non-existent with some dark maltiness . easily the best dunkel i 've ever had .  a - a mildly assertive pour yields a bubbly two-finger head with decent retention and frothy lacing down the glass . really a nice looking beer .  it was pretty smooth for stout and for for the alcohol content . i tried it with a few other beers .

very simply , appearance-wise , this beer is not markedly impressive - with its stillness and particular redness it could easily be mistaken for a glass of pinot or cabernet . accordingly , the nose ( what little manages to announce itself ) is wholly dominated by obvious wine-like grape notes and supple/elegant tannins ; there might be a spicy undertone ( nutmeg ? however , once we have moved beyond these categories , this beer is radiant . the feel is gently carbonated , extremely dense and somewhat ideal .  pours a glorious deep , garnet-tinged amber color , with a thick , creamy , sticky , cream-colored head on top .  trying to think of a sweet red wine , not one i can place , but its defintely tannic , bitter and sweet ... the taste is super interesting , not say its good , but interesting . chocolate wine comes to mine , light feel though . what i do know is that 8 months is too long as it totally changes the beer into something new losing almost all stout character .

the smell is malty , very mild . mouthfeel is thick , rich , almost creamy .  appearance : cloudy golden yellow with an amazing , big , billowy head that last all the way through the beer , incredible lacing too which sticks all over the glass . the best looking tripel i 've ever seen .  its a bit thicker on the palate than american crap beer , but it 's your basic `` serve cold , swill it down , catch a buzz '' beer for the masses .

pretty bland and not really what i was expecting .  pours to a bright copper color with thick white head that lingers throughout , and slowly diminishes to a white foam cap with excellent lacing .  again , dried dark fruit seems to be the dominating taste , and as it warms , a sweet cherry-like flavor comes in m : at first i found this beer a bit too prickly and highly carbonated for my liking ; i purposely agitated the beer by swirling and enjoyed it a bit more when carbonation was less severe great beer that i would drink anytime i needed a belgian fix .

very raisiny and sweet smelling , yeasty , but not all that inspiring , really ... but the taste - where to begin ?  brillient , copper penny colored pour with a full , thick head of near white froth that retains and laces very nicely . just the way i want my ipa to look .  m - a little thin-bodied and watery and a little low on the carbonation .

this poured a typical pilsener pale yellow with a decent head that quickly subsided , smell is a tad skunky but not terrible . this one makes up for that really quickly in the flavor department , bitter in the initial flavor , finishing with a beautiful aromatic barley malt finish .  presentation : it poured beautifully into an oversized wine glass . coming out of the bottle it was an amber color , but in the glass it turned to a deep , dark maroon .  m - the hops lingered a bit too long and had a metallic feel at times .

smell- figs ! drinkability- deciptively drinkable , i could finish up this bottle in a hurry and then find out that it 's 10 % abv afterward . nice .  appearance this beer is absolutely gorgeous . the body is a dark , orangish-brown and murky with lots of carbonation and had a bountiful , brownish-white head that was full without exploding and pitted well on top of the liquid leaving some awesome , shaving cream foam around the edges of my pint glass .  mouthfeel is a little too tingly for me with the carbonation .

definitely a good looking beer , but the last one i tried from hoppy brewing looked good but tasted pretty bad . not a very strong aroma ... what is there is the typical winter warmer spice bouquet . very good , certainly a step up from the weak aroma . i really like the creamy mouthfeel ... just a hint of bitter aftertaste leaves it a mark or so down .  22oz bottle ... a : a deep very dark ruby colored with a huge 2+ inch tan head that fades at a decent pace .  it was an average imperial stout with a thin mouthfeel made exciting with some fruit .

the nose is incredible as it is with many of de dolle beers . big floral esters , mint , lemon , sweet malts and subtle but detectable hops . amazing brew , perfect for summertime , actually this is drinkable anytime ... beware of the burps !  the appearance is truly exceptional . rediculously dark . not even allowing for the amber edges that many stouts boast when backlit , this one is impenetrable to light . a gorgeous head that ranges in color between milk and dark chocolate .  a bit thin , but a very good stout flavor develops in the mouth . i 'd have preferred a bit fuller body .

smell : rather light on the nose despite the big head , just a hint of citrus and maybe a bit of fresh cut grass taste : very light malt that reminds me of cereal and almonds ( just a hint ) and a nice solid refreshing lemon zest hop finish . kick ass lawnmower beer . very good stuff , it 's superb drinkability and the genuinely good ( not superb ) flavor .  2011 batch 1 - 750ml bottle poured into a cbs snifter a : black as night . gorgeous finger-and-a-half dark brown head that leaves a nice full cap throughout consumption .  m - fairly zesty and zingy carbonation that left me feeling a touch bloated after a third of a glass . medium-light body that also has a bit of grain character .

this is the worst nose on an ipa i 've ever encountered . sweet malts dominate .  a : beautiful head about 2 fingers thick that never goes below a half finger thick , ever . golden/amber in color , looks like honey . honestly , one of the best looking ipas ever .  the mouthfeel is a little lacking in carbonation too .

smell : so wonderful ... the smoky peaty aroma fills the nostrils . cloying . i really did n't care for the sweetness of this beer .  this beer pours an inky black with a dark brown head .  like drinking sour grass , probably the best way to put it m - low carbonation , slightly astringent d - not very drinakble , i had to leave a third of it

i am a hophead and i might as well have ordered a lite beer . no hoppiness at all- very bitter and a poor lingering aftertaste .  a : black on top , fades to reddish/brown at the bottom when held up to the light . nice lacing . a real gem .  mouthfeel is not too bad , sharpness coming more from the carbonation than hops .

smell : malt scent with some clear citrus and spice also . taste : malty taste with a slight hop bite .  a 1/2 '' medium brown head takes a very long time to fade to a thick film . lacing is impressive , lots of thick , clingy curtains stick around for a while and eventually fade to thin strings that were still there when i went to wash the glass off .  out of all of the blueberry beers i have had i would have to say this is probably my favorite . very fruity with a somewhat dry finish to it . the blueberries are definitely the star of the show . overall this is a very drinkable beer and makes a great summer brew .

some rich roasted malt aroma is prevalent if you can get past that head that acts like a aroma seal .  found this one at julios randomly ... a : awesome look .  mouthfeel was medium with a bite in front and back and made the roof of my mouth tickle ( odd ) .

smells not so much and like ripe guava ( combination of the hoppy cirtus and sweet frutiness ?  it poured a beautiful copper color with lots of bubbles coming up from the bottom of my beer-clean glass . the beer had abundant head that agressively stuck to the side of my glass and slowly and inconsistently faded , starting from the middle of my glass . this beer really was quite attractive .  i can feel it in my cheeks . it does n't have any off aromas specifically , but it definitely has the acidity for it . undrinkable , i 'm pouring it out .

really quite pale - barely gold . mild grainy aroma with a mild yeast quality . drinking while cold i think kept off any excessive taste from adjuncts .  it has a deep , copper/mahogany color with stunning clarity and a beautiful head . such a nice looking brew !  m : carbonation is a little weak ( especially since i poured moderately , and received an aggressive head ) leaving a mouthfeel thatis not strong enough for me to consider it cask-like . a little watery ... d : all things considered , i really enjoyed this beer .

it had a faint grassy , hoppy smell . the initial taste was some bitterness with a touch of citrus .  this beer is beautiful . red/amber color with a thick rocky head that clings to the side of the glass . head disappears fast though .  the mouthfeel is larger light with a very , very slight fizz .

overall its tough to accurately rate this beer as there is no aroma but no aroma is expected given the hops .  yeti pours out like the darkest of used motor oils , thick and smooth with a monstrous billowing head that never goes away .  the mouthfeel was medium bodied with adequate carbonation .

smell is very faint - a little bit of strawberry , and not much else . the taste , however , is just fantastic . the wheat beer flavor is at the forefront , but the strawberry smooths it out wonderfully .  it settles slowly in a dramatically lumpy fashion leaving a tremendous amount of chunky and webby lace .  it goes down smooth .

smell was zesty , definite hints of citrus and wheat .  the beer pours a nice 2-3 finger beige head with great retention and a lot of beautiful lacing on the glass .  best as it warmed , when the malt flavors of chocolale and toffee become a bit more complex and the mouthfeel seems fuller .

not a bad smell , quite malty at first but there was enough hop aroma to keep it interesting . the was great - full bodied , very malty , but bitter enough to achieve a balance .  a : pours a dark black with a massively thick mocha head that seems to last forever ... excellent lacing throughout .  the only fault is that its a little thin bodied but that 's what makes this brew dangerous .

smell : there is some notable hops ( not overwhelming ) and not much else . taste : the taste is quite curious , as i sipped away it at first tasted like a mild ale and about halfway through the bitterness asserted itself like a pale ale .  reviewed 1/8/2008 ( bottle ) : pours a golden somewhat cloudy yellowish color . big foamy frothy white head with good lacing .  this beer poured nicely with a creamy white head , giving off nice citrus aromas . the flavor was shocking , however , reminding me of kool-aid orange flavor , and with almost as much sweetness . i could n't distinguish any hop bitterness , though it could have used some to balance out the excessive sweetness . this beer tastes as though all the yeast were filtered out , and then orange kool-aid added post-fermentation

s - if you like coffee , this is actually really nice . great roasted coffee and espresso aromas , along with a little unsweetened cocoa and vanilla .  looks really good- reddish amber body , nice pock-marked cream-white head , and active carbonation .  m - moderate carbonation , medium bodied .

the smell was a very solid , but not incredibly inviting cocoa presence . the mouthfeel was incredibly lucious and creamy , just like a porter should be .  lovely looking beer , and very similar in appearance to the classic guinness look , with a large creamy tan head on top of a dark body .  the mouthfeel was medium with a syrupy sweetness on the palate .

absolutly no head during the pour , only around the sides smell seems to be weak but the taste packs a punch .  nice white , foamy head with great retention .  medium bodied , it seems a little flat at the beginning , but there 's sharp carbonation at the finish , which is a little watery and silty .

appearance : too foggy smell : smelled like rotten flesh when it was in the bottle , but better out of the bottle taste is good .  this beer is excellent , from the moment you open it till the las drop i have tried this beer on tap as well and it is good , the 22 ounce bottle for some reason does not taste the same in my opinion as its 12 ounce brother .  mouthfeel is pretty typical , and if anything is a little undercarbonated or slick .

pours a 2 '' tan head and looks a standard coffee brown in the glass . flavor itself was pretty mild but what is cool with this beer is it has the flavor and feel of drinking a mild mocha malt . i found it thoroughly satisfying like a kid at a malt shop slowly draining his glass .  bottled in feb. 2009 , batch # 9 ... appearance : pours a very pretty deep orange , copper ; very clear with tiny bubbles and a huge sticky white head . this is a great looking beer !  the expected lactose or creaminess is absent in the flavor as well as the mouth feel given that this is a milk stout . the carbonation , again , is more soda-like in the mouth instead of frothy or creamy . the drinkability and mouthfeel improved with time as the intensely carbonated head withered away .

aroma is quite subdued , even at a relatively warm temperature the overall aroma feels lacking in complexity and strength of character .  the appearance made it look superbly delicious .  the mouthfeel is a bit too light for my liking .

s- not the strongest of aromas , hard to pick up . i get some pine/citrus hops and belgian yeast spice .  first i have to say the appearance is exceptional . the red color is as someone said very similiar to the color of the label .  pretty average mouthfeel overall .

s : the aroma is of dark and tart fruit , caramelized malts , a good amount of hops and some alcohol . altogether , it kind of smells like cough syrup .  this beer looks amazing in the glass . extremely rich orangish-copper hue .  the body was light and there was not enough carbonation .

nice aroma , blend between surprising coffee nodes and bread and toffee blend . not huge and not too complex , but nice and balanced .  appearance- 3/4 inch full dirty brown head . dark brown , maybe and off black colored pour . full length lacing sheets plaster the glass . lovely sight .  long , super bitter piney bitterness , aftertaste almost of pine-sol but i love the hop attack . problem is that it 's too sweet and slightly syrupy , especially evident in the middle . a little harsh and unbalanced overall , big beer and it shows .

smell is weak , thankfully the taste is not .  pours black with a dark brown creamy head . very nice beer to look at .  in the glass , the elderberry dominates . the taste just off , sour in a nasty way , more like rotten fruit than any sort of pleasant tartness which might be expected from the berries . we gave this a decent try to see if it would get better , but in the end just could n't drink it .

looks great , clear burnt orange/ harvest orange color that has hints of brown . smells has some vague fruity esters , lemons , a hint of pepper , almost a hint of tea leaves . upon re-drinking i can gladly up the score a bit but still feel there are better saisons out there .  this beer looks perfect . theres not as much smell to this one as others like it .  mouthfeel - a bit too carbonated which overrides the wonderful taste at first .

s - not much to it ; sweet , molasses , and a subtle hop character . t - delicious !  reviewed 11/16/2008 ( tap @ the stables , st. louis , mo ) : very cool presentation in a kasteel glass with a castle on the stem of the goblet-like glass . pours a very dark blood red body , with a lasting frothy pink head .  4.5/5 m : crisp , medium body .

it went down very smooth and i enjoyed it . however i was expecting more taste , the bottle says brewed with imported hops but to tell you the truth this beer tasted very similar to the less pricey michelob golden draft light sold here in minnesota .  this one pours a beautiful orange copper color with 3/4 '' off-white head .  picked up a few of these `` oil cans '' at a local liquor mart . this is the only place i 've seen them . i like the regular fosters occasionally , and have fond memories of it from various parties and times in life . after looking at the color , noticed that the can said `` caramel coloring added , '' so nothing real to go by there . i liked this , i guess , but the drinkablility was hampered by a fakey sort of bitterness that did n't hold a candle to the fuller 's and young 's of the world . kind of caught in my throat . i pick up the regular if it 's on special , but for a real bitter , this ai n't it .

as for the odor , maybe my sense of smell was n't at its best , but i did n't detect much of a scent . the taste was very smooth , not nearly as bitter as one would expect from an esb , with a hint of caramel .  liquid is a dark amber topped with a thick finger of brown foam and dense and substantial lacing . carbonation is also very prevalent , making this model stand out much more than previous years . visually stunning .  m - lots of carbonation maybe bordering on too much .

some sweetish caramel malt . not much else in the nose but what 's there is tasty . overall it is very good .  simply beautiful cascading action that lasts for over a minute ! superb tan head retention that is not going away at all !  mouthfeel : medium and semi-smooth . bottom line : this is one of the most bland beers i 've ever had .

s- dull smelling dry hops , wheat malt . well balanced with bitter dry hop nose , complex wheat malt finish . the nose lacks however .  the body of hop head poured an absolutly beautiful copper-orange color , with a sizable custard head . retention and lacing were both excellent , thanks to a constant supply of carbonation from below .  the palate is thinner than expected but not bad .

no faults here ... s : citrus , roasted malt , cocoa , and chocolate malt . all very light aromas . t : acidic darker and roasted malt , the same cocoa as detected in the smell is present here as well .  the head is big , small bubbles below , big ones in the middle and a nice cream dome on top .  s- smoky wood and scotch , one of the more interesting noses on this beer t- malts , with some nice roasted flavors that come through and then a hit of alcohol m- lighter bodied than expected d- a very interesting and drinkable beer , but one i need to be in the mood for

a bit light on the nose . pleasant and fresh , but not ultra complex .  it 's one of the prettiest beers i 've ever seen ! deep , dark brown with a hint of ruby when held up to strong light . a tan frothy and foamy lasts and lasts , leaving waves of sticky lace on the side of the glass ( artful ) .  an amazing brew . medium strength carbonation with a wonderful complex flavor of hops barley and corn . somewhat similar to pbr , but upper canada has an after taste that pbt ca n't compare with . usually i do n't care for beers to have much of an after taste , but with this brew it 's all good . i would recommend this beer to anyone who can get their hand on it .

smell : i personally do n't smell much with this ... a little bit of chocolate and hazelnut .  this beer pours a semi-cloudy pale orange color . the head is an impressive two and a half inches in height , and recedes very slowly into thick , chunky lacing .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied with low carbonation and is a bit watery .

the nose let 's you know this has a good bit of hops . the taste starts off smooth and malty , then the hops kick in and then more creamy goodness finishes this refreshing beer .  a very nice brew that started with an absolutely great black color with an outstanding head and lacing .  it was creamy with an average carbonation level and also average alcoholic strength ( 6.0 % abv ) . overall : awful .

smell is a little off out of the bottle - a bit glassy , but the mouthfeel and drinkability are high .  looks great ! great color , small head .  mouthfeel is a bit too thin , especially in view of the heavenly head and ample lacing .

s - there is n't much of a very strong aroma with this beer , but what is there is hints of caramel , lemon , and pine . d - flirts with being sessionable , but is more of a `` couple pints is good '' deal imho . overall - a very solid pnw ipa . pretty tough to beat for $ 4 a bomber . if you 're in the mood for a decent ipa , this one will deliver .  looks like a perfect ris : pitch black with barely no brown around the edges , even when held up to a bright light . an incredibly creamy , frothy and sticky dark khaki head forms and sticks around for quite a bit . impeccable .  mouthfeel is a bit thin for my liking .

-- horrible ) . beer does not have much of a smell to it . maybe a mild roast , some malt , not much at all . beer is super smooth , beautiful full bodied beer . for some reason the first time i ordered it i expected some smoke but was pleasantly surprised by the lack of it .  pours deep burgundy/ with 3 fingers+ of sand/tan colored head . superior lacing & head retention s : chocolate & coffee ( ?  sweet caramel and an herbal bitterness m- clean , but a bit watery with mediocre carbonation d- i do like to drink this beer every now and then .

poured a nice caramel reddish hue with a light white/grey head with miniscule bubbles around the edge and on the head smells like dough and sweet malt tasted very similar to aroma , sweet malt , doughy yeast and a very faint fruit hop flavor .  a rich gold hue with white one-finger head , laces astonishingly well . looks like a good beer .  m - not as thick as i 'd like it to taste considering how rich the smell is . d - very drinkable , with the lighter mouthfeel it 's easier to forget how much you 've had .

a-golden in color , completely translucent in clarity , about a fingers worth of white head n-not really what i was expecting at all , the nose is more grass and citrus than any funk , some hints of oak and white wine but nothing crazy t-the funk is a little more pronounced , flavor actually reminds me of squatter 's fifth element , there is light green apple , grape , and malt m-light and refreshing with an almost champagne about of carbonation d-not as memorable as the first time i had it , but still a notable american sour , as i noted in the taste , this beer reminds me a lot of squatter 's fifth element , would like to see some age and additional sourness on this  opaque black chocolate under a tall creamy mocha head .  the only downside of this beer was the mouthfeel , which was fairly flat and watery , probably due in part to the low % abv .

s : ho-hum aroma , even as it nears room temperature . ends flowery and just a little soapy . ) compared to the bracingly hoppy ipas 'round these parts , but i do n't mind .  the beer looks really good with a thick brown creamy head , tons of lacing , and a very nice head that lasts and lasts .  m : light to medium bodied and highly carbonated .

light whiffs of fruit sweetness and sprinkles of hop . very bad stoned !  pours out a lowly brown and sits a dark crimson-orange in the glass with a large off-white head , great lacings up and down , excellent head retention . sharp as a tack and bright as the sun ; looks great in a tuliped glass ( what does n't ?  m. a little too sticky , it feels syrupy , but without a sweeter taste it fells a little off .
the smell is hoppy and a little of for some reason .  2006 appearance , great head and retention . easy to create head .  very basic but very good m= average carbonation and average weight .

this beer has the most incredible smell in the world . '' the big wafts of vanilla , caramel , and butterscotch fill the nose and is absolutely delectable . i could enjoy the aroma of this beer for hours . one bomber was enough for me , and i was pleasantly surprised .  l : never seen such a perfect look ; two fingers , lasting foam ; s : pear , citrus , smells like the corsendonk agnus , but with a bit of caramel and celery ; t : as an agnus-addict this taste was a little disappointment ; good , but no more than that ; a bit too sweet and too short of hops/bitterness to complete the taste .  m : finish stays around for quite a while , almost too long , really coats the mouth .

the aroma has some piney hops and faint tropical notes , but it 's not too convincing .  this brew poured a medium head of fine bubbles and left behind a nice lacing as it receded . it has a dark cloudy red brown body and a malty aroma .  m : mouthfeel is a bit thin , considering how robust the initial flavor is .

s - light roasted malts with little pecan , not impressed with the aroma . o - this is a solid brew , i would n't drink more than one personally but a great night cap , prime time would be cool evenings with a maduro .  a very appealing looking brew .  if you closed your eyes and smelled this you would think your smelling a good octoberfest beer due to the scent of carmalized malt and faint hops . has a carmel toasted nut flavor on the tounge and finished dry . i like the fact that this irish red is a little more bitter than most red ales but still not overpowering . tongiht i will be reviewing 4 of hook and ladder beers as i bought a gift pack that came with 3 bottles of 4 different beers . the beers i got were backdraft brown golden ale pipe and drum irish red ember amber ( a type of black and tan made with their backdraft brown ale and golden ale ) . try these beers if u can find them they are good

lots of yeast sediment in the bottle . smell - not much just a little bit of citrusy hops , candy , a bit of alcohol , and a bit of sweet caramel malt . smells of cascade hops . taste - starts out with a sweet caramel malt taste , followed by some grassy and earthy hops , a bit of citrus twang mostly as graperfuit and then the bitterness .  have had this a couple times at churchkey and paradiso in dc & gt ; a : a very sudsy pub cask like look to this one with sticky lacing , a beautiful finger of fluffy head and a darker orange body . great start .  definitely a little too carbonated for my taste - the mouthfeel was a little too creamy , masking the flavor .

the beer smells like fresh paint .  appearance : dark black color , with big chocolate brown head , medium carb smell : chocolate , with malts , and some wood taste : bitter dark chocolate , coffee , alcohol , and roasted malt mouthfeel : dry , slightly bitter , rich full body drinkability : a drinkable imperial stout , the high abv is moderately masked .  smell is cocoa , touch of coffee , licorice , slight vanilla , a whiff of smoke . taste is thick creamy , dark and bakers chocolate , touch of espresso , end is dry and slightly bitter , a woody aftertaste .

the smell : hints of caramel and raisins with some citrus , faintly in the background .  a : this pours an entirely transluscent orange color with red hues and a finger and a half of slightly off-white head that laces better than any beer i have ever seen .  m- the weakness of the beer - moderately light body feels a little weak to me . light carbonation does n't add much .

nose is slightly malty . flavor is dark fruit and some alcohol burn .  this is one great looking brew ... . both big and small bubbles and what appears to be a layer a grease on the head .  body was medium with med/high carbonation and a dry finish .

a nice , cloudy copper with a light ring of a head very faint floral hops on the nose initial biting hops , with a light malt backbone . good hop belches afterward very drinkable , one of the best squatters had to offer  this beer has probably the best head i 've ever seen on a saison . saison de lente pours a massive 3 finger white head that has almost a pancake batter like consistency . the head retention is fantastic . the lacing is just magical . a thick french lacing accompanies the glass even when then the glass is empty .  mouthfeel : i 'm a bit disappointed by the mouthfeel .

this was my first experience with an arcadia ale and i most likely will never try their beer again if i have to pay for it . smell : harsh up front , but sweet and hoppy at the end .  gorgeous , classy looking beer .  mouthfeel , i would like it have been a bit more carbonated , but it did fine .

s : chocolaty , coffee , roasted malt , maybe some caramel tones . the appearance and smell had me so excited for the taste , only to be let down by a watery drink .  pours a deep copper color with a big creamy tan head that lasts forever and leaves a great looking lace all the way down the sides of the glass .  magic hat usually disappoints me , not that their brews are n't good , it 's that some of them just are n't tasty- till now . magic hats roxy rolles is right up there with ithaca 's cascazilla and troegs hopback amber . a definite seasonal must have for me . great ! ! !

faint malty bock smell .  the classic appearance is the widget induced/nitro-draft style , which produces a paler , more uniform head with typical nitro bubbles ( tighter ) . it was almost foamy and left a nice lacing on the glass from the four pulls i took . this is what a stout beer should look like , imho . perfect . the dark , almost black , appearance of the guinness is beautiful .  under carbonated .

smell was a little light but developed after taste was introduced . if agitated there is a burst of floral smell tasted good .  pours hazy copper amber color with a very nice dense 2 finger off white head with fantastic retention , that reduces to a thick lacing cap that lasts till the end of the glass . some fairly nice glass lacing is present around the entire glass .  this one is a bit light and watery but does have a decent taste .

a = pours a nice copper color with a 1/2 '' white head s = smells slightly hoppy with citrus undertones t = very much a citrus taste with slight clove undertones .  poured a gorgeous amber pink , with a thick white fluffy head . plenty of lacing .  the mouthfeel is a bit overcarbonated for the stle but not bad .

strong malty smell , along with some dark fruits soaked in alcohol ... cherries or plums .  bottle from the lcbo the 2008 vintage has held its own agaist the 2007. black with a lovely tan head .  this is the least impressive quad from the trappist breweries ... do n't get me wrong , it has a similar taste profile , although not that perfect as a westy 12 or a rochefort 10 , dark fruit , plums , candy sugar , but i did n't like the mouthfeel on this one . too much sparkling going on ... pretty funny thing is i just absolutely endlessly adore the la trappe quadrupel oak aged batch 1 version ... so so so much better then the regular one , especially when the oak aged version , bottled this summer , is coming around fantastic ! i like their dubbel more too .

little uninspiring .  looks nearly black with about a 3/8 '' caramel colored head from a vigorous pour .  it smells of rotten banana peels , rotten apples , and molding compost . the flavors are very sweet and kind of medicinal . it leaves a clove laiden aftertaste behind , making you think you just had an artificial banana milkshake . i just do n't understand what two brothers was going for on this one .

the aroma is a little understated . there are hints of roasted chocolate and coffee . i was hoping for a bit bigger nose though . flavor is full of roasty chocolate and coffee just like the nose . it is very smooth and very drinkable .  opague black extremely heavy coffee colored heading . that leaves excellent lacing and keeps a nice collar all the way down to the last gulp .  m - somewhat lacking in mouthfeel .

the nose is subtle , but has a little bit of winter spice .  crystal clear straw hue with a two finger dense and frothy head that slowly settles to a thick cap , leaving a solid wall of lacing in its place .  nothing to write home about when it comes to mouthfeel . kind of a club-soda feel to the beer , tingly . though there seems to be a strange `` romanian roulette '' effect where every sixth beer is kinda soapy .

s : notes of bubblegum , a bit of pepper , and a hint of orange , very faint smelling beer . t : starts out like it smells with a bit of a sweet bubblegum flavor with a bit of a sharp pepper but then does a 180 and has a bit of a dry/bitter hop taste , it 's not too strong but it 's definitely there .  i also love the brownish patina imparted to the deep red colour as it sits in a chalice .  i can see why the word peat was used before in a review the mouthfeel was medium to light i will agree it needs some more body to it this is a good brew and with a little tweaking it could become world class .

s-not much going on in the nose . mostly some caramel and malt , with a faint hoppiness . t-very similar to the nose with some caramel and perfect balance between hops and malt . d-for me this is extremely drinkable .  honestly one of the most impressive looking ipa 's i 've encountered .  shockingly light carbonation feel . i think the mouthfeel is off from what it should be .

smell is minimal ( beer could have been too cold at first ) taste is nice and malty that grows as it gets a bit warmer .  pours from the bottle to a reddish orange with medium off-white head that lingers , and excellent lacing .  i feel that it felt a little light on the tongue after it went down .

the aroma is average . it has a weird black malt scent that is a bit tart smelling .  a : pours to a frothey tan head with a deep and beautiful copper body . excellent lacing .  the mouthfeel is a little on the thin and watery side though .

surprisingly malty aroma from the fresh pour . hop aromas are very muted , particularly for the style . while appealing , this does n't produce the tradition ipa smell . like the smell , more malty than the style suggests , but it is still delicious .  pours dark black - thick brown foam , long retention and heavy lacing .  come and drink this corn syrup !

this beer is faintly ripe with doppelbock scents of caramel , mixed dark and roasted malt , heated figs , and an end hint of port wine . smell is the weak point of maximator , but only because all its components are so weakly displayed .  a : moderate pour yields 1.25 fingers dense tan head with superb retention . a beauty .  cake/nutty malt up front with a huge , thick spiced tea hop flavor headbutt with the swallow . not just season 's best , but saranac 's best . i usually find them to be just an average brewery but this stuff is nice .

s - muted floral notes , a certain meaty quality , and some of the malt is coming out in the nose - hints of nut and bread .  the appearance was quite impressive .  m - decent body with a bit more carbonation than i 'd like from this style .

5.0 s : not the nose i would have expected . not as much *roastiness* in the nose as i would expected . definitely some sweet malts and maybe a tough of dry hops . 3.0 t : dry . this is incredibly drinkable .  my bottle looks different than the picture ; guess they changed the label . appearance : clear light amber with a big frothy head of light tan .  mouthfeel : hoppy and rough , but a bit fuzzy .
aroma of malted grains , hops , very nutty and sort of citrusy .  a - poured a completely black with a gigantic 3 finger head .  malty and corny .
