this beer is great , it is really drinkable and similiar to a beer i love by dogfish head. , it pours brown ( obv ) and isnt too thick though , which makes it nice and drinkable . nice caramelly roasted malts and color , try this one if you are into nut browns or similair types .  this one gushed out an extremely creamy , frothy off-white head with a suprisingly long and stable retention . the bottom was also very appealing , golden orange-yellow hue that was opaque and reflective .  m -- slightly too watery , does n't really coat the mouth like i would hope but it washes down clean with no bad lingering tastes d -- this is it here , i think this is the beer i would use to introduce someone new to ipa 's .

hazy and color brings to mind pineapple juice . carbonation factor is high.get some funk in the aroma , not overpowering .  appearance : pours a motor oil black with a 1 finger creamy milk chocolate brown head . excellent lacing . like all the other yetis , this one looks perfect .  this is a very good pumpkin beer . picked a 6 pack up at the local market , came home on a chilly night here in rural mi , and my girlfriend and i finished the whole six pack . lots of pumpkin taste , beautiful color , and an overall great seasonal choice . i would n't drink it in warm weather , but on this cool fall night , it hit the spot . i could see picking this up in the future to bring to a bon fire , or to enjoy while i hand out candy on halloween . cheers !

the smell was slightly chocolate . 2007 bottle 02/23/2008 beautiful smell like gourmet chocolates , an amazing improvement over the last year . this beer is a really good example of a cellar-worthy beer . 2006 vintage 01/10/09 smells malty grains , some chocolate , tastes good and probably ca n't get much better .  drank on-tap at atwood 's tavern , cambridge , ma served in a stemmed glass gorgeous appearance . thick , lasting rings of lacing coated the glass .  mouthfeel : tingly and not quite substantial enough . seems to be the only point where this beer loses some ground .

the smell is very mild with a bit of toasted bready malt coming through . while the smell was a bit small the flavor is the opposite , very big . huge fruity malts up front with a bit of sweet apricots and a touch of raisins , toasted malt and bread qualities linger as a strong juniper and grapefruit bitterness take over and linger on the tongue .  the beer poured beautifully into the glass : a bronze-brownish coloured pint with a thick off white head . the main thing i noticed throughout the duration of the pint was the excellent retention and lacing that the head left .  the taste is also fresh but a with bit of watery mouthfeel .

holy hops . i like me some hops . huge hops and not much else to smell ... maybe a touch of some orange peel or citrus something . i was blasted immediately with the hops from the first taste and on . overall i liked it ... i would n't complain if i drank it again .  poured from a 750ml bottle bottled on november 10 , 2011 into a tulip . a : pitch black with a 1 finger foam head . exactly how a stout should look .  m-its a little undercarbonated but the balance of the sweetness with the malt and subtle hops make for a relitivly complex october beer . d-easy to drink and very nice to have this time of year , easy to session .

s : musky and earth aromas . burnt cherry and very malty . farly nondescript as far as i am concerned . i did not know what to expect , but this is an exceptional beer . though , to fully appreciate this , i need to be more familiar with the style .  a- a perfect golden look in the glass . looks great .  mouthfeel was my only complaint .

smell is of molasses , toasted oat , and french roast coffee . for some reason i detect some alcohol in the nose too , and for a 5.5 % abv i 'm not liking it a whole lot . after the initial appearance and smell , i fell in love with this beer .  a beautiful looking beer with at least a two-finger head that lasts for a while before fading to a nice cap that remains to the end .  perhaps a little watery , fuzzy . quite drinkable but somewhat sweet .

the aromas were very muted . i picked up malt , cask , earth , and some very mild hops .  opaque pitch black , moderate brown head . '' apart from the looks and the aroma : very disappointing .  its sucks to know that in a different format this could be so much more . body and carb is okay , but by this point i 'm already at the meh stage .

a sweet malt . earthy hops , i sense not from dry hopping , but more likely late hops additions . i i had it served from a 12 oz bottle a bit too cold , which undoubtedly muted the aromas and flavors , tending them toward the bitter .  12 oz bottle poured into a snifter - best before oct. 19th 2007 appearance : harsh pouring reveals a generous 2 '' head that lasts quite a long time . the head is tan with tiny bubbles that leaves a bit of lace behind .  flavor is very light malt with a slightly sour pucker at the end . finishes clean with minimal bitterness . overall , this is a very good summer beer . it 's light , refreshing and mild , so it 's a good intro beer for those that are n't into intense beers . however , it has enough of a belgian twist to keep more advanced beer drinkers interested . versatile enough to enjoy one with a meal or multiple at the lake or playing cornhole .

smell : a surprisingly faint aroma , which was somewhat of a turnoff since i love the big malty aroma of doppelbocks .  visually it 's perfect . nice copper color with a fully creamy head .  light carbonation and light-medium bodied . starts as sour apples becomes more sour like lemon juice , dry finish ; easily the least enjoyed belgian i have had . 750ml bottle - gift from vintage cellars blacksburg , va .

aroma is of sour malt with a hint of coffee .  poured from 22oz bottle into `` balloon '' glass the darkest ebony color in the body with a rocky massive foamy/sticky dark tan colored head .  i thought the mouthfeel was a touch watery but the whole packaged seem very much an alluring strong-lawnmower , early evening session beer .

not much of an aroma on this but picked up some slight floral hints and a bit of caramel .  poured a brilliant gold hue with a completely hazed clarity .  mf : relatively light body with medium to high carbonation . would like a little more body , but the flavor more than makes up for it .

this smelled like freshly ground coffee , chocolate , muffins , brownies , and finished with a roasted woodsy character . wow . i want to dip my whole face in this beer .  a : pours a light golden with a couple fingers of dense white head that reduced very slowly into a thick frothy head . beautiful rings/sheets of lacing left with every sip .  mouthfeel lots of fizzy carbonation , lighter bodied , finishes dry . the high carbonation combined with a thinner than usual mouthfeel really did throw off the beer making the flavors less prominent than i feel they could have been had the aforementioned two things been toned down a bit .

s : aroma is of roasted malt , coffee and a hint of bitterness . t : taste of roasted malt , coffee , a bit of sweetness and a nice bitterness through to the finish which is quite dry .  11.2oz bottle poured into a chalice pours a murky , deep brown with a thick , one-finger head that has awesome staying power and leaves rings of lacing down my glass .  an american classic . good fall back beer , or one to enjoy when a less complex brew is desired .

as my first experience with a lambic , i was not sure what to expect from the beer . of course , i knew the facts : brewed in belgium , fermentation occurs when openly exposed to wild bacterium . my first thoughts were as follows : sweet , tangy , yet lacking in the strength of a full-bodied flavor . luke-warm , i discovered the very lack of flavor i had been missing !  think imperial irish dry stout instead of russian imperial stout ... a : bottle opens with a 'gunshot pop '' and pours a dark black with a monstrous 2.5 '' dark tan head . fantastic retention .  mouthfeel is medium bodied with medium to high carbonation .

s : faint scent of roasted malts , chocolate , and coffee . t : a combination of sweet roasted and chocolate malts with hints of coffee .  appearance is flawless . it 's a very dark ruby with a billowing pillow of foam and great lacing .  spicy and yeasty on the finish , this beer is medium-light on the palate with a high level of carbonation , much higher than i care for , really foaming up in my mouth .

smell is nothing exceptional : some obvious coffee and a touch of dark chocolate .  pours into my new belgium globe with very dark brown body that looks almost black in the glass . thick creamy tan head tops the beer and looks stable enough to stick around for the duration .  m : the body is medium and so is the carbonation .

aromas include coffee , some cocoa , and some berries . it 's not highly intense , leaving very little of a mark . overall , this is a highly drinkable , highly refined porter .  ths one poured a dream , you shoulda seen it , looked like a photo from a beer book . billowy head sticking out of the glass all proud and boastful , very cool .  mouthfeel : thin body and medium carbonation overall : a nice geuze , a bit too watery for my liking though .

smells slightly sweet , grassy and floral notes , some fruit maybe ... pleasant enough , but nothing spectacular . nice . this is probably not what a hardcore hophead expects in an ipa .  thought this beer had a really nice color . an excellent color . i 'm thinking mahogony , but i 'm not sure exactly what color that ... but i 'm thinking like a deep deep wood varnish color ... really nice .  m - exceedingly bitter . needs to be a little creamier for this style d - not a session beer .

the smell was delightful . with a hoppy nose and a touch of citris .  pours out like chocolate syrup , fills the glass pitch black with a very dark tan head . billowing foam despite a very cold serving temperature , thick chunks of lace , crazy retention .  mouth feel is sharp and crisp , with a high carbonation level .

served in a ufo hefe glass . t : very good . d : excellent .  nice downward bubbles on pour ... dark brown to black with a slight ruby edge , a tan creamy nitro head , and lace like wallpaper .  i think i 'm a bit parial to this beer for 2 reasons . it 's not by any means a `` specialty '' beer , it 's your typical lager and since it 's been around since before any of us were born it 's got a nostalgic feel . excellent beer in my books , average for most .

pleasant , fairly bright aroma - very fruity . hard to tell where , or if , the amarillo begins . musty , funky brett note .  pours black with off-white/brownish head in one finger thickness that lasts for very long time , generous lacing . perfect .  t- roasty , sweet malts , coffee and dark chocolate m- starts off nice and creamy and full , then towards the middle loses a bit of it 's body and seems to get watery , only to return with a solid finish .

some dms , malt , toffee and something nutty on the nose . flavour - intriguing mix of caramel , toffee , chocolate , nut and something hard to pin down .  ruby and brown shades with decent clarity , a beautiful 1/2 inch head of white foam sits atop with solid retention .  mouthfeel - the one noticeable drawback to this offering is the lack of carbonation . otherwise it felt very good in the mouth .

the aroma is a bit lighter than i 'd expect for a dipa , picking up a grapefruit hop aroma with a strong sweet malt backing , hint of pine .  poured an opaque brown , as expected from a stout , with thick , pillowy tan head and excellent lacing .  this beer has a lot of flavor for a light . too bad its not a good flavor ! nothing impressive at all here . i 'm not sure what they are putting in this beer but its not worth the 7.99 they are charging for a six pack . i would recommend pabst blue ribbion over this any day !

aroma seems a little incomplete , with yeast smells and a touch of leather .  this was poured from the bottle into a consendonk tulip glass . a - clear light golden straw color with a thick foamy , ice cream-like head that is very well retained s - sweet malt and fruity yeast aroma with a slight hop spiciness t - like aroma , sweet malt up front with fruit-like notes and a very slight amount of hops on the finish m - medium body with high carbonation d - this is a decent , well-made beer .  the nose is caramely and very malty . a little too carbinated for a traditional barleywine but lines ones gut like the best of the bunch ! being a sucker for barleywines i have to give this beer high remarks .

not much aroma at all to speak of , which is fairly common among the tripel 's , largely due to the clear candy 's which do n't impart much of a smell . great flavor , a creamy , full body full of a chewy malt and some fruit notes , yet clean with the clear candy .  great retention and lacing .  it 's a black colored beer with ruby edges . fairly nice nose , with a variety of dark fruits , as well as a bit of chocolate and coffee . really nice nose . flavor is fully packed , loaded with dark fruits ( blackberry , plum , cherry and currant ) , as well as some notes of dark chocolate , coffee and a light hint of alcohol . i like it .

very subtle , nothing spectacular . t - light initial wheat flavor that follows with a sweet/citrus aftertaste .  pours a dark , opaque mahogany tone with a solid finger and a half of a beige-colored head . decent retention , good lacing , and a lasting cap .  light bodied though , almost watery . in a way this is an ipa-light - some similar desirable flavors and aromas , but less bitterness , less alcohol , and lighter bodied .

the aroma is slight clove , some bubblegum , but that 's about it . taste is rounded and smooth , with the clovey and bubblegum from the aroma , but also with alcohol warming and candy sugar flavors . medium bodied and drinkable , it 's good but not really a first class beer , and not worth $ 6.29 a bottle ( 22oz , john 's marketplace , portland or ) .  a : a stunning deep brown near black with cranberry highlights . a inch of toasted head comes after a medium pour . the head slowly fades to an impressive 1/3 inch . lacing on a dark beer ?  this review is from notes in my `` travel journal . '' obviously the beer is now `` retired . there is some berry in the attack . the flavor smoothes out to leave a clean finish . it is a very drinkable beer , but not what i normally seek out .

-- slight smell of caramel , even slighter smell of fruit . i had no expectations whatsoever and will definetally try more of this style .  produced a huge rocky head that lasts & lasts and when subsides leaves half its mass on the side of the glass ( i did n't mean for that to rhyme , it just worked out that way . ) the aroma is ok , its floral like perfume but not particularly citrusy or piney or any of those typically american hop descriptors .  the only real flaw for me with this beer is that it 's a bit thin , but that 's a bit nit-picky and did n't detract at all for me from this wonderful beer .

aroma : sweet , grainy wheat accompanied with apple , citrus , and a slight hint of floral hops taste : sharp lemon and apple over a tasty and grainy wheat backbone . drinkability : excellent , as you 'd expect from any wheat beer worth a damn . verdict : saint arnold has created a solid wheat beer , perfect for a summer 's day here in texas .  a brilliant tan head rose quickly to three-fingers and lowered very slowly leaving brilliantly thick patchy lace on the glass .  crisp taste - not heavy as expected ... hints of smokey , woody flavors - has the appeal of a coffee porter ... mouthfeel is average .

good color - darker than i might have expected s - a little sweet .. i dont find this beer to have a pronounced smell of any kind .  nitro-tap , nice pour into a pint glass at henry 's 12th street tavern in portland . color is brownish-black , thick tan head has excellent retention all the way to the end .  mouthfeel can be too fizzy if you do n't make sure to pour high for tall head . when i 'm drinking more than one beer , this is my favorite second or third , as it 's got enough hops to satisfy , is not highly alcoholic , and sells for a real good price where i live .

a - perfectly clear , fresh honey golden color . s - wow . piney citrus . loads of hop aroma . with the nose , i expected a haymaker of hop bitterness , but it was actually fairly subtle to me . m - medium-bodied , nice feel .  a - truly unique looking beer . a black beer almost dark purple looking at times .  dare i say it seems a bit on the thin side . the meatiness in the flavor is not backed up by the body . not bad , but just a little disappointing ... this is a fine stout .

amber brown , with a thin light tan head and a scant malty aroma . full mouth , light chocolate start progressing to caramel with some spice .  captain lawrence st. vincent 's dubbel is a great looking dubbel that tastes pretty good . a : red orange colour and a great 2 cm head that lasts very well . highly carbonated .  feels quite creamy at first , almost in a draft-stout kind of way , which struck me as odd . would rather it be crisper and a bit more carbonated , though .

the aroma is lightly fruity and deeply roasty with some mild bittersweet chocolate , some soft dry tobacco , and stale wet coffee grounds .  the appearance is beautiful . a bit darker than i 'd expect a golden ale to be , but it looked great .  carbonation is ample but the body lacks a little texture .

aroma is soft , but of coarse hops , but for the most part rather clean . medium in body , and smooth .  the bottle popped furiously , and poured with a full head and glowing color .  the body is sufficient to carry the 10 percent alcohol which is impressive by itself . some spicy notes and an effervescent type of feel to it .

s- not getting much smell . brew is a little too cold as it was in my basement . very nice . d- this is a very drinkable beer .  pours a cloudy golden/orange color with a two finger frothy head that has really good retention and leaves lots of sticky lacing .  m : light-medium body with an oily mouthfeel , and a dry and resiny fade overall , not a bad beer , though it does stray from traditional belgian dubbels in a few aspects : not as sweet or yeasty as the classic belgian examples , a little hoppy for the style , and its too light .

smell : roasted , malty scent with a burnt undertone , and hints of coffee .  poured from a 11.6oz brown bottle with a white cap marked `` bottl 2006* 12 % '' into a tulip glass . easily one of the longest lasting , largest frothy heads of foam i have ever seen on any beer . appearance is a rusty yellowish orange color , cloudy and semi-translucent .  m- seems a little thin , but nicely carbonated .

aroma is very soft a little bready malt , and pumpkiny but hard to bring forth . the flavor is nice definately my favorite sam seasonal .  pours the color of any other well crafted imperial stout , pitch black but with an impressive mocha colored inch of foam on top . the head displayed some excellent retention and a creamy layer of bubbles from the cask treatment .  medium-high carbonation .

on its incredibly smart looking clear bottle it even claims to be a bitter ! best compared to the very similar budweiser and millers from the us .  pours an almost transparent golden/light copper with an amazingly fluffy 3 finger head from an extremely gentle pour .  mouthfeel : i 've always thought this was a little off ... not quite enough spine to offset the sweetness .

smell - decent malty pale ale aroma .  pours cloudy yellow orange with thick creamy foam indefatgiable white foam .  this has the syrupy goodness of the 90-minute , but with an added syrupiness ... robust and smooth , like a desert sauce , you could pour this over a bowl of vanilla ice cream instead of a caramel sauce , with its own french vanilla creaminess ... the only thing that detracts here is an odd light metallic twinge at the finish that didnt seem to fit . otherwise , this is a beaut of a big beer with a light profile .

s : dried apple skins , a little banana and some bubble gum on the nose , although even as the beer warms it does not release much aroma . t : on the palate one finds freshly baked bread , some apple and pear , and a bit of spice . its flavor and aroma profile is on the milder side .  biggish , crusty , light tan head leaves lots of hard , sticky lacing . very pretty .  surprisingly light mouthfeel makes it a fairly easy drinker for a 9 % er

s : sweet malty caramel upfront followed by earthy citrus banana with hoppy bitterness on the backend . decent .  650ml bottle poured into tulip july2 2010 a clear deep amber with a massive light beige head that has great retention eventually forming a brain like island leaving plenty of lace all the way down the glass s big grapefruit hops with a fair bit of sweet malt t again loads of hops but with an unexpected mild nutty chocolate a little different but pretty good m slightly sticky with enough carbonation to give it a slightly creamy feel d a 4.25 option would have come in to play once or twice with this one so i drop the 4.5 here , for a strong ale it 's very drinkable and i would drink it again without thinking twice unique beer with no doubt , nice flavors from the hops and lots of malt character .  the mouthfeel was the only thing that detracted from the beer in my opinion , as i found it to be a little to watery for my personal preference .

aroma of caramel , sweet malt , some alcohol , mild nuttiness and not much of a hop component . wow , flavor is suprising given a fairly unassuming aroma . a pretty decent to heavy hop bitterness gives way to a fabulous hop backbone and a floral hop flavor , with slight spiciness and maybe a hint of pepper .  poured into an imperial pint , formed a 1 1/2 '' dense beige head above the slightly cloudy orangey amber brew . head falls way slowly , leaving a tall monolith of froth in the center , and thick coating all down the glass walls .  i 'm not getting much in the way of bitterness anywhere here , which combines with a medium thin body to provide very little in the way of a finish .

bit of smoke in the nose , but overall subdued .  poured a very deep brown with a massive brown head and tons of carbonation .  quite watery for the big flavor this one tastes and smells different from the main stream craft ipas , which is a pretty new category i 'll give it that .

citric , fruity aroma . flavor is dominating by a surpsingly nice fresh , leafy hop flavor throughout the sip , undergirded by amaltiness which starts off sweet and develops a toasty , biscuity character toward the finish .  it is as black as pitch . a nice , pillowy thick 2 finger head formed and stayed for the whole beer .  if you aerate the beer in your mouth , it really releases the co2 . it would do well as a beer to server with medium to strong cheese .

s : smells like roast and acetone ... yup , that 's nail polish . ok , i 'm not very impressed with this beer so far . t : aaaahhh ! d : as long as you hold your nose , this has great drinkability .  served up a breathtaking deep copper amber that is crystal clear . the head is slightly off-white and looks superb with tightly packed , shiny bubbles that stick around forever and leave near perfect lace . if this beer tastes nearly as good as it looks i will be most happy .  very nice m : medium bodied-a bit thicker than i expect from an ipa or a dipa , but it works well with the oaky sweetness of this beer .

smells a little citrusy and and a little wheaty - nothing impressive . a very lemon-like taste that finishes a little bitter and a little like cherries .  pours a deep chestnut brown , with a layer of foamy white goodness on top . laces amazingly . the more beers i try from this brewery the more i realize they sure know how to make a beer look good .  little fruityness . light to medium body , oily , light carbonation . could be a little more carbonated .

light chocolate , clean aroma . one finger dark beige head . big chocolate flavor . reminds me of the hershey 's cocoa powder form .  appearance : this one pours a very dark mohogany with an incredible red hue . great head rentention very frothy .  this is a man 's beer . none of this flowery wine swilling critique lingo . light color , smell and mouth feel , who really cares . outstanding dry & hoppy flavor without sweetness . when bought in the 30 pack , cost is about 50 cents each . the best macro being produced !

i was actually pleasantly surprised by this beer . i acquired it in the winter variety case and finally got to it . very nice red hue to the beer . very carbonated , of course , and more than a hint of cranberry .  the pour is jet black with a nice two finger head on it . the head is a nice mocha color with tiny bubbles holding some of the best retention and lacing i 've ever seen in an impy stout .  too carbonated , the mouthful of liquid seems to almost crumble right away .
i found little to know aroma at all .  head is enormous and really nicely laces . retention is amazing .  m : still a bit watered down , but again , it 's better .

i 'm not up on my tasting formalities , so i 'll forgo the usual format and say this : + extremely malty . not necessarily a bad thing on its own , but in this case it was overwhelmingly , sickly sweet .  appearance : very , very deep clear gold , head on this one is one for the ages , really spectacular . huge , dense , pure white and a bit slick ; looks a bit like whipped egg whites .  m : a lighter body with good carbonation which yields a sensation akin to chewing on a cloud .

s- wheat , citrus , some grass . reminds me a little bit of some freshly baled hay -- sweet . t- very crisp , assertive hop notes that slide easily into citrus .  a : pours a bright light amber with a large dense head that reduced into a delightfully thick dense foam dollop that floated on top of the beer . very active carbonation and fantastic lacing . head stayed forever with very impressive retention .  this was followed up by a sweet , orangish tang on the tongue , followed by a sweet finish , especially in comparison to the berliner wiesse , which i tried earlier . the introduction of the lemon slice to the beer increases the dryness , especially at the finish . a good , summery beer with a name that invokes `` the simpsons . ''

smells of burnt toast , nuts and vodka . fortunately the taste is so very much more than the smell .  great , great look .  mouthfeel too prickly and astringent but medium body is appropriate for style .

not a whole lot of aroma with this one but the sweet , milky , creamy taste more than makes up for it . and this thing is sweet ... .just what you would expect from a sweet milk stout .  a light orange marmalade cropped with a white , creamy top , it looks damn delicious !  a good beer . comes in a .33ml brown bottle , part of a 6 pack sampler from brouwerij van steenberge . a sweet and dark beer , where hops has taken a back seat to the malt profile . not light , but not heavy either . give it a try .

s : as much as i let this warm , the nose really never developed whatsoever . am a bit disappointed ... t : oh wow ; whatever the lack of aroma hid is more than made up for with taste . dirty earthiness adds to the fudge , a gritty/grainy sweetness , accentuated by malted milk balls .  poured a very nice deep copper with fantastic head and nice lacing .  t : wood chips , obviously , tastes like a sauna smells , charcoal , molasses , savory like breakfast sausage , soy sauce , real sharp sweetness that 's broken down by hops lurking in the background and that 's absent at the finish m : medium body , very low carbonation , i 'm surprised this was n't the cask ( it was n't but they did have it ) , dry bitter charcoal finish . the mouthfeel was a big drawback for me , it was very flat , considering this was the draft veraion .

very malty smell . sugary , raisin and malty flavor that mix very smooth .  this beer was a very nice , deep red/brown color , and it had a very nice and thick head .  the carbonation is interesting , but a little too fizzy for me , i feel like this beer has a watery quality to it which i do n't particularly like in a porter . it starts out watery , then the carbonation kicks in .

very bitter citrus smell . sweet to the taste .  a : big creamy tan head , very dark body s : roasted coffee , cherry , chocolate milk t : chocolate , chocolate , chocolate .  drank in a chalice from a bottle in brussels at delirium cafe.. this is very good lambic . it smells great very sweet with cherries . the beer has a beautiful red/brown color with a white head , not a lot lacing . it tastes sweet with cherries dominating but has a nice sour kick too .

nose is mild malt with a hint of floral hops and maybe some citrus .  thanks for the opportunity ... poured into an imperial pint glass , formed a 1/4 '' dark brown ( almost purply black ) head above the opaque black brew . head hangs on , with average lace , which actually is pretty good for the style .  m : smooth on the palate .

smells alright nothing spectacular just a sort of generic beer smell .  poured a dark golden orange to light amber in the glass ... yes , almost the color of the jewel amber . lots of beautiful bubbles in the pour reminding me of a guinness that end up creating a full 2 finger craggy beige head that melts to sticky lace .  mouthfeel is the only real negative to this one , medium bodied and a bit thinner than i 'd like .

aroma is quite light some dark malt and hop but too light and not nearly as aromatic as the bottle . all the key flavors are certainly present with same complexity as bottle-brown , scotch ale & ipa .  black to extremely dark brown in color of the body . huge rocky head that is coffee color .  the colour is a light straw , probably the weakest colour i have seen in a pale lager , the head is very pleasent and has some serious glass cling ... the aroma is very skunky when first opened but quickly disappears and the taste is highly sweet malts on a thin body , very nice for dining , not a stadium brew ... i first reviewed this brew in march of 03 , approx 10 monthes ago .

s : not much in the nose at all . a hint of roasted malts is about it , and that 's faint . not completely unexpected for the style , however . m : creamy , as you 'd expect from a nitro pour , body is on the light side , also about what you 'd expect for this style . easily quaffed . worth checking out .  a : poured a dark clear ( filtered ) chocolatey amber color with a rich white foamy head .  mouthfeel is bubbly crisp and slightly creamy , but overall rather watery .

aroma is malty and estery , nothing to write home about .  poured into a pint glass a : pours very black with a large tan colored head . looks amazing . s : get a slight hop kick up front which gives way to some roasted grain .  carbonation is a little light though .

the smell was really subtle for me and i could n't detect anything more than a slight sweetness like burnt caramel .  pours out very clear straw color with plenty of carbonation and a rich frothy white head that lingers and laces , truly beautiful .  easy drinking but it has a different mouthfeel , it almost leaves a film in my mouth .

the smell is malty with distinct notes of alcohol . not very pleasant . the taste is a little better ; it is very malty with lots of bread-like flavours .  appearance there 's pretty much no flaw to how this beer looks . its a deep , thick black , capped with a super rich , creamy tan head . great retention and solid lacing .  mouthfeel : a bit thin in body but makes up with an even overall texture not much carbonation very wine like with each sip .

light-medium carbonation . medium bodied . starts and finishes sweet this could be mistaken for a belgian . the high abv ( 9 % ) is not really noticeable . pricey - $ 4.50 for a 330ml bottle from wine society tyngsboro , ma .  black color , pitch black .  mouthfeel is a bit thin and watery .

s : honestly , not too much aroma . it definitely tastes better than it smells . pleasing bitterness that is n't ever overbearing , and it sticks on the palate well into the aftertaste . at first the appearance and especially smell were nothing special at all , but it makes up for it with the great taste .  2003 : nice heavy white head tops the cloudy golden hue .  parching on the tongue . almost no flavor : slight sweetness up front , trace of bitterness on finish . really .

aroma was a pleasant roasted malt , but nothing stands out .  this beer looks wonderful . a beautiful mahogany red , cloudy and rich topped with two and a half fingers of rich foam . the beer leaves textbook rings down the glass as you drink it ( rather quickly ) .  on tap this poured as a golden straw colored ale , clear and bright with less than an inch of head . there is an apparent hoppy aroma that followed with a similarly dominant slight-hoppy taste followed by the expected bitters - very tasty . i stopped with one . not to discount its drink-ability , there are just several others i wish to try .

s- light malt and a much more dominate hop aroma . pretty tame overall though .  growler the bruery placentia , ca a clear light golden with a big and thick foaming white head . the head sticks around for quite a while and eventually leaves thick and sticky lacing all down the glass .  lively carbonation is a bit excessive , but the body is quite smooth .

while really good , not as good as aroma . overall : really good . would have liked the flavor to measure up to the aroma but you still ca n't go wrong with this one .  pours an effervescent honey color with3+ fingers of cream colored head . insane lacing & head retention s : grapefruit & lemon , fades a bit as this warms t : follows the nose , plus pineyness , slight breadyness & a touch of leafy hops & dryness hiding behind a ton of grapefruit up front .  the body was a bit too thin for my tastes in this style .

the smell is rather clean with grain upfront , other than traces of floral it is very clean to the nose . the taste is excellent , light bodied , refreshing and crisp .  the humble brown has rarely looked so good .  m- medium body that was slightly under-carbonated . with more carbonation , all the flavors would bite that much more .

this brew poured a very beautiful dark brown color with some nice red flecks . the aroma on this brew has a bit of caramel and some faint malts . not a whole lot of aroma coming from it . as it sits a bit , there is a little bit of a nutty aroma . there is n't much else . though there was a bit of lack in the aroma department , this brew makes up for it in the flavor of the brew . it begins with a wonderful blend pale malts , which is quickly followed with a nice punch of caramel and cocoa . it was exceptionally good . i enjoyed it very much this is a great drink .  pours a truly awesome blood orange reddish tan color with a tan head .  m : the feel is creamy and medium bodied . rather light for a ris and that really detracts from the beer in my opinion . the mouthfeel is lighter than what i come to think of when i thik of a ris .

i had mixed feelings about the noble pils before it even came out , as i had always enjoyed the white ale that sam adams had previously marketed as its spring seasonal . basically , i feel like the white ale should have remained the spring beer offering , whilst this beer should have become a full time staple of the sam adams line-up . great taste , and easy as hell to drink !  head retention was excellent , melting down to a slightly less huge frothy , rocky head . lacing was thick and plentiful ... .a beautiful looking beer .  the nose of the beer is strong and gives off a nice floral hop aroma . the flavor is sweet and semi-tart with fruity tastes . behind the sweet fruit , there is a slight but smooth alcohol presence . the earthy hop bitterness comes in at the end and fades away with the semi-dry finish .

aroma is mild but some chocolate and roasted malt but surprisingly no raspberry really shows up here .  as pretty as beer poured out of a can into a glass can be .  taste/mouthfeel : this beer is slightly oily , with a very limited carbonation .

smells neutral at first , then smells a bit sour . starts a bit sweet then gets tart .  pours beautiful dark brown with red edges , almost black with a huge tan head that sticks around and leaves walls of creamy lace .  m : a light-medium feel to it and kind of syrupy .

the brew is a clear amber , looking a lot like a munich oktoberfest . aroma is mild , with little indication of the beer 's hoppy palate . wisconsin amber has a lot of the drinking characteristics of a pilsner jazzed up with some medium-roasted malts .  pours a fluffy , thick , white , three-fingered head , fades very slowly and leaves gobs of lace .  mouthfeel is ok. fairly light body , more than i 'd think it should be at this abv .

smell is less then expected for a german hefe , little bit of wheat , a little cloves and yeast , no bannana like i was hoping for .  i fricking love the way this beer looks . huge foamy white head , brilliant dark golden color with a cascade of carbonation bubbling up the side .  i sent it back thinking it had gone bad , but the bartender tried it and assured me it was ok. m - average for a macro lager .

the smell is average , its not bad or obtrusive , but there is very little of anything that i could smell , neutral to the most . its fairly simple , but sometimes excellence is in simplicity . very clean finish .  that 's an outstanding looking brew - steady head , chunky like snowfall on fence posts from the beginning , but it melts down a bit to only ring the glass . like deep brown bricks , with hints of orange around the edges - strong looking beer .  mouthfeel- medium body with very little carbonation .

nice . d - i 'm coming to the conclusion that i 'm not a huge fan of hoppy beers . but this is nice . while i ca n't say i 'd like this all the time , i 'd definitely like to revisit it .  appearance- beer pours a wonderful looking amber golden with a thin wispy head one finger high of whipped cream foam . this is about the most perfect appearance i 've seen for a marzen . very impressive from an impressive brewery .  m : medium bodied with not much creaminess or silkiness to talk about .

the smell was a disappointment , as it was hardly even there . i only got a whiff of a little alcohol , malt , and a faint lager-like aroma . the taste , however , makes up for this . a little more complexity would have driven this beer into the upper echelon of great tasting brews , but i thoroughly enjoyed it nonetheless .  this beer was poured a very dark rich chocolate brown with a thin tan head . with this beer being pushed nitrogen , it had a ton of lacing and the head lasted the entire beer .  body is medium , mouthfeel is oily/creamy , carbonation is low but adequate .

not much to say about the aroma . you have to work for it , but when you get the whiff , it 's nice . nutty taste .  excellent head duration to boot , with the dollop of foam in the middle arranged like a hurricane taking shape ; stellar looking beer .  color and mouthfeel are average for the style and fine .

the smell was rather plain , hints of roasted grain and toaste , slight metallic nose , otherwise not much there , the taste however was great , a nice marshmellow smoothness up front followed by a warming dark roasted and coffee flavor with backing of chocolate , goes great with pie and ice cream , highly recommended .  a : pours a deep dark brown that is almost black in appearance .  but it has quite a few pros : this beer is intended to be consumed with food . if you want to have chinese food with a light drink then this one is just what you are looking for ! it 's a typical lager : crystal-clear blonde , discreet taste and weak aroma . i usually do n't drink lager beers but this one i can have by the barrels while there 's food on the table . this beer is what you want to drink when you do n't want to drink !

though , if i had to guess , i would not have picked this out to be a saison . smells of bready malts , with some 'sharp ' somewhat earthy notes , - hard to describe .  pours almost black , with tan 2 finger head .  this is an enjoyable , smooth but tasty strong polish lager . the aroma is fresh , toasty sweet bread , hint of lemon , pine , and rather nice . it has a bit of a czech lager taste to it and the alcohol is essentially unnoticeable . the taste is clearly alcholic , but very smoothly so , with nothing rough opr unpleasant . it has a light caramel quality , bread , and nice , warm spiciness , it 's a bit rasiniy , sweet and spicy with a light bitterness coming to the fore in the finish . it does not taste quite as strong as it is .

i really enjoyed this beer . it really did not have an aroma .  bomber picked up from the brewery , opened after some months aging into goblet : a : quite nice hazy light-golden orange color with a substantial , creamy , lasting head .  medium-full bodied mouthfeel with below average carbonation , the latter being ( beside the appearance ) one of my few criticisms .

some thick lacing towards the top s : nose is probably the weakest part of this beer . not much too it ; some roasted oat and malt t : ah yes , the beer i remember . very flavorful and easy drinking .  appearance : pours a clear orange color with a big 3 '' head that lasts quite a while .  this is n't the fault of the brewer so maby it had great head . the main problem with this beer was infection . i 'm sure it was an infection because when i sniffed it i thought for a second maybe i was at the movies about to dig into a 12 dollar medium popcorn . past the buttery flavor i could taste blueberry almost which i 'm sure was n't intended either . it 'd be interesting to taste one from a different batch .

soapy lacing stayed behind . very crisp aroma of burnt sugars , yeasts and nutmeg . very sweet . and drinkable ... to a point .  what a great looking beer .  medium bodied with medium carbonation . i only wish this average mouthfeel was supporting an average taste .

the aroma is of muted hops and barley . there is n't really much going on in the nose . after smelling this beer i thought it would be rather bland but the flavors pop off the tongue . i would n't call any 8.7 % alcohol beer extremely drinkable , but this is exceptional .  a - this beer pours black in color . this is a beautiful looking beer .  m : surprisingly thin , slightly sticky body with low carbonation . a little weak .

smell : just a simple beer smell hops barley a bit floral . a little floral like th smell .  abv 5 % pours a brilliant , perfectly clear , golden color with a fluffy three finger white head . picture perfect of a pils .  mouthfeel is a bit of a problem for me . the carbonation level is also a factor , making it hard to enjoy in gulps .

this widely available ale saved me from the tyranny of the irish dry stouts when i toured ireland a few years ago . it smells slightly of grainy malt , and not much else .  sampled on 4-7-09 pours a clear deep red/brown , with a huge , foamy , clingy , off-white head that leaves crazy thick lacing .  feel is kinda harsh .

s- mostly chocolate aroma with oats , not very strong aroma though t- lots of bitter chocolate , oats , roasted malts , and strong bittersweet vinegar aftertaste m- very creamy , lighter bodied for the style o- good flavor , very creamy , and highly drinkable .  dark gold , lightly cloudy , with a very big creamy off-white head slowly shrinking to a puffy , rocky smaller head and foamy lace .  carbonation seems spot on .

the aroma was very acidic , almost stale .  pours black with a long lasting brown head that leaves plenty of lacing .  mouthfeel is a bit light , to me , for the style , though it seems appropriate for the flavors that this beer brings to the palate .

very faint smell . medium body , medium carbonation . easy to drink for such a dark and strong ale .  the foam was wheat in color , bubbly , thick , smooth and left a ring around the glass til the end . the color was a dark burgandy/all most black with an orange red highlight in the light .  mouthfeel is a little bit thin .

s - a little bit faint for me , would have like to smell the aroma a little more to get a better idea of what ingredients were used to brew it . but i did get a hint of belgian yeast with a slight funk to it , sweet malts , a small whiff of raisins and oranges . did n't get much hop aroma on this one at all . t - definitely an improvement over the smell ... flavors come out a lot more to define this beer . overall a good belgian ipa , was expecting a little bit more with the a- overall rating but a solid beer from flying dog no doubt !  a - pours a thick 2 fingers of tan head that sticks around for quite some time .  m : okay , mostly wet and satisfyingly quaffable , but with a noticeable alcohol presence in the finish .

the aroma suggests yeasty caramel cream and maybe some grassy hop but overall a pretty neutral effect , with some rubbing alcohol , nothing too alluring but it 's okay . the tongue detects lots of stuff ( unlike the weak aroma ) including earthy pine and dr. pepper medicinal sweetness .  a= pours a beautiful dark brown almost black color with a great two finger perfectly toasty looking head on it that holds awesome retention and wonderful lacing on the glass .  not sure if our north american brethren appreciate this but this is , as far as i can tell the first fairly widely available american style ipa brewed in the uk . the american craft brewing industry which has been accused of being derivative is really starting to influence europe which is great . i am all for my uk brewing industry but i do get a little board of the vast variety of often samey real ale bitters populating manypubs . we definitely have a shortage of hopheads brewing in the uk ! and before anyone shoots me down , greene king ipa is not an ipa ! ! !

the aroma is surprisingly weak and consists of a vague smell of roasted coffee .  it produced a nice , soapy , white head at about 2-fingers . decent retention that left some seriously clumpy lacing behind . this is a vibrant and inviting looking beer .  a bit on the light side of medium in body , with a dryish spicy finish . aftertaste seems watery .
the smell is sweet and lightly spicy this lightly floral and more hoppy than a typical ale of this style .  i enjoy just about everything this beer has to offer .  m - felt a bit thin to me .

if you get it in a bottle it 's not as good since they distribute this beer in green bottles and you start to get some skunkey flavors . this is a very grainy pilsner with a slight hop aroma and taste . this beer is very true to style . that said , if you like a hoppy beer then pass on this one .  that little widget in the can sure does the trick : a majestic light tan head formed in my pint glass atop a layer of mesmerizing , cascading bubbles and a dark brown body .  mouthfeel is a little thin and aftertaste is a little too much ... like the brew has gone stale , although i know it has n't .

a very faint smell , hard to put a nose on it but there 's some sweetness there .  color was a little hard to see as it was fairly dark in the bar but appeared to be a very deep red , that while really dark was no opaque . slightly off-white head that left excellent lacing on the glass . not sure if it was the branded oversized wine glass or what but this was probably the second best looking beer i 've ever seen .  a very special thanks to zeke at the speakeasy for sharing a bottle of this 1995 treat . it still had carbonation in it which was crazy . the beer was very dry at this point . the spiciness of this beer has been cut down from the aging .

s : not a real pungent smell ... .a little dank . not bad but nothing special . t : nice well balanced hop beer .  a= at fridge temp , this ale poured a dark but clear mahogany brown color with a nice reddish glow . the first pour produced a light tan head that was only 1/4 '' but retained very well . retention was incredible and the stickage on my glass looked like emulsified foam ... beautiful .  feel is smooth and well-carbonated though a bit on the thin and watery side . medium-full body , not too heavy . leaves a nice sticky coating around the mouth . a bit thicker and less bitter and it 'd be great .

s : the glass was a foot and a half away from my face and i could immediately smell a warm pumpkin pie coming out of the oven with a nice floral hops on the back . t : the spicy pumpkin flavor swirls with a strong caramel malt flavor .  the head is a huge and fluffy 3 fingers high cloud puff with great retention and excellent lace .  the mouth feel is heavy with a decent amount of carbonation .

small white head that dissipates quickly from my tap pour at the airport taproom . lack of noticeable smell , which i find from most tap beers .  looks fantastic ! s : hoppy ( pine-ish ) with some malt- smelled fairly balanced and inoffensive for a high-gravity offering .  had this during o'briens wet hop festival . pours clear orange with a white ring of bubbles . lots of caramel with some tropical hops in the nose . kind of like a fruitcake . earthy , yet citrusy in the taste . bit sweeter than your normal ipa . grapefruit and blood orange . good stuff .

smelled of carmallized apples and alcohol . nothing extraordinary .  pours into a pint glass a translucent straw yellow with a billowing white head and and amazing lacing that last throughout the drink .  m : over carbonated - fizzy .

s : fresh cut grass scent is present up front which is followed by a grainy malt sweetness . rather simple scent , but i was n't expecting anything complex . pretty average straightforward .  a : damn near perfect in my book . nicely hazy , radiant golden orange color . it 's got a big , soapy head that settles into a cap and leaves big sheets of lacing . so far so good .  mouthfeel- light-moderate mouthfeel . carbonation is moderate-high .

not a big nose on it , but the taste is quite good . i get an almost nutty , roasted , and woodiness to it too .  pours a amber ale color with a super looking coffee colored head with tight tiny bubbles that also remits some great lacing .  creamy , light toffee . very mild bitterness . mild carbonation and foamation , could be a little more vigorous .

aromas of hops , yeast , and mellons . smooth and mellow with plenty of depth ; i really liked this beer , but it did n't present itself in both appearance and smell as well as it tasted .  appearance- deep brown-caramel colored pour . leaves wonderful lace streaks and patches . almost the entire glass was caked with lace after i was finished .  i purchased this beer in a mix and match pack at the recommendation of the guy working at the liquor store = error . the look of the beer was clear and it drank smooth , but it was accompanied by the 'sour beer face . ' the taste was a combination of failure and shame ( with a hint of fruit ) all leading to the grand finale of a quick pour into the drain .

the smell is more toasty malt than anything else , but if you must know that anything else is somewhat grassy barely grapefruity hops and a decent amount of caramel .  '01-'02 : starts by pouring a jet black , your unable to see through it , with a nice dark tan head that settles with deep fluffy pockets .  m - this one finished a little dry , too much so for my liking , but the carbonation was nicely balanced , making it very smooth .

smell : not much , some yeast , some fruit taste : nice cherry flavour , not overly sweet by anymeans . mouthfeel : starts creamy and thick but finishes crisp with the carbonation coming in on the finish dinkability : quite good , i could certainly have more than one .  12 oz bottle into pilsner glass a : beautiful ! crystal clear yellow body topped off by one inch of white creamy foam .  mouf & gt ; easy , average .

surprisingly underwhelming . wow !  a : the perfect clear orange color . great retention .  rich , almost like chicken soup broth , and very low carbonation . in the world of bocks , this could be a new favorite of mine .

s : the weakest aspect of this beer for me . general maltiness is all i get . t : the key here is balance ; a supremely well-crafted beer .  attractive looking brew here .  my first taste of it was great , however it lacks in the balance of the malts , and has sort of a over roasted taste . altogether though , this beer in my opinion is the best of the coors brand and i would recommend for something new . not a everyday beer though .

despite my usual preference for ales , i really enjoy this lager . if the macros produced lagers like this one ( and i 'm sure they could do so ) , american beers would be looked at quite differently by the world of beer experts .  insanely sticky , a spectacular pour .  this one was surprisingly thin in body .

burnt brown head poured pretty thick , foamy and meringue like then faded to light covering with thick edging ... some light lines of lacing ring the glass ... aroma - dark toasted malts , metallic notes , black coffee , some dark brown sugar sweetness , light nuttiness , some blackcurrant and raisin fruitiness , faint liquorice traces , some graininess coming through , dusty hints ... taste - watered down roasted maltiness mixed with nutty notes , some molasses / treacle sweetness , light chocolate mixed with black cherry and blackcurrant fruits , light nutmeg and pepper spiciness , some light vegetal traces just noticeable , cola hints ... feel - way too over carbonated this one which really spoils it both in terms of flavour and drinkability ... overall - a bit disappointing as all the other les fous beers i 've had have been very good ... sort out the carbonation and this could be very good..  the stream of beer coming out of the bottle even looked impressive ! semi-firm tan head , tight bubbles , settles to a sheer cap .  even with the earthy malt flavor , the overall feel stays on the thin side .

s - i am hard pressed to find much in the nose beyond a light , pleasant flowery hop . very good beer , though i feel the appearance and aroma are weak for a bspa .  absolutely beautiful orange red body with a thin white head .  mouthfeel works just fine , but is a little watery . highly drinkable .

original rating date : august 30 , 2008 pours an enticing dark gold , smells of a bit of hops but not as much as i expected , relatively weak on the nose which surprises me as most iipas i 've tried have a great nose . looking down the ratings already here , it seems like i 'm the only one who will score this weak on aroma- maybe my nose is too stuffed ? i want to give this a higher rating but the nose just was n't there for me . either way , excellent iipa , a far better effort than lagunitas ' regular ipa .  a 330ml bottle fills a duvel tulip with garnet elixir topped with lots and lots of creamy head .  m/d - mouthfeel is nothing special , the steely hop bite takes a bit away .

dont really pick up much of an aroma , some malts , some hops , but not much really . great balanced taste of malts and hops .  pours an impossibly crystal-clear straw color . the bubbles are as fine as you will find in a beer , crazy lacing on the sides of the glass .  mouthfeel is lightly carbonated , a little thick ( like a dark lager ... blech ) , and generally mediocre .

the nose is slightly floral , but to be honest , i failed to detect much .  16 ounce can , best by sept. 29 , 2011 . pours extremely hazy orange amber color with a 1 finger fairly dense off white head with good retention that reduces to a thin lacing cap that lasts .  m- thin to medium in body . highly attenuated with a soft carbonation .

adeep , dark , rich brown ; about a 1 inch thick foamy head that disappeared quickly , light lacing on the glass sspicy with a strong plum scent ; a little banana and clove aroma as well . i liked the taste very much but the smell was a little strong and foul for me .  young 's double chocolate stout pours super dark with an excellent thick tan head that remains until the beer is gone .  a bit more body would 've made this an excellent brew .
aroma is some spice , toffee .  pours with a deep red-brown body topped by a medium thick lasting head with good lace .  medium bodied , highly carbonated .

s - roasted grain . bit of coffee , that 's about it .  a - black as night with a thick frothy brown head . fades slowly leaving a thin solid layer of foam on the beer with excellent lacing .  unfortunately , it is basically flat , with a heavy mouthfeel . overall , this beer would be unbelievable with good carbonation .

appearance : pours into a sam adams glass a clear pale yellow with a loose-bubbled white head on top . smell : quite sweet with indications of wheat and lemony citrus .  appearance- pours a crystal clear brownish red , almost cognac , with four fingers of beautifully structured soapy bubbles . the head peaks well above the rim of my glass , and compacts to a creamy , hefeweizen-like consistency . outstanding lacing leaves sheets behind . excellent .  m : very very mild carbonation .

aroma is mild , to put it mildly . a little caramel , a touch of yeasty bread and a hint of banana ( ?  22-oz bottle opened at local beer tasting ( underground bluz ) . a beautiful brew . this beer can do some damage because you wo n't want to stop drinking it !  the mouthfeel is a little off , too light and thin .

nice light smell of roasted nuts and dark caramel .  exceptional appearance with enormous meringue-like dark brown head , opaque black body , and gobs of lace as the beer goes down .  heavy mouthfeel .

smell : gentle hoppy smell .  still a bit of haze but not anything like a hefe . the beer looks great in this glass !  mouthfeel is slightly thin for the style or maybe just thin for how much is going on there ... .like you are expecting more of a stout mouthfeel .

there is a lot going on here . smells kind of like red wine , also smells like a lambic . i 'm guessing the lambic aroma is really brett . the more i smell it , the more i like the smells .  poured this puppy into a duvel tulip , which helped to bring about an ample 4 finger thick fluffy and off white head . the body is very murky and peach in color . head retention is great , as well as the lacing .  if i had to log a complaint , it would be that this stout is too thin and less of a cream offering . however , it is full of flavor and easy to drink despite being 6.5 % abv .

smells ok ... ca n't exactly put my finger on what is wrong ... but it may have something to do with the `` party pig '' it came from .  this beer is so dark that it makes the glass appear as if it 's jet black . it 's beautiful . no head , no carbonation , just black .  this is about my only complaint of this beer-too much carbonation ! carbonation gives a foamy/frothy mouthfeel .

s - roasted malts , but there is some brine or olives on this that makes me feel like it has turned a little bit . there 's some good and bad , taking this to average .  great black appearance with cascade of bubbles when poured that lasted a minute , leaving 1/2 inch tan head that stayed until the glass was empty .  very good light lager . hints of barley and hops , with a smooth slightly dry aftertaste . this brew had a short lived white foamy head and lower than normal carbonation . i would highly recommend this to any light beer drinker .

smell : some bready caramel malt sweetness . not a ton going on here . overall : a solid irish red .  pours a deep , rich plummy color topped by a lively head of sloppy , sticky looking foam . this has a very healthy head that sticks around and laces majestically .  carbonation is n't bad , with fairly good activity after each drink . mouth-feel is a bit dry .

smell : it smells a little strong , perhaps hops .  a deep amber reddish beer with a mother of pearl head . the head on this brew is large fluffy , lasting and pungent .  m-a bit watery for my tastes but the taste makes you forget about it being slightly thin .

aroma is mellow . nothing super amazing going on here .  dugana pours beautifully for a 2.5 finger thick off white head , with great retention .  it has constantly proved itself to be my favorite local utah brew ( this use to be called the 2002 unofficial ale ) . if the pour makes your mouth literally water , you know it 's good . damn good beer ,

smell is faint , like cupcakes baking in the oven as you approach the house ( no , that does n't actually happen in my household ) . not as hoppy as i expected , but the hops are delicious and balance the beer nicely . but it 's still a terrific beer .  pours a dark copper with a large , foamy white head that hung around forever . large amounts of thick lacing left on the glass surface . this is one beautiful beer .  rated as a stout the mouthfeel is a bit thin , the carbonation is a bit high , and the finish is a bit less than one would expect .

aroma - not much of aroma . taste - cola and lightly fruity flavors . nothing amazing , but nothing to be shy about .  a beautiful appearance , two thick fingers of creamy light coco head with spectacular lacing coating the glass .  the mouthfeel has a strange little zing that seems inappropriate for the style .

smell is faint . i get some hop and yeasty malt , but not a really forward nose .  a- dark brown with an off white creamy one finger head that laces nicely to the last drop .  mouthfeel is a bit light .

s : some bourbon and booziness , but for me the nose was pretty underwhelming .  anyways , into the erdinger glass ... a - really impressed with this head .  mouthfeel is fairly carbonated , a bit sour , finishing dry and crisp .
s - very grape . almost smells like lighter fluid .  spectacular retention and thick , chunky lace .  m : meh . disappointingly flat . i 'd like more carbonation .

nice lacing as well . a seriously good-looking brew . smell : malt right off the bat , with a certain underlying spiciness . the taste is terrific & # 8212 ; for a pale ale . not the best seasonal , per se , but a really tasty ale .  pour revelaed an extremely thick and long lasting creamy white head.as it reduced it left rings of lace in the glass.the color presented was orange and somewhat cloudy.mouthfeel wasnt very crisp and seemed a bit watery.the finish left a sharp sweet or tart twist that dissapeared real quick.a bit bitter in the back of the throat with a wheaty grain taste.a spicy aroma thats not too strong but is there.tastes of oranges , lemon , cloves , corriander , and honey are noted.overall good with a medium body .  taste : a bit thin for a porter , almost to the point of being slightly watery .

aroma is of espresso , burnt grains , bittersweet chocolate , vanilla , and black walnut . taste is thin , burnt , vanilla and french roast coffee ... there is nothing more .  this brew pours into the glass with a black body topped by a thick creamy , light brown head with a good amount of lacing left behind .  medium to thick body , light almost too light level of carbonation with a sweet almost sticky mouthfeel .

he posted a note in the midwest forum that a hudson store rec 'd a case or two & i promptyly left home for the 25 minute drive that netted me my first kentucky breafast stout . and as is proper for an imperial stout , it 's a very dark version of black . the smell 's a little disappointing . coffee , it screams . as it warms it gets a little more subtle , but there 's still nothing else .  look : bright golden color , white head of creamy foam with 2 fingers thick , very good lacing , has a sticker that say it was the best beer in the world in 2002 , let see if it 's true ; smell : biscuity malts and fruit essences ; taste : pine and spicy hops , molasses , some biscuity malts , alcohol and sugars at the finish ; mouthfeel : dry and very bitter , bittersweet and spicy finish , the body is creamy and thick ; drinkability : the first time i try the `` tripel '' style , very spicy .  ginger is one of my favorite flavors . this beer has a wonderful ginger taste , which is exactly what i would expect from a beer with this name . further , there is a decent bitterness & a slight sweetness as well . i 'm not a huge fan of spiced beers normally , but this one is really nice . recommended .

lacing got more impressive as the glass emptied . i quite enjoyed this beer and found it more interesting than the leffe blonde ; my only criticism might be that it 's a bit too rich at times , but that 's a minor distraction . my preferred leffe right now .  the retention was downright insane and it essentially sat there like whipped cream . beautiful looking beer .  a really really long aftertaste in the nose .
smells mild . pine and clean alcohol .  a : orange colour and a huge 4 cm head that sticks around due to the high carbonation .  lowish carbonation and a slightly thin mouthfeel .

aroma - the faintest aroma of grain , a bare trace of sweetness . maybe a hint of grape , might just the power of suggestion though .  amazing retention and lacing .  the mouthfeel of the beer was , like most porter and ale styles , very average . however , the mouthfeel did not detract from the overall feel of the beer .

nice and leggy . smell : not much there .  almost impossible to open due to the stupid wax coating covering the whole swing top . lightly hazed bronze color with a nice full pillowy light beige head , nice active carbonation , and nice lace sheets .  the mouthfeel was medium/light bodied with a fine , prickly carbonation .

s : some malt characters , bread and toffee mostly . after that not to much going on in the nose . very subtle hints of hops but that 's reaching for it . d : very drinkable beer !  there is lots retention and great lacing . it might be best lacing i 've vere seen .  s : candied pineapple , yeast , and hops well balanced t : a typical ipa taste with accents of pineapple ; yeasts and hops , well balanced m/d a bit thin , carbonation too small and too much , abv on the high side and quite noticeable good beer

* the smell is feint , but boy does that thick and milky head stick around ! * it 's lke a scottish ale but without the bite ; not harsh . * smooth and milky * major big swath of milky lace * taste is sweet actually ; some chocolate * the scotch ale taste is there , but very mild ; not as pungent as usual * has a alcohol presence , but it is subtle * it 's a balanced scotch ale , not brutal .  bottle poured into a tulip glass . brilliant clarity . thick white crop of foam with good retention and moderate lacing .  i wish the carbonation was a little more noticeable in the mouth .

a strong blonde ale . there may be hops , but very subdued .  almost black with a cream colored head measuring maybe one finger . i love pouring it out of the gan into a pint glass and watching it mix and cascade turning from the color of mud to the color of .  could use both more body and carbonation .

light tan head sits upon this almost purple/amber colored beer . not much in the way of aroma . this concerned me and i was not hopeful .  a : jet black with a nice dark mocha head that sits just barely above the beer . perfect for the style s : has a very nice mellow scotch smell that is not too harsh along side a slight sweetness of vanilla and honey .  thin body ample carbonation overall : this is slightly better than bud light but still not really worth drinking

aroma : slight grainy aroma . i was surprised i did n't pick up on those traits in the aroma . grapefruit notes . i really liked the way this beer came together .  a- really nice big belgian-style head on top of a fizzy , slightly hazy , light straw colored body . looks lovely in a belgian tulip glass .  taste is more of the same ... some wild floral flavors , hints of citrus ... seems like the dominant flavors have switched from the citrus to the floral characteristics . i like it , for sure , but could use some balance . i 'm not a big fan of the bitter taste left in the mouth ... but it 's still plenty drinkable . a definitely above-average ale , but not the best .

appearance - black with a little off white head smell - theres not too much to the smell , kind of a sweet roasted smell to it taste/ mouthfeel - has a chocolate roasted flavor , is very smooth and a little thick .  full black color with a thick , creamy head .  m - thought it was a little flat , but not bad .

it had a mild banana-hop aroma . it started fizzy and buttery then finshed smoothly in a banana floral flavor . indeed , this was another very nice brew .  deep brown pour with a gigantic , rocky , tan head .  the beer poured hard but the carbonation ended up being low and the mouthfeel medium .

nice beer . not a great saison , but a very good one . not the funkiest saison , but i kind of like that . almost a saison/belgian pale ale cross .  pitch black with a full dark amber head that settles to very thick sticky lacing .  the body is rather thin though .

interestingly , taste is unlike the smell ... and that 's a good thing . aroma is typical lager , run-of-the-mill beer .  almost black colour , with a very good head .  palate : medium body , thinner than expected actually , but goes down smooth .

poured a nice golden color with a dense rocky head pronounced piney and citrusy aroma , along with an earthy spice to it . huge hop bouquet . this beer seemed a little thin and light bodied for an ipa .  this beer poured a cloudy deep gold that bordered on light amber . it 's pure white head was thick and rich , solid lacing adorned the glass .  pours a three finger light tan head that fades quickly to a ring leaving a little lace . dark cloudy amber color . light carbonation and light bodied . caramel nose . starts balanced but then a caramel flavor that stays to a clean finish . a tasty wheat . $ 2.49 for a 500ml bottle from john 's grocery iowa city , ia .

i have to disagree with the other reviews of this beer : working as a beertender here in florida , i have never once recommended this beer and had someone not like it . it is a great replication of an english mild or amber ale by wild goose , probably the best beer they make ( that we can get here in fl ) .  i was first impressed with the color - almost black ! big , creamy , frothy head .  mouthfeel was avg ; like a nice dark beer .

nose is kind of small and basic . mild green apple , sense of sweet malts and candi . not very big or noticeable or even complex .  just an absolutely pitch black beer that poured like motor oil and had one of the darkest , longest lasting heads i have seen on an imperial stout .  the mouth is a little lighter than years past .

this rauchmalt is combined with modest amounts of crystal malt and two types of chocolate malt that add sweet and chocolaty notes to balance the assertive smoke qualities . hops really take a backseat in this style , so as not to interfere with the complex smoky aromatics '' -- free state this pours a very dark brown almost black . unfortunately , the aroma is weak . some very small tinges of smoke come out , but not much else .  looks picture perfect . despite my allergies , i can actually smell floral hops .  mouthfeel is fine - it 's a very light lager .

s- perhaps it was my surroundings , but the aroma was very subtle . picked up a little roasted caramel mingled with unmistakably belgian sour yeast .  it pours a thick , viscous black with a large dark tan hea that slowly recedes .  m : um . it was carbonated and did n't leave any odd off flavours on the palate .

not too much in the way of the aroma department , kind of dissapointing .  bottled april 22 , 2009 poured into a pint glass amber with a very thick white head . very good retention and lacing .  m- light in body and light to medium in carbonation .

it 's very drinkable and has a pleasant , subtle mix of grain , hops , and english yeast . the aroma is very muted , even for this style , i just get a little grain dust , but the taste holds lightly caramel barely and gentle , spicy hops that finish the beer out . overall , a great session beer and a rare locally-brewed example of the style .  dark copper with a 2 finger off-white head from a 22 into a pint glass . i drink slower , so i poured the remainder almost 30 minutes later and it still formed a 2 finger head . this is much lighter in the smoke than any rauch that most people have had .  sprecher brewing company is one of milwaukee 's first micro 's and in fact its the one that really got me into quality beer tasting and home brewing . this is one of my favorite octoberfest beers as far as drink-ability as many octo 's are a bit overly heavy for me . this one really leaves your palate refreshed and ready for more . i lived in germany for two years and never found a beer at a octoberfest there that was like american octoberfest style of brews but thats why i like them they are unique even if maybe they are n't trying to be .

there was a faint earth and citrus aroma but nothing really pronounced .  pours a pretty deep black with dark tan head that clings to the glass . looking quite appealing .  3.0 m : medium body . smooth , but not creamy .

s- some roasted coffee malts , a little peat ?  a - a beautiful pour . deep amber with an inch of off-white head . as the head slowly goes away it leaves great lace and ends up in a creamy , bumpy layer on top of the brew .  mouthfeel is a little thin , though .

color and smell is nothing to get excited about .  a : an outstanding looking beer . dark plum color with a pinch of tannish head and amazing coating lacing . stunning .  my only gripe with this beer was the mouthfeel . it was rather thin and watery with a mild yet large bubbled effervescence .

the smell of th ebeer is of subtle hops , again , nothing to over-powering .  bomber poured a clear dark reddish brown nearly black with a lasting brown head .  m : somewhat thin body , slightly watery ; could do with more carbonation also .

the smell was fruity , sweet and slightly hoppy .  - served at cellar temperature appearance : sort of hazy ( unfiltered beer ) golden color with orange highlights . the head is off white and bubbly , like a champagne . cakey top part of the head and lots of sticky lace left on the sides of the glass .  m- low carbonation and very low mouthfeel .

big chocolate smell , hint of coffee .  on tap o'brien 's pub san diego , ca black with a lot of visible carbonation and a thin brown head . regular , lined lacing down the glass . very attractive and perfect for a black ipa . roasted malts and pine aromas combine , though i would suggest that the roast is fairly dominant .  a delightful golden color graced by a pale yellow head . i did n't get much lacing , but i believe that was due to a freshly-washed glass ( served at a bar ) . nice hops come through in this one . it is a little bitter and spicy , but also has some good vanilla and tones of malt . not the most fantastic example of its style , but tasty and very drinkable .

aroma is mainly of brown malts with a slight roastiness and nuts . nothing else to note here . kinda boring really , but right there with the style .  appearance : looks beautiful . jet black stout , brown creamy head pours thick with a thin half finger head .  mouf & gt ; nice , nothing special drinkability & gt ; sure thing

groggy hazy brown color in the body . a little sour , but the malt comes through in the aroma . flavor is a superbly sweet caramel malt , but with a kick of almond .  wow , orange , slightly reddish , as it let 's the light pass through ... it 's beautiful . such a strong head , off-white .  there is a very little carbonation factor in this beer .

the nose has some sweetness and faint hops , but seems a bit muted . i do n't think i have a cold or anything ... hrm . smooth citrusy american hops flow into the big , boozy backbone . in all , this was a very enjoyable beer and i might have to pick up another bottle when i head back for groceries tomorrow night .  a : beautiful beer ! it 's a perfectly clear light amber color topped by a big-bubble , thin but foamy head . lacing is alright , but the beer looks so good it makes up for that in other areas .  perhaps a bit thin for the style , which i suppose makes it a good pale ale for summertime quaffing .

s : smells like oranges and has a slight malty scent , like sweet smelling syrup . the sent is very light though .  this beer pours beautifully , glowing , hazed apricot amber in color with 3 fingers of fluffy froth topped by rocky peaks . retention is epic and lace coats my maredsous goblet .  slight hint of the hop flower but the malt dominates , sweet , crisp , fresh and pleasing to the senses with the start lightly sweet , satisfactory malt presence , and top light to middling in feel . this is a style where i like the lighter body , as it lets the flavoring hops shine through , quite quaffable , a damn fine session beer me thinks , and i thank royalt for this bottle .

s : nothing really distinct in the aroma . the alcohol definitely stands out and the smell reminds me of a good whiskey .  this beer was so pretty that i had to stop and take a picture . a beautiful translucent golden color with a billowing white head .  m - at times , a bit of a metallic feel to the beer .

s : yeast hops and some sweetness from the malt . not really that great a nose on this . definitely it 's weak point . t : sweetness from the malt , citrus from the hops , the yeast adds a slight spiciness .  a- looks awesome . pours a crytal clear light brassy orange , with a massive white oamy , fluffy head that slowly shrinks down leaving behind all kinds of webbing lace .  no sediment at all when bought fresh . this really brought out flavors you could not taste beforehand . a wedge of orange or lemon is a nice touch also . best served a little warmer than most beers . goes really well with food . a beer you could drink all night especially during a good bar-b-que .

a- pours chocolate milk color into black with the creamiest of tan heads . s- aroma is soft and roasted , not much going on . perfect amount of malt .  a - very dark murky brown pour , extremely large ( 4-finger ) head . really beautiful .  mouthfeel is carbonated , but creamy and smooth . lacks the dry bite that i look for in a dipa .

light malt and grainy presence upfront with nice floral hop notes and undertones of grassy hops . overall , quite flavorful and easy drinking , tasted fresh despite the freshness date being about 3 weeks past .  appearance- deeper colored golden pour with a full inch plus rocky head with a good 1/4 inch of staying power . great looking beer .  feels thin .

the smell was very faint , hints of breads and malts . great taste ; earthy , bready , and lightly hoppy .  a : a medium amber color with a very robust creamy white head . it has a very creamy and milky head . lacing is incredible . s : it smells of citrus ( orange or grapefruit ) with floral notes .  much like the ingredient list on the back , there are scent of malted barley , malted wheat , hops , and yeast which gives it an almost caramel scent . starts out making you think this will be a heavy tasting beer with its malted ingredients like a stout but instead it finishes rather light . drinks rather smooth as the malted ingredients really hit the taste buds . finishes rather clean smooth . a decent beer with a rather interesting drinking experience .
