s- the nose is very restrained , which may have to do with the cold temperature the beer was served at . a mildly bready nose , with not much else there . t- impressive in the mouth .  tasted in mid-may 2009. nearly opaque , black/brown , with reddish brown on the edges under the light . great lacing , forming curtains in the latter half of the glass .  had some fruity and clove flavors but was covered up due way too many hops for the style - not to mention that it was bitter . i barely finished it . other reviewers liked this beer and seemed to have a much different experience than i did which leaves me to believe that they have consistency problems or maybe they use different formulas for each location ? btw this one was sampled at the brewpub near the fleet center .

aroma is very yeasty and bready . nothing really outstanding here , but a pretty solidly made beer .  poured into duvel tulip glass , half beer half very thick foamy head . very solid beer .  mouthfeel is a little thin , but not offensively so .

the smell was pretty vague for me ... can pick up on some floral and citrus hops and sweet caramel malts .  brown 33cl bottle with an artsy looking label . pours a peach orange-honey -very murky with a big 1inch + cap and holds very well down to 1 finger after a few minutes . very fluffy and fresh-looking lace which leaves thick puffs on glass . the head holds so well it is similar to egg-whites with very soft peaks .  just the right amount of hops . even though you can taste the fruits and spice , you can also taste the high alc % . drinkability : very drinkable , but if you more than one in a session , watch out : ) overall : a better than average tripel .

the smell is that of a traditional lager with a little roasted malt to it .  got a single of this the other day , and poured it into my mug and the appearance is beautiful . hazy straw color , best looking ive seen in a hefe .  leaves you breathless -- groping for words to describe what is one of the worst beers i 've ever tasted . i have had enough bacterial beers to recognize the usual flavors .

what i liked most was that it was well balanced and not a hop bomb in my opinion . i love sierra nevada pale ale and i think fans of that will like this too if not more . very drinkable and probably could go through quite a bit on a warm sunny day .  poured a translucent mustard/straw yellow with a huge , rocky , white head that faded into clumps of white froth . beautiful lacing .  m- a bit over carbonated for me , but other than the crisp nature of most kiwi beers , nice malty and dry .

very nice aroma ! very nice beer .  made a great appearance , poured a classic beer golden with a very large creamy foamy white head with a lot of sticking .  m - moderate carbonation-almost too much , dry finish , medium bodied due to the carbonation .

had on tap at the rockcats game a- dark dark brown with red overtones , thin white head that lasted only a few seconds s- some malts not to much nose here t- some nice malts with a nice clean refreshing finish m- thin but as expected for the style d- great drinkablity from this and any brown ale . while this is not the best brown ale i have a had it certainly is a good beer i would have again . i think brown ales are one of the most sessionable ales around .  looks great on a goblet . amazing retention and lacing .  m : surprisingly on the more carbonated side with a slight fizzy mouthfeel .

my mouth is watering s - super floral , i do n't even need to put my nose that close to get wonderful citrus and pine notes t - a bit sweet to me . m - sweetness sticks a the tongue to much , leaves a sugary oily aftertaste , decent carbonation o - a good ipa , but not the best  highly envigorated light brown head of fine bubbles that left behind a nice lacing on the pour .  a light- to moderate mouthfeel , hints of sour flavor linger at the back of the tongue after the swallow . i do n't pick up much of a hint of carbonation in the mouthfeel .

foam didnt leave lace it left a coating of thick shaving cream , very nic ! s-dominated by sweet caramel malts with low floral/ citruy hops .  bottle to a tulip pours a clear red body , and by red i mean excellent vibrant red . has a fizzy white head that doesnt stay for the party .  mouthfeel medium body for the style with sharp carbonation .

the aroma is composed of citrus and yeast . i detect the slight prenence of hops in the aroma . the flavor is slight on the front of the tongue , but the hops are prevelent on the back of the tongue .  a tawny amber gem in the glass , champagne bubbles like fireworks , and an incredible mountainous head .  the mouthfeel is thiner but still good .

n : lemon peel , citrus and some kiwi ( ? ) with some sweet malt smells . hops come and go in the aroma , knocked out a bit from the orange and coriander .  a-amber with sediment and good frothy head . the color an intense head gives this one high scores .  there is little ( hardly any ) carbonation here , and the mouthfeel really does n't pack a punch at all .

it do n't smell all that strong or sweet , even for the style this seems little tame . light nodes of dark roasted barley . that 's it . tastes a god sight better .  the colour is pitch-black ; the two finger head is pale beige , airy and uneven . massive amounts of lacing .  m : light bodied and well carbonated .

for the price it isnt worth it weekly or nightly it goes down smooth with a good taste there really isnt a smell and it looks like an other beer in this category  pours a big white head that takes up half a tulip glass , then settles to a half inch of meringue . body is dark yellow with some wit-like cloudiness .  mouth feel : a bit thin on the palet , or maybe the aroma and taste make you expect more in the way of mouth feel .

aroma : grassy and a bit metallic , also spritzy . taste : heavy toasted undertones slapped with a veneer of molten dark chocolate .  on-tap at beachwood bbq , on to the beer : the head retention is great on top this coal black beer . great , thick lacing sticks to the glass .  m : very carbonated .

appearance- it has a nice straw golden yellow body . smell- pretty plain and not much aroma to speak of which i thought was odd for bavarian beer . taste- it has a very nice but even hoppy taste for a beer of this style .  much better than guinness off the nitro-keg , but not as good as a regular quality stout . very imposing solid black brew with a giant head .  mouthfeel suffers a little bit as i feel a higher abv would 've left this coating the tongue a little better . it seemed a little too thin to match its flavor profile .

s - mostly pine , citrus smell coming from hops . not as strong most ipa 's go .  a pint of the black stuff , or the priest , looks as good as ever , enjoyable to watch it settle over a minute or so .  a little less carbonation and this probably enters `` special '' territory .

overall : 3.85 appearance : 4.5 | smell : 3 | taste : 4 | mouthfeel : 3.5 | drinkability : 4 740  appearance is beautiful . pours an oaky golden light brown . leaving a dense one finger head on top of the beer .  the carbonation is heavy and it adds harshness to the palate . medium-full body .

s : smell was a little lacking , but did smell quite refreshing , quite fir for spring !  on-cask at the brewpub : hazyish copper tinted hay color with a puffy topping of oatmeal cream . keeps its cap for a great length and laces well across the glass in small curtains and spots .  take this beer for what it is ... a nice `` treat . '' it 's not something you will want to drink all night long . but for a nightcap , or change of pace this beer fits the bill . the vanilla taste is not overpowering , it 's there , but not so bold and overpowering that it seems fake .

i just had a hop devil and that leaves me with only one more hop devil and one troeg 's pale ale , so i decided to save those for another day and steal one of these from my sister . something sweet like candy with a touch of an adjunct ... corn maybe ? maybe a banana like runt t : pretty much follows the smell .  pours a nice amber color with a white head and excellent lacing .  thin to medium bodied with moderate carbonation .

aroma is quite subdued . subtle citrus and toasted malt about sums it up . taste follows suit , but offers a bit more .  pours a deep brown with ruby highlights into a tulip . creamy off-white/light khaki head leaves excellent lacing and retention .  mouthfeel was a bit heavy and undercarbonated , but that may have been more of the fault of the bar i was at , and not the beer its self .

a great summer ale . taste is citrusy . all in all , this is not a complex beer or anything really special .  pours deep brown with a stiff egg custard-colored head that fades slowly .  the mouth fell was a little thin for stout .

s - sweet , malty nose with strong notes of molasses . smelling this blind i would not have guessed ipa .  poured into a new belgium snifter a - a beautiful clear dusk sunset color , 2 finger head that lingered and lacing through and through and awesome tiny bubbles for days s - pine , citrus , malt , floral , cotton , sweet , grains and maybe a bit toasty t - very nice bitter sweet , pine , orange , melon , pineapple , very hoppy and yet super bitter sweet malty m - coats the mouth a bit with some super bitter sweet lingering .  m/t : light to medium body , watery and a good amount of carbonation . however with the light body , low bitterness and virtually zero aftertaste , i could session this beer .

s - aroma is mainly bitter chocolate and a hint of brown sugar along with just a hint of hops .  it has a great thick fluffy dark mocha colored head perched upon a jet black body . the head was still present a good 5 minutes after pouring .  the body was medium to medium light .

s - slightly sweet and caramelized with a non-specific bitter balance and a bit of minerality . t - lots of mineral flavor , some sweetness , and a sharp grassy bitterness that lingers on the finish .  perfect appearence for an ipa , with a strong , full foaming head that lasts .  mouthfeel : slighty watery good .

smells strongly of banana and bubblegum , with only a touch of clove . a candied note and a bit of white bread as well .  gorgeous . a few streamers feed the head , which retains ok and leaves nice lacing .  mouthfeel : typical red stickyness drinkability : i love this beer .

s : nice sweet smell , but not too complex .  a - pours a very dark brown - almost black - with a two-finger , well-carbonated , beige head that slowly dissipates to a 1 cm head . very attractive drink , as well as bottle which is slightly shorter and wider than most 12 oz bottles .  mouthfeel is high carbonated foamy and slightly mouthcoating .

on pouring there was a slight fine head that dissapated very quicky . the pour was at about 50 deg f in a large goblet to hopefully release the promised aroma . while there was some faint aroma , i expected some richness and it just was n't special .  the appearance is simply beautiful . a rich brown that seems to be characteristic of most trappist ales . this actually sort of reminds me of the way eku 28 eisbock smells , which is odd for a trappist .  tart and dry feel , but not overly so . lower carbonation detracts a little , really the only flaw in my mind .

the smell was uneventful , with hints of honey and orange .  poured into a standard snifter at about 55 degrees f , 1-inch head , light lacing , deep beautiful cloudy magenta .  mouthfeel is light , and carbonation is set at medium .

for such a strong tasting beer the aromas are difficult to pick up . mostly what i get for a smell is a malty sweetness .  bottle : poured a clear golden color ale with a big foamy head with good retention and good lacing .  thin bodied , and just sufficient carbonation , but i suspect the growler is at fault much more than the beer .

the smell is pretty faint .  bottle : poured a deep pitch-black stout with a motor oil consistency and a small foamy head with good retention and some lacing .  m - crisp and bitey , high carbonation - the bottle overflowed when i opened it .

smell : there is very little coming through to my nose . a hint of fruity smell , somewhat like apples and oranges . coupled with very nice hops .  has my favorite froth for this style , thick and sticky , goes nowhere fast and the color looks bread .  the motuhfeel is moderately carbonated and slightly watery .

it smells of corn syrup and stale hops ( or some other foul off smell ) .  `` mad bitch '' has an great look . upon pouring it creates a beautiful white head that lasts for the duration of the drink . the beer is an opaque , honey color that is incredibly appetizing .  mouthfeel is on the thin side for a stout .

surprisingly little spice aroma . relatively dry malt with very light hop . frankly , small in the nose .  a : pours a hazy golden with a thick bubbly white head that slowly faded into a thick film that lasted the whole beer through and left an incredible fuzzy sheet of solid lacing down the glass . beautiful .  nice aroma of hops but i would hope for a bit more being a hops lover . the celebration ale , from the same company , seems to hit the spot more than this beer but still worthy of a place in the fridge and still better than many micro beer ipa ii . sierra nevada seems to me to be the only mass beer company that brews excellent beer for `` mass beer '' prices .

was presented in the proper bitburger glass with the full head expected on a german pilsner . the smell has a uniqque sweetness .  a - black ... cool s - nutty and fresh with some fruits behind but not really much of a scent t - tastes like an oil mixed with dirt .  mouthfeel was ok , not too thin , right amount of carbonation .

it 's flavor is very rich w/ a slightly bitter finish . the maltiness is very enjoyable . another fine beer from victory  a - murky apple juice with and incredible pillow head ... slow to leave , chunky lace left .  the carbonation is around medium . there is a watery texture to the beer which is not pleasant .

tannish head sits heavy at first , fades and laces . rusty malt scent . deep and dark .  appearance - black with no light passing through . good tan head on top . looks like a very nice stout or porter . nice amount of head but with even less lacing then their other beers .  guest two usually drinks michalob ultra , coors light , or busch light . since this is my girlfriends dad he knows about my passion for quality beer so i 'll often encourage him to sample what i am drinking . he rarely enjoys any of them and most of the time makes a look of disgust after the first sip . he drank two bitburgers in about a half hour without one little peep about the taste . i noticed these reactions before i had the opportunity to sample this beer myself . later in the evening , after the music was turned down and the midnight snacks were partaken of , i tried one . they were right , this beer sucks over a year later i have grown to like this beer alot .

ok , twist my arm ... pours an absolutely clear pale golden colour , with a few fingers of thick foamy white head , which leaves consistent lacing around the glass . the aroma is of cereal grain , the malt being the only thing coming through , until it warmed a bit , and then a bit of floral hoppiness was detectable .  has a really nice fluffy one finger tan head that sticks around . lacing covers a huge portion of the glass .  m : very carbonated - almost too much .

a- beautiful rich amber with a dense creamy head . s- a little faint , but my allergies are clogging my nose a bit so , it 's probably better than i can tell . some floral , some hoppy spiciness . first i get the fresh pine and resin notes , very bright and spicy , with floral overtones throughout . i do n't like bitterness and its the only fault i have with this beer , but since it is a tribute to hops its really not a fault at all .  the appearance was a perfect deep color with a incredible head .  m - fairly thin body and medium carbonation . nothing special on the mouthfeel .

s : nice nose . lots of vanilla and caramel , with well integrated bourbon . this is about a 4.25 in the nose , but i 'm feeling generous . t : not as good . the second half of this beer is just unpleasant : hot , overly bitter , and astringent .  nitro-can encouraged frothy tan head , superb retention , some lace , almost opaque hue .  the taste is sweet and smooth , with a hint of hops but the most prevalent taste is of lemon . finishes with a very refreshing aftertaste . i would defiantly suggest this beer to even non craft beer drinkers .

aroma is weak , very faint hops and a little malt .  bottle into an english pint glass appearance - dark brown/red hue reminds me of high grade saddle leather . a very handsome brew , sir .  the flavor too is ever so slight wine barrel aging with a weird and awkward type sour . it 's really off putting . this barrel aging was awful . this beer is weak and severely overrated . it was awful both times .

deep black in color-nice slight tan head that lingers down the glass.subtle aroma of malt.slight chocolate smell.roasted flavor dominates.hints of licorice.very subtle sourness in the backround.full bodied mouthfeel.a very drinkable beer-comes off more as a stout then old ale to me.very enjoyable none the less .  pours a completely opaque pitch black . light brown head with some big bubbles around the edges .  m : not too bad , there was a little bit of body .

s : here 's my one complaint : light citric hops , light caramel malt . good , but way too light . my nose was wet before i picked up anything .  poured from the 22oz bomber into a belgian duvel glass . appearance- beer pours a clear brown with red hues with a finger thick cap of irish cream foam .  this feels thin for some reason . carbonation is good and proper .

smell : quite sweet , hints of fruit and a bit metallic with a hint of tomato . not a lot of hops here .  this amber ale pours with a clear amber body topped by a thick head with lots of lacing left on the glass .  mouthful mouthful is okay . has decent carbonation , but i 've had better as far as carbonation goes .

s-the nose is light , pale malt up front , notes of citrus with grassy hops behind .  beautiful nitro thick creamy tan head over a black body . has a lovely way of settling to a creamy solid chunk that wo n't spill out of the glass if you tilt it .  despite the nearly opaque black color , the flavor of this one is surprisingly light . there are sweet malt notes , a delicious fruitiness and some fairly rich yeasty , estery notes . i keep over-looking this brewery , but every time i try one of their beers im usually pretty impressed . this particular beer is tasty , refined and very drinkable . recommended .

not much smell what was there was slight maltiness . great kolsch flavor , really nice for the style .  nice tight eggshell head . nearly brilliantly clear .  mouthfeel is ok. a litte too dry for my liking though .

s : chocolate malt , cocoa , coffee grounds and a hint of plastic that fades out after a few minutes of sitting out .  pours a cloudy amber brown into a wine glass with two fingers worth of frothy , white head . the lacing clings to the inside of the glass for dear life , and is quite exquisite .  very ashy , very charred , and it really lacks some body and sweetness to back up the astringency . feel is very light , a shame , because a thick , chewy , silky body is a necessity in the style .

the nose was surprisingly subtle ; could n't pick up much besides a distant chocolate and tartness .  this poured out a rich golden color with a lovely red-orange glow that danced reflective light off my fingertips . a rush of tiny bubbles formed a thick white head that dissipated at an average pace , leaving foamy crystals that clung to the sides of my tulip glass . superb !  it was my first fruity beer . it kinda tasted like an apricot . i was expecting most of a fruit taste like wine , but no . and i liked the picture on the bottle . and since it came ithaca i just had to try it . over all the beer was worth it . it 's good . : )

no smell whatsoever .  poured into michelob celebrate glassware ; awesome head retention for several minutes . fantastic lacing .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied and syrupy with a bit of sharp carbonation .
s : mild malt aroma with a slight hop note in the end .  looks really viscous and is extremely dark . excellent cascading head .  mouthfeel - very enjoyable borderline complex character .

mild roast with a bit of fruit like character .  this brew poured a medium creamy long lasting dark brown head of small to large sized bubbles .  taste : mirrors the smell , but the flavors are weaker than their aroma counterparts because of a thin mouthfeel .

nice job by a new ( to me ) bartender . amber shade to the brew , with a slight aroma of sweet malts and hops . nice representative of the style .  impressive looking ale..bright clear golden yellow , with a rich , thick , creamy head and literally walls of lacing .  mouthfeel is fullbodied , and slightly cloying .

trying back to back kolsch beers today , poured into a standard pint glass a light clear golden with a large fluffy white head that never fully settles , another spritzy lookin klosch , this head a great head to hit as well.aromas are muted , only some light toasty grain , this is a crisp dry kolsch , spicy/herbal hop and toasted grain flavors mainly , i like the crispness of this beer.now this a perfect warm weather brew that again isnt a throw back beer , i like this alot .  a : this pours pitch black . a large tan head ( over two fingers forms ) with great retention .  the only thing i felt was it could use a little more carbonation to balance the tart flavor and make it more perky .

s : most noticablly wheat with additions of banana , grapes , rose and coriander . t : really tart , sour brew .  very pretty two-finger head .  body is on the thin side of medium and the finish is both mildly astringent and slightly bitter .

s : not a lot of aroma . mainly sweet , bready malt . t : quite earthy , probably from the yeast , as well as the hops . d : very drinkable .  pours an opaque , oil-slick jet black with a big , durable tan head that never completely goes away .  mouthfeel : bubbly and light body . the mouthfeel is a little peculiar and affects my experience .

it 's a bit subdued though . overall , a very nice iipa .  pours a lovely , crystal clear dark amber color with a nice 1/2 '' tan head that persists all the way down , coating the entire glass with heavy lacing . the best looking ipa i 've ever seen .  the mouthfeel is decent , but could be a bit more robust to support the flavors .

s - mild aroma ( i wish i let it warm up a bit , at 11 % i would n't be surprised if it opens up ) . soft woody hops . touch of melon . d - the hops are strong enough to slow you down , and while not harsh in your mouth , the alcohol lets you know it 's there .  the head of foam was nothing short of exceptional . it had a 1 1/2 inch creamy head of tan colored foam that looked good enough to eat .  muted roastiness and chocolate malt notes . deep black body with a decently firm and lasting thumb thick head . roasted coffee beans int he fore followed by toasted and burnt bread and some mild chocolate notes int he finish . finish is dry and coffee tinged great classic porter .

nothing exceptional here .  the pour was very good and this is easily one of the best looking beers i have ever seen with its excelent head , color and champagne like bubbles .  m - a little strong on the carbonation for my taste .

smell : aromas of spice , yeast , and a hint of citrus . what it lacks in smell it makes up in appearance and ever moreso , taste .  pours pitch black and thick , and makes a milk chocolaty looking huge amount of foam .  mouthfeel - rather bubbly , fairly thin .

subtle aroma , what is there is nice ; roasty , malty , sweet . taste is very good ; sweet molasses , malted chocolate , bitter chocolate , a little hops , finishes bitter-sweet . it is very pleasant to say the least !  a deep mocha head emerges from the bottom of the glass to form a nice half inch layer . exactly the appearance a big stout should uphold ; textbook .  decent palate , a little thin like the others in the series , but fairly smooth .

smells solid . a nice malty backbone , a touch of caramel and some slightly toasted wheat .  beautiful , clear dark copper color . excellent clarity here . a moderate cap of light whipped cream , tiny bubbles mostly , sits at the top . this is as pretty as an ipa can be .  it has a pretty high carbonation .

aroma is not much . just pils lager aroma . taste is great .  tremendous head and a deep , dark brown body . the lowly brown ale usually isnt going to win beauty contests , but this is about as good as one will look .  im augustus gloop : ) m - carb a little low , a little on the sweet side .

s - was not very aromatic although i could faintly detect some coffee maltiness . t - while i am not a frequent drinker of porters , i found this one to be good . very tasty . d - the overall effect of the smooth taste and the unexpected light-medium body made this porter very drinkable . i think porter fans will appreciate its coffee/chocolate characteristics and more casual porter drinkers will find it very approachable . very good on its own and would probably pair well with a hearty stew , a roast or possibly a chowder .  perfect appearance . really smooth 2 finger ashy cocobutter brown head . dark black balled body that looks beautiful in my snifter .  not too many micro 's that come out with a light ale . hats off to them for bringing this to market to allow folks who are used to drinking american mass producted swill to move into a easy drinking michigan micro brew . lighter than sam adams but more flavor then the bud and miller 's of the world .

the nose was a very faint , if any .  this beer poured black with a large tan creamy head , that lasted through out the beer .  nice flavors , with a nice two-row malty sweetness and a huge piney and slight citrusy hop flavor that is very much in front ; good overall , but very unbalanced , even considering the style . goes down fine , but there is quite a bit of hop scratchiness .

smell is suprisingly light . some malts and a citris hop profile , but not in big quantities .  a : pours a clear golden with a massive frothy , rocky head with great sustain .  m : a bit overcarbonated , dry , thin , light-medium bodied .

the aroma hints at more of a tart belgian ale than a ami wheat or even s witbier . the atste is mildly tart , this is ok becasue it 's so differebt from what i 'm used too .  pours a luscious and very tempting opaque sable with a thick , frothy tan head that leaves a fair amount of lacing .  it 's sort of smokey but in an artificial way . rubber and alcohol . the rubber turned into a slightly smokey malt flavor but still lingered in there . alcohol dominated any sort of flavors coming through . i just did n't enjoy this beer at all . if i ever cross paths again with this beer i 'll re-review it .

s : moderate hop aroma slight malt . t : initial sweetness followed by strong hop bitterness .  an agressive pour was neither necessary nor desired to result in a glass 1/3 full of beer and 2/3 dense , off-white foam . robust carbonation , with many small bubbles .  the mouthfeel is light , but hey , its a light beer ! for drinkability , again , one of the beers that could probably never offend me .

heineken light smells exactly like a skunk . if you enjoy the smell of burning tires , heineken light is the beer for you .  nice retention and very good lacing . clear amber color makes this an all around great looking brew .  the palate is bland , sweet , and clean . the strongest aspect of this beer is its mouthfeel , it is medium , sturdy carbonation , very basic but appropriate .

smell : not much here , smelled like your average porter . weak coffee scents were all i got . taste : like guinness draught with some balls .  pours a bright , clear gold , with a three finger high column of dimpled white head . good head retention too . really it is absolutely gorgeous . i do n't think a saison could look any better ... the aroma has a bit of citrus ( lemon ) , slight grass , and mild pepper .  mouthfeel is a bit fizzy , and another beer where bottle-conditioning would have a positive impact .

pours like strong coffee except it has virtually no aroma . as mentioned earlier , there is no nose with this beer .  pours a dark brown-black with a huge creamy tan head that retains well and laces the glass .  i like a little heavier of a mouthfeel than this offers , but the lighter feel is not surprising considering the crystal appearance .

smell : pretty faint compared to what i was expecting . some burnt malt , stout-like aroma . faint hops aroma , crisp ut a littel disapointing . improved as it cooled revealing more burnt malts . wonderfully complex stout .  a - extremely dark brown body with a dark brown head to go along with it . the thick and frothy head started out at about 4 inches and ever so slowly faded down leaving a thick humocky topography .  carbonation is fizzy on the tongue where it should be soft and creamy .

smell is mildly skunked but at least less so than their last oak aged beer i tried .  this is a real doppelbock that is rich in flavor . the smell is that of over ripe fruit . i love all bock beers especially doppelbock so i can say with out a doubt this beer is going into my top 10 .  slightly under carbonated for my taste but not really a flaw .

aroma was surprisingly weak , notes of smoky roasted malt and hints of coffee .  glass : snifter temp : cellared @ approx 45 degrees this is perfect appearance for a stout . it 's as black as black can be . the head takes a long while to recede to a nice thick surface covering , over an 1/8th of an inch thick . visually , this is quite an impressive beer .  but there are hints of dark fruits that seem to disintegrate on your tongue , slight astringent alcohol tate/smelll this is defiantly a very drinkable brew .

the aroma is very appealing . sweet hoppy fruit notes , strawberry licorice , apricot nectar . very nice .  apperance - this beer poured from the tap thick and creamy . it was bright golden yellow once the body cleared up from the nitrogen . nice thumb thick head .  feel seems to be about medium in body , but slightly watery , with a lingering semi-bitter dark unsweetened chocolate/coffee bean aftertaste .

has an awesome color too it , good all the way around ... not very scented though but that to me is by far the least important qualty of a beer .  the color is a deep , very pretty dark amber . this is a beautiful beer .  mouthfeel was ok .

smells mostly of sweet malt , with some fruit and wine-like oak . very nice complexity where the malt sweetness starts off , followed by fruit and some spices , then it has a crisp finish that 's malty and tails off with some more malt that 's roasted , delicious and dry . an overall great beer that is belgian in style and complexity , even though it 's a french beer ; clearly the belgian influence has dominated the taste of this beer , which i am thankful for .  pours a golden-yellow with a huge white head . lace is all over the glass . beautiful .  feel is a bit coarse , but just a bit .

the aroma was subtle and i tried to pick up the smokiness but really could n't . mostly it smelled like a pale ale just not as hoppy and citrusy.the beer has a nice velvety mouthfeel but was a lot crisper than i thought it would be .  let 's start with first impressions : this big beer makes a big impression on appearance . dark and sinister looking , the rough-textured mocha-colored head sits atop the black body like a russian fur cap . lacing is full and sticky .  perhaps another way to explain the feeling would be a textured shandy . noting the high praise this saison received , i have trouble fathoming such a bad experience .

those of you who could n't smell this , be glad , the smell was horrid . smelled like rotten egg . it took me a few hours to get over the smell of it .  great retention and lacing !  very pleasant indeed . great hop character . this is a fairly balanced ipa . hard to say , it might just be because this particular bottle is more on the room temp side , but i would like more effervescence . a good beer all in all . i will be sure to drink it again , only a little colder and faster . more drinking , less typing ... .

very clean aroma and taste , classic sammy smith . the complex grain profile makes it so delicious .  pours out a slightly chill-hazed brassy tangerine with a wealth of tiny bubbles making their way to the head . head is massive , foamy , and almost spills over the top . leaves some near solid lacing on the glass .  smell is a cross between musty and estery at first , then just corn . tastes like corn , but considerably worse than a typical macro . it has some off flavors , that i ca n't really identify . bad .

i like a good pale ale and this one was just right . is paired very well with japanese food .  reddish copper in color , impressive head with incredible retention and massive lacing down the sides of my pub glass .  on the thin side , and i dont get much carbonation .

the initial pour sends a wafting of grapefruity hop notes into the nose , though sadly the aroma fades away , becoming very subdued .  a : pale straw , great carbonation , crystal clear , and a lovely full head .  wonderful flavor , with deep malt tones , a great smokiness , hints of peat , and a touch of caramel . goes down quite smoothly , but it does have an odd , almost generic , flavor on the tongue at the very end .

the nose is entirely too one dimensional though . it smells almost like straight up cold coffee , with just barely a appreciable hint of dark chocolate .  the color was hazy lemon yellow with two fingers of rocky , yellow-tinted head . the cap retained itself beautifully and the lacing was in solid bands .  s : slightly citrus , faint banana t : citrus & yeast & candy sugar m : bit thin , but not uncommon for a triple o : i am sure age did this one well reading the prior reviews ... think i paid $ 3.50 for it , well worth the price and a good brown bagger at a tasting .

honey is very pronounced edging near a braggat . both in the aroma and the taste . the hops are non-existent until the finish were they are quite strong . overall i think it 's too sweet and i could barely finish the sample . too cloying .  pours almost a coffee brown with a hint of amber red in the bottom of the glass . nice 2 fingers of off white bubbles tops the glass .  it is medium-bodied with soft carbonation and seems perhaps more watery than i 'd expect . it leaves the mouth feeling a bit astringent .

the aroma was mostly a bready malt smell with just a hint of hops and a bit of a clove scent . i would prefer more interesting citrus flavors , but it is still very good .  pours to a very dark brown , only slightly ruby colored liquid with a massive fluffy white head that coats the entire circumference of the glass in a perfect frilly victoria 's secret crotchless panty-style lacing . she really is quite sexy looking .  mouthfeel is somewhere between ultra clean and a little soapy - if that makes sense .

s : i smelled hops and some sweetness maybe from cinnamon , that 's about it . d : it is a great christmas ale .  head holds well making this an incredibly good looking beer .  mouthfeel is a little light for a beer this big , but that would likely improve with age . carbonation is a tad too prickly for my personal tastes .

not much of a nose on this english ipa .  the way the carbonation and creamy foam mixes with the super dark body of the beer is gorgeous . through the glass , it looked like the bubbles were cascading like a waterfall , only upwards . anyway , the body is opaque and the head is super creamy and tan in apprearance . the head stuck around for a long time and left decent lacing .  being from the adirondacks i quickly likened this to adirondack brewery 's bear naked ale , yet a lager version , and a bit more wheat-filled . the mouth-feel is nice , but nothing special ( not flat , not too bubbly ) . in short , its a dandy brew- we all enjoyed it and thought it was pretty cool to have something that is only currently available in growlers from the brewery ( spring seasonal ) , drink up !

appearance : straw color , effervenscence , good head , awesome lacing smell : this is blasphemy but it smelled sorta like mgd .  from the nitro-can , started as a full glass of thick , creamy foam . slowly the foam turned over from bottom to top revealing a deep yellow beer with a steady half-inch foamy white cap .  it seems to light and over carbonated for a stout .

aroma : a bit unpleasant : musty and earthy .  got this one in trade , thanks eric ... a : perfect look . thick 1 and 1/2 inch off-white head that slowly fades leaving nice lacing around the glass .  my only complaint is that i wish the mouthfeel was thicker . it was smooth , but a bit watery to me .

buttery nut aroma .  pours a pitch black color with a tan colored head that fades slowly , leaving a thin layer of foam and some heavy lacing .  the carbonation is mild ; there are almost no bubbles at all .

smell : light malt sweetness is so soft it is almost hard to detect .  appearance , beer pours a red golden with a huge pillowy off tan head that lingers and clings to the sides of the glass thickly . big bubbles and small bubbles intermingle making this beer look alive on the pour . the red gold color is more of a ruby when held to the light , this is one impressive looking barleywine .  yack ! i 've had this lots over the years , but this time it got a major problem with butterscotch . aroma smacks me down wth that butterscotch - ugh . but , somewhere in there is some malt and a little chocolate , good malt . flavor is butterscotch - blaaahh . ca n't finish it . draft lines are clean here too . no more , pleeeeze

crazy lacing & head retention s : leafy hops , not much else t : leafy hops , biscuitty malt & some sulphuric notes , plus a bit of citrus hops up front . finishes fruity , dry , a bit chalky even & with leafy hops mf : medium bodied with low carbonation & nice balance drinks easy for the abv , wished the hops & or malt stuck out a bit more , but a solid effort , this is probably much better on cask , i 'm betting  appearance : as poured the beer is a nice lightly hazed golden apricot color with a 1 fluffy off white head that leaves rings , legs and small patches of lacing as it recedes .  carbonation is a bit low for the style .

light nose of little consequence . the taste is very nice with limited and pleasant spiciness and a nice bread sense .  pours a dark brown with a healthy sandy light tan head that lingers at a fairly thick level and laces the glass heavily .  m - it drys out in the mouth a little too quickly for me .

as a long time drinker and former hamms beer route salesman this is still a beer that holds up well.ca n't count the cases of this that has passed my lips but wish i could find it in the bottle . now if they would only bring back hamms preferred stock ... we 'd be back in hog heaven . for the money its a real drinkable beer .  this beer has a frothy , three finger thick , almost rocky pale white head that sits atop a body that is brilliantly clear and a pale straw color . the color is about perfect and the head is one of the longest lasting and best ones i have seen on a macro-lager .  mouthfeel medium full for the style with carbonation that is a bit too strong for my taste .

has a solid malt flavor with a huge hop aroma . i could use a tad more bitterness but that is just a personal preference .  some of shakespeare 's stuff is pretty dark , but shakespeare stout a nihilistic black , with a big head the color of creamy coffee . the little black bubbles peppering the head make it look alluringly like a chocolate chip cookie .  too cloudy and not nearly enough hop profile . at first i wondered if the waitress had given me the wrong beer . i would have characterized it as a weak summer wheat beer had they not told me it was a plisner . there was nothing objectionable about the beer itself . i drank it all . it just was n't what a pilsner should be .
the smell was very modest and faintly malty .  a - has two full fingers of ultra-fine reddish-tan head . what a beauty !  medium carbonation .

nothing outstanding .  pours crystal clear orange-amber color with a dense 2 finger off white head with great retention that reduces to a fairly thick lacing cap that lasts the entire glass .  m- the mouth feel is a bit overly carbonated , yet not thin .

smell iis ok , but slightly astringent with little discernable difference between malt and hops . beyond the astringent aspect , there is a slight flowery essence . i would highly recommend this beer as a delicious , drinkable ale for a hot and sweaty day .  probably the most impressive head i have ever seen on a beer .  mouthfeel is medium with more carbonation that i expected due to no head showing up .

nice crisp pils aroma . smells nice and bready but not very complex . tastes great . very crisp and refreshing .  i really enjoyed this one . perfect copper looking beer .  m : thin , do n't take that the wrong way though but easy drinking .

definatley sweet smelling but not overly pungent . bland ! holly crap i was expecting more , dont know why but what a let down when it hits the toungue .  appearance : beautiful deep gold color , a lushous two-fingered layer of white foam , lots of rising bubbles , good head retention , flecks of lace aroma : dusty , cinnamony , malty , honey-like sweetness , floral hops , plummy fruitiness , perfumy ( sage and roses ?  light to medium bodied , carbonation seems to be at the right level .

a hazy copper pour with a sustaining head , the beer smells sort of indistinct for the hops and malt you 'd expect .  pours a deep , opaque mahogany , almost black . there 's a 3-finger cafe au lait head with a moderate amount of layered lacing .  m : the mouthfeel was a bit thin compared with other sours , although this did not detract from the overall enjoyment of the beer .

my first beer with agave added . smell : hints of honey and orange blossom , slightly muted .  beautiful 3 finger head , caramel , frothy and persistent , reddish mahogany nice stream of bubbles , good lacing ; if this did n't look so inviting i would put it on a shelf and leave it there forever !  the last 2/3 of my beer was a bit thin , but this was quite refresing and very easy to drink .

regeneration very good . hoppy front end , chocolate notes , roasted malts and a long finish , nicely balanced , oatmeal , any spices were subdued .  a- pours a brownish color with red hues noted against a white background . the clear nature of the beer allows me to see the carbonation , which is modest looking at best . the head is plentiful and puffy looking , retaining well and leaving behind a thick film of dense foam on the glass .  m- actually the mouthfeel is n't that bad but it was really hard to focus on that while i was drinking joan rivers perfume .

s : a very light scent in general but the coriander spice fragrance comes out with a slight clove banana type aroma . t : has a truly unique flavor .  the head is quite impressive , off white in color , composed of thousands and thousands of tiny bubbles .  mouthfeel is too thin for my liking .

i do agree the the smell is light but i get hops and very faint citrus .  i poured this one from a 12oz brown bottle into a tulip pint glass . a= this stout poured black as night with zero light penetration . with a very aggressive pour , the dark tan head rose a full 2 '' and took a long time to settle to a thin cap .  mouthfeel : both the carbonation and body are on the higher end of the light range .

aroma 3/5 nondescript . bunch of swirls coax a slightly chocolaty malt aroma , and perhaps oak . some of the usual stout aroma when the beer got warm enough .  it lasts forever and settles to a nice pillow . usually old ales have no head at all . i 'm amazed this looks so good .  mouthfeel is okay , no carbonation to speak of .

s - malt ; i always find that sa beers are lacking the aroma department t - malt , malt , malt : notes of caramel and toffee a discernible along with a slightly vinous , fruity quality .  there is a magical cascading effect within the beer as it settles . a beautiful off white head remains perfect throughout the experience lacing is awesome .  mouthfeel - foam is scarce and small bubbles and light caramel that fades quickly . slightly thin .

s : smells of plastic and some astringent malts .  dark brown/black body with a dense chocolaty head . a thick cap remained throughout .  slightly sour , a bit thin , highly carbonated . quite drinkable .

a translucent orange body , sorta lie copper or a slightly lighter orange blossom honey . a solid malty body , chewy and a bit hoppy , hell of a lot better than the nose . this is a solid english pale ale , solid body of hops and malts , nothing to let you down initial taste is a bit bitter with mostly malts .  into a pint glass , pours a kind of honey amber copper , with a heaping huge off-white head , settling down to a thick foam , lots and lots of lacing in rings and spiderwebs and bubbles down the glass . and upon second pour , the head swells again to two inches of foamy delight , a great big mustache is my reward .  mouthfeel is medium-light , and carbonation is medium-light .

been a while since i 've had a stout . burnt roasty smell with coffee , cocoa , and cream ... a smokey , woody , hot cocoa almost .  a : pours a cloudy , medium brown color with two fingers of billowy , pale tan head . exceptional retention and lace , vigorous carbonation .  average feel for the genre i 'd say . it 's pleasant in sips and gulps and a few of em would be just as enjoyable as one .

pours a light brown with a reddish tint , it dosnt have much of a scent to it except for a slight cirtus .  pours dark mahogany with a thick tan head .  mouthfeel the beer is slick on the tongue with strong carbonation . the body is a little lacking , medium-light .

the aroma is exceptional as you can smell this ale when you pour it out of the bottle . deep dark fruity ester mingle with a citrussy coriander spiciness make for an excellent aroma , this is the first beer i have tried in which the aroma exceeds the flavor . the rich aroma led me to a letdown as the flavor was much more subdued than i expected . the body of this ale is an immense letdown as a scotch wee heavy imo should have a bit more viscosity and sweetness but this is a rather thin ale in terms of body . the scotch ales always throw me off due to the lack of hops and for some reason i have a hard time enjoying tha malt flavors unless they are balanced by a signifigant amount of hops .  served in the `` new '' sam adams lager pint glass , the beer pours dark , dark brown ( might as well be black ) with an inch frothy brown head . head retention and lacing are both pretty good .  bought this over a month to two months a go and decided to give it a go . it is an ipa so it does have a nice bright orange to copper color . the taste and the smell are sweet and fruity , the only bad thing i have to to say about it , is the taste of tea is very lacking . i cant pick it up but , other than that i wish that stone , ishii and baird made this more as a yearly offering , cause its really good

overall i enjoyed it , the smell still does n't please me but the beer in general is quite good .  poured into my duvel tulip a - pours a dark reddish-brown color with a huge pillowy tan head . this is absolutely beautiful , and took a good 3 minutes to recede enough for me to drink it !  average body and carbonation .

smell is dark fruit , roasted malts , vanilla , oak , and a touch of coffee/chocolate .  appearance : extremely voluptuous head , almost overflowing , with lots of carbonation and bubbles . color is pitch black , no nuances there .  it 's got a little bit of a piney finish that 's quite refreshing . maybe closer to watery , but not bad . d- very drinkable esb .

bitterness is very balanced and in the background . very drinkable lager ! clean tasting and pretty smooth .  pours a beautiful clear golden orange with a plentiful fluffy head and excellent sticky lacing .  had this today on tap @ hibernia in boston . diacetyl ? in an ipa ? and what 's with the low hop profile and mega-sweetness of this beer ? my pint was quite cloudy too . beer drinkers of the world ... this is not an ipa , and it 's a pretty crappy beer to boot .

nose is predominately light brown sugar , and a hint of ginger .  a : pours absolutely perfect ! cloudy , creamy orange body with a glorious mountain of head that fills just to the edge of the glass and hangs around until the glass is empty .  m - it 's a bit thin for the style .

some faint nutty malt aromas -- not much else really detectable in the nose . very pleasant taste -- toasty malts up front , big biscuity flavors in the middle , giving way to some citrus toward the finish with the slightest traces of buttery diacetyl , followed by a hoppy finish .  appearance - this beer arrived in a tall , branded pilsner style glass and was yellow-orange with a offwhite , two finger head exhibiting good retention and heavy lacing . impressive carbonation showed off the whole time .  this beer is not awful but it is not good either . if use to be better , i think , back in the days before aluminum cans and pull up tabs . beer is fizzy and gives a good head and that is about the only good quality it has .

s : i got virtually no scent until it warmed up and i got chocolate and nice coffee but mostly roast and alc . t : great taste , smooth high gravity , the coffee taste is great .  you get the beautiful nitrogen show and then it settles with a dark brown , almost black , body with a nice light tan head .  maybe a touch too much carbonation .

edit & lt ; this is actually a review for `` guinness extra cold , '' ( that 's right - they were actually bragging about how cold a stout was ) which was damn near ubiquitous in otherwise decent pubs throughout the uk when i was there in the summer of 2001 . guinness extra cold is basically the same as what one often gets when having a guinness in an american bar . oddly enough , when i was in england two years ago this was the only kind of guinness i found in the pubs i ventured into .  a - huge head , really fluffy . beautiful amber color with appealing haziness .  mouthfeel is pretty thin and wine like tbh the beer has more wine qualities than beer , carbonation is also a bit high .

s- wheat , slightly hoppy , somewhat faint . d- i find this beer to be extremely drinkable .  a : this thing has a huge head . a perfect billowy light-tan colored head with so much fluff , it might as well be whipped cream . the beer is a darker shade of brown when poured , and nearly black in the glass .  mouthfeel was medium with a mild lager sweetness accompanied by loads of off flavors , including apples and grapes .
the aroma is pretty muffled by the head .  a : pours opaque jet black with a formidable tan head -- nice retention .  mouthfeel : medium bodied .

the scent is pretty muted , it smells woody with some spicing and a tiny bit of citrus the flavor profile is interesting , it 's one of those distinctly staged brews .  the beer is an oil black , with no foreseeable brown hue when held to the light . the head is impressive , huge , sea-foam that stays around for a long , long time .  some hop aroma and flavour , a little to light in the body for my liking .

smell : yeasty wheat , dry and straightforward , expect for a slight strofoamish hint in the background .  this one pours a hazy yellowish orange with a white head that just will not go away . looks great overall .  ran into the maui brewing company while killing time until our dinner reservations were ready . there was a very slight bitterness in the aftertaste but was well hidden in the passion fruit sweetness . found the beer to start like any average golden ale but the aftertaste was what i really liked about it sorta like an ice tea aftertaste .

the aroma is a pretty subtle combination of lemony and herbal notes .  the liquid is dark amber and clear and is topped off by a plentiful marshmallowy tan colored head . the retention and lacing are out of this world . mountains of foam cling to the glass indefinitely .  i did notice after a while that it has been pulled from tap that it acquires a lack of a better word , a buttery taste that really dos n't go good with anything . i do like this beer and i 'm not bashing it . the buttery taste in my opinion did not take effect until thirty or so minutes after pour . i do keep some in my fridge . i have shiner before to make burgers with , which turned out great . good beer for beer lovers .

smell was at first scent , that of a macro lager . not a whole lot in the smell department.. taste was pretty complex , yet smooth .  purchased as a 22 from wine and beer westpark in glen allen , va - tulip pours dark but with mahogany edges , perfect head with awesome lacing .  mouthfeel was a bit thin , but the taste was clean and minty on the tongue .

n = some hints of alcohol , skunk , fruit , but not a good indication of the taste .  bottle comes a fantastic cascading pour producing a thick , frothy tan head atop a translucent , deep brown body .  i could drink this one all night long . just the right amount of sweetness with a little more than expected carbonation . pale yellow in color , lemony aroma.very clean with little aftertaste . easy to drink and very enjoyable . will definately drink again .

ah ... sierra nevada pale ale ... . smell is mild and not tons of identity here . a bit of a metallic smell . nothing overpowering .  dark brown head over a black body . there were tons of good stouts opened at the tasting , but this rose to the top of the heap . lovely stuff  m - very carbonated , to the point that it almost stings on the way down .

smell is roasted grain , coffee , caramelized sugar .  thick dense white head with great retention .  a : solid black , modest lacing even at the beginning , but once the beer was gone so was the lacing s : malty , chicory , lingers nicely t : dominated by coffee ; bitter stout ; the oak comes through nicely ; not very complex m : casked , so it does n't really buzz in the mouth overall , a really good beer , but not as complex as i was hoping ; still , very worthwhile

above average head retention & lacing s : lemony with white pepper & orange peel t : follows the nose , also some breadyness & candi sugar , apple peels & general spiceyness up front . finishes with apple peel , lemony & herbal hops & a lovely spiceyness & just a bit of grapefruit at the apex mf : medium bodied , lively carbonation , very nice balance superb drinkabilty i could stay on this all night !  presentation : 750ml brown bottle , corked and caged , with great label , poured into a belgian-style chalice that 's been in the family for 3 generations apperance : absolutely stunning dark garnet brew with huge ivory whipped cream head , lots of carbonation with amazing cap retention smell : big powdery belgian yeast tones , a bit of juicy dark fruit , light phenols and spice ... it all melds together nicely , but nothing really jumps out individually , it 's a bit understated actually taste : much bigger/spicier than the soft aromas suggest ... .there 's lots of sweet spice up front here , with ( cloves ) ?  it 's almost too sticky and thick to be pleasureable , kind of like a toned-down bourbon county stout . i 'm not a big fan of the finish , which comes off like sweet wort of a stout ( oily and a bit thin ) . m : very thick , with some relief , but then a lingering silkiness .

the aroma is pretty unremarkable with the typical malt smell .  excellent retention . something you could stick your finger in and feel the foams welcoming grasp .  initial taste of a sparkling mouthfeel with a puckering sour cherries that coat the mouth incredabily . the palate duration is average . medium body .

not much of an aroma at all , but what is there smells `` like beer '' ... slightly hoppy and slightly malty . it smells like what you remember beer smelling like as a child . it is very drinkable .  appearance : pours into an allagash tulip a slightly hazy pale gold with a huge , fluffy , white , large-bubbled head . an insane stream of bubbles rockets up through the beer keeping the head constantly refreshed .  the mouthfeel goes a bit aloof here and has too much carbonation .

light aromas of sweet fruit and a hint of chocolate ... but it is very faint !  black hole is the visual m.o . the head is mammoth and very interesting . dark mocha color around the bottom near the liquid and a lighter tan color up top . very cool .  the only knock here is that it was a little thin . m = is it possible to be creamy and watery at the same time ?

very sweet sour nose and gives a consistent very thickish foamy head leaving lots of delicate complex lacing all over the glass .  the pour is a nice blackout black color with a good looking two finger head on it that holds it 's retention and has excellent lacing . the heads color is a nice dark tan color .  have you ever canned tomatoes ? if you have , you should be familiar with the smell and flavor tomatoes have when cooked . this beer had an overwhelmingly strong odor and taste of spicy stewed tomatoes . it was too strong to drink . i know this is not normal for this beer from the other reviews of it i have read ( and the style does n't allow for many strong flavors ) , but it was only days past the best by date and had been stored in a refrigerator . there was also some floating particles in the beer which i also assume is not normal , pilsners typically being filtered . i will come back and rerate , but i 've been told by some fellow raters that i should take this beer into account for my rating .

the malt smells wonderful but no hop aroma .  750 ml bottle cage & cork & gt ; chimay gob deep , dark amber color , red hues with a blissful carbonation with a two-finger deep head at first , solid white , thick and dense and lots of life , the retention is as good , if not better than any i 've seen . amazing look .  m- the mouthfeel is a little lighter than expected , almost watered down .

upon first pour the nose is negligent , revealing only a slight twinge of alcohol . very little hops in the nose .  i love the appearence of this beer , the deep dark color and the nice tan foamy head make for an inviting glass .  m : lighter body , medium carbonation , somewhat watery thin feel to the body , with a crisp finish .

the aroma was light as only some malts were detectable . overall a very nice brew that was very flavorful but not overwhelming for the food .  batch 77 a- a luminescent , cloudy , orange liquid with a thick and creamy bone-white head that is dense enough to dimple the surface of the liquid .  well , so ... if it 's a barleywine or imperial or whatever , well ... then it 's probably thin on the mouth , eh ?

) aroma is mostly malt but not very impressive overall .  the 2005 is a brighter copper , with the most beautiful , nearly unbroken sheet of off-white lacing on the other side of the glass . gorgeous . on the 2010 , no lacing , bigger bubbles , thinner cap .  this beer has a fairly heavy body , a bit too much for my tastes .

that is what i found myself doing today ... colt 45 is a classic malt liquor . the smell was skunky . i do n't know if it was left in the light too long at the store or what , it was skunky . i do n't care how poor i am , there is no way i 'm drinking this swill .  produces a huge , thick and creamy head with superb retention throughout the entire glass . just a beautiful looking beer .  mouthfeel was moderate , not super heavy or light .

smells deep , malty , nots of caramel , bread and munich . slight metalic note as well .  appearance - i really like this one , a rich caramel color and moderate foaming taste - hmmm .  it looks like a pale ale should , there 's some yeast on the bottom of the bottle and the head stays for a bit . i 'd rather have a bit more malt presence , it 's just too hoppy and bitter for me . drinkability , if i had to choose between this and a macro , i 'd take this . edit on 10-3-04 i 've raised my review score , since i 've either started loving the hop , my tastes have changed or the fact that this is one of the few decent beers you can get around here on a night out and i 've become more accoustomed to it .

no strong smells here , picked up on roasted barley a little bit .  this comes in a 750ml bottle and i like the art work on their labels this one pours a half a glass of beer and half a glass of head . beautiful thick white head that clings to the glass like no other . the body is a bright lemon yellow an cloudy .  the mouthfeel is slightly buttery but leans more towars a syrup-like feel . carbonation would be greatly appreciated and add a very unique feel for this beer .

no smell , no taste but a little sugar and so heavily carbonated that by the time i finnished i wanted to do a barney gumble-style burp .  pours a dark black color with a large tan head , fades slowly and leaves lots of lacing on the glass .  m : fine , nothing special d : probably too sweet for a lot of people , but i 'm a fan .

the nose ... wow . i get bubble gum and cotton candy , with a strong citrus and floral hop character . this smells fantastic ... eeeh ! ! it 's not a bad thing , just strange . i think it 's too aggressively hopped and unbalanced in the taste department for my tastes , but still damn good .  my first 5 for appearance , and it 's well deserved .  a : dark reddish copper ; flat head ; strong carb ; not much lacing s : strong raspberry aroma , very inviting ; occludes other smells t : expected sweet -- it is n't ; the raspberry dominates , but it 's quite sour , draped over a wheat-beer-like base ; i must confess , this tasted terrible to me ; it tasted like nothing else i 've had , so i do n't think this is something against the genre m : good carbonation redeems the experience a bit overall , a terrible beer , for me .

aroma is faint or nil . sharply carbonated and very little up front hoppiness . a welcome refreshment from over-oaked beers that have been popular with us craft breweries the past couple years . i would have guessed oak aged english brown as much as german dunkel , though .  a quick swirl brings nice crimson flashes to the glass , quite amazing ... the aroma flows to my nostrils from feet away .  m - pretty watery and thin .

by far the best smelling pumpkin beer i 've had , and one of the best i 've had , period , in a long time . t- not quite as good as the smell , but still pretty good . cinnamon , nutmeg , pumpkin , orange creamsickle , and alcohol .  cloudier than the surface of jupiter . a great looking , one finger head , sticks around for quite a while .  mouthfeel is a bit of a letdown.. crisp but not as crisp as i had hoped . overall drinkability is good , the taste makes up for what it lacks in mouthfeel .

the head was huge and creamy which gave off some strange aromas . something like peanuts and sour yeast .  a : beautiful , clear , dark ruby body under a majestic two-finger head of creamy , sticky tan foam . tons of lace . truly spectacular . s : a little underpowered - light acetic sting , some sweet fruit , and a bit of husky malt .  the beer feels just a bit thin on the tongue .

all of the pleasant aromas of the nose have vanished leaving some nasty diacetyl and way too much breadiness .  pours a vibrant amber with dark gold highlights and great head retention .  mf : a bit thin , light body , medium to high carbonation d : another winner from sierra nevada .

smells of noble hops and that 's really about it , pretty much standard for a german lager , i guess . tastes more bitter than i expected , and a little sweeter than i expected .  incredible looking esb . pours with the cascading effect and settles to a bright amber color .  mouthfeel is just a tad watery .

s - malt aroma accented by hops .  it was presented in a room-temperature glass with a thin , bone-white head with moderate retention . the color was spot on - a beautiful , deep-golden yellow with ne-quality clarity .  slightly thin ( but not watery ) on the mouthfeel , which turned me off initially , until i could appreciate all that was going on in this beer .

smell : it 's kind of a let-down smell wise actually . some slightly sour hops and some nutty malts . does n't really smell that great to be honest .  a : pours a crystal clear amber color with a fluffy white head that sticks around for a long time . without a doubt one of the best looking ipas i 've had in a while .  mouthfeel was very thin for the style , but added to the higher level of drinkability .

s- light sweet malt and some mild chocolate . pretty mild overall .  gorgeous looking beer s- getting a bunch of citrus , but the aroma is really weak .  m- medium body with medium carbonation . a bit to high carbonation for this brew but still has a light creaminess to it . nice blend of flavors just mouthfeel is lacking a bit imo . also the head could of been a lot better especially due to how much carbonation .

maybe it 's just me , but i did n't get much aroma from this . just a hint of toasted grain .  looks very lively . this looks amazing and out of control .  the mouthfeel was a little on the watery side but i did n't feel like it ruined the experience .

12 ounce green bottle appearance : clear yellow color with little head and little to no lacing smell : a little hard to describe but would say it has a strong bitter almost skunky smell taste : has a lot better taste then smell which was a little surprising .  huge off-white head formed with large bubbles , eventually forming large craters in the top of the incredibly retentive head . as good of head retention as i 've ever seen . perfect dipa appearance .  m -- light carbonation . good body with a lightly soft mouthfeel .

aroma is disappointingly mild . honestly smells like a watered down lot 6 with very minimal spirit presence .  a : pours an extremely dark ruby red that appears almost black .  kind of leaves your mouth feeling very acidic .

hay and some sweetness give this beer a fairly simple aroma . grainy flavored beer with some faint pale malt sweetness .  a - very very dark . very fluffy head and lots of lacing .  mouthfeel - medium body with a very active carbonation .

smell is a very subdued smoky chocolate , a bit earthy and a faint whiff of bbq sauce .  maredsous 8 on tap in a tulip glass . black cherry color with a nice creamy head . excellent lacing , thick on the glass .  first sip reveals a much thinner body than i expected and average carbonation .

s-very faint . citrusy hops , malt notes , and some sweetness .  pours jet black with 3 fingers of brownish , mocha head that just screams ice cream float . tons of sticky lacing & very good head retention s : roasty malt , rich , dark & fruitty with woody hops , & booze once warm t : roasty malt , dark choclate , herbal hops along with molasses , leafy & minty hops up front .  m : medium body ( maybe a little light for a stout ? moderate carbonation ( more than expected in a stout ? ) . mildly dry in the finish .

aromas is of carmel malts.nice , but a bit weak.body is medium with a bit too much fizz for me .  almost no froth , no noticeable bubbles , very good looking beer .  mouthfeel : the carbonation seems oddly low , but the body is medium light which gives the beer a little bit of oomph that it needs .

based on tasting notes poured golden with 1/2 '' of white head , with good head retention & very good lacing s : some herbal & lemony hops t : lemony hops , & a little breadyness .  a - pours a dark , murky brown with ruby highlights .  m - this is where the beer ranks fairly average for me . under carbonated and a little bit flat , would have liked it to be heavier , stickier , and have more of a bite .

s - very little nose . vague impression of american hops ; lightly sweet and citrusy .  a - this beer has an incredible appearance , murky dark brown with an awesome lasting tan head that leaves some foam and great lacing .  a beautiful creamy white head rests on top of a medium body . appearance is a transparent mild orange with a light brown hue . carbonation appears heavy but on first sip is found to be more moderate than apparant . heavy lace is left a head that never seems to go away . aroma is floral , clean , and crisp . flavor is hoppy and slightly bitter . toffee like flavor is prevelant in its aftertaste .

it did n't smell like much , which is dissapointing . i look forward to the roasted and hoppy aroma of russian stouts , but this one did n't come through very well .  black boss porter , poland the bottle is very bold and to the point , solid block cap , impressive . poured into pint glass : this beer is rich black color with a creamy brownish head , the head is small but retains well and long . the nicest red/mahogany color come thought when hit by light .  it was a little thin .

s - okay , you can smell the malt and you can tell there are hops although they are not predominent as in many ipas . d - very drinkable .  guinness is one of the worlds greatest beers , hands down . rich , tasty , creamy , heartwarming .  m- a little thin , but not too bad . nicely carbonated , with a slight bitter hoppiness at the tail end .

s : typical grain and bready aroma . t : surprisingly less bitter than i expected .  pours hazy gold with a massive , fluffy white head . very promising appearance , but way overcarbonated if you 're shooting for anything lambic-esque .  mouthfeel : it feels like an astringent hop bitterness , but i sure as heck ca n't taste any hops .

s : fairly subtle aroma of english hops , a bit overpowered by carbon dioxide - as with many bottle versions this one was probably overcarbonated for the style .  very pretty beer . deep dark brown , with a huge , tan head that stays for a while and leaves lovely lacing around the glass . just gorgeous .  m : light body , watery touch , smooth with low carbonated in the mouth .
musty aromas and smokey grains come in strong with this one . this aint no fru-fru grand cru micro .  impressive retention , plenty of lacing .  the body is light but somewhat creamy .

the aroma is pleasant but muted , with a nondescript sweet and somewhat tart character .  pours into a nonic the darkest shade of brown , almost black . huge frothy tan head that leaves gobs of lacing around the glass with good head retention .  m- smooth , but a tad thin . carbonation is good , as is the thoroughly smooth finish with a tad of warmth .

the aroma is light and a little metallic . a nice english style ale , in that it has the tea like dominance along with a leathery and slightly fruity finish .  poured from a growler into a pint glass . pours a deep , clear ruby-brown with wonderful garnet highlights when held to the light . a fat , frothy head of light tan foam shows marvelous retention , holding tight throughout and lasting to the finish , grabbing tightly to the walls of the glass , leaving behind thick , bubbly curtains of lace as the glass empties .  carbonation was fairly low , with thin to medium body .
the smell is a little odd to me , very tinny , almost like it was in a can .  an absolutely gorgeous looking beer !  4/5 m : surprisingly thin side of medium , slightly tongue numbing , spritzy .

however , for a cheap beer the can i quenched my thirst with was very refreshing . it will beat bud light always . miller lite has good taste compared to it 's peers in the cheapo light beer section . and if consuming large amounts of beer is your game this is your beer . it is best consumed very chilled and on draft .  pours a cloudy gold with a beautiful creamy two finger head that does n't let up much .  taste some roasted chocolate flavors . flavor lingers on the tongue after each sip . not quite what i would consider a savoring beer , but tasty none the less . i could drink this beer around the fire in the winter or after raking leaves in the fall .

smelled very malty with a little pinch of hops . tasted malty and sweet , with caramel and toffee undertones and a roasty finish .  beautiful looking beer : brown with auburn highlights ( no i 'm not a hair stylist ) . a pleasure to look at .  the mouthfeel is a little thin , very dry , but well carbonated .

the scent is a malty mix of grains and corn . very wheaty smell with a very slight hint of hops .  this is my first bigfoot so we will see how the talk stands up ... a- really dark ruby red in my snifter . big sandy , fluffy head perched atop . at this point the head seems unwavering . but it eventually faded leaving all sorts of lace .  m : pretty light-bodied . i was expecting something more viscous .

it smells like adjuncts honestly , not good at all . that smell is for suckers though .  pours copper in color , red hues and gets lighter the more you drink ... how surprising . a massive off-white head , tight bubbles of carbonation and superb staying power .  m - medium body , not a lot of carbonation .

i think if i were to drink this out of a regular pint the aroma would have come off better . t : again chocolate and coffee .  filled growler at whole foods - dfh snifter pours amazing , heavy looking brew with a nice fat head .  a malty mouthful without much carbonation . resiny flavors fill the mouth but do n't obscure the big malt . this one is quite drinkable with an interesting mix of flavors that rise out of the basic malty sweetness .

there is definitely a nice malty aroma as well . it definitely wants me to take a sip . t : the taste is somewhat disappointing to me following the pleasant aroma . there is n't a lot going on here .  makes a great presentation with three fingers of light tan head that sticks around for a good bit .  the carbonation is moderate high . i think it is a bit high for the style but the carbonation does not take anything away from the beer .

s : smells hoppy , nothing special going on really . some citrus .  pours a massive , incredibly thick , dense and chunky white head that is long lasting .  mouthfeel : high carbonation gives the impression of a thinner mouthfeel , and the carbonic acid and alcohol bite knock this one down a little in the mouthfeel rating .

scents i can pick up are grain , oats , cream , irish dry stout-esque . there is also some sour and hop notes . i reckon this is probably the epitome of an oatmeal stout .  multilayered rings everywhere - one of the best lace patterns i 've seen from a beer in a long while .  light feel with lots of carbonation .

feeling inside the neck , it is totally smooth so i have no reservation about the safety of the beer , but the carbonation is another thing ... aroma - roasted grain , kind of woody , a touch of coffee beans .  750 ml bottle , procured at the pacific park market in aliso , a : pours a pretty much opaque burnt orange . huge frothy white head from the bottle conditioning , leaving lots of lace .  the mouthfeel has average carbonation and ismedium bodied yet feels a bit thin at the same time , as it falls off the toungue quite quickly .

smells of boring malts and slight ethanol . faint candy aromas and some noble hops can be detected .  a- black beer into ayinger glass , huge head with infinite retention , probably 4 fingers on average . nice light mocha color and a ton of lace everywhere .  m : the only thing that let me down was the thin and carbonated mouthfeel .

the aroma is somewhat faint , i pick up some raisins and grains , pretty disappointing for a bsda .  very inviting . as the bottle says ... dark and dreamy . leaves rich foamy rings and walls of lacing .  the body is is a serious letdown , nowhere near rich/full enough and it crosses the line into watery . the carbonation is appropriately subdued , and does n't overtake the lackluster body .

the smell is a little off putting , but once you take the first sip it is very easy to get over the smell .  poured with a firm sturdy , foamed up head .  thanks walter a-a nice rich amber , good head , some lacing that turned into a small bubble ring s-a slight bready smell , some citrus ( makes me think of citra hop ) slight sweetness and then tart t- close to the same as the smell , there is a slight tangyness in the middle of the drink , it 's a good thing m- it 's moderately lively not as much bite and tingle i was expecting , a clean wet finish o/d- overall i really like this , it 's not the craziest ipa but it 's more than just decent , drinkability , i can see myself finishing this growler , this is a tasty beer and one i really like

unusual , overwhelming and lovely aroma of port wine , raisins and dried figs , hints of barnyard . i understand that some people find it cloying , but with a beer this rich in aroma and flavour , i accept the sweetness .  old plowshare stout is a very dark reddish brown ale with a frothy , bubbly light brown head that has great retention and leaves lumpy lacing .  m : i feel that this could have used a little more body and less carbonation , but overall ... not bad .

great lacing & head retention s : musty grain , herbal & woody hops t : follows the nose , rye peppery notes & crispness , plus a whisper of smoke & some grassy hops climbing up as well up front .  magic hat roxy rolles is a dim , deep reddish amber ale with a huge , frothy , rocky , creamy yellow-tan head that has excellent retention and lacing . looks superb .  m : earthy with a little grapefruit at the begining and a little pine at the finish . light carbonation .

smell is pretty mild with just a hint of roast malt and caramel .  perfect deep burgundy in color with a large , creamy and dense head of light tan foam .  i know some ba 's knock this onw because its not rare or amazing but i love it . if i am in a bar that i do n't think has a lot to choose from sam adams is the first word out of my mouth . its not too expensive and tastes good for what you pay .

smell : an earthy plant kind of smell , not a whole lot there .  pours a very deep brown from a 550ml bottle with a two finger head that retains . it 's opaque and pushes pitch black .  the carbonation and the color were good , but this did n't make up for the off taste and smell .

s - sweet roasted malts up front , then a little sourness like spoiled milk , and coffee .  whoa ... a : freakin ' black as my heart with a big tan head and lots of lacing . i really do think dark beers are the nicest to behold .  body is light and a bit watery , not too syruppy at all .

smell : a bit musty , some hints of banana in there , but not as appealing in the glass smell-wise as it was when i cracked the bottle . quite nice .  appearance is near perfect for this style .  mouthfeel was week and its not complex at all .
