it smells great , but the flavor just ca n't back it up .  the two versions are enough alike that any impression of 15th anniversary will translate to 16th ; therefore , my review of 15th anniversary follows : [ `` great divide 15th anniversary wood aged double ipa poured a beautiful copper with red hints when held to light . there was a massive creamy head and huge amounts of lace clung to the glass .  it 's light on body , and not especially interesting - but as fruit beers go , this was excellent .

the smell was excellent . i happen to love maple ( though i confess it is n't something i usually have in my beer ) , and the rich malty aroma of nutty maple notes was divine . ah , well this is a toughie for me because i 'm sure that this is the perfect beer for my girlfriends who are n't so crazy about things that resemble hops , barley , malt ... or hmmm.. beer .  had awesome retention and never showed signs of totally leaving .  ambrosial start , lots of malt , the top skimpy in feel with the finish having a delightful hop spicy bite , the carbonation moderate and the aftertaste droughty and long lasting .

i just love this beer along with pulled pork and ribs . upon smelling it , one will notice a slight sweet , malty aroma , but again , nothing special . where this beer shines is in the taste category . plus , it 's relatively cheap and easy to find in almost any store that sells more than 2 different types of beers .  a clear , dark amber , dark caramel colored beer emerges and is topped by a super creamy , white head . lacing is so dense i can barely see through the glass .  the body is pretty light though and clean .

s - light citrus hop aroma . not much else .  this brew is really gorgeous . nice hint of red , obviously , but the cloudiness swirls around and give the beer a nice look . head is off-white and puffy ; almost too big even with a careful pour .  ( m ) - this is where the beer starts to fail in my opinion .

smell- very light smell . a bit of grain and that 's about it . taste- very flavorful . very impressed with this one .  pours dark ruby with a gargantuan head .  mouth : such a light and watery mouthfeel that it becomes distracting pondering the feel when you should be appreciating the tastes . drink : the nearly too-light mouthfeel is redeemed by the drinkability of this brew .

s : herbaceous and slightly spicy , with some suggestion of lime citrus and fresh berry fruit . overall intensity of the smell is weak , giving an impression of vacancy . t : begins off-dry , with pithy grapefruit peel and crackery pilsner malt .  pours a golden orange with lots of suspended floaties . it has a huge spongy white head that retains well and laces the glass .  light bodied d- in moderation , this beer is perfect for a 2 beer session .

smell : not much of a nose on this one , although what there is of it smells like a saison ought to - some clove and spiciness along with a bit of citrus . taste : wow . overall : $ 14 a bomber was a bit steep , but i as i sit here enjoying this beer i am very happy that i splurged on it and i ca n't wait to split the other bottle with my girlfriend . this is great work by the guys at flossmoor , i just wish it had a bit more of a nose . one of the better saisons i have had .  a - quite a beautiful opaque orange body with finger hight white head . s - very malty ( strange for a hefe ) , average yeast aroma for the style and very spicy and sweet aromas .  had a typical pilsner mouthfeel .

it is also carbonated like a fresca soda , which seemed a bit odd , but it also helped to create a great aroma . i could really smell the cascades in this one when i poured it , but as the carbonation dies the hop aroma turned to a sweet malt nose .  poured this 12 ounce gem into a british pint glass and really enjoyed this smooth stout jet black appearance with 2 fingers of foamy tan colored head and retention ; this brew looks perfect , and staring at that glass rekindles an image of a british pub aroma of a sweet , biscuitty , and dark chocolate notes rich , full bodied , toasty malt , balanced with some hops which accentuate the side of my tongue , and a finish with a bit of zing that lingers on the palate .  feel left me a bit disappointed , however , as it was thin -- too thin for this big of flavor .

s : had no conception this was a strong ale . i found the smell to be mild with some fairly noticeable hop notes . t : hoppy but not overpowering . d : another reviewer noted a `` double pilsner '' and i think this is dead on . good thing i only had one .  pours a real nice rich caramel color with a solid dense frothy eggshell colored head with excellent retention and light lacing .  m : medium-full bodied , zero carbonation , silky . d : lacks the warming feeling that is usually related to a winter warmer .

this is one of the five winter beers offered at cambridge brewing , an irish dry stout . it 's drinkable like all the other dry stout , and quite tasty to boot .  lively . golden with a dense creamy head ... after all it is the cream of manchester ... a nickname i 've never felt comfortable with .  m : thin to medium viscosity , wet and distractingly acidic at times on the palate , with moderate carbonation .

the aroma is very weak . actually , i ca n't get any aroma , even with a big swirl .  a beautiful deep amber with ruby and copper hues . frothy white head with superb retention and lacing down the glass .  the body is lighter than i expected , and the taste is a little more burnt than i would 've preferred .

i really miss schlitz . schlitz has more of a hops flavor than any other american lager that i 've tried . but i think that schlitz is the best american adjunct lager out there today .  bottle ( 2003 ) churchill 's pub & grille san marcos , ca hazy yellow and golden with a nearly 2-finger white head . spots and lines of lacing down the glass . perfect for the style .  a medium to full body . possibly a little too thick ( syrupy was mentioned earlier by easyr which sums it up well ) as it took me a while to make headway down the glass ( unusual for me ) .

not a lot of aroma . crisp mouthfeel with a very nice bready , wheat flavor .  classic pride look - inviting transparent brown body with a reasonably large head , albeit casked up suds . leaves superb lace on the glass . awesome .  hate to say it , but the bottle/case i have is absolutely awful . other than a hint of coriander spice all i got was an overwelming sourness that made this one of the few i had to pour down the drain . they obviously put wayyy too much orange peel in their mix . if you can get past the sourness it is par for a wit bier course . i 'm hoping this was a bad/expired batch because ... .as far as mill street goes imo , stick to the coffee porter ...

the aroma was underwhelming but neutral grainy .  a - golden yellow with a huge , chunky white head . excellent retention ang big chunky lace up and down the glass . beautiful beer .  the taste is very good , it could use a bit more body but the flavors are great . tons of chocolate and roastiness dominate the profile but there is also some caramel and hops . the bitterness is at a great level in comparison to the sweetness , especially for the style . the guy below me has it right : not quite edmund fitz or blake butte but this one is one of the supeb examples of the style .

slight malty nose . starts mellow with some sweetness , finish is more malt than hop with no aftertaste .  from a bottle this poured a pale golden color . very clear , well carbonated with fine bubbles of co2 and topped off with a very attractive creamy head of foam . this certainly looks like a premium beer on the highest order .  great big head , perfectly tempting aroma , somewhat thin mouthfeel .

aroma - some light oak mingled with toasted grain , oak coming out much more as it sets up . no sign of any chocolate though . at length , the oak tends to dominate , likely assisted by the cayenne .  the beer itself pulls a pitch black into the glass and lets no light through . darkness is right . head retention is decent , leaves a perfect lacing behind .  m - not much fizz , easy drinking if you like it .

i smelled the apricot in this , as well as an odd corn-ish scent .  poured a deep dark reddish-brown into my guinness pint glass , and the tan head reached the top . beautiful .  the mouthfeel has a little bit more carbonation than i would like a brew of this calibre to have , thus the 3.0 .

surprisingly the aroma is relatively uneventful with some roasted malt and dark fruit .  pours brown with ruby hints . there are two healthy fingers of head ( boy , is this a live beer ) and the retention and lacing are top notch .  a tad thin .

strong vanilla notes , sugar , and faint chocolate aroma..southern tier really has a knack for completely nailing the nose on their brews t - do n't know if i could drink any more than the 9oz i was poured . this is incredibly sweet , and extremely rich . a perfect dessert beer .  appearance : a hard pour gave me about three fingers of sturdy looking off-white foam . good lacing and head retention .  mouthfeel is pretty good , but a little on the watery side for a chocolate/dessert beer . with the abv at 6 % and the body a little thinner than other chocolate stouts , one could have a couple of these in one night .

smell : strong coffee , roasted malt , sweet molasses , and some sweet dark berry aroma at the end . very small amount of alcohol towards the end .  appearance : poured a milky orangy and yellowish hazy color , typical of hefeweizens , especially authentic german ones . yielded a huge 3 finger creamy head that came right out of the glass but maintained its shape is it was thick and creamy .  m : a little thin in body d : good .

nothing to exceptional about the aroma . taste is very nice .  appearance- very dark , almost black pour . fat 2 inch head just about overflowing out of the glass and excellent lacing .  as for the go-down : thin & lightly carbonated , not aggressive but not annoying either & no aftertaste .

nose has almost nothing , light malts , some bread and a hint of butter .  pours out a rich and dark amber/auburn colour with a big eggshell white head that is big and frothy and has staying power .  i wont go through the details but if you are looking for an ipa do not drink this beer . it may sound novel , but black ipa is a retarded name for this , its not an ipa whatsoever . no hop flavor in the taste , not even close . im pissed i paid 4.30 for this . ridiculous .

the aroma is thick with heavily caramelized bananas and dates.sometimes it reminds me of nail polish .  i got this beer from the local gas station and thought i should try it because im a big fan of seasonals . the appearance is great just like every other goose island .  m - medium/light body with little carbonation good with spicy food .

sexy stuff . smells of roast malt and cocoa . very faint , should be stronger .  beautiful dark dark brown to black color with a nice brown head .  very dry with a bitter finish . a little sticky from all the sweetness .

some old , musty , leafy type aromas . smells like fall .  i was up in hell 's kitchen for halloween and my buddy took me to this place scruffy duffy 's ( coolest damn sports bar ever , check it out if your ever in ny ) and would n't let me order anything until i tried a guinness on tap . dark and smooth , almost coffee like .  maybe a little bit of caramel malts to balance out that chocolate . the body is ok - seems quite normal for what you can buy - but i 'd just like it a bit heavier . ) they could increase the body a little , maybe go heavier on the caramel malts and add a few more bittering hops .

smells of a typica quad , a bit spicey and harsh .  great looking beer .  now i understand the meaning of the word `` swill '' . i have an enormous amount of respect for european beers . avoid . trust me .

mild bakers ' chocolate with a roasted toffee smell . nothing exciting ; expected .  pours a deliciously cloudy , rich red with a nice thick & dark tan head .  the beer really lacks in body . carbonation is great . overall this was a good beer but the body creates a void .

lacey nice head : enough for taste , but not too much . a light mouth , followed by a rich , wide bitter taste , that lingers on the tongue . ) this makes it easy to quaff , yet still satisfying to linger over . paired exceptionally well with cold sesame noodles .  they share the same appearance if poured into the same glass , and the head is excellent . the taste is almost identical , with the can version being perhaps a little more bitter . i think these nitro cans are a great invention .  mouthfeel : medium-bodied with moderate carbonation .

the aroma is peaty smoky malts , leather and tobacco and maybe some vegetables . sweet toffee comes out as it warms . it 's unusual and odd and i 'm not sure if i like it .  black with a nice brown head that leaves good lace rings .  mouthfeel is fairly thin but not unpleasant .

now , i 'm an ale lover , so to be greeted by a lager was less than exciting . it goes down smoothly with a light aftertaste . i hope they are n't disappointed when i leave town .  appearance shows off a pale orange body with a cloudy clook . a sticky and rocky cream colored head sits atop almost 2 inches thick and slowly fades .  i found the body to be a bit thin carbonation medium to low .

smell : overall very mild caramel , brown sugar , and pine cones .  ahh , maudite . a beautiful beer from a beautiful brewery . pours a dark , stained oak or cherry colour . nice , 2 1/2 finger froth head that clings to the glass .  ( m ) smooth , oily , and flat . it 's a solid beer , or a solid base of a beer that could be improved only with a better mouthfeel .

s - all i could really seem to pick up on was the hops . pine and floral tones , but none of the malt that the description had hinted at .  beautiful ruby red color .  the huge head tipped me off and my first taste confirmed that this beer was infected . as a homebrewer , i 'm sure to sample every beer i brew before i give it to a friend . a little qc goes a long way .

huh . ok , big punch in the mouth for flavor . lovely beer .  poured into an ommegang chalice a reddish/purplish brown color with a solid half-inch of head.. perfect for the style .  m : the feel is slightly creamy but on the lighter side of medium bodied . could be a bit thicker here ... d : if you like coffee beers i could see someone drinking good amount of these .

nice black color with edges of brown , poured to a medium head that dissipated quite quickly . some malty sweetness up front which fades into a roasted malt taste . very small hop bitterness and most of the rest of the bitterness is from the roasted malts . goes down smooth and is quite tasty . ~jonathan passow  pours opaque black with a thick brown head .  the aroma was quite pleasant ... cirtus and floral hops with a light , bready malt . strong citrus hops up front , but it quickly became bitter , finished bitter and left a strong aftertaste . this is the first beer i 've poured out in a long time .

s : citrius hops , not the strongest aroma . t : bitter finish .  appearance : gorgeous beer with strong lacing throughout the entire glass . it looked sooo good , but there is almost no aroma .  i found that the beer smelled and tasted rather skunky , unlike most other beers that i had tasted and was deeply disappointed by it . it felt ok in the mouth and looked very nice in its green bottle but was not worth my time .

not much of an aroma , a slight nutty sweet smell . great sweet nutty , caramel , hint of toffee flavor .  very dark , nearly black , dark ruby edges , huge three finger head that falls slowly , becomes rocky , excellent lacing , and a cap that sticks around throughout .  m : full bodied but way too over-carbonated .

fairly non-assuming .  this beer looks perfect ! the bright , clear yellow beer , the fluffy white foam , the constant stream of fine carbon dioxide bubble , the everlasting lace left by each sip , it was exactly how a beer this style should be made to look like .  wtf did they do to this beer ? this is the first time i tried it since they put in the new brewhouse and i 'm not impressed . this used to be a wonderfully drinkable beer with orange and subtle spice flavors that made it quite refreshing . now its just overloaded with phenolics and all you can taste and smell is cloves . i ca n't get past the phenolic flavors enough to even finish a bottle . just horrible .

lots of yeast sediment . s- a little citrus but mostly smelling lots of big hops ! d - very smooth highly drinkable . reviewed 5-25-10 1st review !  bright transparent golden hue with a two inch frothy white head . lots of bubbles and good lacing . perfect appearance .  this beer was skunky ... skunky like a becks . and i couldnt find any other component of this beer redeeming enough to get over that skunkyness . my encounter with this beer started out ok ... it has a pale yellow appearance with a medium amount of head . taste exhibited becks ( or maybe even becks light ) levels of skunkitude , again with a bit of clove chasing after it to apologize . definitely not recommended .

this is a good beer . it poured a nice light amber with a small head . the taste was surprising and full flavored for the style with a good balance between hops and it 's great sweet malt backbone . the mouthfeel was exceptionally creamy .  this beer had a beautiful pour into a tulip glass . very dark and rich , with a dark roasted tan head that was very thick and continually rebuilt itself every time i swirled the glass .  but i felt the feel was a bit thin .

scent is hard to get a hold of i ca n't seem to get what i am looking for in this style . i do get nice hops , citrus and sweet malt but it is not as pronounced as i would expect . drinkability is exceptional for this 9 % beer .  wow , the pour results in an inch thick head and a nice burned orange body . the lacing left behind is like an intricate work of art .  not sure what they used for malt , but very sugary at first . the hops comes in and stays with you . almost like an ipa with the first snoot full of hops . i suppose they have to keep winning people over cause of the whole inbev deal . king of beers , so i am not surprised .
smelled of sweet malt and tart fruits .  poured an opaque ink jet black with a nice khaki head with good lacing .  m-medium carbonation . medium body , slick .

a - looks like dr. pepper or even a cherry coke s - caramel popcorn up front and bold , hint of caramel t - it tastes like caramel popcorn , candy , hazelnut and then finishes with a little coffee m - average on carbonation and finishes dry d - this beer is quite different but gets a little old because the smell and taste is like candy when i first opened this beer it hit me right away with all the popcorn .  a wonderfully thick head sits on top of an incredibly amber colored beer . my favorite look easily .  smooth mouthfeel with a moderate amount of carbonation and just a little watery in the finish .

this is one of my favorites , this is the alt which is available year around at the brewery on tap . the bottle pales in comparison to the tap version . love to spend a rainy afternoon enjoying an alt and the good company at the brewery . when at the berwery , i hope you get to meet nick , one of the last great bartenders - great way to spent a portland afternoon .  it pours midnight black with a huge , dark coffee-with-milk mead that does n't die easily and when it does , it leaves lacing thicker than most beers have head .  body is not as full as i would like , but this is one heck of a tasty beer .

smell of some sweet malts , that 's about it .  light-sucking black with a monumental 2.5 finger head of a nice deep tan . great retention and lacing . ca n't ask for a better appearance than this .  had this on tap when i was being introduced to the lager style of beer . it 's smell is very specific to the beer and is appealing if you are craving a medium-bodied lager . its has a malty intake and a bit of a spicy , hoppy after taste . it goes down smoothly but the taste tends to stick around and interfere with ordered food . it is very drinkable but as stated , but be careful when drinking this with food .

slight cocoa powder and multi-grain . would 've scored higher but i did n't detect much smell from the bottle or my special samual adams glass .  a : very good looking brew - copper/red clear body with white head .  tastes like , yeah , tart blueberries ( probably artificial blueberries ) . just sweet & weird & sweet ... really tough to finish one . much like a cheap , too-tart wine cooler .

the aroma is sweet grain and yeast . it 's not a strong smelling beer by any stretch . i really had to get my nose in there to pick up any aroma . the flavor is delicious .  pours a translucent medium copper with some awesome bubbling and a thick doughy head .  less fizzy than anticipated in the mouth .

this irish stout surprised me in all regards . the color is pitch black , with only a thin amount of head on top holding in a slight coffee/nutty scent . the taste is of toasted barley and coffee , and is balanced extremely well .  poured into a tulip . this beer is a beautiful gold . stunning and fragrant .  mouthfeel/overall : the body is very light , and it has pretty high carbonation .

smells like burnt , lightly smokey malt with no real hop or yeast profile . tastes firmer than it smells . smokiness presides over a rich , very dark malt profile of nuts , peat , and burnt grain .  a : pours a clear golden color with two fingers of creamy white head that fades slowly , leaving countless strips of lacing on the glass .  m- very light beer , at 3 % alcohol , nice carbonation throughout and thin almost watery .

the dortmunder style is one of my favorites , easy going , not an everyday ( though it could be ) and thisone is done well . a frothy , pillow-like white head that stuck around and laced oh so well . the aroma was not overpowering , maybe alittle grass-like . this homebrew could be a great macro `` try-this '' offering great job , great beer !  pours a light , burnt orange , very clear . the beautiful amber-orange gives it an amazing radiant quality , looks delicious and refreshing . also great for the beach , on a deck or patio watching the sun set to match the color of this gorgeous beer , especially since it will go great with chips and salsa .  little lacing . it has an oktoberfest feeling , but not full fledge on the taste . very drinkable . i think i will serve it at my halloween party because of the label and easy drinking style .
s : sweet malts , pine , not that aromatic .  beautiful looking beer .  m/d : the mouthfeel was a tad low , as i assume to the three years in a swingtop , but by no means distracting .

superoir lacing & very good head retention s : nothing up front , but then earthy hoppyness & whisper of fruit . this was the only area this beer let me down t : huge grapefruitty hops & then a little fruittyness up front .  poured a illowing ornage with a big white head and excellent carbonation . thick pour and cloudy .  light-medium bodied with crisp high carb .

s : sweet malts and yeast on the nose for the most part . slight breadiness as well as a smidgen of hops , but not much .  appearance : black in color sporting a two finger creamy head that lasted a long time .  tastes like an aged beer , its very dry and cuvee-like . significant hops.its wierd but it does smell like a barleywine . a bit undewhelming mouthfeel.there was some problem with foam in the taps , and maybe if i had this in the wee hours . still good .

s - surprising amount of malt in the nose , and an equally surprising lack of hops .  this beer pours a hazy golden color with an absolutely massive head that retains very well and leaves huge chunks of lacing .  perfect carbonation and ridiculously easy to drink .

the aroma was spectacular , one of the best i have ever been privy to . though the look could use a touch of tinkering , the amazing aroma and depth of flavors more than made up for it . a unique and enjoyable offering unlike any other saison i 've ever had .  pours thick and black with a big fluffy head with excellent retention . looks rich and dessert-like .  the beer itself is pretty thick , and mixed with the lingering foamy head , it feels great in the mouth for savoring what taste there actually is .

very nice nose . sipping is quite sweet . however , this was much more than i was expecting ; very nice .  poured this brew into a la chouffe glass , just like the last tasting . makes lots of bright white foam , and has a hazy golden colored body .  the mouthfeel of this beer is great . they do an excellent job with the carbonation and creating the perfect body for a beer .

this reminds me a bit of pte with that ridiculously great aroma and bitterness but not quite having the citric hop flavor that i would normally want in a dipa . this beer is incredibly bitter on the back end and the hot alcohol make this beer difficult to session .  motor oil black with a head like you would see on a rootbeer float .  ( m ) - this is ridiculously smooth despite its hop dryness and woody bite . great carbonation level and balance .

light aroma of roasted malts with some nice caramel tones .  lacing is phenomenal , it sticks around the whole time , leaving great looking webbing on the glass .  m : full body , and shockingly creamy . this brew is extremely smooth of the mouth .

nose is very full and really inviting . aromas jump out of the glass a buttery toffee . a big abv sipper with a great nose . sorry jay-bone , just did n't cut it for me .  pours a moderately clear reddish hue . massive cap of tan foam does not seem to want to go anywhere , stubbornly leaving sheets of lace on the glass .  very smooth and rich taste though and perfectly balanced . wonderfull to drink though think it should be drank as i do n't think that more age makes this one any better .

750ml bottle with cork , like their local series . smells of the local 1 , champagne , cork , lemon meringue or orange marmalade , some tropical fruits or pina colada , wet vegetation . surprisingly , i taste the hop in the flavor more than the aroma . a unique hop . corky . kudos for making a dry and hoppy saison , and getting it to texas ! worth trying .  lovely auburn red color blows me away .  m : one of the most silky smooth beers i have had in quite a while . i would love it on cask , although the low carbonation is nearly perfect .

that 's a good thing in my book . overall a fantastic aipa .  this beer is a very dark brown with a dense , light tan head that provides excellent lacing .  the mouthfeel is very smooth , with minimal aftertaste .

s : very sweet and malty , mostly apple and not much more . has a quality something along the line of other fruit beers like bbc 's cherry wheat .  poured into a guinness tulip pint on st patty 's day with a big , booming , thick , puffy head that slowly reduces to lacing . very nice .  mouthfeel is thick and creamy , very nice .

s : it smells great . fresh , crisp , hints of the hoppiness of an ipa . mf : very interesting and different . overall : very interesting and complex beer .  once cracked it pours a deep , impenetrable black with a thick , high , pillowy light tan head that leaves intricate webs of lacing .  excellent medium mouthfeel , that is slick yet dry - i could drink many of these but i am confident that time will lend complexity -- - please !

there are several layers to the nose that create a great amount of depth . and finishes of with a chocolate covered apple character very nice . taste : the taste starts out very similar to the nose with very light touches of bourbon and oak but for me the beer has more chocolate than anything else very rich dark chocolate character and finishes off nicely with just a touch of apple mouthfeel : medium body with low carbonation overall : very good beer .  appearance : nice darkish red hue , when held up to night it assumes a lovely chestnut colour .  the mouthfeel is exceptional and that is all i am going to say about this .

this has one of the best aromas of an ipa that i 've ever had . sticky , piney , resiny aroma . i find this to be a very drinkable ipa .  quite close to black with a fine textured tan head . i love the way the beer horizon ( the separation between the beer and the head ) looks . it stayed that way throughout the beer .  the mouthfeel is great , for the bittersweetness from the roasted malts provide the ideal amount of oomph to an otherwise creamy body .

aroma is burnt grains , mustiness , and mettalic aromas close to battery acid . just smells like beer . bitter burnt grains with some minimal chocolate and coffee flavors .  pours a very clear copper color with a fluffy white head . leaves lots of lacing on the glass as it slowly recedes .  m : super creamy as it should be .

s : smells phenomenal ! booze , oak , and sweet sugars upfront . breadiness on the backend . t : good . not great . has a nice boozy / oakiness to it , not a whole lot else .  the cascade hop explosion was still there , but i was able to handle it this time around and i really enjoyed it . ruby-amber color , bordering on red . awsome color .  finshes warming , hoppy & bready , very balanced approach mf : chewy with low carbonation & great balance dangerously drinkable , this would put you on your butt after a couple of pints but a really nice dipa

aromatic and hoppy from the different types of hops used - there is some fruit and alot of pine . this is pure heaven in a glass from the aroma to the taste and finish everything is enjoyable . the abv is not to high but you can still a get decent buzz but drinking a few .  clear golden amber body with a steady level of carbonation and head that leaves a quarter inch of film like white head ; crystal clear .  mouthfeel was virtually perfect .

poured into a de molen sniffer . smell : great nose , full of dark chocolate , slight sour cherry , bourbon and vanilla taste : great taste as well , this beer is very complex and still very balanced . the smell and taste are wonderful , for me it seems an attempt of the molen to produce their own cuvee delphine from struise .  poured into a tulip a nice dark brown color , nice carbonation , awesome fuckn ' head , never seen a head like this from a bw , two-finger creamy tannish head , tons of sticky lacing and islands through out the drink .  i love the mouthfeel on this beer , probably my favorite part of it .

incredibly complex aroma , a deep strong dark with dirt , sour grass , tart apple , a cornucopia of spices . perfect touch of the rustic .  huge head , somewhat lasting , good lacing , smallish bubbles .  mouthfeel is heavy bodied and velvety smooth .

aroma : strong but nice lemon wheat aroma . the aroma was nice but it goes downwards after that .  2009 vintage poured into a pint glass a : aggressive pour yields 3/4 finger cream colored head with good retention . clear reddish copper liquid is beautiful s : herbal and earthy hop aroma .  its very smooth and velvety , very nice .

the nose is heavy on the rye malt- showing a more pure breadiness with fruity tones of buttery apples , white raisin , faint cinnamon , light brown sugar , plum . the parallels to rye whiskey are awesome in this . the medium bodied palate is caramelly sweet up front with a mild bitterness that ushers in the rye maltiness- drying and spicy with lots of fruity tones .  bottle 1347/3700 a- pours a deep rich black with a nice brownish head .  m - so so smooth , much more than expected , carbonation in perfect and maintains a light body . perfect .

it has fantastic light floral hop aromas . the alcohol content is n't particularly high and their are some superior apas around .  incredible retention , eventually falling to a quarter-inch layer of froth . impressive start .  the mouthfeel was buttery smooth as silk with full body and low carbonation .

the beer smells absolutely beautiful . like bittersweet chocolate and espresso , with some caramel and molasses notes . this beer smells really fantastic . taste is a lot of the same .  pours a deep brown , transparent with an off white head . huge head that sticks to the glass and remains about and inch thick . tight head , quite beautiful .  thick lushious body and moderate carbonation .

absolutely amazing grapefruit , lemon , and orange aroma . also has a touch of sweet toffee and vanilla . this was a beautiful hazy golden pour , with typical cask frothy head . very well balanced flavor , then a wonderful dry bitter finish . this is an amazing brew , and the cask only adds to it .  poured a dark mahogany with a big light brown head that left some lacing .  m : medium body with a fantastic carbonation balance ! amazing here !

aroma is fabulous , even at this temperature . delicious . well worth the $ 6 canadian that i paid for it .  burnt amber with a fluffy , light tan head of good size and staying power . lots of foamy lace left in the tulip as the head never really dies but eventually falls to a cm or so in height . there 's still some retention before the glass is finished . very nice .  mouthfeel is what always gets me on these beers , i love the chewy creamy coats your throat feeling here .

s : this is an amazing smell . chocolate , malt , cream , milk , caramel , coffee and vanilla can all be found . nice . m : silky smooth .  a - pours a gorgeous pure orange color with a nice white dense head . it recedes slowly and it is sticky and very attractive .  the mouthful is creamy with perfect carbonation .
s - banana , apricot and a spicy hint .  a- pours a deep black color with a huge , fluffy , brown head that leaves tons of lacing as it goes down .  smooth as hell , perfect weight and carbonation .

s : big yeast smell right up front . the yeast and hops work really well together . excellent nose . t : wow . d : very nice beer . still excellent beer all around .  color is a nutty brown color and very crisp . the head is full and pillowy and stays pillowy and the head and lacing combine and only the middle falls into a thin layer .  mouthfeel - heavy body with mild carbonation . it 's perfect to me .

boozy aroma with vanilla and oak apparent , notes of toffee and coconut , roast and chocolate , faint licorice and figs . great texture , full without being heavy , moderate carbonation that provided an airy mouthfeel , a bit of astringency from the kilned grains and wood , slightly sticky .  essentially , but not quite , black , it has a large tan head , creamy and long-lasting , slowly shrinking to a permanent frothy head with some nice lace .  a nice smoothness develops into a wonderful creaminess .

smell - pumpkin , nutmeg , cinnamon , malts , brown sugar , spices . smells like liquid pumpkin pie . rather smooth and easy drinking .  ( bottle into pint glass - sampled 4/5/10 ) picture perfect pour with a dark brown color and creamy off white head .  very creamy feel with a smooth molasses aftertaste .

s - bourbon , bourbon , bourbon , buttery toffee , roasted cashews , malted vanilla milkshake , tiny amount of hops , pecan pie , and harsh booze . this is the best smelling barleywine this nose has ever smelled . perfect . t - harsh and boozy , but delicious . caramelized sugar up front with tons of bourbon .  1 pint 6 oz tall dark brown bottle with a racer checkered flag on the label with red and yellow print , pewter cap . great retention and clumpy lace .  mouthfeel is quite exceptional .

a very intriguing nose , wow , minty , citrusy , lemon-grass , soft licorice notes , very pleasant even with its slight funk of oxidation . this is actually quite nice even with its funk , i could deal with a little less carbonation .  pours very dark , almost black with dense head that does not dissipate till the end of pint , leaving thick and dense lacing . amazing .  mouthfeel is outstanding , slick and effervescent .

s-this beer has one of the most pleasant aromas that i have smelt in a long time .  a - extremely dark brown body topped by a frothy bark tan head standing a couple inches tall . the head has some great stamina ! the lacing this beauty leaves is also worth noting .  sweet malts are offset by crisp hops together producing a wonderful balance and mouthfeel . sooo smooth !

very sessionable , but only an adequate porter with the exception of the nose which is amazing .  great head retention & lacing s : grapefruit & lemon hops , plus honey malt t : citrussy hops up front , along with slight honey malt & metallic hops .  mouthfeel : low carbonation leads to thirsty gulps .

this may be the best smelling pilsener i 've ever experienced . lovely complex , floral hop aroma . pleasant light grained malt in the background . overall , a superior beer .  a : this dark lager poured a beautiful clear amber color that showed off a ton of carbonation . i was extremely impressed by the appearance of this beer .  perfect mouthfeel .

nose is wonderful leafy green sappy noble hop over slightly sweet biscuity malt . wonderful pilsner nose . medium weight in the mouth with a good balance of hop flavor , hop bitterness and malt to the finish , where the hop bitterness really comes to the fore .  bear republic big bear black stout is an impenetrably black ale with a huge , chunky , foamy , light-chestnut colored head that coats the glass .  very nice full bodied mouthfeel . easily drinkable .

and all very fresh . smells like being in the woods and breathing in a fresh , brisk , spring air in the morning after it 's been raining . it almost `` bites '' . not as complex in the mouth as it is in the nose though . m-medium bodied . i 'm not normally a fan of hoppy beers but this is so well made that you ca n't help but enjoy it .  ) this ipa is a hazy , tarnished gold with a light frothy head and excellent lacing .  pours a rich copper with a creamy one finger head that that settles nicely leaving some light lace , deep intese fruity aromas with some underlying but very noticeable pine.wow a big flavorful barleywine very pacific coast piney and resiny upfront with a big fruity alcolholic finish the alcohol really hits.just a sublime creamy mouthfeel and pretty slick going down the hatch and it warms the insides.wow truley and awesome big brew a night cap that cant be beat .

i love how the smell changes over time . got ta give 3f props for the phenomenal smell , tho .  the beer poured a beautiful translucent red colour with a 1 inch tan coloured head .  thick creamy mouthfeel and mild carbonation . smooth silky mouthfeel is lucious .

a : beautiful deep dark red , with a foamy , rich head s : unbelievably fragrant of cherries t : this is a sweet cherry beer . yummy .  lighter and brighter looking than i expected , nelson poured without any `` redness '' i typically , and erroneously , associate with rye beers . a clear hay golden hue , with a beautiful cream white head ; excellent retention and lacing .  mouthfeel is exceptional . it feels good in the mouth but leaves no lasting memories on the taste buds .

t - not as complex as i had hoped for , but still good . starts off with bourbon vanilla flavors with some caramel malt sweetness mid palate , then big oak flavors with a bit of spice through the long finish .  pours a cloudy yellow/gold color , with a huge thick fluffy white head . a good deal of carbonation helped this head hold for what seemed like an eternity .  m : medium body with the perfect amount of smooth , yet lively , carbonation . truly excellent .

very powerful sweet aroma . overall : fantastic beer , will definitely get again .  pours a deep , hazy amber hue , giving rise to a humongous light tan head that fills half the vessel .  m - perfect carbonation .

aromas of lots of different berries ( strawberies , blueberries , blackberries , and raspberries ) . i would get a different berry every time i sniffed . the berries were done nice ! good thing i like all the types of berries in this one .  pours a pitch black dark into snifter glass with a rich , creamy head that lasts a great deal of time and a heavy lace remains . probably the darkest looking beer you will find and a wonderful head .  where this brew really stands out is the creamy mouthfeel . that smoothness works to perfection with sweetness , but does n't work quite as well with bitterness .
another cheer for this perfect blend .  appearance & gt ; looks like an giant-sized perfect pull of espresso .  m- great body , great carbonation . feels good .

grapefruit ! my favorite aroma in beer and life for some strange reason , but enough about me ... .once i break from my grapefruit coma , i do notice pine and a little lemon rind in the background t - there is that damn grapefruit again , i just ca n't get away from it . immense hop flavor with a surprising amount of malt that finds its way through the hops .  pours out almost pitch black but some light shines through around the edges . a nice fluffy , off-white two finger head has nice retention and leaves heavy lace behind . a huge pillow stays on top of the beer .  mouthfeel : true german feeling on this beer . medium viscosity , rolls across the palate smoothly and is perfectly carbonated . great overall feel and authenticity .

s-awesome aroma of top quality chocolate starts things off ... then a little bailey 's irish cream notes ... .caramel ... the more i smell this the more of the irish creme coffee notes but light on the java ... also some plums , and raisins ... .really a great smelling beer . t-dark unsweetened chocolate ... .charred raisins ... licorice ... good amount of pure hop bitterness ... .a lit bit like rogue is in the hopping ... .some alcohol is flexing its muscles and is quite evident ... .exudes what you 'd expect from an impy.. m-rich , and full bodied..velvety.. d-damn nice impy that ranks on the top tier ... i like a couple others better than this but that is no knock on this beer because there are really some kick ass impy 's being made these days ... a must try if you like this style..  poured into a fluted glass around 6c a : copper and crystal clear , with a nice 2 finger tan head that lasts a long time and laces nicely .  m - smooth and creamy ! d - surprisingly good for an american porter .

smell mildly sweet with a slight hop skunkness .  poured a dark hazy brown , tan head , with good retention .  mouthfeel : oh wow , this is super-good . very , very creamy on the palate , with moderate ( but focused ) carbonation .

a : opaque , poured with small bubble head , thin veil of head , gives way over time to bubbles on side of glass but when glass is rotated there is still a ton of carbonation trapped in the beer s : full bourbon nose , malty , bourbon dominates , treacle , vanilla , intense t : full-flavored , extreme malt and bourbon flavor , not a great degree of heat , i love bourbon but it seems just a bit too much , toned down once beer warmed up m : warming , rounded , creamy , good body and mouthfeel without tons of etoh , strong bourbon aftertaste  copious carbonation visible throughout . head is a dense , small-celled foam that swarms out of the pour vigorously , and stays for ages , fading to a mottled cap .  fantastic mouthfeel .

the smell reveals roasted malts with a light buttery whiff .  pours a brilliant copper ; a vigorous pour produces only a one-inch head but a nice , tight , foamy one .  mouthfeel knocks this thing out of the park .

smell : hops across the board , floral with fruits all paired with citrus . great , strong hop scent , but not aggravating in the least , floral .  a : poured perfectly dark brown with an abundant creamy light brown head . great retention and fantastic lacing .  tastes great with a full creamy feel as it slides down . bitterness follows in the wake , lightly lingering , lapping leisurely .

nose is simply stunning . soaring sour limeade with an intense barnyard element , a good smack of leather , and just a hint of very sweet malt .  appearance : golden with a nice amount of head that stays with it until the last drink .  mouthfeel is medium bodied with low to medium carbonation , fantastically smooth beer , very very nice .

aroma was a bit lacking . maybe my sniffer was n't working at full power , but i detected very little aroma aside from a faint toffee smell .  a absolutely beautiful looking beer .  really great mouthfeel of this one has won me over .

this is delicious beer . the aroma is just like liquor soaked fruit , with a hint of cinnamon . it 's got a nice clear amber color .  appearance : pours a very hazy apricot/orange color . great thick & foamy white head with excellent retention .  mouthfeel is perfection . perfectly carbonated and very refreshing .

smell is great . coffee beans and some roasted aromas , a touch of chocolate .  pours a tremendously jet black coloring , with a dark brown , foamy head that dissipates as you drink .  feels amazingly clean and fresh while keeping the flavor of charred wood and grains . smooth , creamy , full bodied , and almost a velvet nature . the carbonation is played on in the background as an overcoat . the simplicity of it overwhelms me .

another great beer from denmark , this little country is no slouch in craft beer world.poured into an imperial nonic a near jet black except from some chocolate brown highlights when held to the light , a large blooming lighter mocha colored head atop.to me the aromas couldnt get any better , a fantastic display of chocolate and resiny hop , maybe the best aroma of any stout i have come across , if you like the hops no matter the style its spot on.the mouthfeel is a little sharp and not as full on as i would have liked.bitter chocolate , dark fruit , and a healthy dose of resiny hop make for a well rounded flavor profile , if that mouthfeel was just a little more smooth ! a really good beer that is close to being great , love the hop play going on .  a - incredible crimson-amber color with a lasting two-finger off-white head .  perfectly carbonated , with a thick chewy body and a strong alcohol burn .

s : wonderful nose . toasted notes with some malt character hiding behind it .  deep golden to light amber colored with a big head that settles into a nice thin layer of foam with moderate lacing as you get through the pint .  mouthfeel is fantastic .

this is a phenomenal aroma i ca n't get enough of ! t - sharp rye comes out in the flavor much more so than the aroma lets on . it actually overwhelms most everything else . d - very good take on the saison style that 's completely unique .  very dark ruby red colored body with tightly knit khaki colored head .  m - this is by far the smoothest ipa i 've ever had . the pour from a hand pump straight from the cask creates the perfect texture for this beer .

body was cloudy and amber aroma was outstanding . moderate hoppiness and perfume .  this beer was poured unhurriedly into a flute . lots of swirling carbonation and three solid finger s of thick creamy head .  m - extremely smooth .

smell : the smell really is impressive . heavy heavy coffee . good malt to support , but great coffee aromas . taste : feels like i 'm enjoying a nice cup of coffee fresh out of the percolator after waking up in a tent .  not sure if i need a spoon for this one . pours thick as anything i have ever seen .  m : the mouthfeel is dense and creamy and frothy ... and almost stout-like . excellent .

very nice presentation . aroma is forresty ( real word ? ) with grassy , herbal , piney , sprucy hop notes along with citrus notes of grapefruit and lemon rind .  the imperial stout was very black in color with a dark brown head . very pretty .  mouthfeel - very smooth with a rich body and muted carbonation .

smells really really good , actually . i suppose old men are always less handsome when they take their clothes off .  bear republic tribute ale is a very clear , very lively , deep crimson brown berr with a huge , lumpy , beige head .  mouthfeel is silky smooth , really nice . body fairly full and the beer leaves an impression all the way over the tongue .
wonderful . just the perfect amount of fruit mixed with the belgian wheat goodness .  excellent lacing . a great looking beer .  mouthfeel : the mouthfeel is absolutely incredible for a milk stout .

very resilient aromatics , wonderful . taste - a brief sweet malt start goes nowhere before some serious hops kick in .  a : this beer pours a beautiful hazy red color with a fluffy off white head . the color of this beer is amazing .  full bodied with creamy carbonation and a lingering sweet licorice finish .
smooth melted creamy chocolate with tart raspberry , kissed with dark fruits ; plums , prunes and blackberries .  a pretty good looking beer .  mouthfeel : perfect , just like champagne .

s : the smell is unbelievable . tons of robust , fresh raspberries blended with a nice cherry and lemony tartness . slightly acidic smelling with a hint of vinegar . not as robust and/or flavorful as the smell led me to believe , but this is great nonetheless . mouth puckering raspberry goodness to start , followed by some lemon rinds , dry oak , and slight vinegar . it was very good , but we all thought it was lacking something .  a : fantastic clarity , golden , and a relentless head , a 3 millimeter head is still visible after 20 minutes , leaving rings of lace in its wake .  m : lovely . sort of creamy , without being too heavy .

anyhow , when you have a need for hops , this one certainly takes care of the fix . aroma , yes , just like it should be- huge citrus , flowers , grapefruit rind , oranges , probably lemons and limes if i was n't diving in so fast . this beer has a nice solid body holding in a creamy , milky nectar thats very smooth . the finish is bitter but smooth , maybe a little woody from all the hops . it only lacks a little malt complexity in the flavor , the malt seems a bit basic but does hold up well to the hop explosion .  pours into 't hofbrouwerijke chalice a deep dark chocolate brown with a huge , i mean huge , light brown head . this is a head that just wo n't quit . it 's stunning .  the mouth feel is the richest and thickest i have ever tasted in a beer !

look : it poured a transparent orange-brown colour with a thin tannish head that did not disappear smell : exceptional . it smells delicious . a little sour with some sweetness in there .  pours a clear golden color with a thick , fluffy , off-white head .  mouthfeel is the star here . it 's plush , velvety ... is nice .

it poured well , looked great , and has a good aroma but , it was not to my liking .  while it pours beautifully with a deep copper color and wonderful head , this brew is all looks and no personality .  the taste starts with a slight carbonation . the carbonation builds to reveal a sweet velvet feel . a milk chocolate flavor with a roasted finisht showcases a great mouth on this beer .

mmmm , that head really released a lot of wonderful aromas . pine and citrus predominate and , man , it smells good . very 'merry christmas ' , but not in the tinsel-and-cookies kinda way , but the 'i 'm some crank wandering around in a pine forest and i 'm giving presents to strangers ' kinda way . it definately ai n't normal , but it sure is delicious .  a- clear dark reddish copper hue with a billowy tan head that last forever and leaves tons of sticky lacing on the glass . edit : holy shit , this beer is so hoppy it turns your tongue yellow !  mouthfeel ; very tight and lively carbonation , slick and creamy in the finish , pretty complex and admirable .

s ) pumpkin pie ... this really has it covered . this is spiced , but not over the top , which made me very happy . a very nice balance of pumpkin and beer . this is quite smooth . nice finish and aftertaste . o ) i have n't really had many pumpkin beers , but i 've heard good things about this one , so i finally gave it a shot . i 'm really glad i did .  22 oz bomber pours copper to orange with a 4 fingers+ offwhite head with effervesence . great lacing & head retention s : fruit & oak-like notes taste : apricot & oakey notes up front .  fairly crisp in the mouth , with an exceptional smoothness going down .

the aroma is full on citrus hops . love it . the flavor is much more balanced than the nose . the citrus blast is there but the malt `` grinds '' away at it . overall another great beer from surly .  damm , skippy , now thats what a stout should look like ! deep , cream black pour . an absolutely beautiful , thick and fluffy brown head , clings to the side of the glass endlessly .  outstanding mouthfeel ! very drinkable .

aroma is sweet delicious malt bomb extravaganza . dark fruits , plenty of sweet caramel laced with burnt sugars , no heat at all , and a small amount of oaty malted milk ball aroma . a+ aroma for sure . this is one amazing beer , it woo'ed the hell out of me .  pours a huge head with crazy retention that wo n't leave the glass .  mouthfeel : fantastic . great carbonation , no real aftertaste and washes easily over the palate .

a - clear honey colored with very little head . s - smells of ripe cherries , raspberries , honey , alcohol , mango , citrus , brandy , apple juice , flowers , and apricots . t - tastes of cherry , alcohol , brandy , citrus , candied sugar , sherry , and honey .  the most delicate looking head i 've ever seen , pillowy and white , thick and longlasting . beautiful .  mouthfeel is outstanding . super thick and syrupy , that flavor coats the palate forever .

s - big aroma of cherry juice , some apple juice , molasses , malts , just a great smell . t - a nice balance of molasses , licorice , malts , some cherry .  a great effort from smutty ; this bp pours a saturated opaque espresso brown , leaving a rich dark bronzed brown head . very well bittered and rounded in the mouth with sweet roasted malts , carob and tongue tingling acids .  mouthfeel is creamy smooth , thick body , low carbonation .

head is a bright off white , watery and light , not much retention or lacing ... outstanding aroma , very funky floral muskyness , some nice brett ... taste has some nice things going , this is a musky sour brett saison , not sweetness , makes no bones about it . crushable musky saison , well worth trying .  pours a dramatic thundercloud of head , beige/tan and mountainous , rocky .  mouthfeel is thick and chewy , as it should be fir a beer of this strength .

the aroma is so spot-on for the style that it makes me wonder how skull coast did it ... how do you get that much non-artificial-smelling watermelon aroma into a beer ? just exceptional , with juicy , fruity 'melon notes backed by a hint of wheat and hops .  the pour is black with a billowing light brown head with some very nice lace .  the rich , smooth , roasted chocolate flavor works well with the silky body . this is definitely highly recommended , as the beers tend to be from great lakes brewing company .

smells amazing ! t - not too much smoke , bet definitely present .  a busty foamy cap on top ... head is monstrous ! not only is the head big its retention is just as good . head was a soft tan ( cappuccino ) color with craters , mounds , and dense chunks forming all the while leaving a bleary coating of lace . a very good look to this one s : i am having a bit of trouble grasping this one but had no problem realizing this one is sweet and rich .  m : really a standout porter . carbonation is perfectly dialed in and gives a very subtle tingle on the tongue .

the smell is truly incredible , and the taste is malty and pleasant .  pours liquid gold and with a huge porcelain head .  it 's wonderful . alcohol tingles a little in the mouth and it 's certainly present in the aroma but buried 'neath the fruity yeast . expertly woven into the beery fabric of this brew .

definitely a woodsy component going on , and i 'm thinking rosemary bark or dried thyme . not much funk , really , but the acid backbone is there making for a quite enjoyable drink on its own . phenomenal .  pours black and thick . substantial tan head that forms of a billion tiny bubbles then morphs into a very slow fading creamy foam .  mouthfeel- damn , this sh*t is creamy ! smooth , medium carbonation , but goes down super smooth . nice light bitterness in the aftertaste .

smell is phenomenal , sweeter , spicy , floral hops , fruity esters , just very appealing to me , lots of aroma without overpowering . perhaps if the aroma was so appealing to me , the taste would seem better , as there 's really nothing wrong with it , pretty standard witte . drinkability is pretty good , if only for the aroma .  a - golden and slightly hazed with coppery highlights and a foamy , cushiony head that jets to the surface and clings to the glass like glue as it subsides . head retention is fantastic , and would be even without the aid of the etching at the bottom of the glass . fantastic .  m. just perfect for what it is . very smooth and thick .

murky , fluffy smells ... well , wheaty and sweety ! the perfect hefe .  this is one of the most distinctive brews i 've ever had ; the 400 pounds of peaches they throw in really show through . beer had a very pale golden coloration that i didnt think fit it to well .  slick mouthfeel with perfect level of carbonation .

s : creme brulee ? the nose on this beer is amazing . loads of vanilla , caramel , cream , butterscotch and a tad bit of roasted malt .  pours near flat . no head , no lacing .  mouthfeel/overall : this beer is every bit of full bodied ; thick , chewy and creamy . everything an imperial stout should be . overall , a very good imperial stout that i 'd love to have full time access to .

hard pour gets a beautiful head to rise up , just a little more than two fingers worth of off-white frothiness . smells phenomenal . a bouquet of citrus hops , with a little bit of floral and maybe piney for good measure . so nicely balanced , just a little bit of bitter and the rest is flavor . the alcohol would probably catch me a buzz after just a couple , but it certainly weighs in a little lower than some comparable ipas , which is nice .  '' pours to a slightly hazy dark orange-caramel with a small white head and just ok retention and minimal lacing .  not the stunner i was hoping for m- beautiful mouth feel . i sure hope this is not the `` great sculpin '' i 've been waiting for for that past few years .

it 's quite clear and straw/amber colored . it has a very strong smell of fresh hops . pine , citrus , and maybe a bit of tropical fruit , but quite spicy . the smell is the only part of this beer to reflect it 's ipa label .  directly from the fridge , after pouring there was almost no head .  mouthfeel : very thick and very very smooth , wonderful mouthfeel .

hops . a touch of skunk . excellent aroma . t- hops ( pine forward ) .  pours a clear amber with a smallish head that quickly settles to a thin cap . moderate amounts of lacing is left on the glass .  a faint bit of tannins in the middle of the tongue starts the finish , which is incredibly long with trailing , vineous notes of chocolate and spiced orange peel . ya it 's a bit like those warheads candies , but it 's tucked in such an incredible silky richness .

s- it does have a nice smell of oranges .  a : this beer poured a nice , brown-red colour . i was glad that the colour was nice to look at because the head barely bothered to make an appearance .  it is exceptionally smooth and drinks perfectly for the style .

aroma of a quad / stout mix with the figs , plums and spices plus a hint of grape hi-c infused vanilla . full bodied , viscous without being cloying , chewy . the alcohol is amazingly restrained , not even the inherent warmth you 'd expect at this abv level .  a - pitch black with a thin mocha-colored head . so-so retention and poor lacing .  mouth-feel was velvety smooth and creamy .

this beer smell awesome ! ! ! as i drink it , the problem is , what flavors match up with these aromas ? the beer has a great london/english fruity estery taste with christmas ale type flavors of nutmeg and cinimmon . i wish i had more than one of these to review beacuse its a really complex ale that i would like to clone . a very drinkable ale with a great nutty spicey fruity finish .  pours with about a quarter inch of medium colored head which recedes very quickly to a film .  mouthfeel : thick and chewy , yet not syrupy . carbonation is low and appropriate . in other words , spot on .

typical intense heller aroma , roasted pork and tons of smoked ham , sweet maple syrup , campfire , just rich malt altogether and intense smokiness . it somehow reminds vermont maple smoked cheddars which is no little task . taste is actually quite wheaty and fruity ( banana , lemon ) so its actually pretty well made since it was clearly the intention , but i dont really enjoy the atmosphere created from wheaty dusty tartness mixed with the big smokiness .  the beer pours dark , not much head exists but enough to know the beer has bubbles .  m : medium in body with a really smooth and creamy feel on the tongue .

upon opening the bottle you receive a pleasant aroma and on pouring the smell is obviously even more intense . the mouthfeel is actually kind of weak and bitter , surprisingly , given the pleasant look and smell of this beer .  was a little gun shy given my last wee heavy experience..aka mcewan's certainly not as dark as my last wee ... .more like a cola in color and clarity with a rich tan head , zero lacing .  however , the mouthfeel of this beer is phenomenal , on the tim of your tongue it tingles , in the middle it is smooth as silk , on on the edges it is a touch syrupy ( amazing ) a good beer , but not worth the price they charge for it .

there was very little scent from the pint , a faint smell of hops and nothing else , very bland .  not much in terms of head , and what is sits atop a body of dark ruby . ahhh , lifts the nostrils into the heavens and beyond into the great void of ecstasy .  still i thought the aroma was alittle weak , but once it hits your mouth it is amazing .

as soon as i opened the bottle , i was smacked with a heavy hoppy smell , easily reminded me it 's an ipa i 'm dealing with . s : an amazing combination of hops , pine , citrus , maybe some grape . t : interesting , with the token ipa hoppiness being the most notable aspect of it all . d : daunting at first , especially for me , not a huge fan of ipas , but i have to respect this beer . the dynamic flavor-smell combinations are remarkable , and though it 's not my favorite , the never-departing flavor may be the reminder that it is something to be reckoned with .  served in a 12oz goblet , darkly translucent but very close to opaque . dark dark brown color with reddish appearance at the edges , thin tan head that disippates to nothing but the thinnest of rings around the glass .  super thick dark chocolate flavor , light coffee flavors , good coffee bitterness near the finish super creamy , heavier in body , extremely smooth and hopefully i 've mentioned the creaminess overall , i love this stout , give me more

a - dark brown on the edges black in the center body with a small white head that quickly ran away s - sweet citrus hop flavor with a big malty aroma t - big citrusy hop flavor with a huge sweet malty backbone .  minimal head and little carbonation movement , smell : sweet molasses , alcohol , roast malt .  the mouthfeel is super creamy and smooth . this beer coats the entire mouth in an almost velvety way .
just excellent .  a : tried to entice a head , but it came out like oil and left a thin deep brown head that lasted for a few minutes .  it is a full bodied beer with perfect carbonation .

2010 bottle had a ton of suspended sediment in a burnt orange body . wow , aroma is the big winner here . pumpkin pie with crust as it warms ; some clove came thru as well , and even somewhat herbal . pretty authentic pumpkin flavor - vegetable/squash quality , and good amount of spices , incl cinnamon , nutmeg , and clove - but not overpowering . decent volume of malty sweetness / richness ... touch of campfire as it warms . outstanding drinkability - this is the most aromatic and flavorful pumpkin ale you can buy at this level of abv .  orange amber color was semi clear . head was well formed but disapated fairly quickly , lacing was scarce .  typical stone excellent mouthfeel .

s- very complex with sweet milk chocolate predominating mixed with a good amount of raisin , smells like a raisin candy bar in a good way . t- not as complex as the nose but still tasty . lots of chocolate with a finish of the whipped cream , the other flavors seem lost in the mix .  planet porter is a lightweight porter with a sienna brown color .  the mouth feel was excellent and one could tell the cask was being maintained properly .

really delicious smell t : very tannic finish ... almost too much . not as sour as the smell suggests , but very nice . lots of flavor going on !  got a nice 1 finger head on the pour but the coloring of the body is fairly weak . very light orange almost the shade of a pilsner which is not a good look for an ipa . smell is very juicy sweet pineapple with the expected belgian yeast twang of clove and banana .  full bodied , super creamy and smooth . very nice .

s - the spicy , phenolic aroma hit me as soon as i opened the bottle , and once the beer has a chance to open up in the glass it expands into notes of chocolate , dark cherries , raisins , almonds , pepper , cinnamon , and lots of clove . d - very complex beer that manages to avoid being overbearing despite the high alcohol and big flavors . the smell is absolutely spectacular , reminds me of samichlaus , but more interesting . the flavor is quite interesting as well , and i really like the way it finishes , but there is something about the initial sweetness or phenolic character that i find a little cloying .  a : pours dark black , looks thick , very thin head on all glasses poured .  mouthfeel is fabulous with an amazing carbonation . it 's perfect .

really complex nose . smoke , bourbon , dark cherry sour notes . the taste was excellent . really nice with the bourbon not over powering .  this -bal barleywine pours with almost zero head .  mouthfeel is quite amazing , therefore the 5 .

smell : delicious and complex . truly a melange of different aromas . coffee bean , caramel , toffee , chocolate . wonderfully palatable . drinkability : very drinkable . excellent complexity of flavors .  appearance : the beer is a slightly cloudy beer . with good head retention . the beer has a thick white head when pourd and reduces to a thin lacy head .  visibly effervescent , the mouth feel is perfect ... classic rich micro bubbles lend a smooth creamy texture .

great chocolate smell as soon as the cap came off , smelled just like a candy bar .  pours dark brown , small tan head quickly fizzes away to a thin ring .  the hop particles make it sticky as hell , the rim of my glass is sticky , my lips are sticky , and the mouthfeel is outstanding ! as far as double ipas go ( which let 's face it this is really comparable to an ipa ) , i still prefer either pliny or any of the alpine ipas , but this is a nice change of pace .

abv present , but smells delicious . alcohol , somewhat dry .  dark-brown and cloudy in appearance , the pint glass i was handed had been pre-poured , so i ca n't say a lot about the head . the sweetness up front balanced nicely with the beer 's hops , and in combination with an enjoyable , full body , the pint drank easily while sitting outside the brewery on a beautiful march day .  m- the first thing i notice with this is how smooth and creamy it is . d- a very enjoyable english barleywine . tasty .

smell is a tart , floral aroma with crisp , clean edge ; simply put , it 's delightful . this ale 's taste is a crafty hop blen dover a clean , crisp start .  a : pours a black body with a small , tan head with no real retention and minimal lacing .  m : thick , full-bodied , and very creamy . low to moderate carbonation .
this is just perfect . pine and citrus are both detectable . but ... ahhh , it smells so good !  looks pretty limp .  mouthfeel was full , thick , and creamy with a rich sweetness on the tongue .

very enjoyable beer . highly quaffable and deliciously decadent .  the beer pours a dark brown with an off-white head ... small with not a lot of lacing or retention .  mouthfeel was phenomenal - silky smooth and with a slight hops bite on the tongue , giving 'way on the finish to a great caramel sweetness .

smell- unbelievable aroma ! overall- has a great aroma but falls short with the taste .  bomber , a : pours mahogany with a small off-white head , fair retention , light lace .  this is a big , complex , full bodied beer . the huge amounts of malts in this thing are chewy and even feel like they stick to the teeth some .

it smells awesome , everything works together and you get something else every whiff no issues here t much more booze then the nose , more toffee , smoke , and fruit with some burnt brown sugar , still very nice but without as much balance m enters silky then the bubbles make it feel creamy , quite thick and the flavors linger , the heat lingers too and that 's my only complaint in this area o for a big fresh barley wine i thought it was pretty good , the barrel agings there but not overpowering and its oh so mellow i was hoping this one would suck so i would n't need to buy a couple of them to age , pretty expensive but this would be amazing after some time , pretty mellow considering the 13.8 % fresh i can only imagine this 5 years down the road  a decent sized white head that dissipates quickly over a macro-brew-looking yellow-clearish beer . not a great appearance . but i really , really enjoyed this one despite its underwhelming appearance .  m - this is one of my favorite parts so far about this brew . moderate amounts of carbonation that whirls around your tounge and warms it in the process .

this has to be one of the most interesting beers on the nose ~ lots of malty rye mixing it up with a bready note , lots of spice ( a mild chai cocktail - mostly clove ) , some green spruce notes ( probably juniper berries ) and gobs of orange and lemon zest . overall a beer that really smells great , tastes pretty good , and finishes nicely .  a- golden straw color with a tiny little thin white head . nothing much to the appearance here .  the mouthfeel was silky smooth , and i think it was the best feeling oatmeal stout i have ever had . the low carbonation perfectly complemented the medium body , and the smoothness from the oatmeal made it a joy to drink .

the beer is certainly lighter than i expected with an almost straw color . the nose on this brew is phenomenal ! i 'm immediately transported to magical grapefruit land as the beer screams citrus into my nostrils . there is a piney base note to this smell to that compliments the soaring citrus very well . not on hops of course , as the grapefruity citrus notes yielded to a piney bite on the finish , but rather the malt character . while still a world class ipa , i felt that the backbone of this brew just was n't quite as strong as i would have liked and the huge hop profile was almost overwhelming .  a dark orange body with a swiftly descending head that leaves no trace -- semi-opaque ... solid malt aroma with hints of fruitiness to develop a sense of complexity.. slightly effervescent , with a mellow , medium body that is pleasantly fulfilling ... smooth , malty presence in the back of the mouth ; little hops to speak of , but at this refreshing a taste , they 'd only get in the way !  mouthfeel is thick as hell and creamy , perfect for a big ris this is smooth as hell , much smoother than beers with this much ash flavor usually are .

smell is downright incredible , with lots of oily hops , citrus , and a complexity i ca n't describe .  once you get past the weird label , you find a decent ipa .  smooth creamy mouthfeel that keeps you wanting another drink .

s - nice ! grapefruit aroma with some hints of pine fill my nose . very attractive flowery hops , with some bready biscuity malt hidden along the way . nice co2 .  appearance - cloudy yellow color , with small head that faded out .  f : wonderfully thick .

smell is hops - straight , beautiful hop smell . seriously , smells awesome . okay , taste is lagging behind a ways .  a really dark brown with barely any head at all . at first glance this beer looks thin .  super thick mouthfeel .

very little to smell here . faint hops and not much else .  almost a stout feel , but smoother . i wish i had poured in a glass to see what it looked like .  the best part of the rwanda gatsinga coffee stout is in my opinion the mouthfeel which is extremely smooth and leaves a pleasant malty coffee-dominated aftertaste and a smile on your face .

very nice start of a semi-grainy and fully malted pilsner barley . delicious .  bottle poured into pint glass appearance : nothing to write home about . light lacing , amber-gold in color .  huge bodied and full ( again , suggesting iipa classification ) . this is a beauty on cask .

this smelled like the kitchen while my mom bakes banana bread .  possibly the worse beer i have ever had..sickeningly sweet..i let it sit for a week in my fridge and it still bubbled over with head . tastes like sugar and the 1st beer i 've ever simply poured down the drain..is there a quality control problem here or is this standard for the beer ?  however , it tastes great and feels great in the mouth .

smells great though . tart aromas and there is some great fruity and malty notes there too .  appearance was ligter than i expected and had virtually no head .  the taste is initially of a very light porter and with a clean aftertaste that becomes a fruit sensation on the palate . the hop/malt balance is the real achievement here and it really contributes to the supreme drinkability . the smell upon opening the bottle is not an effective contrival of the taste that this beer is hiding as it only gives you an idea of the rooted flavor that is to be unleashed , the supreme balance and sublime flavor . great bier .

5.0 s : wow ! this is n't the strongest smelling dipa i 've had ( it 's up there ) , but it is the most harmonious mixture of citrus i 've ever experienced . pineapple and mango are the most intense , followed by orange , tangerine , and grapefruit . 3.5 t : the taste is a bit disappointing after the nose . 3.0 m : lighter medium body , but it strangely lays heavy on the tongue . 3.5 d : pretty good , but one of the reason i really like dipas are for the awesome creamy mouthfeels .  small white head , has pretty much no retention or lacing .  the mouthfeel was amazing . nearly full-bodied .

amazing . taste almost supports the smell but not to the degree i 'd hoped . if this veered away from the spicy sweetness it offers in the mouth toward the cherry vagueness of the smell i could see this being an absolutely impeccable ale .  12oz brown bottle with no freshness date . pours a medium brown with some amber , a 1 finger head and decent lace .  awesome . drinkability : the mouthfeel is the star here , and not detecting most of the alcohol only helps .

the aroma is amazing ! sweet bourboney ( sp ? ) aroma , along with just the right amount of hops and a hefty malt sweetness . very good . all the flavors and aroma go together so well , and the low abv make this a very sessionable brew .  a - pours a chestnut brown s - toffee , caramelized brown sugar , toasted wheat bread , maple , toasted nuts . t - lots of nutty malt , some light sorghum , notes of caramel , vanilla , dry bread sprinkle with a dash of cocoa powder , hints of over-ripened blueberry . finishes with nutty dry bread aftertaste . very good beer . way better than expected . a standout beer in it 's class .  great full and luxurious mouthfeel , witha soft , albeit intense carbonation that really lifts the brew .

it smells fantastic . sweet floral hops , with citrus present . t - very good , but its a little more bitter and less citrusy than the aroma led me to expect .  2004 vintage pours cloudy light brown with a few bubbles , but no head retention to speak of .  perfect example for a ris , and probably my favorite mouthfeel amongst them all .

smells great ! ! !  2009 vintage pours a very effervescent straw color with 3 fingers of fluffy ivory colored head . hazes a bit a the bottom , duh ... average head retention & lacing s : grassy with apple peels , plus lemons t : apple peels , white grape , lemony hops & a wee bit of dirt & tartness up front .  m/d : a full , silky smooth brew with low ( perfect ) carbonation .

allspice cinnamon and nutmeg all very strong a beautiful smelling ! t-the spices hit upfront with an impressive strength .  pours a dark brown almost black with very minimal thin head s : great aromas going on here . was disappointed with the lack of head so the appearance took a knock on points but overall a wonderful offering from brau brothers !  in my mind , this is the perfect feel for an imperial stout .

s : great smelling beer . c-hops and american malts . potent nose . d : great beer , absolutely delicious , with the delicate touch of a masterful brewer .  this beer poured a light yellow-orange with only about a one-finger head , and not much lacing . the smooth carbonation level and the dry finish made this a very drinkable beer .  taste again where do i start ... sweet , spicy dark fruits soaked in alcohol ( raisins , currents , dates ) , toasted caramel notes , bready , some brandy / rum traces , biscuity , warming alcohol , spicy hop bitterness forces itself through the sweet maltiness , light madeira wine hints ... feel - so silky smooth ... rich and creamy ... light viscousness.. low drinkablilty for this one - a beer for savouring and sipping slowly ... overall - a phenomenal beer ... highly recommended .

not much pop when opening the bottle , but the aroma just spills out . aroma is of sweet vanilla , wet wood , molasses , orange peel , plum and raisin , caramelized sugar , nutmeg , hazelnut -- there is something in the aroma here that reminds me of holiday fruit bread . not fruit cake , but a fruit bread -- a real heavy , oaty loaf of bread with dense chunks of chewy fruit . i wonder , did the high abv knock some of the flavors around ?  growler poured into a weizen glass . an aggressive pour at that , but the 3 fingers of foam reduces to a skim in short order . lazy streaks of lacing here and there .  m- feel is exceptionally clean and smooth .

s : great smell , fruity although i can not place exactly what fruit .  extremely dark with no head at all and no visible carbonation .  nice caramel aftertaste held on the tongue by the thick mouthfeel . creamy thick mouthfeel and modest carbonation .
