the mystery beer in my joe 's garage variety pack , poured a deep brown with dark near crimson hue when held up to the light with a large 2 finger mocha colored head.perfect 5 for me aroma wise its american big on the fruity , piney hop mixed with chocolate and earth just fantastic love the big hop profile.the same goes for the flavors big piney drier hop profile intertwined with bitter chocolate with a earthy raw nut lingering finish.a little prickly on the mouth but nothing to take away from the great flavors of the beer , damn i wish there more porters like this it is the most hoppedup version i think i have had to date .  this beer poured a-not-too-shiny copper red with a good amount of head which quickly faded to a thin lace .  m - absolutely creamy and delectable ! the amazing , tiny bubbled froth envelopes and contains any alcohol sharpness that would otherwise make this 8.0 % beer a bit fiery in the swallow . superb . d - the mouthfeel makes this otherwise straight-up scotch ale an incredibly drinkable beverage . but be careful ! at 8 % , this beer is like getting a two-for-one special in each pint !

the smell is intense and wonderful , very unique and really lends to the overall quality of this beer .  kerberos is a tangerine orange , pretty cloudy . the head was small after a pretty vigorous pour , and did n't last too long . a small web of lace stuck to the snifter .  considering the abv , the mouthfeel is perfect . d - at 12 % , you obviously ca n't have that many .

well i poured this into a pint glass and it has a good head , a pink hue and good watermelon aroma . this is very easy to drink !  this beer looks a bit too light for an english ipa .  m : outstanding mouthfeel , is very smoothe and refreshing .

it has a very sweet aroma to it and that makes it all the more appealing . smell is more prevalent the more it warms up .  pours cloudy and warm chestnut under a diminutive cap of slightly pink foam that receeds to a film suddenly and quickly .  mouthfeel is intensely smooth and velvety , creamy and luscious . lactic milk sugar contributes a boatload of palate-smudging heft . although it 's not one for sessioning , it has a sublime quality that makes you savor every sip .

amazing . t : sweet malt that has plenty of peat flavors that i love so much in scottish ales .  a : poured a orangish copper color with good carbonation and a small white head s : rye , caramel , citrus t : wow .  the texture is just flat-out perfect and this is about as easy to drink as you can want .

smell is amazing ! nice and sweet and very hoppy . very appealing and aromatic . a very good blonde .  i poured this one from a 12oz brown bottle into a shaker pint glass . a= this ale poured a very clear golden color ( filtered i would say ) with a fairly low carbonation release and a 1/2 '' white head . the head dropped to zero very quickly and did not leave any lacing behind .  the mouth feel is perfect - not watery , not syrupy , well carbonated , and very refreshing .

a : dark brown with yeast particles s : could be the strongest smelling dark fruit belgian style beer ever .  12oz bottle poured into an oversized wine glass pours a murky brown colour with just a thin head and a light lacing on the top .  mouthfeel is full and round .

smells very different than any amber i have had but still smells good . t - i get some of the spices and hops but tastes very watered down , really disappointing .  the appearance is nothing special -dark purple-black -- some ruby elements at the top part of the glass .  the alcohol burns just a bit in the back of my throat , but overall the mouthfeel on this is amazing . d- wow !

s : this beer smells great . a very nice balance of booze with piney/citrusey hops . was slightly underwhelmed by the flavor after experiencing such tantalizing aroma smelling the beer . it is still a hearty and satisfying , flavorful brew .  the serving glass and size might have affected the appearance negatively . appearance 3/5 deep amber , slightly hazy , with a moderate off white head , poor head retention and some lacing .  the mouthfeel is right on and this one is immensely drinkable .

smell is extremely fruity , primarily peaches with some apples , oranges , and lemons coming through as well . this is a pretty interesting and unique beer for the style . a pleasant surprise .  poured a pale godlen orange , witha white head that fades to some bubbles which ultimately disappear . leaves behind no retention or lace .  very light carbonation and a perfect body for a porter , combined with what i have already mentioned , makes this a very drinkable proposition .

glorious aroma of silky dark chocolate and dark-roast coffee beans . very pleasant . the dry , slightly acidic roasty finish leads well into another sip .  appearance : thin and inattentive off white lace that barely stays around . this ale is very clear with a bright shaded orangey copper hue .  the mouthfeel was spot on and the taste was close behind .

mesmerizing , really .  shared a 6 pack with some friends ( peacebone116 and his wife and my wife ) , sadly didnt have the option to get an appearance since we drank them from the bottles on a picnic . a n/a since it wasnt poured into a glass , so ill go middle of the road with a 3 .  m - big bodied , thick , and viscous as hell . middling carbonation fades to a really dry and herbal finish like green tea . wicks all moisture from my mouth !

a delicious aroma of coffee , and bready malts , and a flavor which delivers with a nice hop bitterness at the finish .  pours a deep dark black with hints of brown around the edges . the very thin half-finger brown head did n't last very long .  m- full body in the mouth and sticky on the lips .

great hop bouquet -- sweet and juicy , with citrus highlights laid over a smooth backbone of stonefruit ( mostly red ; think cherries , plums , grapes ) , and a little oak . i really like the aroma this beer puts out . the body of the beer is a lovely dark amber color that tinges toward straw around the edges of the glass .  poured from a 12oz bottle a - looks more like a hefeweizen than an ipa . very cloudy , unfiltered , with lots of floating yeast .  the mouth-feel was what was remarkable to me , very thick and creamy , i would liken it to a stout milkshake , really satisfying and enjoyable to drink .

s : a typical fff piney , citrus hop parade hits you strong up front , with delicious burnt cocoa , cinnamon , and brown sugar following . an epic nose that promises much . t : unfortunately , the nose can not keep it 's promise . there is still some malt left underneath , but it is just not coming through like it does in the nose . as a huge fan of toasty porters and stouts , it ; 's kind of a let down for me .  appearance- poured a cherry , dark brown color with almost no head ! strange .  sweet flavor that i ca n't put my mind on ... m - excellent presentation , really enjoyable to the senses .

smells very sweet , what you 'd expect . perfect for dessert or a nightcap .  without any lace or head , but certainly had adequate carbonation . highly drinkable beer that grew on my palate .  a - opaque for sure ; not quite black , but very dark brown ; 1/2 '' tan/light brown , creamy head that diminishes to a thin layer pretty quickly ; lacing here and there , around the glass s - very nice aroma going on here ; notes of roasty malts , dark chocolate , hints of milky sweetness , and nice qualities of gingerbread too t - dark chocolate , vanilla , cinnamon , and ginger come first ; milky sweetness lasts from start to finish that is reminiscent of espresso ; slight bitter finish with roasted coffee beans and ginger as well m - medium to full bodied ; slight dry finish ; some carbonation that feels nice on the tongue ; can feel some warmth from the 9.2 % abv ; texture is very milky , creamy , velvety smooth o - i just ca n't get over how exceptionally smooth this beer really is .

it poured a very nice clear copper color , and while it did not have much head it looked good and it also had a nice aroma , however , it had one of the strangest tastes i have had in a beer .  pours a murky orange with a thin , clingy head . nothing special in this regard .  the mouthfeel is luxurious , thick , and chewy . amazing . i am impressed with this brew . flavors are great and the mouthfeel is unearthly .

majestic sniffs . taste is equally multifacited . one of the maltier versions i 've encountered , laid out in a doughy , bready fashion . this is a very fine hefeweizen  12oz bottle poured into a pint glass pours a copper-straw with obvious carbonation bubbles rising to the surface . any head quickly fades to nothing .  taste & mouthfeel : smoothness is impeccable within the moderate body , big doughy biscuity malt flavour is the showcase of this brew .
smells absolutely fantastic . chocolate , oats , sweet malt , cream .  hazy , reddish brown color with a sparse ring of head .  m : very creamy feeling , small bubbles , not too sticky .

smell is a wonderful grapefruit burst .  it 's what purple haze wants to be when it grows up .  i keep tasting chocolate ice cream ... dry chocolate ice cream ... not cloy at all ... very fantastic finish and mouthfeel ... german beer ftw will buy again !

smell- mmmmm , nice floral and citrus scents hit you right away . not too harsh , but about what you should expect out of an ipa . very tasty . mouthfeel- nice carbonation level .  appearance : chestnut color , low head retention .  mouthfeel : delightfully creamy and full-bodied . very pleasant .

smells of strong peat , as you 'd expect with the name `` islay '' , but there is nice chocolate and roast balance . sweet flavour actually . very creamy mouthfeel , very sweet .  bottled 08.09.11 looks like a cloudy white wine . golden yellow ... virtually no head .  appearance : amber , clear carbonated , medium head smell : alcohol , grapefruit , and citrus taste : alcohol , grapefruit , malts , hops , and slight caramel mouthfeel : smooth , slightly hard finish , can feel the carbonation ... it is amazing how smooth and unbitter this beer is for a beer with its abv drinkability : i will have this again , but may be one of the few that prefer the 60 minute ipa .

smell : this is one of the most complex aromas i 've ever come across . what first appears mildly hoppy explodes into a crazy , fruity , tangy aroma of raspberries , currants , candy sugar , caramel malt , and a number of other notes that i could n't place my finger on . taste : almost underwhelming after the fantastic aroma , but lives up to the hype . alcohol also has a presence here with a slight burn on the midpalate , but actually kind of pleasant . surprisingly subdued and also very smooth . mouthfeel : velvet smooth and full bodied as it just slides down the back of the throat .  a- pours a very pale straw yellow with a pretty white head that quickly dissipates .  the mouth feel is amazing on this beer .

s : the bouquet is quite vibrant , with grapefruit and pineapple jumping out of the glass .  im not a beer enthusiast , i just love the taste of beer , i dont care how it looks , or anything like that i just drink the stuff , i tried this beer today being a fan of the ofallon wheat and gold , and i was surprised . its like a porter light . its listed as a bock ale , but i say is a porter light. , just enough chocolate .  mouth is extremely crisp , clean with tremendous carbonation and a nice light body .

s : this is seriously the best part of the beer . the smell is a pronounced chorus of woodiness , vanilla , chocolate , and booze . is this nirvana ? t : starts out with a creamy chocolate taste which is followed by a sharp stab of flavor and alcohol burn on the tongue . d : overall a very impressive beer .  presentation dark brown glass 330 ml bottle with freshness date on rear label . a- midnight , dark opaque brown , very slim off-white head which disappeared quickly .  mouthfeel the best part of this beer , really smooth with just a little bit of carbonation .

how many citrus fruits are there ? this one has aromas of all of them -- i 'm picking up kumquat , grapefruit , lime and tangerine ( piney rind ) at the very least . all those citrusy hops i smelled are seriously restrained in the taste . from classic to extreme , from belgian to beefy american , from populist to just plain weird , dogfish head 's got it all . i 'd be their bitch in a heartbeat .  pours copper with thick tan head that slowly fades to patchy layer , scant patches of lacing .  lush , creamy mouthfeel , that really could n't improve at all .

smell - a wonderful yeast or dough or wheat smell dominates , with orange or another citrus fruit tagging along . irresistibly smooth finish , tastes much the way it smells although the wheat is less noticeable .  poured a semi - cloudy pale golden yellow with a small head .  taste : excellent entry on the tongue & palate , beautiful , yeasty , rich and fruity . soft , yet earthy , hoppy , full-bodies , and delicious . an excellent tripel , for the sugary aspect was much more subdued than other offerings which misinterpreted , perhaps , the portions of the sweetness in the style . seemed nothing more , or less , than perfect , without being mindblowing .
honestly , i 've never really cared for the smell of budweiser .  pours a hazy gold with a small off-white head .  interesting effervescent mouthfeel makes it a pleasure to savor .

one of the best smelling beers i 've ever tried . good amount of pumpkin . clean and delicious . lighter side of medium in body . not sure if this is a drastic improvement from regular pumking , but this is surely tasty .  i was not dissappointed though . it does n't pour with much head or lace but is still evident of a very good beer ; even after poured it has a residual head-in the bottle nonetheless .  a - bright golden orange color with some chill haze present , two fingers of white frothy head that leaves thick froth-lace s - not too much rye here , just hints ... hops and bready malt t - hop bitterness up front , sweet bready malts in the back , only a hint of rye in the middle ... the malt backing is about as significant as it gets ... taste 's more like a straight up ipa than most rye beers i 've had m - hops tingle the tongue and give way to very thick , chewy malts that slide down nicely ... full-bodied and very enjoyable d - this is a reeeally well-balanced beer , i just wanted more rye flavor .

complex and strong aroma of wild flowers , banana , orange and coriander .  light golden color ; a little lighter than expected . smells hoppy ( citric , very grapefruit-like ) with an underlying sweetness . hops are very flavorful ( citric ) and also bring a decent bitterness , but are never harsh at any point . very tasty and drinkable beer that packs a punch .  mouthfeel is very good , a light bodied beer with excellent carbonation ; it dances on the tongue and finishes smooth .

s : brown sugar , sour cherries , grain , candy . t : grainy astringency , light sourness , brown sugar , wet cardboard .  poured into a piraat tulip glass , creating about an inch head that faded 5 minutes later to a lingering ring . the color is auburn with more orange higlights around the edges , very hazy .  great mouthfeel .

exquisite aroma . lime zest , clover honey , white grapes , earthy yeast , ripe granny smith apples , and a spicy component of white pepper and coriander . taste opens very citrusy , with lemon pulp and lime zest notes but honey drenched summer green apple hints balance nicely . a hint of coriander underneath and a pleasant yeast character make for a complex and very tasty experience . excellent saison by any standards .  not like motor oil , more like tobacco water . it 's damn near a hop bomb . very drinkable . i get a real dry finish from porters , maybe it 's relative to the color , but that dryness coupled with the hops makes me want more & more each sip i take .  mouthfeel- this is an exceptionally smooth saison , with the mouthfeel rivaling that of the saison dupont , my favorite of the style and one of my favorite beers . the tank 7 is definitely a thicker beer , very complimentary to the flavors .

smell is incredible . a big sugar smell is predominant accompanied by nice dark malts . there is a nice thickness to it as well , that makes it incredibly smooth . drinkable beer for a strong abv .  the beer doesn & # 8217 ; t really produce an impressive head : thin with some large bubbles .  perfect . d : great taste , but a bit rich to drink in volume .

s. pears on the nose once i open the bottle . i 'm excited to take a sip . not a great representation of the style , but a surprisingly champagne-like beer : they hit the bottle 's stated target on the mark , but i 'm still disappointed that all of the wonderful scents did n't fully transition into the taste .  there were a few big bubbles , but very minimal head . there was lacing but it did n't really stick to the glass .  the mouthfeel is outstanding , like an expensive champagne and it finishes very dry .

dipas aroma 's are awesomely hard to describe .  very drinkable.it is refreshing to have a microbrewey beer , that is not that bitter , and very drinkable.gets you very drunk.be careful because the alcohol creeps up on you with this beer.tasted citrus.i also tasted a bit of nutmeg in the aftertaste.this beer is very easy to drink.exceptional drinkability . this is the quintessential summer ale.a light , very drinkable , however , complex enough to be a microbrewery beer.i highly recommend this beer . this is a good recommendation to the general public.inasmuch as this beer is drinkable and light , many people will enjoy this . moreover , what is cool about recommending this beer , is that many people are not aware of this beer and micro beer 's in general.this was a perfect find on a june saturday , great beer to have at a high school or college graduation party.this is a great party beer , and will generate conversation at a graduation party , because numerous people have not heard of brooklyn , even suprisingly , in new york .  mouthfeel- light palate with great carbonation that tickles the senses nicely .

exquisite nose has brandy , oak , vanilla , dark pitted fruits , candy malts , port wine and whiskey . taste does not hold the same complexity . some tart cherries , plums , caramel , toffee , wood , vanilla , wine grapes and cognac . past prime for sure , but still an interesting beer .  dusky , opaque apricot capped with biscuit-color 1-finger head . head quickly dissipates and leaves errant swirls of lace supported by sparse , lazy streamers .  it has a wonderfully creamy mouthfeel that makes each sip a pleasure .

it smelled of the mediterranean sea and beautiful , long-legged , not to be fucked with , italian women with sensuous lips . a very sweet , lemony ipa that is excellent for what it is , and enjoyable , for a time .  poured into a snifter ... a : a silky waterfall of black liquid pours an opaque body with a small dark tanned head that dessipates quickly . there 's no visible lacing .  mouthfeel . amazing , thick rich and seems sweet but comes together .

oddly adjunct lager aroma detected at arms length . aroma is weak and watery with more of that adjunct lager character . lame .  a-bright , fluffy white head , 2-finger off the pour , then reducing gradually to a sparse bubble layer . slightly hazed light golden beer showed visible carbonation bubbles rising playfully .  very nice finish ... it is incredibly smooth for an imperial beer .

a - black as can be with what started as a monster tan head that has died down a bit but still lingers s - big roasted aroma 's mingle with notes of vanilla . this is just what i look for .  very little lacing on the glass .  wonderful carbonation .

the best thing about this beer is the aroma imo . awesome , very awesome . beer is thin and falls flat on the flavors at first . its a good beer , just not my favorite .  had to try this while at dragonmead as you do n't see many pumpkins around in april . amber color , clean with minimal off white head that fades quickly .  great creamy thick mouthfeel , light carbonation .

s - amazing nose ; delicious notes of chocolate , slight coffee , and super smooth oat , with roastiness present but generally transformed into the aforementioned dimensions . it reminds me of the smell of instant caf mocha , prior to the addition of hot water . ) finally , there is an appreciable hop that comes in at the end and lingers , providing herbal and vaguely floral notes on the finish .  little to no head fades quickly yet leaves very thin trace lacing behind . not a great looking ipa but not bad either .  body is velvety , full , round , and waiting to be enjoyed like a dangerous fruit i have in mind heh heh . finish is a fascinating contrast between exquisite and coarse , not too long and proly not a session unless ur into gettin hauled off .

very weird . the aroma was a bit off and the tastes could be a bit more `` in your face '' but it was worth the try .  appearance : nice dark brown but again the snow-globe of floaties that this brewery is known for . not much of a head and minimal lacing . ok , same old story , yet another very good beer from abbaye des rocs you just need to get past the floaties ( as usual ) .  the silky smooth mouthfeel was fantastic and carbonation was spot on .

smells heavy of cherries , very good smell . taste is just as heavy with the cherries .  pours a light orange color ( lighter than most pumpkin ales ) with just a bit of lacing and some nice initial head .  mouthfeel : truly phenomenal creamy medium body with the slightest touch of syrup likeness .

really really strong nose - very sweet with notes of baking spices , vanilla , vanilla cake batter , pumpkin . there is also something about it that i 'm not sure i 've ever smelled before ... and i love it . t : lives up to the smell .  certainly does n't look overly intresting .  the mouthfeel on this is exceptional , so smooth will alcohol masterfully controlled .

aroma was ridiculously appealing - sweet malt , caramel , maple , vanilla , oak , some dark fruit , and alcohol . wow . d - this was a sipper , but drinkability benefited from the fact that it tasted so damn good .  a - pours a rusty amber color , small one finger head with plenty of carbonation . very good beer by fff  m- big , full body ... oily , almost syrupy with unattenuated sugars . very chewy , and it coats the mouth so well . just wonderful .

hardly any smell , a little bit of malt maybe .  from the brewery , thanks neighbors ! a - golden in color , no head , light carbonation .  m - fairly heavy body and solid flavors with moderate carbonation . the flavors are spot , the mouthfeel is amazing and its very drinkable .

the nice octagonal packaging certainly stood out on the crowded supermarket shelf . the nose was a complex mixture of various fruits , spices and nuts along with a floral scent of hops . whilst it was n't awful to take , it was n't ver pleasant either . surprisingly light with some of the fruits and spices coming through but these were faint in comparisson to the nose , the taste was dominated by ( all too floral ) hops .  poured from a capped unlabeled bottle from my buddy adam . no head on pour , some carbonation .  mouthfeel is fantastic ... light , dry , well carbonated , and quite bitter .

the aroma is phenominal . funky , yeasty , wet wood , barn yard , and sour lemons and oranges .  i thought this was a pretty decent brown . the clear brown elixir is topped by a little head with some lacing left behind .  m - perfect . it 's velvet on the tongue .

... smell needs major improvement ... heads abit low for my liking ... golden copper in colour ... hides the abv quite well ... lacing is very nice ... smooth and drinkable but lacks that special something to make it stand out ... 'jiminy jilikers ' ''  no head , not even a film . i 'm taking a bit off for the absence of head .  mouthfeel : it is crisp , light , and perfectly carbonated .
s- very wonderful aroma here . very nice hop smells come from this .  wheat beers are notoriously summer quafs , and the raspberry ufo is no exception .  '' love the mouthfeel .

the nose is fantastic , being all floral spicy hop . the flavour is terrific too , delivering a spicy , sappy , resiny , sticky malt and hop elixir .  big malt aroma ( munich-type , sort of crystal but with a light roasty component ) with some grainy cereal notes . seems a little light colored for the style , just barely off gold , with a touch of haziness . smallish head that fades after a little while . very nice malty profile . hop bitterness is well in balance but still very subtle . clean fermentation .  mouthfeel is extremely smooth & this is a perfect beer to sip on on a lazy pm with no kids in sight !

amazing smell ; right in line with what i expect from stone .  poured a bomber into a pint glass , producing a decent head , a golden amber color and not much else .  s - sweet malt , molasses , licorice and red grapes t - sweet dark malt and licorice with a pleasant spice finish m - strong carbonation with a chalky finish that subdues the strong alcohol taste nicely d - very strong licorice and spice flavors combined with a great mouthfeel that balances the alcohol

s : about what you 'd expect from an ipa- flowery , with lots of citrus . i 'm detecting lemon , melon , and other tropical fruits . i 'm used to lemony scents from ipas , but this one has something different- it 's the distinct melon i 'm getting from the nose . t : very `` clean '' tasting , lots of citrus at the beginning . the ending is quite bitter , but not a much as some ipa 's i 've tried .  a - clear , deep honey color . the head is thin and leaves scattered lacing .  body is the best part of this brew . flavors are all in check , mouthfeel is full and fat , with a straw-like dryness at the finish . this beer is exceptionally drinkable .

the smell is outstanding , very malty and reminiscent of autumn .  hazy orange/gold color . big , creamy and very dry with driving , fine bubbles . alcohol sweetness is at the center of a complex of toasted nut , dried apple and dried apricot flavors . extremely drinkable though for such a heady brew .  m : awesomely smooth .

just plainly delicious as hell . goddamn , what a insanely alluring nose . on the palate , the dark grains come to the fore , with a rich roasted character , leavening to a light burnt cacao husk note .  it pours an average golden amber with a decent off-white head , but appearance is this beer 's weakest suit .  wonderful body .

big roasty coffee with cocoa aroma is readily evident upon , without lifting the glass .  poured a dark black color with a ring of tan bubbles that quickly fades to nothing .  the mouthfeel was awesome with silky smooth liquid and superb carbonation .

break out the smoked sausage , the perfect beer to accompany it is here . alaskan smoked porter is beautifully smokey . one whiff makes you think you 're in a great deli , loaded w/ good smoked sausage .  pours a slightly hazy , pale gold color with just a thin white head .  the texture on this is great . with the silky texture and sweetness , this is a good sipper , but nothing you 'd have more than 2 of in a single sitting .

an amazingly rich and creamy nose with strong aromas of toffee , cream , and roasted marshmallows . body is very good . drinkability : whatever hesitancy i had after seeing how it looked following the pour were overcome by the amazing aroma . a solid , flavorful drink that i would kill to try on cask .  a- after a fairly aggressive pour , i get a 1 finger head that quickly recedes into a bubbly lacing . the body is a lovely orange with no sediment .  what got me hooked was how smooth and creamy this beer was . fantastic . this beer is by far one of the richest and creamiest beers i have ever had .

s - great smelling ! lots of nice fruit and hoppy deliciousness . overall , a fantastic beer . it 's odd that it 's an amber , as it tastes a lot like an ipa .  bomber this one poured out light and orangey with a bit of chill haze . left a delicate lace on the glass .  caramel , mocha , strong booze , brown sugar , raisins , figs , chocalate t-malt , mocha , booze , brown sugar , caramel , raisins figs , chocalate m-spicy , creamy , thick , barely carbonated d- pretty thick & filling .

it has the wonderful spicy aroma that the style should always have . slight phenols , cloves , a sweet bready malt and a beautiful underlying fruitiness are all there . it finishes very very clean and does n't linger at all .  however , deep copper color with golden highlights . no foam .  the light bodied liquid is easily gulped down and that jusssttt perfect carbonation tickles the tongue making for an extremely thirst-quenching and refreshing pilsner .

poured from a growler into my new holland high gravity series glass a - black as can be with a small circle of tan/brown head s - tootsie rolls with a hint of hersheys chocolate . is this really a beer ? t - tootsie rolls with a hint of hersheys chocolate ... seriously though a little more going on in the flavor however .  paid $ 9.99 for party source to fill my growler ... the beer pours a very dark brown base , with a medium white head , 20 minutes of head retention and a speck or two of lacing on the glass .  the mouthfeel is absolutely perfect for a porter , so smooth and silky .

this fella was simply awesome . it smelled a lot sweeter than the normal ab , with the oak scent peaking through at the tail end of the nose .  pour is disappointing , honestly . a tiny fizz of head gives way to nothing in less than a minute . the good thing is , and this is what keeps it at an average score , is that the color is a beautiful golden-orange . the light really plays around , and i see a few carb trails so , strange that it has no head .  mouthfeel : wonderful balance all over the pallets and each taste-bud . the slightly raised abv can give cause to the minor warmth in mouthfeel .

the smell is the highlight of this beer- nutmeg , pumpkin , vanilla , cinnamon and a gram cracker crust smell that emerges as it warms up . tastes like pumpkin pie spices with a hop kick up front with a delicious carmelized sugar like on top of the pie in the middle , delicious . unfortunately , the finish and aftertaste is so dominant of nutmeg that all other flavors are lost . drinkability up front is exceptional but the negative finish makes it average . if they could balance out that nutmeg finish , this would be the best pumpkin beer i 've had .  when poured with vigour , it ends up a pale and bright golden colour , with minimal head , although what 's there leaves some very dense and intricate lacing .  silky smooth thick bodied with a perfect amount of light carbonation and a ridiculously long lasting , balanced tart and sweet aftertaste .

the smell is bland lacking depth . the taste is much more rewarding showing the depth which the smell was missing .  the beer pours a dark amber/brown , forming a thin white head that fades quickly .  m - smooth , silky , full body with the perfect amount of carbonation o - great brew !

aromas are lemon citrus and light spicings of coriander and nutmeg , with a toasty character , also . pineapple and mango aromas release as the beer warms .  if you 've ever had melbourn bros apricot , this kind of reminds me of that in terms of taste . very spritzy -- like carbonated pineapple juice with a zest of lemon . almost no head when i poured it , but you certainly do n't need head on this beer to catch a good aroma ; it 's exceptionally strong .  m- the mouth feel is excellent for this beer .

smell is simply awesome - like a buttery biscuit drizzled in honey , sitting in the middle of a pine forest . amazingly drinkable for the abv , and this is how the beer becomes dangerous .  a - a cloudy white gold . this actually seems more `` white '' than many belgian whites . not much in the way of head , a tad disappointing .  the mouth feel is awesome . i let a full gulp roll around from cheek to cheek just to let my tongue play in the surf .

boisterous smoked malt aroma , meaty , beaty , big , & bouncy , with light noble hops accompanying .  nice oily sheen to this ; some head retention & above average lacing s : plums & other dark fruit , a bit of leafy hops t : boozey plums , dark cherry , woody hops , dryness & a bit of cakeyness up front .  it 's as smooth as silk - perfectly suited as a dinner and desert sipper and easily the best porter i 've had the pleasure of tasting .

the aroma is great . tons of grapefruit and orange . it 's perfect . wow it 's smooth .  well ill be once ya get a good pilsner , it does make a difference ! very sturdy brew here , started off by a lemon yellow pour , with a smallish white head ( lil disappointing ) .  the malt is well back but the beer still has a nice light body . the palate is a great balance of all that and a nice honey quality in the background .

the smell of this thing is very lively , wow , its all over the place , funky as hell , smokey banana and smoked salmon or bacon , dull lemon , musty horse blanket , soft rubber , and feet .  a cinnamon-colored head rises after a vigorous pour but fizzles away after a few seconds , leaving a thin , frothy ring .  it 's exceptionally smooth with little carbonation .

aroma is pungent with grapefruit , sharp citric hops , with cloaked , faint suggestions of oranges , apples , and toasty grains .  on-tap in a flute at the capital ale house in richmond , this beer arrives orangey and crystal-clear , with low carbonation and a thin , vanishing head .  m : an incredibly thick body and big , foamy carbonation . i love the way this feels .

the smell was exceptional and exciting , with a remarkable variety of spicy tones that are too complex to describe . with great anticipation , i tried the first sip , which was heavenly . and then it happened ... a nasty aftertaste that i could n't quite place but did n't like .  lots of yeast sediment floating in a thick yellow-orange haze .  mouthfeel : so smooth and creamy . very refreshing .

the smoky aroma was evocative of a tantalizing backyard bbq wafting my direction , but that merely hinted at the in-yo-face smokiness of the brew itself .  hop monkey is a chill hazed dull orange with wispy off white collar that leaves very light , scattered lace .  wonderful mouthfeel .

for the record , fresh - this might be the mightiest tasting ipa out there . smells like mango , citrus , pine needles , pineapple , melon etc . also has a nice sweet malt aroma in the background . lots of piney resin with a pineapple/mango twang . o : overall , a finely crafted ipa . among my favs all-time and easily my top 3 from out west .  a - beautiful golden brown color with a thin and quickly disappearing head . this would have been an easy `` 4 '' it it would have had some better head and retention .  the texture is amazing . thick and silky , but because of the low abv , drinking this is just too easy .

s : intense volatile pine , fresh grass , lightly toasted bread -- a very attractive , yet clean , smell . d : this ipa is a lightweight when it comes to taste , featuring a flavor profile that just ca n't live up to the remarkable smell . clean flavor qualities are taken too far at times , with only the finish really representing the style faithfully . it is genuinely appealing to sniff and to gaze upon , though .  poured with a nice tan head which quickly subsided and a tiny bit of lace . color is a hazy amber brown .  the mouthfeel is smooth and nicely done . excellent carbonation drinkability is good as well .

it smells like when i picked hops and stuck my head into a box of them . it smells so fresh it 's wonderful . the taste was rather assertive in hoppiness .  apperance : rubarb and red apple in color . head was minimal and so was retention . color was light and tan .  the mouthfeel is great and smooth as can be .

the grapes come through again from the aroma but the flavour depth is n't as good as the nose . a decent ipa with lots of great aroma but lacking a bit of flavour . a really nice showcase of the nelson sauvin hop and a great idea from mikkeller .  this beer had an inviting lightly roasted grain aroma , rich amber color , and a crisp mouth feel . while i am primarily an ale drinker , this lager had enough body to satisfy while being light enough to have a few .  great mouthfeel - full yet fluffy , almost leaving my tongue numb .

i look at these two next to each other and woder if i have not walked into a paint shop and someone mixed my color swatch perfectly ... the aroma is fantastic . it has all the elments of a wonderful malt bomb , and just enough hop remnants to keep it interesting .  a - deep orange , almost amber in color with a thin layer of off white head that disappears into a ring of bubbles around the edge almost immediately .  a very heavy body that is infinitely swishable in your mouth and extremely creamy . this beer is truly fascinating .

the smell is extremely vibrant and spicy reminding me immediately of egg-nog . despite being very interesting and flavorful it becomes difficult to drink about halfway through .  i have to admit i do n't usually spring for hefes , but i noticed this on the shelves locally and recalled it was highly thought of by the ba crowd , so i picked up a 16oz bottle and cracked it open over dinner just to see what the fuss was about . i 'm glad i did , because this was a very solid beer . the first thing that hit me upon pouring this unfiltered , tan beer was the lovely smells dancing on the top of the fluffy head . cloves , cinnamon , yeast , lemon , banana ... just an explosion of wonderful scents . it 's quite drinkable and relatively cheap for what you 're getting .  the smoothness of the beer is very impressive , exceptional smoothness in what has to be a rather potent brew .

great smell good apperance .  pale orange like an unripe loquat . smells just like a pumpkin pie . taste like a pumpkin pie with a lot of spices .  the best thing about this brew is the mouthfeel , which is thick and expands as it moves across the tongue to the back of the mouth . modestly drinkable , but with this great thick mouthfeel , it 's one to be savored slowly .

tried to hold it up to some light , and managed to spill ( experimental error , or general incompetance ) i 'm finding it a little weak in the nose , generally unexpressive . solid dark roast , a little espresso , perhaps a little sarsaparilla . tastes deep , heavy , and satisfying .  pint dated for march ( end of month ) appearance dark red body ; almost a soda-like head ; left the scene like a sodas head ; lace was barely in the house smell black coffee ; a bit of molasses , earth , grass , roast and chocolate taste a touch of smoke and caramel blends with roast ; malts dominate ; bitterness takes a back seat mouthfeel a relatively rich body is cut into by a muted but consistent crisp ride of carbonation ; end is a bit peculiar dry but also a bit layering on back of the tongue ; nevertheless , overall the feel is smooth enough drinkability the close detracts from the drinkability but overall it is satisfying this would be nice ale for the summer barbecue .  m- incredibly smooth with a nice carbonation .

this is very easily the best smelling beer i 've ever whiffed . taste is very disappointing . the smell is this brews strongest point , but it is also the source of the beer 's greatest flaw .  respectable cover of off white tiny bubbles that slowly collars and disappears leaving a few wisps of lace .  mouthfeel is absurdly rich and creamy , silky smooth and slurpalicious . ) it 's the best feature of this brew . i mean , i like the taste , love the mouthfeel , and would enjoy having two or three of these , but that abv is on the high end .

wonderful aroma . really brilliantly done . moderate in strength , but fascinating . t : wonderful apricot fruit esters perfectly complement the wheat foundation .  a : pours a clear dark yellow with a medium head that dissipates very quickly .  m : medium bodied with a good amount of carbonation . exceptional in this category . appearance and mouthfeel are certainly worth noting .

smell is of bourbon barrels , alcohol and some deep plum and cherry/chocolate on the nose . taste follows with notes of the barrel and a very lingering close ... nice.. good feel and the drinkability is extravagant given the potency , as the alcohol is present on the nose but not on the tongue .  pours a clear , relatively pale brownish red . half finger light tan head formed on the pour then quickly dissipated . quite lightly and finely carbonated . essentially no lacings .  m : great , chewy and resiny , full-bodied and robust , with a smooth finish , compared to the rest of the sip , just what i 'm looking for in a double ipa .

the aroma was very fresh , like a breeze on a river , ( stunning ! ) floral hops and hints of citrus along with caramel malt ; a sweet and inviting blend . muted orange rind , grapefruit notes and a doughy malt/yeast blend were present but the bitterness that sat atop them i found unpleasant .  a : pours a murky orange/ruby color with a thin cap of fluffy tan head that sits on top .  m : glorious . so creamy and good . reminds me of a cask pour .

amazingly complex . taste follows nose and begins with dark malts and honey sweetness .  poured this 375 ml green bottle into a lindemans flute . the first pour was clear golden with many tiny bubbles clinging to the sides . the second pour was murkier .  amazing mouthfeel . viscous , rich and creamy without being syrupy .

the smell is strong with brandy ( and seemingly bourbon ) and dark fruity sweet malts , caramel , and vanilla . very pleasant . holy shit , what this beer would be if it were carbonated ! dark fruit sweetness complimented by a smooth and invigorating alcohol presence ( 12.5 % ) , much like an imperial stout ... its damn decent right now , but so much greater in my carbonated imagination .  pours a dark , clear brown with a very small head .  m : the best feature of this beer . rich , creamy , and silky as it goes down .

appearance - a light golden color , with small amount of head around the sides of the beer smell - this is the best part of the beer , its light with just a hint of of orange/citrus . taste - bitter , which comes as a shock after the smell .  a : pours a dark brown with ruby highlights . a small beige head forms and recedes to a ring in an instant . not much lace to speak of .  mouthfeel is very crisp and smooth with some thickness from the yeast and bite from the hops .
this smells amazing ! t - the taste is good , not great ... yet .  orange hazy full head reduces to a thin layer .  excellent ! incredible smooth and silky mouthfeel .

it is good , but one at a time .  very carbonated , a light and bubbly beer . the head fluffs up and then dies down , a shame . the color is a golden white , a bit of a haze .  extreme balance and smoothness in this beer , its quite good . big full body with a champaign like fizzyness . im impressed .

smells creamy/milky with rich , almost sweet coffee , chocolate , kaluha , cocoa , and a touch of green hops . absolutely divine . the flavor is roasty with burnt/charred malts , coffee , chocolate , and a medium bitterness .  pours a murky brown-fuschia with an odd colored pink/brown head . not exactly a looker .  first sip reveals a soft creamy texture with mild rolling carbonation .

aromas of tart cherries right off the bat mixed with nicely roasted malts and a woody bourbon aroma as well . i really enjoy the tart cherry integration .  a - near clear , orange , lots of cling leaves to disk . m - medium body , good carb .  all kinds of malty goodness going on here - silky smooth , slightly pinpoint carbonation .

one of the best smelling beers i have tried .  pours a dark brown , near black , color with brown highlights around the edges . minimal lacing . apperance is nothing special .  entering the mouth , i immediately take notice of the huge mouthfeel on this . this is fluffy , powdery , quaffable , and has this charming soft carbonation that is typical of great beers . palate displays a superb spicy bitterness executed in incredible balance and harmony ( this and the mouthfeel are the 2 attractions imo ) , gentle woodiness .

it is astoundingly complex . t - it tastes like a better-than-average barleywine , but not by much . d - a mixed bag ; full of lore and hype , looks intriguing , smells wildly complex , tastes like an old abused barleywine .  dark brown color , slightly opaque , a 2/3-finger head that hangs around for a decent while before disappearing ; the drink does n't leave too much lacing behind .  full , thick , rich mouth feel .

smell is impressive . it practically filled the room as soon as i popped the crack . super floral hoppy , it just smells beautiful . taste is more muted and one sided , but still tasty . overall , quite good beer .  my second dark lager of the evening ... .a murky brown lager that pour with ample carbonation , but somehow the head falls flat ... .disappointing .  mouthfeel is where this one shines , smooth as can be and perfectly carbonated , a light yet creamy quality .

appearance : beautiful murky caramel color with a hint of dried apricot . smell : amazing sweet english butter toffee with candied strawberries . very very rich and delicious . mouthfull : thick and smooth exceptional beer by another great quebec brewery .  a little head retention & no lacing s : slight earthy hops up front then a little fruittyness t : piney hops up front followed by fruittyness & a slight grainyness .  the mouthfeel on this beer is almost perfect . a nice smooth drinkable beer .

nose is certainly affected with the trademark jolly pumpkin barrel aroma/flavor.. light vanilla wood without imparting too much diacetyl . finally , i 've found the beer this balances with perfectly.. the creamy whipped dreaminess of the barrel versus the stark , bright , ripe fruits of an american dubbel.. this exudes a mindblowing aroma . superb . blueberry ice cream scent with a blondie underneath . delectable . taste does n't disappoint either . jolly pumpkin seems to be a real one trick pony , but this is one of the times when that pony executes its trick perfectly .  first observations : whoa , what a smell ! the appearance is dark , of course ... .well more of a dark red . not much head or retention , but i did n't expect much .  this beer feels absolutely perfect in the mouth .

it reeks of pumpkin pie without being too aggressive with it . the pumpkin pie aroma does n't dominate the taste and it actually tastes like a beer instead of some kind of pumpkin pie flavored wine cooler .  appearance : bronze with a coarse , thinning beige head .  smooth and rich on the tongue .

( s ) - a ridiculously rich aroma . awesome whiffs of oaky bourbon with sweet toffee and caramel with an even more glorious smell of cocoa covered dark cherries behind it . its strong , but smells really stinking good .  pours a very hazy deep copper with a slight orange/tan head . leaves a mere wisp of foam and some lacing .  thin in the mouth but heavy on the tongue . perfect for the style and the season .

s : very , very nice . belgian yeast and sweet breads hit first , closely followed by pine and citrus hops . nice complexity and balance here .  a : pours red-brown , with slight haze and a light haze that quickly drops to nothing .  mouthfeel : exceptionally smooth and silky as can be .

smell : very sweet . some booze cuts through the richness . incredibly decadent . taste : one of those beers where you say `` wow , '' after the first sip .  somewhat amber color for an ipa . a very interesting ipa , and probably the best beer from magic hat in awhile .  thick with just a little bit of slickness and just enough carbonation . sly fox oatmeal stout is a solid beer with a fantastic mouthfeel ; probably something i would order again .

good lacing & head retention s : intense almost burnt caramel & malt & some alcohol t : smokey caramel & a little aclohol up front , then a hint of cherry & oak . finishes with dryness , a slight smokeyness & a praline sweetness mf : sticky rich body with excellent carbonation & balance drinks good , but 2 would be about my limit .  pours a nice rich brown , not much head .  mouthfeel- medium bodied ale for sure and had small amount of carbonation . very creamy , and left a easy feel on the tongue .

smell is of bourbon , wood , malt , brown sugar , toffee , and dark fruits . overall , this is a fantastic beer with very complex aromas and flavors . i am really glad i was able to try this one .  oh , it looks like a euro pils , and to some extent , smells like a pilsner .  the aroma speaks strongly of roasted grains , as you would expect from a stout , while on the tongue the beer has tremendous body .

the aromas are very fine and intense i was very impressed ! !  pours a beautiful deep brown , very little head quickly recedes- no lacing .  regular boris has the most incredible smooth palate and this follows suit . so silky smooth from the oatmeal . definitely an interest beer for this alone .

for me , this was one of the most appealing scents i 'd smelled in a long time .  pours a copper color with what starts out as a nice creamy head but almost instantly recedes into a thin film . minimal lacing left behind .  m : the feel is exactly how i like my imperial stouts . there is a decent amount of carbonation in there as well .

aroma : coffee and chocolate malt meld accented by a whiff of hops and a touch of smoke . nice complexity and balance leads to a very appealing invitation . overall impression : thick and creamy with a wonderful nose . unfortunately the taste just didnt live up to the billing .  aroma : malt base with some mild floral hop notes appearance : deep gold that looks too light for a bock in my opinion . nice white head , even from the 3rd or 4th pour from the growler , and nice rocky lace .  one of the best mouthfuls ever !
but overall still a nice dipa and one you could drink a couple of .  some froth and lace .  mouthfeel is really impressive . very gradual on the tongue and extraordinarily balanced .

s- super hoppy and sweet with a mixture of predominant pine flavor and underlying grapefruit notes ... absolutely exquisite . t- taste is very reminiscent of pliny the elder but possibly better balanced .  a- pours a jet black color . oily slickness on the sides of the glass but no lacing at all .  great bubbly mouthfeel , no aftertaste at all .

i have to say that the smell of this is fantastic . t : wow , the taste is a bit of surprise .  a : pours almost pitch black with some deep ruby highlights around the edges , capped by a thin layer of mocha-colored head . retention is poor as the head dissipates almost immediately , leaving scant lacing .  m- really interesting . a dry feeling on the sides of the tongue and a sweet feeling in the back . really well done .

( i have cheap , nasty wine coolers for that ) this is my first ever malt liquor . wheee pours a clear straw with a not-bad head . definitely a sweetish , chemically smell , but not overwhelming.is that some hops ? could be ... hiding behind the solvent .  poured rather hazy in the glass with minimal head after a vigorous dispense .  finishes dry with nice mocha notes & a touch of charred grain mf : very oily & smooth as all hell with low carbonation & nice stickyness .
m- thick and oily , slick and refreshing . d- very tart and complex flavor combination of hops .  cloudy caramel colour with little to no head .  moderate body , excellent smoothness .

very inviting , to say the least .  acloudy reddish brown with a thin tan sheet of foam on top , no head to speak of , but laced well as i drank it down sspicy , raison , plum , apricot , pear , lots of fruity smells here tnot much like the smell , buttery toffee flavor , maybe some mild fruit tones , flavor is very mild and enjoyable if you like mild ales msmooth and velvetish , medium bodied , not much for carbonation dvery differentthe smell really threw me on this one ; i expected the taste to be more fruity .  the carbonation is just right here .

very authentic aroma ... think of opening the cupboard to access your spice rack , then getting a whiff of fresh rosemary . d - another innovative beer with an authentic aroma and flavor .  pours a clear orange-y amber with an initially large white head , which reduces to a thin haze .  the mouthfeel was awesome - very creamy and full bodied .

a-dark brown/black s-nice blend of cocoa and leafy hops..really impresses on the nose . t-hops are a little more forward on the taste ... .interesting hop dimensions ... some bright citrus ... .and some grungy pine and weed like notes ... roasted malts ... .also some darker cocoa ... m-rich ... fuller bodied ... .feels bigger than a regular black ipa ... body fits ... o-top notch effort .  pours a light amber with a cloud and a small head that dissipates quickly .  mouthfeel - smooth , evenly carbonated , and a perfectly solid body .

d : nice big i.p.a. , best smelling i have had yet , very flavorful and the malt has been kept in check and the hops can come right through .  a : pours a bit cloudy .  super creamy mouthfeel w/o any overcarbed bite .

aroma is exceptional , with a great sweet citrus smell that bursts from the bottle and makes you want to take a huge gulp . this is n't a horrible beer , and if you love bitterness , you should love it .  pours orangey yellow ... not spectacular . poured too cold , but strong lacing nonetheless .  mouthfeel is medium-thick but amazingly silky . carbonation is moderate .

an impressive nose . t : mouth puckering bitterness is the first thing i noticed . d , notes : this is very good . the type of beer that bas help move to the best of list .  rusty , deep brown . thin , big-bubbled tan head recedes quickly and leaves negligable lace .  m- mouthfeel on this is incredible . medium to full bodied , chewy and creamy , moist , and not a hint of alcoholic bite .

aroma : very complex . banana , clove , butter , bubblegum , and hints of alcohol .  pours murky burnished copper , bit of brown seeping in , with a thin , soapy tan head on top , that at least lasts for quite awhile on its own .  m/d : a full body that is creamy and velvety smooth .

smoked gouda cheese , which is one of my favorite cheeses , some peet smokiness , a bit of earthiness , and a little sourness .  from notes ... had this on tap in prague at a chinese restaurant off of hastalska street a : dark copper colored beer with a small but lasting head s : not much , but some malt and hops ... t : much more filling and thick than a traditional pils m : smoother and thicker , but still crisp d : very good beer , a nice change of pace from the pils abound in prague .  m= perfect dryness and crispness .

nose : this thing has everything : an early combination of chocolate , caramel , and nuts presents a whole pecan pie on a silver platter . all this is followed by some dark chocolate covered cherries and fruitcake aroma . it has a sweet plastic lasting flavor that warns off any hops . has a bit of a smoky swallow which is nice , but does n't mellow the bubble gum . this one is getting thrown behind bars for 3-5 - then we 'll see if it 's more under control .  an apple ale , this has a nice golden hue , but with no head or lacing to speak of . huge apple aromas !  m : full-bodied and lightly carbonated with a soft and creamy texture . alcohol noticable in a nice warming effect .

s : smell is great . bourbon , vanilla , and coffee . t : tastes of bourbon , vanilla , and coffee with hints of toffee and roasted malts . d : this is very drinkable , especially for the abv .  pours typical saison ... hazy golden straw , filled with hints of brown highlights .  m - creamy and rich . the carbonation is very laidback ... almost feels as if it floats on the tongue . very soft ... puffy , in a way .

one of the nicest smelling dipas ( imperial pale ? ) i 've experienced t : initially starts out with lots of bitterness from the hops .  from a growler into a frosty mason-jar mug at purv 's beer and more in peckville , pa lighter in appearance than i had expected . smell was of straight cocoa powder and a little bit of spice from the chili pepper mouthfeel was very nice considering the light color .  m - amazing . low to moderate carbonation ( expected ) and full bodied .

the aroma was like a big hop garden bouquet with a little sugared pixie dust spread all over . i was ready for the taste and ready to be blown away , but was not .  poured with a little head , but after the initial head was gone , could n't get it back . no lacing at all .  a very smooth , luxurious malt backbone enhances the mouthfeel , but a bitter smack of hops reminds me that i 'm drinking an ipa . quite enjoyable .

tons of chocolate malt , coffee , anise , plums , raisons a fruit blender of aromas . it really needed more hops to balance this bad boy out .  here it goes : looks kind of like filtered apple cider . maybe a little more orange . more inviting than most , but it does have some funk to it .  feels wonderful on the tongue , perfect for a summer or spring day .

the smell is defiantly banana bread , a welcoming aroma .  cloudy , deep amber-straw . almost half a finger of bubbly white head that does n't last long .  loved the residual stickiness . d- it 's remarkable how fff can make such big beers and hide the alcohol so well .

tasted june 25th 2011 ( from notes ) poured into a la chouffe tulip a - deep copper , one finger off white head and some lacing s - lots of alcohol , very hoppy , pineapple , pine , grass , very yeasty , sweet malt , sugar , high octane everything , flowers , grass and tons of everything awesome t - really sweet up front and than a wall of bitter . this is a great ipa . i am starting to be a big fan of yulesmith final thought - 8 % + abv and only $ 7 a bottle . this one is worth it and if you find this on tap somewhere , please email me  pours out a thick , browny , sludge ( hah ) with a little bit of thin head , which completely dissipitates to just a mild lacing around the edges of the glass . a huge whiff of toffee notes , rock candy , and what seems to be raspberry twists . this ca n't be an american beer , where are the hops ? for what it is , it is incredibly good to drink slowly .  m : as expected it has a wonderful feel to it that only a belgian can give . thick and creamy with a medium weight that gives way to an extremely crisp finish .

excellent . sweet and sour fruits cominate the taste , but caramel malts creep slowly in , along with alcohol , honey , and even some wood . the feel ends up pleasantly sweet and smooth .  picked this up at the biergarten in jenks : pours an effervescent apricot/caramel with 2 fingers of cream colored head . average head retention & lacing s : orchard fruit in abundance , burnt candi-sugar , peaches , green apple peels & honey , almost pulled a 4.5 t : persimmons , pears , white grapes , candi-sugar , a touch of brown sugar & dryness up front , some lemons & grassyness there as well .  medium bodied , excellent mouthfeel .

smell is very sexy - pure belgian goodness . taste is very good . this beer is very drinkable . each sip is very nice as you get a great whif of that aroma . belgian yeast is very impressive - the unique flavor qualities never get old ; they are very subtle .  a- pours a nice shade of a light amber/orange with a paper thin white head that immediately fades . looks good , but the head situation is greatly disappointing .  mouthfeel is where this beer really shines , and makes one understand why some folks are such lager fans . the balance in this beer is amazing , with everything seemingly in the right preportion .

i 'll tell you that the smell is freaking awesome . have n't tasted the beer yet , but smells of good things to come ... here we go . s - freaking awesome . especially since i considered this some bland , flavored light beer t - nice .  it 's dark brown in appearance with no head .  m- great mouthfeel .

smell is super fruity sweetness , excellent complexities including wood , vanilla and a bit of alcohol . taste is an explosion of goodness . i love that barleywines come in 12oz bottles** , as that 's the size that i 'd prefer to have this style of beer in .  a - poured very little head , and left very little lacing.. and i know my glass is clean . looks like an ipa ... nice orangey-amber glow .  starts with roasted coffee flavor , mouthfeel is incredible smooth .

absolutely fantastic aroma , but let down by it 's flavours .  kind of goofy throw back ( 50 's ) look bottle ( works well with the duke ellington i am listening to at the moment ... ) eyeballs ... straw with a brownish tinge , nice head , withstanding well , solid carbonation , nothing fancy nothing rancid nose ... bready , almost belgian esque but a bit breifer.. malt and subdued hops like honeysuckle rather than a full on bouquet.. pleasant enough mouth action ... a nice fullness without being heavy in the least , fills the mouth amply without over carbonation , the feel is excellent across the whole pallette , this reminds me of what a `` mild '' fullers esb would tast like , quite enjoyable , nothing overwhelming , just a nice malt ( not too sweet ) start and bare bones hops that finishes dry enough to not drown out the wonderfull mouthfell verdict : an excellent session beer , not as agressive as say long trail ale in america but similar in its ease of sip and nice full feel across the whole mouth .  m- very , very thick and chewy . also quite heavy .

smell is unbelievable . tons of chocolate , dark fruit , and malted milk balls .  slightly lighter than i would expect . fizzy beige head of .5 cm fades quickly to nothing . first sip reveals an average body with fine rolling carbonation and smooth silky texture .  the mouthfeel is outstanding . substantial , but not quite so thick as to confuse it with a stout .

smell has a strong piney grapefruit aroma , the grapefruit really shines through as the star , the aroma kind of reminds me of the 1260 triple ipa .  pours a thin a off white head that rapidly dissipates into the ethers . body is deep brown-black . the oakiness becomes a bit more pronounced ion the flavor along with some of the accompanying bourbon . new hollands crown jewel indeed . i drank this around cellar temperature which really seemed to bring out its full character .  mouth feel is incredible with some good champagne bubbling going on .

sour raspberries + classic cantillon funk = awesome . i love it . t : raspberry essence jumps into my palate and my nose as i raise the glass , and as soon as the beer hits my tongue the fruit gets displaced by intense sourness + moderate cantillon funk . delightful . o : i expect every cantillon i drink to be amazing , but based on other reviews i really was n't hoping for anything special from the framboise .  looks pretty average for an american double .  mouthfeel very full and smooth .

back to the smell - oak , but the lovely old sort . . .  pours a thick deep black with a very thin tan head . no retention , no lace .  extremely smooth tasting beer . bodied is so full its nearly chewable . mouthfeel is full and round . finish is clean and very smooth .

the smell is really quite wonderful ; nearly perfect . the roast and sweetness are the perfect marriage of complimentary elements .  had this on-tap at ccb 's tasting room during the hunahpu release even on september 24 , 2011 . a : very dark brown , almost black body with a superficial tanned coffee head that dissipated quick . no lacing present . o : it was a good way to start the evening with this beer , which definitely starts shining after it warms up a bit .  m- extremely smooth with the right amount of carbonation d- this one goes down too easily .

there is also a nice toffee and molasses sweetness to keep the aroma balanced . there are also hints of dark berries : to me it smelled like blueberry and raspberry . it is a very enticing aroma . taste : more roasted glory , and the first sip was a shock of burnt bitterness ; the overpowering intensity , though , passed after a couple sips .  a- murky brown amber , wispy head .  matches perfectly with the thickness of the body .

i 've always like tryign various fruit beers ... .and this one was certainly one of the better ones that i have tried . the raspberries are extremely prevalent to both smell and taste , but not to the point of being overwhelming .  appearance : tawny brown , quite hazy , thinnish layer of tan frothy foam , ok head retention aroma : rich malty caramel , tangerine , woodsy hops , raisins flavor : smooth malt sweetness with hints of orange marmalade , stewed prunes , hazelnuts , and herbally hops ; finishes semisweet with a brief fruity aftertaste mouthfeel : medium body , gentle carbonation , smooth and soft texture , slight warmth in the throat other comments : quite a scrumptious bitter .  super easy going down with a perfect dry finish .

beer also appeared to be quite carbonated smell : hot-day-amn . the smell of this one is trump tight . the eastern spices are like aroma therapy . those clove-ish spices blend with the hops and a sweet fruit scent to create an enticing aroma . taste : from the second this one hits your lips you just know that this is an `` americanized '' tripel .  it was hard to judge appearance since it was in a brown bottle , but it seems to be a little cloudy with just a bit of foam .  in the mouth , the tiny bubbles announce and incredibly smooth and balanced beer , with a roasted , slightly sweet flavor .

aroma : an amazing , complex aroma which far exceeds any other pils aroma i have smelled . lemony , peppery , summery , yeasty and malty all zipping around my nose . taste : does n't live up to the aroma but is n't bad .  there is a decent amount of head but it dies down quickly .  great palate , though . even when it gets warm , great warmth and sliky smooth syrups .

wonderful mixed aroma with qualities of malt behind the wonderful saaz hops . this is a really nice beer .  very small , quickly evaporating head and absolutely no lacing .  the carbonation is spot on and helps bring the subtle notes of roast to the front . this also makes this beer one of the best feeling brews i 've ever had .

nice maple , nice cognac pipe tobacco aroma going on as well as some nice syrup smell . great . t- initially , some nice matliness , caramel/maple , then some dry hops .  a : pitch black color , no head , no lacing s : raisins , figs , sweet woodiness t : sweet oak , raisins , figs , smoky chocolate ; finishes with a nice smoky wood bitterness m : medium-thick , lightly carbonated , velvety smooth o : this did n't quite live up to the enormous hype , but it 's still a world-class beer nonetheless .  the first thing i noticed actually was the incredible mouthfeel .

this beer was very jeckyll and hyde for me . the smell is also terrific : citrusy , apricot , peach ( as others have noted ) .  drank from a bottle the taste was that of really good choclete and hints of coffe . no real bitter taste had a light smell of choclete to it over all etremelly drinkable and refreshing . alsohada light carbination not too much or little justenough to givethe right amount of fizz this beer is in my opinon up there as far as import beers farsuppour to a guiness wich is overlly bitter .  m - thick , very smooth and very viscous with little carbonation .

i love the smell of this stuff , there is n't a better smelling stout in the world , even if its from a can .  extremely cloudy , almost milky thick pale orange golden color .  perhaps there is similar inconsistency here , and i will be wowed by the bottles i brought home sometime in the future ... mouthfeel is by far the best characteristic , supple , creamy and light .

s - easily the beer 's most remarkable feature . wonderful aroma of blackberries and blueberries with a slightly sourish tint . t - although it does n't quite live up to the aroma in terms of complexity , this is still quite good . early palate some sour dark fruits are balanced out by a moderate caramel flavor .  bought a michelob mixed sampler 12 pack for $ 9.99 wow , big surprise here ! i may be a spring chicken when it comes to beer drinking but this was one of the better hefe 's i 've had and to think it comes from ab .  big , viscous mouthfeel does great things for this beer , transmitting a pretty large package ( 10 % , significant ibu count ) into an easy-to-sip package .

beautiful smell of bourbon it 's you first then caramel , vanilla , and a hint of oak .  pours a caramel to reddish color with a lightly colored head . the head is not very impressive looking .  the mouthfeel is light , with excellent particulates that roam the mouth . a most excellent brew that i would n't hesitate to try again .

i smell fresh cat piss , pine , grapefruit peel , fresh , fresh fresh hops ! ! ! ! still hard to live up to the smell . the mouthfeel is good and i have to say that if this beer was on tap i would stop for a pint or three every day .  a : pours a rather hazy , blonde yellowish colour . disturbing the settled yeast added a good amount of sediment to the pour .  bordering on chewy as you work toward swallowing . carbonation was excellent on tap , just enough to contribute to a dry and clean finish despite the initial sweetness of the beer .

very nice scent , potent citrus and floral hops .  appearance- the color reminds me of cedar wood an earthy dark amber/red . mouthfeel- light on palate and definetly lends itself to match with food nicely like breaded shrimp .  mouthfeel is full but not too heavy .

huge tropical fruit aromas on this one -- passion fruit , mango , pineapple and bubble gum . creamy , with a good warming alcohol finish .  got this beer on tap at the flying saucer . pours a yellowish amber body with finger width white head .  m : rich and creamy . very chewy and thick . little carbonation .

very interesting . concrete and ginger . refreshing and smooth but a bit more bland than i expected based on the wonderful aroma . nicely mellow and subtle .  i love marin brewing co. beers and this is a well made ale . i just do n't think it 's my style . looked like a lager which was a bit surprising as i expected something darker .  perfect carbonation to it .

yeasty aroma with bready , semi-sweet wheat . the anchor house/ mineral smell is here and that is fine . hops are subtle and slightly floral .  pours a deep orange amber with a light tan head that lingers for a while .  m - huge , thick , syrupy , creamy , perfect carbonation .

aroma was an incredible with scents of spicy dark bread .  really a weird pour as it comes out a very nice hazelnut color but with no head at all to speak of .  perfectly constructed mouthfeel for a schwarzbier .

smell : strong grapefruit was the only thing that really hit me . nothing to write home about on the nose . taste : wow . an outstanding american ipa .  white head is foamy and small , with little retention . leaves very little lace . like a pils on steroids .  the mouthfeel on this ale was great , and i think the mouthfeel of just about any beer is enhanced by cask conditioning . it had a nice thick feel on the tongue .

s : this smells amazing . raspberry and strawberry jam with bread and peanut butter . unbelievable , the aroma could n't be better . impressive . m : lower medium body with upper moderate carbonation . overall : the flavor is good , but the aroma is unreal . i could n't take my nose out of the glass .  pours a crystal-clear straw-yellow body with a quickly dissipating off-white head .  palate duration is excellent . medium body .

it has a pleasantly pungent , complex smell . all sorts of flower and herbal along with some mint .  from a bottle provided by doublej , thanks jon , a : pours a lightly hazy gold with a spotty light white head , average head retention , some lace .  mouthfeel is rich and creamy .

three floyds beers have a unique aroma . the hops come across , thick and flowery . ive heard they use amarillo and columbus hops for aroma . many brewers could learn from these folks . milk chocolate , coffee , a little toasted malt with just a mild flowery hop flavor on the finish . slick , smooth and rich mouth feel , very nice , very drinkable .  poured into my duvel tulip . appearance- cognac colored pour..i guess caramel , maybe ruby caramel . 1/2 inch head on pour which is gone before you can say doppelbock . no lacing at all .  m- great mouth feel . very smooth and not over-carbonated .

exceptional aroma . very hoppy , and you get it at the first sip , then the sweetness , finishes bitter , with all the hops of an ipa but more subdued .  a coppery orange with minimal head that leaves a thin lacing around the glass .  t- the taste is starts out very smooth and creamy from the mouthfeel with some of roasted malts quickly followed by a nice bitter finish . m- the mouthfeel is silky smooth from the oatmeal with a moderate amount of carbonation . d- very good stuff , and not too boozy for a 9 % beer even though you can feel the warmth .

smell : the aroma of the beer is full of hoppy promises . oily pine tar resins combine with a citrus and tropical fruits explosions of grapefruit , lemon , mango and pineapple bombard my nose .  pours to a thin white head and clear darkish gold color . good for the hot summer .  mild-medium carbonation just enough to excite the palate . to me , this is almost the perfect mouthfeel .

s - toffee , cocoa powder , nutty , then as it warms sweet citrus oil , green pine needles . slabs of caramel mix with alcohol vapors and fill the glass with a robust sweetness . t - starts with a mix of semi/sweet chocolate , sweet toffee malt , then an undertow of hops rush in with mint and citrus . the aroma is so good it 's hard to explain .  a- pours black in color . not a oil black , but its still black . there is very little head and minimal lacing left .  the feel is big and thick .

an interesting double ipa with a very malty edge and bitter finish . smells of floral hops , much caramel and honey and autumn mornings . honestly it smells a lot better than the taste .  a : pours black with a finger of tan head that recedes into a thin ring with no lacing .  smooth , airy , luscious , divine mouthfeel . tremendous ! a wonderful bsda .

smell was outstanding . malts , and dried fruits , raisins , prunes , etc , very complex and really builds the base for the beer . very , very nice . no bitterness to speak of and a lingering toffee sweetness at the end . overall an excellent doppelbock , right up there in my top 3 .  halfway through and the head is gone , with nary a speck of lacing .  mouthfeel is just perfect . the way this thing finishes it has a slight peppery aspect but it is dry and clean .

s : nothing sticks out faint smell of hops .  the head is a moderate-lived cocoa-colored affair that recedes into a floating patch of film on top of the brew . a few rings here and there , but generally no lacing .  mouthfeel is heavy and smooth with a small amount of carbonation , very nice .

this smell is really on the money and superbly enjoyable . tasted honey sweet with dark malts and dark fruits that fades into a smoky birch bark and a really dirty lime or rhubarb sourness .  god , that sounds so snobby and like such b/s ... nonetheless , it pours a very nice orange/beige and again had no head mainly because i believe that i poured it wrong . damnit , that 's two meals for me .  mouthfeel is probably the best part of this beer .

smells great ( but nothing like a gumball imo ) . incredible . very bitter for a pale ale , or pale wheat ale , whatever . it certainly smelled good , but nothing more than the typical tropical fruit-heavy pale/ipa .  little head accompanied a dark clear golden colour . little cardination and some lacing .  mouthfeel : thick and smooth in every sense of the words -- a very pleasant experience indeed !

smells like delicious ginger snaps , cinnamon and some clove . delicious . it has a medium body with a good amount of carbonation . definitely a sipper , but a very good sipper .  12 oz bottle , pours a hazy amber with very little head , even with pouring into the middle of the glass .  mouthfeel is so big thick and creamy .

smell only needs one word : raspberries . lots of raspberries . also smells a bit tart and kind of like juice . very sweet and tart at the same time .  pours a somewhat cloudy red mahogany , with minimal head .  beautiful .

well it pour nicely and the blonde beer with a nice haze had a very decent white head that lasted a long time . i had to fight for my first sip throught he generous head and was greeted with a bland hefe . this time i spent a moment smell the beer and could not really detect any of the usual hefe-weizen smells it seemed muted , but overall i found it lacking .  bottle to sniffer appearance : pours with a small brown head that quickly dissipates , looks of black coffee the carbonation barley able to keep the head alive .  m- awesome thick mouthfeel on this seasonal .

the aroma , which was really the high point of this beer , was quite terrific -- roasty malt with hints of chocolate and black cherries .  the beer pours a hazy golden orange with a small amount of head .  the body is just fantastic : full , creamy and smooth .

well after all the hype i had to give this one a try , pours motor oil black with two finger tan head , smells of alcohol and burnt espresso , tastes the exact same , if i were to roast some espresso beans until they were charred all the way through , then threw them into a blender with ice and vodka , thats exactly how this tasted to me .  poured deep copper , clear with not a lot of head . and what did foam up went away somewhat quickly . almost no lacing .  mouthfeel is perfect . not too thick and good carbonation .

appearance is nice , dark but that red cherry goodness shines . smell is the winner here with loads of cherries and chocolate . taste is good , and hits big with cherries , a little dark smoke and chocolate .  a-light amber/reddish color with a small head nothing much else s- smells of spices coriander and pumpkin , smells just like fall in my humble opinion t- tastes just like it smells full of pumpkin with heavy spices .  full bodied and silky .

the aroma continues to provoke the senses with a luscious , mouthwatering perfume . its flavor had a tough time catching up to its exceptional aroma , but still came through with a graceful sequence of sweet malts modestly checked with a light hop scheme .  pours an orangish-amber into a pint glass with very little foam .  very full body that stretches the cheeks . just such chewy hops .

does n't quite live up to the smell , but still very pleasant and highly sessionable .  i was a bit apprehensive with my first sip of the saranac black and tan because it poured almost no head ( at first i thought i had gotten a bad one ) .  m : the carbonation on this one is perfect . perfect mouthfeel .

aroma was very pleasing . deep and rotund hop nose is neither too flowering , too citrusy , and definitely stops shy of being too grassy . really a unique aroma , something that has become kind of rare these last few years .  pours dark brown with very little head .  m : very viscous and full . smooth carbonation and a nice stickyness make the mouthfeel very complimenting to the taste .
