nose has a surprising sweetness with tropical fruit esters of subtle pineapple and mango : both were of the dried and sweetened kind of fruit rather than fresh . citrus , earthy , grassy hops balanced with biscuit sweet and bitter malts .  golden amber color , thin white head that dissipates very quickly . extremely drinkable , with a lot of flavor while it is in your mouth but no aftertaste , so it begs for the next sip .  m : very soft , finely carbonated medium body .

s - lively lemon oil aroma , very fresh and unique . lots of spicy wheat and slightly fruity yeast . the aroma is spectacular , it smells like oil squeezed out of a fresh lemon peel , though the flavor is not quite as good .  pours a clear dark brown with slight beige head .  mouthfeel is perfect -- light but not watery , highly carbonated ... perfect for the style .

there is little aroma with the beer a slight sweet smell .  this pours a nice dark brown with an off white head . little retention and virtually no lacing .  the first thing one notices , upon pouring , is the consistency : this beer appears thicker than most , and may or may not have legs , likely a contributing factor to this beers exceptional mouthfeel .

this smells just terrific . the flavors on the palate generallyh replicate the nose , except they 're not as intense and the brown sugar and chocolate seem to dominate the flavor profile .  a - pours very dark brown in color with some light that is able to make it through around the edges revealing some ruby highlights . the tan head was quite minimal showing very little retention and leaving very little lace .  smells like a smoke beer ... .i get a little chocolate in the nose ... but the roasted smell is overpowering ... taste is sweet on the front end ... and an overall smooth taste ... .with a little bitterness on the back end ... very nice feel ... .creamy and smooth perfect for the style ... .velvet like smoothness ... drinkability is not bad ... although it is a stout and it weighs you down ...

smell is incredible : pure piney , grapefruity hops with a veneer of rich malt . and that in itself is amazing ! finishes like an unsweetened soda .  exceptionally fizzy cloudy and golden appearance .  solid mouthfeel , smooth and dense with animated carbonation .

aroma : heavenly . roasted malt , chocolate , a hint of coffee , and i detected a hint of whiskey aroma that was very pleasant . taste and mouthfeel : slightly chewy but not quite creamy .  poured chilled in tall pilsner glass a : little carbonation ; minimal head ; clear , solid yellow s : clove , yeast ; inviting aroma t : dry , spiced , medium hops ; light on the belgian side of things ( e.g. , bottle conditioning ) ; not very intense flavor overall , a good solid beer , drawing sound inspiration from the belgians .  the alcohol is kept well in check allowing the finish to cascade over the palate with a ton of character and wonderful texture . strong , long finish .

the smell on this one is incredible , and leaves little to be desired . a lot of chocolate hits the nostrils as well as bitter espresso . this is by far the best porter i have ever smelled , thus far . the taste is not quite up to par here .  the off-white head is modest in size and quickly recedes to a ring and an island of foam . what little head is left behind manages to leave some scattered lacing .  the mouthfeel is a true hallmark of this beer .

aroma packs an immediate bourbon punch and is balanced by rich vanilla and milk chocolate . molasses , raisins , brown sugar and caramel with very little roast , burnt or hop aromas . non-existent alcohol and the sweetness is very pleasant and smooth . flavor is similarly smooth and balanced with surprisingly more of a milk chocolate , vanilla and molasses presence than in the nose . bourbon is still present , particularly in the finish , but never harsh . warming throughout , yet the balance between the barrel and base beer is remarkable . mouthfeel is slightly thinner than hoped for , medium thick with light carbonation ; slightly milky in character . i do n't feel like this detracts from my enjoyment of the beer , but for the style would have expected something a little more robust .  12oz bottle poured into imperial pint glass a - pours a very cloudy , orangish/brown bark color with a 3/4 inch light tan head . lacing is moderate when tipped , and head rests at a thin layer .  initially the softness of the carbonation and the sweetness of the fruity flavors makes it like a sweet soda ( can anyone remember tahitian treat ? again with the yeast character and the near rancid presence ( the brett i presume ) , yet the overall soft flavors and soft feel are greatly appealing and enjoyable . the light , fine and bubbly carbonation brings an element of childhood fun to the drink ( how about fizzies , anyone remember that ) as it brings a tickle to the nose and tongue . light overall feel and great softness . soft and light and tasty ( again in a soda pop manner ) .

aroma is unusual and very pleasant : something akin to meadowland following a spring shower blended with a peatiness and cooked vine fruits .  medium amber with little head .  a big sturdy body on this one ... no doubt held up by some quality malts used , gives way to a sublime smooth and velvety mouthfeel that has a slight crispness in the end . about perfect in every sense .

huge deep malty scents , with lots of caramel and toffee and a nixe bit of earthiness , as well .  pours a pleasant amber/red with a huge head of foam , yet virtually no lace .  perfect ris mouthfeel .

this is one of the best smelling beers i have ever had .  a- vigorous pour yields a thin layer of tan head sitting atop an opaque beer . no lacing is apparent as what little head there was dissipated rather quickly . nice job shorts !  m - perfect . exactly how a dipa should be .

it smells wonderfully of coffee bean and dark chocolate . the taste is just a little bit dry at the finish for me , but very rich and complex roasted flavors going on here .  even with a center pour not much of a head , thin coating of cream white with no real staying power nor lacing .  solid body , creamy mouthfeel .

smells fucking amazing . this is the best-smelling beer i 've ever had . it smells like exotic , spiced , fresh-roasted coffee , like you 're standing in [ trendy east side coffee shop ] . really good , but not quite on the same transcendent level as the nose .  pours a deep amber from the bottle , off-white head that dissipates quickly leaving thin lacing .  mouthfeel : the mouthfeel is outstanding . it sparkles just enough to give the palate a good tickle , but not so much that it scrapes away all of its flavor .
almost smells like a tire .  pours an amber brownish tint that holds an inch thick white cap .  mouthfeel is very syrupy and very rich with a dense body .
aromas are awesome . i can smell this for a couple of feet away .  demon fish , 750 ml bottle .  so creamy and smooth it 's almost not a beer ...

excellent . t- sharp hop bitterness with a floral blanket overall . slightly sticky d- smooth , smells great and tasts great .  growler , half inch whit head that fades quickly to some foam around the top and a ring . color is a little boring , clear copper ish .  sour , some cherries , but most of all very tart and bone dry ; element of french cheese in it ( brie ) , some cream ; m : lovely alcohol , nice tartness , very drinkable ; o : not too complex but but very good kriek , which i will buy whenever i see it .
it 's a good inviting smell .  pours a murky brown with a thin ring , not the most attractive beer at this point .  mouthfeel is heavy and smooth with a nice small bite of carbonation , wonderful .

syrupy but not in an over the top fashion . s. phenomenal , tons of coffee , vanilla caramel and sweet chocolate , with a sense of dryness . there is a lot of complexity in the nose , i like it . t. sweet bourbon , oak dryness , all smells mentioned above , bitter coffee all the way through al little rough on the mix of flavors but still great . creamy and crunchy . i would categorize this along with bell 's expedition stout as being a bad boy of the style . its not a smooth and user friendly drink .  bottle poured into a snifter a- yellow with a white two finger head . looks like a light beer not a double ipa .  a great take on belgium ale ; apples , pears , lemons , apricot and orange flavors nustle their way thru a carbonated full bodied swig .

the aroma of it is amazing , almost a pumpkin cider type smell .  pours a very hazy , dark golden apricot/brown color with a half finger white head that quickly fades into a thin lasting ring . minimal spots of lacing left behind .  the texture is rich and creamy and coasts your mouth in deliciousness .

nose presents juicy flavors of dried mango and apricot with a bit of citrus and rosewater .  12oz bottle poured into a nb tulip glass . a : pours a dark black . no head .  perfect . d- a very unique pumpkin ale .

smells great ! you go the same whitepepper honey spice wheatishness of duvel only with a wonderfully crisp , weedy background . tastes very nearly as good as it smells . big nodes of weeds , pollen , and wild flowers backing up a spicy , crisp , lightly lemony belgian pale .  a - poured a dark copper with no visible carbonation , no head as it was poured all the way to the top , no lacing and no retention .  mouthfeel was great , it was very rich and smooth with little carbonation but it fit the stout just right .

aroma of roast , ash , chocolate , dried fruits , vanilla , bourbon , caramel malts , and alcohol . taste of dark fruit , some tropical , sticky molasses , roasted malts , vanilla , and bourbon - alcohol .  incredibly drinkable , leaves the drinker craving another ! typically , i prefer a beer that hits the total of the palette , but this beer is an excellent example of its style .  only lightly effervescent , making the mouthfeel of this beer fantastic . i could n't picture the mouthfeel of this beer being any better . the amazing mouthfeel coupled with the well developed and super tasty character of this beer make it an easy drinker .

s : extreme vanilla , boozy bourbon notes . otherwise this is solid . d : weighing in at 13 % abv , one gibcs could do you in ... yet , i think i could handle two ... and that 's saying a lot , especially after starting this session w/ one tripel karmeliet and one piraat ( both 33cl ) . an excellent extreme imperial stout .  12oz can - & gt ; nondescript pint a ~ steady pour reveals very red body with pretty good sized head . appearance is not the highlight of this brew though .  the mouthfeel is perfect for the style ; adequately carbonated and finished silky and creamy .

taste- delicious representation of the smell . strong hops up front , especially for a pale ale , then dry malt .  color is a deep garnet with amber highlights . gave me a thin cap of tan head and very little lacing .  mouthfeel is great . just the right level of thickness here .

citrus ( grapefruit ) - yes , strong and good , wow . apricot flavor notes .  i have no idea how fresh this bottle was . the best before date was very faint and hardly ledgible . light amber/gold , airy head disappated quickly but did leave decent lacing . top rating for drinkability comes from the fact that it was pretty darn good despite my doubts about the age .  very full in the mouth , coating , oily bitterness lingering and alcohol warmth continues to expand over my palate , throat , stomach as i enjoy this beer .

hops are juicy smelling . very complex and citrus-fruity aroma . t : mmmm ! d : this is a tasty beer on the verge of being terrific . a solid offering , i would have a few of these .  poured into a piraat tulip glass . has a 1cm golden head with but does n't linger with some mild lacing .  mouthfeel is medium bodied , very smooth and creamy . overall this is pretty damn good .

i can not pick much up in the smell , maybe i have a cold . maybe it smells a little grainy . similar to the other `` beers of america collection . '' well , the taste is kind of lacking much like the smell .  good initial head , but it dissipates to a single layer . the lace is spotty and light .  unbelievably smooth . feel is so outstanding for a heavy dark lager .

perfect . not as great as the nose but still excellent . m : prickly hops , of course , some mild warmth from the alcohol , and some light carbonation .  clear yellowish golden color with a surprisingly fluffy white head .  taste- for a double ipa , this beer is not on a mission to wreck the palate ... with so much flavor i 'm surprised that the malts weigh in so heavily . solid . it 's sudsy ( the name of my beloved late parakeet ) and sublime . drinkability- one real attribute about this bruiser of a beer is that the abv ( 10 % ) is completely hidden ... it 's nowhere in any of the above categories . this is more like a nectar , thick and juicy , garnering respect for each sip .

one of the best smelling beers i 've tried .  poured into a weizen style glass that creates very little head atop a golden-straw colored body .  the mouthfeel is great , nice and thick and perfectly carbonated .

aroma is amazing - brandy , caramel , brown sugar , dark fruits , vanilla , and oak . bummer i 'll probably never have it again , as rare as it is .  besides the color ( pale yellow with a tinge of orange ) , everything else is amazing .  mouthfeel is lucious : creamy and oily , rich in the mouth , but smooth enough to want more and more .

s : a lot of good stuff going on here . dark , rich , even sort of ... tropical .  22 oz bottle poured into a tulip glass a-pours a deep reddish brown with a half finger white head that dissipates nearly as quickly as it forms . a few scant bubbles and a ring around the glass is all that remains after a half minute .  the moutfeel is exceptional - full bodied and thick with appropriate carbonation .

s : holy hops , batman ! intense , complex , and amazing . t : starts off with citrus and herbal hops , then transitions to a bit of caramel malt before finishing with a wave of piney bitterness . delicious . m : medium bodied with a good dose of initially spiky , finally smooth carbonation .  the beer pours a translucent dark red color with no head at all .  the carbonation is fantastic -- beer feels creamy and smooth- almost velvety .

taste is a bit of a let down compared to the amazing aroma . a really good ipa .  gold color capped by a thin head . it does n't look as bright as i expected so i take a closer glance . i see a fine haze of tiny particles in the glass , though i only poured in half the bottle .  mouthfeel : a smooth sugary viscous mouthfeel that is balanced nicely by the carbonation .

s- very large coffee smell . great complexity . t- taste starts with sweet fruits and a little bit of chocolate then is balance excellently by fresh bitter coffee .  honey amber color , light thin head .  exceptional mouthfeel and drinkability .

the smell issue and alcohol after taste put it off my future list .  a - poured a hazy amber color with some cloudiness and sediment visible . head was decent , lacing was minimal .  m : a great , great medium body , that grazes you at the tail with sharp carbonation .

the smell did n't give much away other than chocolatey malt and hops , so when i took the first sip i was surprised and utterly pleased . notes of fruit , a little nutty with a slightly bitter spicy hop aftertaste .  appears a light gold with a dense 1 finger white head that lasts for a minute .  m-grand canyon deep and gordian knot complex . amazingly tantalizing on the palate . while it looks still in the glass it bursts with palate stimulating carbonation with each sip . like an amusement park in your mouth ! this is a highly enjoyable and palate stimulating sipper . a mighty fine drinking brew .

the nose here is at first reminiscent of a barleywine ( raisiny , sweet ) , then an imperial stout ( chocolatey , roasty ) , and ultimately an outstanding cabernet ( earthy and leathery notes on top of dark fruits and floral perfumes ) . i find this to be an ideal complexity - notable not for its blunt force but for the way it continues to surprise . cigar box certainly comes to mind . barleywine-type sweetness is much more prevalent in this dimension , although it interacts in interesting ways with a darker , roasted quality . the finish is warm in a pleasing way . outstanding beer for slow sipping and contemplation .  look : brown color with ruby shades , very thin foamy head ( maybe because of the glass ) .  like other fine belgian beers the carbonation produces a surreal creamy consistency that serves to deliver maximum taste .

s - incredible aromas in this beer . even if is a lambic , the smells are very fine and not off-flavours .  from the growler the beer pours a murky orangish brown color . the head was n't all that great , but that could be due to a dirty growler , glass or the fact that i 've had it in the growler for four days . because of the aforementioned ( i assume ) lacing is also lacking .  really coats the mouth for an excellent mouthfeel .

the aroma is awesome . right away it reminds me of kuhnhenn raspberry eisbock with huge notes of sweet raspberries and chocolate .  a - pretty darned black , minimal mocha head that ends fast , lacing thin and unimpressive .  mouthfeel is very delicious with some creamy notes but some nice crisps and sharp grassy hop notes .

the smell is sweet , spicy , almost vinous , and very complex . each time i think i have an aroma captured it changes into something else .  very little head and no lacing or retention .  the feeling in your mouth , however is gorgeous ! smooth , silky , incredible.. so incredibly good that i actually said 'incredible ' in a french accent because it deserved such smoothness ... i 'm not going to lie , as for drinkability.. i 'm not as into this as anchor 's or even sierra nevada 's , christmas offerings this year , but it is still very drinkable to this lass .

s : wonderful fruity belgian goodness . caramel malty dubbel is a smell warms me up even on a hot evening . allagash has some of the nicest smelling belgians that come to mind .  a - poured out a clear , dark burgundy color with a very small , thin head of off-white foam .  body is medium-full for style , and this is just about perfect on the way down .

very nice . the taste is quite good , mostly dominated by malts .  a : pours a deep brown with dark ruby highlights around the edges . about a half finger of foam fades quickly leaving almost nothing on top and no lacing . kinda looks like a coke or root beer .  mouthfeel is just perfect - thick , rich , and creamy , with a slightly oily sheen that coats the mouth and throat .

s- not much happening here . a little hoppy , a little sweet . pretty balanced , leans more toward hops . the hops used taste a little different from other apa 's and ipa 's i 've tasted . d- because of the clean and crisp hops , i could drink it all day . it 's not the best out there , but is pretty good and worth trying .  pours hazy copper with a creamy 1 finger tan head that faded about average time ; good lacing that clings to the glass and leaves rings .  very palatable and no alcohol taste at all m - silky smooth , great carbonation .

if you like hops , you 'll like this . it is overloaded with hops , but very very tasty .  sampled at the bbf a - pours a nice slightly hazy pale light gold almost orange with a very light head that fades quickly leaving minimal lacing .  it 's thick , creamy , rich , and robust .

very pleasant aroma . i may have picked up some caramel in the flavor as well as some sharp citrus aspects and some sweetness .  a : semi copper and clear . thin , tan head that dissipates quickly . two , despite the heavy graham and pumpkin , you never lose the fact that this is indeed a beer .  the mouthfeel is great on this one too , effervescent and full at the same time .

a good looking beer that smells perfect , but ca n't hold up in the taste realm .  a - poured a dark copper with a one finger khaki head and no visible carbonation . no retention and slight lacing .  mouth is rich and sticky yet wonderfully smooth .

wonderful citrus aroma of oranges and grapefruits . the nose is n't just there , it smacks you in the face - and this is a wonderful thing . if i could give higher than a five for aroma on this beer i would . taste - this beer is called hop dragon and consequently is all about hops . great bitter kick that almost goes unnoticed because of all the other great things about this beer .  who needs a lemon in a wheat beer when you can have some apricot instead ? on to the beer : yellow to orange in color that 's cloudy .  this brew is a tremendously creamy medium-body with a tantalizing , light bite about the tongue what can i say !

huge amounts of fruitiness , candy , and grapefruit on the nose . sweet , light , and apricots also show up a bit . reminds me of some type of orange/apricot candy i 've had before but can not put my finger on it . very light , very fruity , yet tart but it is quite a curious taste . very easy to drink and although i do n't see myself buying a lot of lindeman 's myself i will highly recommend this to anyone trying a geuze !  appearance- slightly hazy , bright orange color with 1.5 finger eggshell white , foamy head . head settles rather quickly but leaves some residual lacing .  m - perfect for a porter .

awesomely hoppy nose of ripe citrus and waxy tropical notes with a good dose of pine too- mango , ruby red grapefruit , papaya , peach , grassy lemon mint . very pungent . overall , very juicy and delicious , with my one complaint being that the beer finishes a little short .  small amount of head but it dissipated almost completely .  mouthfeel is super creamy and silky smooth .

many `` damn '' s and `` holy s*** '' s could be heard as we sniffed the mercifully small portions in our tasting glasses . tons of whiskey , vanilla , burnt caramel , butterscotch . taste features big woody vanilla along with chocolate , caramel , coffee , and big booze ( how could it not ) . lot of whiskey . some sweetness , but really nowhere near as sweet as i thought it might be . feel is thick and syrupy , but look at what you 're drinking - this is one of those beers you could probably pour over your pancakes .  i do n't actually know what it looked like because i had it poured in a cinema that was very dark . no head , though , i know that .  ( not a huge coffee stout fan ) ( blasphemous i know ) the greatest thing about this beer is the smooth creamy texture that is present while drinking .

it has a saccharin-sweet juicy bubblegum aroma , blended with kiwis and mangos .  i 'd never seen any in my neck of the woods , but a close friend brought me a bottle back from oakland , on the basis of me being a huge zappa fan and beer nut . the only thing that put me off a little was the huge amount of yeast floaties that came with it , although they did nothing to detract from it 's flavor .  while there was no head , the carbonation is just right ; the body is no thinner or heavier than it should be .

smells amazing . chocolate and some buttery , boozy notes emerge with warming .  pours a hazy golden color with a one fingered head that quickly fades to a barely noticeable cap .  perfect . d- a remarkably smooth beer , although a bit mild .

the head falls to an island of loose bubbles , a ring , and dusting that leaves spots of lacing.. mind blowing aroma . orange , mango , papaya , grapefruit , pineapple ... candied hops ! sweet and floral , it tickles my nose and begs to be tasted . i taste tropical fruits , with lots of green and white pepper , it is earthy and reminds me of kind-buds .  amber brown , perfectly clear , with a single finger of soapy white pilsner-like head that settles to a ring quickly .  m- the mouthfeel is full bodied with a perfect amount of carbonation .

havs a very mild aroma and only nice a mild hint of spices .  the beer poured black , with a tan head that had low retention and lacing .  mouthfeel is exceptional ! this beer is smooth , silky , creamy .

s : grapefruit and evergreen needles . you can smell the aroma of bold hops from yards away . t : simcoe , welcome aboard .  a ) 1/4 a head . quickly disappeared . looks like medium carbonation .  mouthfeel was creamy and exceptional . i was surprised to be able to drink the whole thing since i am not a fan of coffee at all , but this was a pleasant change of pace for me .

smell was out of this world . very fresh hop smell , got me all excited about the fist sip , but ... taste was very underwhelming .  it comes with about a fingers worth of off white head . little to no retention , no lacing left on the glass .  the mouthfeel of this beer might be its most remarkable consistency ; velvety , silken slickness .

the color was reddish-amber and the smell was fantastic ! floral , sweet hops - strong and complex . the taste is hops up front and hops on the end - not as complex as the smell .  a - raspberry/brown color , not head nor lace .  m- creamy and full-bodied . what else would you expect from the style ?

no aroma to speak of , which is unfortunate , because it would complement the interesting flavors . somewhat malty , but this is obscured by the many flavors rolling around - sweet pear and apple , a bit of butterscotch , with gentle hops riding beneath .  poured into a snifter on 7/5/10 many thanks to pdxhops dark brown in color , settling black in the glass . in fact all foam disappears save a ring . no lace .  mouthfeel is full bodied and smooth that feels pretty creamy on the tongue .
seems very complex , i love it . t : disappointed from the smell .  absolutely no head on the pour .  m - perfect carbonation . awesome smoothness . dry .

plenty of citrus fruits and pine , along with some other fruitiness ( maybe strawberry and mango ) make this an alluring smelling gem . the tastebuds are greeted with the expected large dose of hop bitterness , but balanced nicely by a little bit of sweet malts .  a - pours with a thin fizzy white head that dissipates quickly .  mouthfeel is astonishingly smooth and creamy for such a rich , complex ale .

complex , unique , and very intriguing . lots of vanilla , caramel , and pumpkin with cinnamon , nutmeg , and allspice . big and flavorful , intriguing , and easy to drink in a non-session beer kind of way .  poured from 750ml cork and caged bottle into a long stem tulip glass around 40~45 f. nose : dark fruit , plums , maple syrup , clove and other spices . appearance : dark red/brown with small but persistent ring of bubbles .  the mouthfeel is oh so smooth and creamy , just perfect !

just flat out wonderful , this is just an exceptional nose here . the nose on this is just flat out fantastic .  bottled 08 04 2008 a- nice amber bronze with decent but short lived head that laces .  m : the mouthfeel is what really sold me on this beer .

s- smell is of corn and metal .  appearance : light golden brown , slightly cloudy with decent head retention on the white head aroma : definate piney notes , with some sharp citrusy grapefruit in the aroma .  t- pretty solid all around . very smooth , robust , and thick .

pours with a fat thumb head , with decent stout lacing ... smell is amazing , lots of sweet bourbon and chocolate plum ... lots of bourbon upfront but it really is remarkable how enjoyable it is , despite the fact that its like sipping straight bourbon ... this beer would age soooo beautifully ! a wonderful beer that i was honored to have tried at a really fun event , but that open bar kicked my butt in the end ! !  visual : pale straw , gold in color . no head .  the mouthfeel is outstanding , substantial and even sticky .

anyhow , it 's yet another rare euro pale that is apparently only sold in russia and iowa . smells light and weedy . nothing much going on here , though absolutely nothing is off .  the body pours quite a pale yellow , with a moderate haze and thinnish bone-white head .  mouthfeel : perfection . the bead is neither too large nor too small .

s : a really interesting mix , i get a strong strawberry aroma mixed with a heavy caramel smell . there is also a nice hop/citrus aroma in the middle , some tangerine maybe . overall a really nice beer , very drinkable .  looking forward to this evem after the disappointing eipa and apa a- very hazy , milky even , brown . white head looks like warm milk froth . lots of stuff floating about .  mouthfeel is a heavy but perfect . heavy with lots of lactose , light but fizzi carbonation .

s : smell on this beer is amazing . i gave this beer a 5 . the beer smells like a cream stuffed pumpkin . d : drinkable for the style but still 1 bomb is good for me .  pours a burgandy color with no head or lace .  this beer 's greatest attrubite is , in fact , its spectacualrly creamy mouthfeel .

a floral citrus smell hits you hard with a smell of some sweetness to it that seems to be hiding in this hoppy beer . mouthfeel- a good amount of carbonation to it between medium to heavy in its feel , about average in my opionion drinkability-is n't the best but with conditioning you can become very use to it and then it becomes very appealing . just brilliant .  pours a deep red/brown with no head at all .  the mouthfeel is , in a word , glorious . smooth on the tip of the tongue , then seeming to evaporate off your tongue leaving a crisp , somewhat spicy finish .

smell is amazing ! you can pick out both beers , which is the goal of black and tans . prism hits the nail on the head , because in the beer , you can pick out the lemony hops of the pale ale and it goes very well with the licorice aroma of the porter . carbonation is right on , not too much , and at a very natural level . it brings something else to the table , and yet it works for the style .  beer arrived with almost no head at all . color was very dark , almost appearing black at first .  so very soft on the palette - really a unique mouthfeel , just velvety smooth .

overall , this is a complex smelling beer and wonderfully balanced . t : disappointingly not as good as the smell .  lacing is okay , head is minimal , not much retention..leaves barely anything on top aroma : sweet and fruity , hops ( citrus ) taste : malts come in well and finish off with a citrus hop finish .  it is very creamy and very smooth . it 's like chocolate silk . very delicious .

quite delicious , but not quite as good as the nose led me to believe . m. thin with a good level of carbonation d. i was a bit disappointed with the taste after the incredible smell , but the mouthfeel is really what let me down here .  appearance : really cloudy , reminds me of a wit . pours yellow with an orange tint .  what i really loved was the mouthfeel . very good for a lager style beer .
smell is sweet with a strong alcohol odor amd some hints of wood .  the color is a pale straw yellow with a nice white head .  the mouthfeel is fucking perfect : it 's thick and creamy .

aroma is way way hoppy . pretty good , almost a back sweetness to it . pretty piny in the aroma .  growler from firehouse saloon in rochester ny a- a pretty standard deep brown/black with a 1/4 '' head of soapy mocha bubbles .  my favorite thing about this obviously the sweet rich malt character which adds to a very nice body for a beer of this alcohol content .

below average head retention , but the aroma more than makes up for a lackluster appearance as it brims with bold espresso and sweet chocolate notes . one of the best-smelling coffee beers i 've had recently , and the malt backbone is nothing to scoff at , either . overall , brewhouse coffee stout is amazingly aromatic , but could use a few tweaks here and there with regards to the appearance and mouthfeel .  love the bottle , too bad the price is so high . a : pours a dark ruby/brown color with a small off-white head forms , comprised of rather large bubbles , and dissipates rather quickly . very thin lacing forms , but does not last .  the mouthfeel on this beer is great , so creamy with just enough bubbles that make it not to syrupy .

) aromas are in the background and define it with a rugged , backcountry character .  pours mahogany with 3+ fingers of mocha head . average lacing & head retention s : roasty malt & chocolate , plus a slight iron scent t : chocolate , roasty malt , & some dryness up front .  full effervescent body , huge amounts of carbonation . an unusual beer that 's quite good .

very very nice . very complex .  a - opaque black ( as a black cauldron ) . a thin khaki ring of head remains for a few minutes , then is gone forever .  mouthfeel : has a great mouthfeel . it has exceptional smoothness .

smell is on the sweet side but hoppy as well , sweet bubblegum scent , weed , juicy citrus and a malt punch , great scent . taste is enjoyable , alot of different things balancing sweet and hoppy in that order with the above mentioned scents going into the taste without the weed .  pours an effervescent crimson/caramel with 2+ fingers of sand colored head . average lacing & head retention s : cherry juice by the ton , some tartness & woody notes t : cherry juice with some booze warmth & not much else up front , maybe a touch of tartness .  this was the first belgian i ever had . it has a very creamy smoothness that i really love . finishes long and dry with more fruityness .

smells like halloween ! very welcoming . it sure is an imperial . very crisp , sexy beer . spices are rounded , clove , cinnamon , vanilla bean , and most importantly , fresh pumpkin .  orange in color and cloudy . a pretty color to be sure but otherwise not outstanding . lots of sediment in the bottle , so pour carefully .  the feeling is very nice , sticky and big , but not viscous and syrupy . really nice in that aspect . the carbonation was lively and enjoyable , made this one easy to drink .

smelled pretty nice too , with some malt and floral kick to it .  this pours out as a red-hued amber color with good carbonation that creates a scattered , bubbly head that dissipated pretty fast .  the mouthfeel is full and warming , in fact , this beer is a huge belly warmer .

brewery states they did pick up some brett recently , popped the cork off ... corked talked about brett to me , more fruit than funk . hops stay modest . mild tartness , infancy of the brett ? it does have a ghost-like funk within . sweet roasted finish , pretty much burnt sugar . not a hair short of being great , the brewery admits to some funk ... wish i had another bottle to see where it goes .  there was absolutely no head or carbonation and even a vigorous pour resulted only in some air bubbles on top .  m - medium body and low carbonation , so incredibly smooth . perfect mouthfeel .

smell : strong citrus aroma boasting orange , pineapple and sappy resin . they really knocked it out of the park in the smell , what an inviting and pleasing scent . has west coast written all over it . overall : a pretty impressive brew from cisco brewers .  served on a tulip glass . a - hazy straw to pale gold pour , unremarkable head , short retention , fair surface ring and some lacing .  super creamy mouthfeel , medium body and carbonation level .

a truly profound smell . has all the plums and figs of a dickens novel .  i have experienced a bad batch of this brew , which was cloudy , and `` off '' in flavor . not quite translucent , which is not a negative , imho . nice white head .  wonderfully smooth mouthfeel , but not much of anything else that would make this beer standout .

the aroma was , well , heavenly . deep dark fruitiness leads the way with raisins and plums . a deep inhale yeilds only wisps of alcohol that contribute complexity . the flavor was just a step behind the aroma with dark fruits again in full force followed by caramel maltiness .  part of a taster flight , about a 5oz pour to a funkwerks tulip . pours a nice medium yellow with only a hint of haze , small white head that dissipates fairly quickly and no lacing .  but what might be the true feats here are , on the one hand , the quality and sock of the flavors given the abv , and the insanely creamy mouthfeel on the other .

a very easy drinking doppelbock , with terrific aromas , and a surprisingly `` light '' flavor and mouthfeel .  a refreshing light-bodied ale that goes down easy a- very clear amber-yellow with thin , big-bubbled head s- smells a bit like honey along with a bottle/metal hint .  t : the taste was about average for a stout , almost identical in flavor to guinness m : amazing mouthfeel , so creamy and so smooth .

smell is very mild , some malts , not much going on here . taste is very good , malts , nutty , chocolate , very flavorfull .  pours a one finger yellow-tan head over a cloudy light-gold liquid . this beer is quite drinkable , the glass is already half gone already . really nice lacing on the inside of the glass . i had a glass of this on tap at the brewery and it was very much like this from a bottle .  mouthfeel : amazing . creamy and smooth , thick .

i absolutely loved the smell of this , chocolatey , with some sweet fruits from the yeast and subtle hop profile .  i 've had plenty of these in my day , but this is the first i 've actually sat down with to review ... a - pours a slightly cloudy , orangish copper color , a little darker than alot of ipas . head grows to about 1 inch before settling down to a thin outer layer .  m : wow ! just so damn smooth .

the smell of this 2 year old beer is so rich and strong . it smells of sweet fruits and a little bit of alcohol .  a- poured a amberish coppery orange color if that makes sense . one finger off white head that shows light retention .  rich roasty chocalaty with a fabulous creamy mouthfeel . mouth again is just amazing . another great brew by troegs .

the aroma is like a fresh hop cone very nice . from what you expect with the aroma is a slight let down but that said it is nice . the taste malty to start the taste turns to a earthy hop flavor .  pours a clear orange with a two fingers worth of fluffy head that subsided quickly . a good bit of lacing down the glass . this is a highly drinkable beer that masks the alcohol well .  bitter black chocolate moves into the woodiness and finishes boozy m- creamy , full-bodied , coats the mouth and boozy heat d- really impressed with this one .

exceptional smell of toffee , caramel , nutty . wanted to eat something that smelled like this . slightly bitter note on the nose . sweet with a more bitter nutty taste .  the body of the liquid was hazy , but i would hesitate to call it cloudy . as the head subsided , it left a very sticky lacing on the edges of the glass that looked like bar soap froth on a wash cloth . average for the style , but nice never-the-less .  mouthfeel is exceptional . very smooth , great carbonation , but not enough to distract from the flavors going on .

aromas are full of the whiskey barrel , but really well balanced with a ton of tree fruit - especially apricots and apples . flavors are a rich mix of fruits , thick bread/yeast , honey - lots of honey , just a kiss of hops , vanilla icing , maybe some fruitcake ... just a lot going on here . and fairly sweet , but delicious . as it warms , it converts to creme brulee and banana pudding - but never loses the whiskey barrel .  a : it pours a bright orange color with a finger of white head that does n't last and does n't lace very well either .  the mouthfeel , though , was the best part . it fills your mouth with mousse like consistency with very round edges .

there was almost no smell initially after some warming i started to notice some malty essences , some molasses . pretty light taste wise .  poured pretty dark for an ipa , kind of an ice tea brown , but there are some other darker ipas out there where that fact is considered part of their novelty . 1 '' head gradually dissipated to lace .  complexity is not disturbed by the great thick airy body . thick enough that the high carbonation appears just smooth and creamy . it feels like theyve brewed it with oatmeal .

heavy caramels , bourbon , dark fruits , a fruity sweetness and a touch of tobacco.. this is really a fantastic smelling barleywine . i 'd dare to say it is one of the best smelling barleywines that i 've had to date . kudos to a great bouquet . plenty of caramel malt to provide a creamy mouthfeel , king henry takes off with sweetness but not cloyingly so .  6 % abv 45 ibu a : straw-red in color with a good amount of haze . there is a decent off-white head that floats atop this brew .  great mouthfeel and is smooth on the palate with a hoppy bitterness that lasts forever .
really loved the nose .  12 oz bottle , bottled 06/18/08 a : deep black under a small tan head . no lace , no retention .  wonderful full mouthfeel .

aroma is very inviting with apple , pear , and an awesome yeastiness . the taste is n't as fruity and glorious as the incredible aroma but it is nice and earthy . there is a great toastiness to it and great caramel , bread and diacetyl butter flavor .  ) poured into a pint glass a : pours golden pale orange with less than a finger of thin white head . not great retention .  the feel is awesome . maybe it is the milk sugar , but something gives it an icy , silky feel that is wonderful . overall good , a beer that i would have one of on occasion .

it had a very beautiful aroma of dried fruit and alcohol . almost wine like to the nose , and was enjoyed by everyone i offered it to .  pours a pale , clear , gold/yellow with almost zero head .  it seemed to just coat my whole mouth on its way down .

i noticed a nice hop bouquet on the nose which suggests it was dry-hopped . maybe it was n't , perhaps just really fresh as the beer had a born on date suggesting the beer was less than two weeks old .  a slight head forms which is bone white , but quickly fades to nothing .  has that totally coating feel like a warm thick cask draught , just almost oily in its feel and velvety ( aside from the alcohol ) . really like this about this beer .

longneck into a cascazilla pint glass purchased at the brewery : ( a very cool glass with some red hops on it ) a - copper/red hue with about a 1/2 inch head that quickly died down to an outer ring and no lacing - maybe it was the glass ' fault s - straight up pine and citrus from the hops , also some malt sweetness in there t - a burst of hops to start with . taste like west coast hops , and not too bitter , probably lots of late mid/late hop additions and dry-hopping , as there is a great hop flavor and aroma to this beer without too much bitterness . good supporting role by the malt to keep the hops in check . awesome job combining the characteristics of a red ale and an ipa .  this bottle pours a hazy amber with little head . carbonation is a bit low , and it 's not the prettiest beer in the world .  m : incredibly creamy leaving a nice coating around the mouth that tingles slightly .

probably the sweetest ipa i 've run across . aroma of candy and berries . nicely hopped with clear strawberry and other berry notes .  a - poured out a somewhat cloudy , copper color with a small , tan head that left no lace .  very full and creamy mouth . damn tasty .

smell : super strong pine , grapefruit , and bitterness warns the tastebuds through the nose what is to come . taste : hearty caramel sweetness with a very strong and biting bitterenss .  appearance : burgundy amber orange body , clear as a sunrise with a sad , fizzy beige head that hardly lasts long enough even to describe it .  mouthfeel is truly wonderful , with a heavy , syrupy feel mixed in with a light tingle from some hidden carbonation and the alcohol itself .

s- smell is awesome . tons of tropical fruits pineapple , apricot , and grapefruit a bit of sweetness coming through from the malts . t- follows the nose really well . a very nice hop forward beer .  somewhat cloudy yellow-orange with a small white head .  very smooth and full bodied mouthfeel , with medium carbonation .

outstanding imo . a : normal , yellowish/orange .  received one fat finger of head that quickly faded . brownish copper colored body was clear .  the mouthfeel as mentioned earlier , is very thick and creamy . very little carbonation .

amazingly complex aroma of hand-made chocolates . very mild and easy drinking . definately nothing double powered on the flavor . surprisingly clean . very light body . very drinkable .  2009 375ml bottle a : pours a murky chestnut brown with amber highlights near the edges . bottle gave a muted `` pop '' but not going on with the bubblies ; does n't offer more than a ring and a few swirls of carmel-colored head .  first gulp of this was outstanding.. nice creamy , mouthfeel to it that just bombards your mouth with sweet , delicious beer flavor .

big hop aroma -- a bit sugary , citric and piney . lots and lots going on just in the scent , and i can feel the back of my tongue tingling already .  currant jam . appearance : very hazy orange-copper . minimal head with some lacing .  the mouthfeel was exquisite . tiny bubbles caress , going a little foamy , opening the flavor as it hits the back of your mouth .

refreshing , quite complex , and just the right temperate on the citrus .  dense two finger head shows good retention but weak lacing .  mouthfeel- the texture of this beer in the mouth is stunning and absolutely *perfect* .

the smell is amazing , strong coffee aroma , more so than any other coffee stout i 've had , easily the best aspect of this stout . the taste is a bit more reserved with the coffee as it 's hard to beat the strong aroma , but there is a good deal of coffee and roasted malt , hint of chocolate , and a decent bitterness in the end .  a - the low , poorly retained off-white head is disappointing as is the hazy golden yellow color .  m : nice light body on it with mild carbonation , which was perfect for this style of ale .

the aroma is fantastic , sweet , sour , chocolate malt all blending to a wonderful bouquet . taste is a bit too spicy , but otherwise very pleasantly complex . mouthfeel is dry and acrid , not as smooth as some others .  pours clear golden with a thin white head . the appearance is not much to write about .  this is one of the thickest beers i 've had . very heavy and smooth mouthfeel .

you can smell the fresh raspberry puree aroma from almost 2 feet away ! the first sip hits you with an insane burst , it tastes like you just bit into a big overly ripe juicy berry . i really enjoyed this but personally could not do more than say 2 or so glasses at a sitting , since there is so much flavor , so it would not be a good session beer , but it really is very great tasting !  this beer tastes like bacon if bacon = good and beer = good and this beer = bacon then for you , the beer = good if you do n't like bacon , do not get this beer .  mouth is very crisp and finishes clean , excellent carbonation . leaves a nice tingling on the tongue . drink is very good i usually would n't want an ipa for a session beer but this one i definetly would have a few more for the evening .

smell is very in your face . yeast hits you first , with hints of bananas which are definitely prevalent . really nice beer , one that i would love to have again .  cloudy , obviously , but golden amber color with a modest white head that left a ring pretty quickly .  excellent balance and mouthfeel , could be a great session beer .

a : almost totally opaque , thin tan head that generates late and dissipates quickly , not much lacing s : smells like a campfire is the best way to put it , some light hops and malt , but mostly that charcoal mesquite , wow t : again , the campfire , but a little more subdued , some chocolate notes in the middle , with a hop bitterness in the back that mixes with the rough , almost metallic charcoal character m : pretty thick , coats the entire mouth and stays with you for a while d : a true sipper , amazing for the style , but it 's so intense , i had a little trouble finishing the bottle , one would be enough for me for quite a while  it really reminds me of swamp water with little head to speak of .  exactly how i like my stouts to feel -- heavy and chewy .

s- totally amazing smell . just like pumkin pie .  either way this is a solid , if not spectacular , example of the style . slightly hazy and mild amber in color you can almost see the hops coming .  the mouthfeel is dry with a long and deep finish which is full of blackened malt and char . very very nice .

amazing smell -- coffee and chocolate dominate the aromas with some caramel in the background .  pretty much the definitiion for an amber ale . poured at about the right temperature for a small to medium , light tan head that soon settled out .  ideal texture for an ipa .

5.0 s : lots of oatmeal is apparent . this may be the most oatmeal laden beer i 've had . awesome balance between sweet and roasted flavors . 4.0 t : the taste is just about as good as the nose , but the mouthfeel is too distracting for me to enjoy it .  bottleshare from darthkostrizer with bhobs and alucard4 pours a hazy reddish brown with a very quick dissipating bubbly head .  the way this tastes is absolutely nothing like the way it smells ... m - full , pleasing mouthfeel . the best part of this beer .

aromas are fantastic ( pure wild ale ) . plenty of interesting aroma & flavor , and smooth going down .  bottle part of mixed 12-pack . has pale yellow color .  the mouthfeel is silky smooth and really rounds the beer out nicely .

very nice . the taste is very unique .  a straw-colored pilsner that pours with an initial frothiness that falls quickly leaving a little bit of lace .  they served it properly too - the temperature was perfect ( not co cold ) . pretty close to perfect .

smell is rather striking and unique . slight hints of spice most likely from the chilles , with a really sweet grainy hop note .  i got just a little head in my chalice , and what i got did n't stay long .  the palate is delightfully smooth and creamy . overall , this is an outstanding dipa that is sure to fill anyones hop fix for the evening .

my favorite part of the beer was the aroma . it had this very intense chocolaty smell that while sipping was very pleasing to the senses .  i heard such great things about this beer that i figured i should enjoy my first from the can . smooth ; very good for the summer . best canned beer i have ever had ( the rumors were true ) . recommended if you want a stronger pale ale for a backyard cook out , or a few beers doing house work .  perfect creamy mouthfeel .

awesome . the taste is again huge with cherry flavor without sweetness , cherry pits , a decent amount of sourness , with a good lactic tartness on the finish .  pretty much no lacing .  light carbonation , rich smooth mouthcoating sensation from the oatmeal .

smells great . big , overripe tropical fruit and citrus with a little bit of grass underneath . i actually coughed and spilled some while pouring and thought , `` man , that smells awesome ! '' while cleaning it up . still good , just a letdown after the nose .  pours a very cloudy yellow with a very small white head that disapears to a thin white line immediatly .  mouthfeel was awesome . farily prickly carbonation with some slight drying on the finish due to the barrel aging .
the smell is mild , clean and neutral . or , to be frank , very boring .  a - a quick-dissolving tan foam settles to ... nothing . lightly hazed dark ruby-brown body .  awesome mouthfeel .

the smell was so pungent i could smell it a foot and a half away , which was great . this beer was a great pleasure both to see and smell . taste : immediate bitterness that is the mainstay throughout the beer . perhaps , the appearance and smell had me too excited , but i was somehat dissappointed in the taste .  pours with a black body topped by a thick , fizzy , quickly disappearing brown head with little lacing .  great mouthfeel .

lovely aroma of figs , coffee , licorice , lavender , pinesap , chocolate & mint . the dark roasted malts smell so very fresh , almost as if they were right there damp in the palm of your hands .  dark brown but not black like i was expecting . decent one finger head that leaves quickly smells of rich chinook hops and a sugary malt sweetness .  m : one of the fullest and creamiest dipas i 've ever had .

i smell orange , tangerine , kind buds , papaya , pine , and hints of rock candy . the aroma is lovely ! it smells like someone is peeling an orange next to me . good , but not as amazing as the nose .  copper-orange pour with a small off-white head .  m-medium carbonation with a great creamy finish d-hmm i actually like this a lot ... .i 'm very confused by the other peoples ' reviews ... the taste is n't too complex but its otherwise a great drink .

this had a wonderful nose of tropical fruits , sugars , and malts , with a little herbal hop bitterness thrown into the mix as well . the taste was more of the same , fruity , sweet and delicious . this did have a medicinal , somewhat metallic , after taste though that kind of reminded me of orval .  poured from the bottle into a pint glass a - pours a dark copper with virtually no head . perhaps that explains the lackluster head ...  mouthfeel is superb . great level of spice , perfect carbonation , medium body .

very enticing . taste has quite a bit of belgian yeast and spice .  this is actually a very drinkable beer . it 's called a pale ale but it 's much drier with a lot less malt feel . the beer is a great , low-alcohol , hot weather alternative to a good lager or pilsner . the character is somewhere between a kolsch and an extra pale ale or even a bitter .  a nice chewy , creamy malt backbone makes each sip a pleasure .

huge hop aroma , a nice scottish style malt presnece behind the agresive hop bitterenes .  darkish amber in colour with a persistent head , albeit it quite thin in texture .  unbelievably smooth in mouthfeel - bittersweet chocolate and bitter roasted notes played effortlessly on your tongue .

aroma is hugely redolent of skunky , sticky bud if you ask me . hugely hoppy , very fresh , quite similar to rubbing a fresh hop cone in your hands and sniffing . not unenjoyable , but very bitter , so much that i did n't really notice much else .  it looks like a black colored ale . it doesnt look amazing who cares , inviting enough .  first sip reveals a smooth silky textured beer with a fairly thick body and gentle rolling carbonation . there is a sticky sweet residue on my lips after each sip and the boozy warmth lingers as well . the booze factor makes this a sipper and it is a little sweet and boozy to drink a full bomber .

smell was delicious . nutmeg , cinnamon , holiday cheer ... everything a holiday ale should smell like . overall this beer was good . i would definitely try the 2012 redition .  it poured opaque black , nearly zero foam .  great mouthfeel .

smell is beautifully complex & bright , like i just walked into an herb garden : really picking up on the rosemary , floral notes that are big but gentle , something kind of savory like oregano , maybe some basil or mint notes in there . seriously , this is fantastic , i do n't think i 've ever smelled a beer like it .  my pour created a finger of tawny head with decent retention . color was a slightly hazy orangish-amber .  mouthfeel was full and rich . this is a very good beer , and quite a unique one .

aromas are just awesome ... deep rich fruits , candy sugar , plenty of oak barrel , dark bread-like yeast character , and some orange peel in the back . maple and molasses in the sweetness , with just a touch of citrus rhind hops in the finish . not overly chewy , which was nice for this strength of beer .  served in a flute . transparent amber-brown body with visible bubbles streams . no cap , lace , etc .  the mouthfeel is perfect . it is full bodied with low carbonation , and oh so smooth .

the smell is that of boston lager , rather skunky with hints of hops and malts .  the color is very very dark brown , and a bit murky .  m : thin to medium viscosity , simultaneously wet and creamy on the palate developing into a sublime smoothness , with moderate carbonation that keeps the texture from becoming heavy or lifeless .

the smell is exceptional . tons of different scents .  slight film persists , but no real head retention or lacing s : sour & oaky notes t : sweet cherry , then sourness , oaky dryness & small hint of vanilla up front .  mouthfeel is damn near perfect for an o'fest , i think . impeccable balance .

s : sour cherries are noticeable before the glass reaches my nose . t : the aroma carries well into the taste as the sour dark cherry hits the palate first and then gives way to the sweetness which tastes more like a jolly rancher than sweet tart .  pours a straw yellow from a 12oz bottle to a standard pint glass . dissipating to a half finger head with good lacing .  some of the best damn mouthfeel you will ever get in a beer too .

smells like apples , tastes like hops . very tasty . the fragrance certainly did not match the taste , which is a good thing .  i was dissapointed with the appearance . when poured it did'nt reveal any type of head or lacing .  the mouthfeel is velvety and thick .

the aroma is that of a rich red wine , high in fresh fruit and tart cherry . complex undertones reveal the earthiness of damp autumn woodland , as it warms . the alcohol is greater than anticipated , and interesting , given that it is labeled as 4 % . a ton of character , oud beersel is my opinion of a stunning example of what this style can achieve . unpretentious and impeccably crafted , this is a gastronomical work of art .  appearance : very effervescent . poured a absolutely clear golden yellow , very small off white head .  feel : low carbonation , medium body that is extremely smooth for so low abv , very nice drying finish .
when i pulled the cork out , a delightful smell hit me right away , but went away quickly .  great retention and poor lacing .  excellent in the mouth .

s : bold and healthy hop aroma . perfect ipa smell . t : dry and hoppy .  pale gold and crystal clear . modest white head ( about one finger ) that becomes a thin film and then a ring . lacing is minor perhaps due to glass washed in the dishwasher . a perfect easy drinking summer pils .  body is n't the first thing you notice , but once the distraction of the sour wears off , you realize this brew is very smooth , neither tacky nor sticky , nor drying . carbonation can be swirled up , and compliments the feel of the sour in your cheeks quite well . all in all , a crazy departure from the normal dfh offerings and dang fine weissen .

s : light and hoppy , but i think maybe my glass smells a bit wierd .  on tap @ the brewery 03-26-09 pours a light hazy yellow , my friend ordered hefeweizen and i actually thought it was the dipa based on appearance .  deliciously smooth . coating the entire mouth with a lasting finish .

excellent ! overall : amazing aroma , very complex and inviting , but i think it set me up for a super complex flavor profile that was n't there .  tomos watkin osb pours a deep amber with just barely off-white two-finger foamy head .  m= smooth and crisp . feels resinous as well which is great for an ipa . d= super drinkable .

probably the best aroma of any ale i 've tasted all year . amazing ester profile .  there is very little head on this beer ; the head leaves rather quickly .  the finish lingers for a while , almost spicy with a slight alcohol burn m - pretty ideal for this style i thought .

really smells nice . the taste mimicks the nose ... .nice balance between the cloves and banana notes ... also some subtle but enjoyable caramel maltiness .  pours a reddish amber with a quickly fleeting rocky off white head .  mouthfeel is smooth and creamy , with a lighter body , almost cask like .

smell is absolutely fantastic ! huge , un-mistakable aroma of honey .  nice head and golden beercolor with big particles in the beer . nose is strange for a white ; bretty , hoppy and sourness giving this brew a unfamiliar witbier nose .  m- full bodied and creamy . very smooth and silky in the mouth . full bodied but not heavy .

smell & gt ; sweet and resiny . a perfect balance of the two scents without much alcohol heat .  poured into a tulip glass . dark opaque effervescing with a slight reddish hue .  mouthfeel is amazing on this one .

when i first opened the bottle i could smell the cherrys right away . it was a very sweet smell which suprised me that the beer was not as sweet as the smell . very nice appearance .  to say the least , this is a monster beer , a complete monster . loaded with vanilla , chocolate , figs , prunes..etc . a dark , opaque beer , with little head ( only drawback ) .  mouthfeel is medium bodied and smooth . an excellent feel .

s - great smell . dark fruits such as raisins and plums maybe . o - good over all .  poured slightly chilled in flared glass a : no head , decent beads , clear mead color s : honey , persistent smell of honeysuckle t : light ale , very floral , very complex ; lots of honey , lavender ; it 's like drinking a fancy handsoap ( meant to be a compliment ) ; buttery undertone ; ok , let 's call it soapy , but i think this flavor profile calls for that .  silky , creamy , and perfectly textured , this mouthfeel ca n't be beat .

anyways always seem to go with styles not fitting to the season and well we are in the mist of june and i 'm loving me some barley wines at the moment ! smell , well imagine a bowl of uncooked fruit cake batter . rum , raisins , dark fruits and figs , dates sweet molasses and soft belgium brown sugar . taste ; velvety fruit cake batter , more of the same from the nose . this beer is deliciously smooth and creamy . such a dessert evening sipper for sure . although they are great beers it just seems to me they dont fit in well with the style of barley wines . the hour passed and it might of been the alcohol but i could of had another 12 oz .  it poured clear until i hit the yeast at the bottom of the bottle - thus , a hazy auburn body topped by a very thin off-white head that drops almost immediately .  mouthfeel is incredibly smooth and creamy - almost reminded me of a nearly flat ginger ale , with more depth/body .

i prefered the tap version as the apricots were so intense in the aroma as the bottle had more funk and barnyard . apricot , lemon and peach flavors . moderate acidity for a cantillon . the palate could be drier and the carbonation more lively but this a stellar offering by cantillon once again .  there was very little head to speak of even with a vigorous pour .  m - smooth as silk .

m : moderate to heavy mouthfeel d : smells was awesome , taste was too much for me .  i would prefer the appearance to be a little more hazy & gt ; & gt ; & gt ; but this stuff comes from germany so i guess these guys know good beer & gt ; & gt ; & gt ; the smell is reminiscent of banana i do n't get too much clove to it & gt ; & gt ; i also ge an earthy smell too & gt ; & gt ; & gt ; it tastes just like it smells & gt ; & gt ; & gt ; very easy to drink & gt ; & gt ; & gt ; watery mouthfeel not my favorite beer style but excellently true to style !  body is full but not heavy and has a great creamy smoothness . almost feels like an oatmeal stout .

aroma is powerfully sour and very champagney . this is a very good beer , and quite a unique one .  there was no lace .  this is so creamy and not too carbonated , its just enough to get both senses of substantial and refreshing . quite thick , not so much as syrup but a few steps under . one please , fills the stomach nicely , not too harsh on the throat or stomach . it has a nice balance between warmth and coolness in the stomach .

the nose is deep , thick , prodigious coffee and some raisiny dark chocolate notes , and roasted dark sweet grains .  appearance was a bit light in color and with less head than i would 've expected , but you do n't taste with your eyes , so i 'm willing to forgive that this beer is not terribly photogenic .  this beer is on the lighter side of medium-bodied beers and boasts an exceptionally pleasant mouthfeel . carbonation is perfectly balanced , i could n't imagine any improvement here .

the beer has massive yeasty bready smells . the beer has a very good combination of fruity ( apples , grapes , pears , plums ) jelly smells . oddly enough the smells of this beer bring back memories of my grandmothers kitchen smell .  appearance : pours an opaque bronze with a thin bubbly head that quickly disappears smell : a strong burst of malt and a bit of hops on the finish taste : toasted malt dominates , but there is a subtle spicy finish not apparent in the aroma .  body is full but not cloying . exceptional silky velvet mouthfeel that is full-bodied yet providing a smooth viscosity .

s - smell is terrific and pops way more than a lot of nitro beers i 've had .  a- amber- orange with minimal head , but good retention of what head it has ... slightly cloudy ( chill haze ? ) not super-pretty .  m : creamy and delicious . everything is dead on here .

a - typical brown color that comes with this type of beer ; little to no head retention s - wonderful aroma ; slight caramel and hops ; this is what a brown ale should smell like !  the appearence was ok , looks just like everyother beer i have seen before .  excellent for it 's style .

exquisite critrusy , lemony aroma ; actually smells 'juicy ' . just amazing . flavour consists of traditional hefeweizen attributes with the addition of citrusy , american style hops .  poured from 12oz bottle into 20oz brooklyn brewery branded tulip pint glass . appearance : dark cola color with a small tan head that dissipates quickly and leaves a ring of lace .  smooth grit with comfort .

gives a snootful of dark chocolate and sweet dark molasses from 6 inches away , truly intense aroma . flavor is gently dominated by the chocolate , leans a little toward chocolate flavor extract , but nothing definitive .  it looks pretty much just like an ordinary old dark beer . its really really black , the head that rises with a pour is small and off white , there is really no retention at all , no lacing .  the mouthfeel was very very thick and creamy and not as thin as say a sierra nevada .

aroma is incredibly full and delicious . very very nice aroma . the flavor is just as incredible as the aroma . cherries , both sweet and sour are here in abundance , as well as a bit of graininess , and almost a thin flaky pastry flavor .  otter creek turns out some very drinkable beers , but often the brewery has been short on experimentation . unexpected notes of grapefruit and light burnt sugar open the nostrils . the taste is richly satisfying yet not overpowering , with a good balance of malt and hops . mouthfeel is quite good - in this case , a little bubbly , a little syrupy - and in all this is a beer one could drink at length .  amazingly smooth going down ; full bodied with light carbonation .

the aroma on this beer was exceptional . cinnamon and plum came across strongly , along with hints of ethanol and orange rind . it had a nice bitter finish , but i struggled for awhile to get a handle on the sweet , fruit flavors that seemed to stay with the beer for the duration . i was thinking cherry with a few orange notes , it seemed very familiar , and then i finally put my finger on what it was reminding me of : cough syrup .  pours a light amber color with ruby low lights , a small puffy head , some clingy lacing and a moderate amount of visible carbonation .  nice touch of bitterness lingers as i contemplate the rich , full mouth feel . nice beer , much more approachable than the expedition .

the smell was bourbon and caramel . sometimes these things can taste like beer with a shot of liquor - not so with this one . all in all , quite excellent .  dusky brown appearance , with ruby highlights at the edges , very slim and soon gone head , nothing to speak of .  mouthfeel : on the heavy side of the medium-bodied scale and creamy smooth .

the nose of this beer is simply amazing . pure fresh cherries , almost like a top notch but soft lambic . some light caramel and hops could be smelled as well , but mostly fresh fresh soft cherries . light caramel tone , but just very clean and malty . the bottle is a little disapointing to be honest , but on tap this beer is simply amazing . fresh cherries and soft clean crisp malt .  a clear light orange with a dense yet soft off-white head with good retention , there 's also not much lacing present . decent in appearance , this is also quite enjoyable on the nose .  m- full , smooth mouthfeel .

under all of this , i can still smell some gumball and barnyard odors . an amazing smell and likely a very unique one . t - more grapefruit pith and that same pine , but i still ca n't figure it out .  recieved this bottle froma friend at ab in st. louis . not a test bottle , but , a production bottle . a : milky brown , tan puffy head . nice lacing .  moutfeel : probably the best part of this beer is the mouthfeel . thick and sugary , with a ton of creaminess to start . a crisp , drying effect then takes over your throat and palate upon swallowing . then you are left with an alcohol bite that is both satisfying and warming .

smells delicious and this scent would be a great air freshener .  this beer pours a clear tawny color . the head is half an inch in height , and recedes quickly into a thin cap of lacing .  s : smells like sweet malt , spices that i ca n't pick out , some red/dark fruits , vanilla t : tastes just like the smell with more vanilla and even bourbon but in a mellow way , like a fruity , sweet , light bourbon..some alcohol flavor too m : very full bodied , almost to the point of creamy d : highly drinkable for the flavor but less so for the alcohol kick

aroma is awesome . yeast .  appearance : hazy and somewhat cloudy yellow ... a decent head .  very nice feel in the mouth -- rich , thick , tingling bubbles , kind of evaporates on the tongue . medium-heavy body , quite a bit of honey , i get this apple quality .

brett funkiness shows its face , but is n't as prominent as in others from similar varieties . like the smell , the brett funkiness is more subtle than others .  a : dark orangish amber with a tannish hue . not much head to speak of and minimal lacing .  mouthfeel is full and rich , easy to sip and enjoy . sweetness hinders the drinkability a bit , one bottle at a time is enough for me .

750ml bottle into duvel tulip a : golden/almost straw color with 3 '' thick , white whipped-cream like foam s : mango ! tropical fruit . smell of a very `` sticky '' and sweet fruit . once the foam dissipated , i can smell some `` yogurty '' belgian yeast . t : low-medium , maltiness with some husky ( tannin ) character upfront . noticed a very clean belgian yeast flavor after my palate got used to the beer . d : highly drinkable .  it pours pale , cloudy gold with a thin near-white head that really does n't hang around to party .  mouthfeel is perfect - smooth and velvety without being clingy or cloying .

nose was rich with fudgy chocolate , smoke and charcoal .  a : muddy brown with limited tan head that quickly fades but leaves lace on he edge .  thick and creamy . everything i look for in an imperial stout . light carbonation .

s : intoxicating mixture of sour fruit ( both peach , of course , and , oddly , raspberries ) and green aromatic wood - like sawdust from a live tree in springtime . unique and incredible . t : starts out with peach , then gets truly sour and funky ( with some great sappy sawdust coming through ) and finishes with some sweeter fruit and vanilla . great . m : fairly light-bodied with abundant soft carbonation . perfect for the style .  pours a bright , clear straw sunshine yellow . very quick , spongey head and one string of bubbles .  the mouthfeel was phenomenal . to have a cask conditioned beer is such a treat , and i 'm glad my neighborhood bar always has one beer on cask .

s -- good smell , a bit of the hops and malt . kind of smells like an ipa t -- taste was initially promising with a slight hop taste to it .  poured into a tulip . a soapy copper tinged head starts out very strong , but recedes to a ring at the beer 's edge fairly quickly .  m : the feel is excellent with fine carbonation lending a creaminess that is top-tier and a clean scrubbing finish with the right balance of crispness and aftertaste . d : an fine tripel with classic light fruit flavors mixed artfully with pepper and spice and a top-notch mouthfeel compose a very good brew .

nose is quite complex with some really nice notes of oak , vanilla , chocolate , roasted malt , and some light coffee . the taste does n't mix these together quite as well , but is still tasty . great feel coming from all different directions and quite drinkable for the big beer that it is .  on tap and enjoyed at steve 's birthday bash , snifter : a- coppery red with a small head and spotty lace .  very nice rich and creamy full body on this one , super smooth on the palate .

very yeasty , smells much like a barn -- earthy . sorry too many cat box smells .  pours a nice cloudy yellow as expected but this taste of it is just .  m : very soft carbonation and easy on the palate as a good session beer should be .

poured from the bottle into a nonic glass a- pours a dark orange amber color with a two finger frothy , slightly fluffy head that leaves some sticky , patching lacing , and high streaming carbonation s- a strong bouquet citrus , pine , and floral hop aroma t- balance of piney and citrus hops , caramel malt backbone , pretty strong woodiness , hits you with hops on the front and finishes with a strong piney hop finish , leaves a bitter aftertaste m- pretty smooth drinking , finishes a little watery o- a good ipa that packs a lot of bitterness and is very aromatic .  a - pours a very mirky yellow/orange color , small head that vanishes , no lace , cap , or retention .  m : so good i ca n't get enough . nice thickness with light carbonation and a good oily texture make this a delightful treat for my mouth .

s - the nose on this one is as good as it gets . t - just wonderful - almost as perfect as the nose . this outstanding beer 's only downfall . d - great . tons of booze and heat on this one , but the outstanding vanilla and coconut flavors allow me to drink as much of this as is available !  of all of the seasonal brews the guys at cbc put out , this is by far their standout . simply put : this is an excellent beer out of the tap , but only average out of the bottle . it 's never given # 1 billing - this is not a perfect beer by any stretch - but it is an incredibly drinkable beer , especially on a warm spring day near a college campus if you know what i mean .  in addition , there are hop oils , caramel , some sweetness and perhaps molasses along with a medium body that is oh so smooth and coats the mouth well . delicious and well balanced .

smell : very , very fruity ! it smells almost as good as a lady .  could n't get a head going on it . no lacing . dark brown in color .  bear republic really , really nailed the mouthfeel on this one .

sweet fruity aroma with a little bit of maltiness .  bottle w/ some bad ass artwork on the label ( i love flying dog 's illustrations ) cloudy golden color w/ a very thin head that quickly dissappeared to nothing , no lacing to speak of .  the feel is very silky .

s : pumpkin pie baby ! very nice . t : pumpkin spice , clove , nutmeg and caramel from the malts .  on to the beer : there was no head on this beer when i received it in my tulip . the color is chocolate brown wih hues of caramel orange . very lightly carbonated , and no , this was n't from the infamous bottles of the 2008 vintage , but a keg ( sorry , do n't know what vintage ) .  i really this the mouthfeel is perfect on this beer .

a - black with a huge coffee colored head s - smells delicious - very sweet , chocolate malts . the most balanced smell to a stout i have had the pleasure of knowing .  a : dark orange , very translucent . you can see that it 's quite fizzy . layer of golden foam quickly dissipates .  really wonderful . the mouthfeel is the most impressive and outstanding attribute of this beer .

on the nose , fresh fruits , cherries , peaches , green apples , pears , simply amazing . a bit twangy and just on the border of being chewy , but not quite . dry and a bit laid back ; decent yeasty body with some reserved sugar , candy cane offerings . sticky as it warms , sort of a bubble gum palate and a bit rustic .  mmmm ... the appearance is n't anything abnormal/fantastic/special or anything else to write home about ... it looks like an ipa .  mouthfeel : perfect mouthfeel .

the aroma of this beer is amazing ! hops hops and more hops ! very deep and complex . citrus , spice , pine ... but not much of the barley makes it through . wow this is hoppy !  a- dark amber with large off-white head that slowly dissipates to nothing .  mouthfeel is thick with smooth and creamy carbonation .

pours a deep amber ruby body with a nice modest off white head . smells of a massive combination of strong barley wine and oak . there 's flavors of raisons , plums and caramel on the nose with lots of vanilla and toasted notes from the oak . bourbon and dark fruit play out initially .  it looks much like a standard macro-brewers lager but the similarity ends there .  smooth and creamy , very soft carbonation . booze is extremely well hidden .

massively nutty aroma , packed with roasted peanut butter , walnut brownies , and nuttella - very inviting . not terribly smoky ( more roasty ) , just a mild edge of charcoal that also lends a hint of toasted marshmallow . plenty of coffee notes as well - this is just about perfect , exactly what i want in the style . strangely , there is not a hint of alcohol in this beer - which makes this dangerously drinkable , but still , not exactly a lawnmower beer !  bottle a pale golden , yellowish straw color . aggressive pour yielded little head , but decent carbonation and some nice sediment .  medium bodied but carbonation is bright and exciting , reminiscent of deschutes ' black butte porter , very refreshing . ca n't say enough about how great the mouthfeel deschutes puts out on some of their beers , red chair fits that bill .

s- this beer smells great , typical ipa smells ; pine mandarin , pineapple , grapefruit .  paid $ 15 even for the midwest taster ... the appearence was a cola colored base with a nice tannish head , minimal retention and no real lacing .  the mouthfeel is dead-on creamy .

s : as soon as i popped this one , i loved the smell of it . i was hoping after the great smell , it would have a taste i loved , but unfortunately not a taste that suits me .  poured a hazy straw color with 3 fingers of off-white head . average head retention & lacing s : slight straw with grassy & lemon notes t : lemon & orange hops up front .  m : thick and rich , with a nice amount of fine , late-developing carbonation . perfect for such a big beer .
