smell is one of the best ever , strong flowery , grassy smell . slight grainy smell also . you know what is about to happen .  12oz bottle , no date , in sa glass a : black with a one finger tan head that goes to ring rather quick s : roasted malts , espresso , oats and a little chocolate t : coffee , faintly bitter chocolate like bakers m : full body , little carbonation quite creamy d : enjoyable could have more than one .  it 's definitely thick , but it does n't feel anywhere near as syrupy as it looks . o : this beer has a great appearance and mouthfeel .

this is beautiful , and refined . man , the nose really had me going , but the taste did n't follow through .  pours a golden yellow with very little head .  m - medium bodied really smooth with perfect carbonation .

it pours like a big , english old ale . smell- fat and sweet , it 's a beautiful display of wood and chocolate covered cherries ... but more like the liquid that surrounds the cherries . notes of old leatherbound library books and rum soaked dark fruits abound .  a- straw with some haze .  extremely satisfying in this regard .

the smell was everything you would expect from a beer as hoppy as this . the smell of hop oil was big .  pours a dark clear gold with a 1 inch foamy light brown head that fades to nothing . no lacing on this one .  full bodied , heavy on the palate and full of flavor . i love it .

s : abundant floral hops , definately some cascade . the perfect combination of floral , bittering , aroma , in a showcasing of hops that is presented beautifully , well balanced and tame but not lame .  poured into a snifter , with a half inch head that all but disappears in seconds . very dark , mostly opaque body , a shade browner than black , with a touch of red at the edges when held to light .  mouthfeel is big full and smooth very rich and easy drinking with a really satisfing warming in the gut .

the first smell i picked up on was tropical fruit smells , including banana and something else ( ca n't put my nose on it ) . there was also a spiciness , and sort of a leatheryness , and a slight maltyness that i find typical of most belgians and pilsners ( pilsner malt ? there was a lot going on in the aroma , which makes me want to revisit this beer and think it through more carefully .  pours a hazy mud brown with little to no head .  this has been sitting in the cellar for about a year and i am convinced it has the absolute perfect mouthfeel .

looks find s- awesome citrus hop aroma , much more aggressive than i expected from a tiny , 4 % bitter . insane ! lovely m- body is overall pretty thin , nothing to see here o- awesome sessionable beer .  pours a clear orange with a 1 inch white head that fades to an oily film .  m : the mouthfeel is delightful . fairly thick for an ipa , almost creamy with mild carbonation .

the smell is wonderful . tannin , grapes , apples , apple peels , raisins , caramel , touch of cocoa , and a hint of alcohol .  poured a hazy orange/dark peach color , providing not much of a head and leaving behind hardly any lacing to speak of .  perfect carbonation .

very promising . and then : the taste is a bit disappointing after that great smell . good , but not exceptional .  poured from a 12oz brown bottle into a clear pint glass . a : not-quite-black dark brown with a tiny wisp of a tan head that materializes with some delay but does n't stick around long and leaves a few dots of lace . the lack of head made me wonder about packaging issues , although the flavor was excellent .  ( m ) mouthfeel is perfect for this beer .

aroma is a sweet malt-candy smell , bready , with a note of ginger and sourness . this beer tastes almost as good as it smells .  pours a less than clear reddish brown . head only lasts a fleeting moment with no lacing to speak of .  mf - perfect ! soft carb .

s - beautiful dark malt and deep cherry aroma .  i 've had the bottle , and there is some weird floaters in there , but they did n't bother me . there is little head and is a nice amber in color .  just take a sip and get lost in the nearly overpowering flavor explosion and the creamy tingly mouthfeel of this wondrous scottish ale .

smells absolutely wonderful ... pungent aroma of hops all the way ... piney , citrusy hops and i 'm loving it ... i want to smell this all night ... terrific blend of piney/grapefuit hops and sweet malts.. thought this was going to be a hop bomb all the way which would have been fine but i 'm surprised at the balance on this one .  it looks like they wo n't last long . half the head is gone within 1 minute .  great mouth feel on this one . no hops or bitterness present at first , but bitter in the finish .

quite impressive - i just could n't stop bringing this one to my nose .  not bright and vivid like mirror pond , not at all cloudy . head was some what reluctant , white and thin with decent retention .  mouthfeel is perfect , my ideal belgian .

aroma is unable to be discerned in this sitting , it 's quite faint .  1/8 '' white head that dissipates quickly with minimal slippery lacing .  the mouthfeel is amazing , thick and solid with a lingering savory finish .

i loved the spicy taste when i first tried it , reminded me of christmas in the summer , and the smell was very delightful . i would definatly get this beer again if i was out with some buddies , and being that it is a summer beer it was perfect for a summer night in georgia .  small , short-lived white head tops a golden colored brew , slight haze but mostly clear .  silky silky smooth on the mouth , it makes it feel as light bodied but if you take the time to get a feel it 's almost medium . just fantastic . o- this is deffinitely a good saison , the mouthfeel is the highlight .

flavour is bit more restrained , still very nice with all the traditional hefe characteristics , wheaty and yeasty with cloves but also some caramel and brown bread . aftertaste is , like with most wheat beers , very moderate but nice . can you expect a hefeweizen to be much better than this ?  good lacing , poor head retention .  feel is really nice as well , lightly creamy and buttery with super calming smoothness and a bit of chewyness with a slightly bread dough drying in the finish .

huge sweet and bready malts rise to the nose upon an initial whiff .  pours a light bronze with notable carbonation .  finishes fruitty & spicy mf : huge & well balanced this was bit ponderous , but tasty .

big fluffy two finger head that wafts the hop aromas well , tons of lace and excellent carbonation . color is a kind of murky dark amber . smells great . i love it , the quintessential california hop heaven . tons of grapefruit cascade , melon , guava , apples , cherries- all with a subtle fresh-cut woodsy pine backbone and soothing aroma of fresh mountain air .  preface - i always rate brews to style ... a - very average . no head . or lacing .  m - the mouthfeel is fantastic . medium and a little creamy with just the right amount of carbonation .

a big , beautiful whack of tropical fruits on the nose - pineapple , passionfruit . superb . the tropical fruits are still there on the palate but perhaps a little more resinous than i was expecting .  ok retention with little fingers of lace .  m : light and refreshing with a perfect amount of carbonation .

smell : great aromas of licorice and chocolate . overall , the beer is a bit rough around the edges , perhaps from importation , but that is certainly part of its charm .  a - pours a deep brown with very distinct ruby highlights . thin off-white head and very little lacing .  mouthfeel : fantastic . rich without being syrupy . carbonation is just right .

s - earthy , estery fruit with guava fragrance , slight anise notes .  lots of sediment just waiting to get moved around in the bottom of this beer . not enough foam or head , or lacing for an ipa imho .  dark malts , some chocolate , medium to full bodied and very smooth from start to finish .

at the beginning i tend to agree with most of the other reviews and it is very hoppy . the next time i want this much hops i will go into my homebrew supplies and get a cup of hops and just chew on it .  pours a pale copper color with an off white head from a brown twist off bottle .  mouthfeel is fine and not heavy .

yep , it 's a black beer . it started well with a nice head and aroma . sweet fruit and coffee flavors , not too heavy .  appears a hazy yellow color and a heavy pour yields a thin , large bubbled head that fades to a sheen rapidly .  mouthfeel was real good .

smell - sweet cherry with a sour breath to it , almost like a flemish red . sour , most definitely sour , with a fruity aroma to it ; most likely banana . very pungent , while not bad , not very saison like .  pours an efferevescent bronze with a thumb of offwhite head . not a lot of head retention or lacing s : bready malt & aged or old hops .  very rich flavor of dark malts and smoke , with hints of coffee and chocolate as well . the finish is almost all smoke , much too intense for my liking . ive used this many times in making caribou pot roasts in the crockpot . they even have a recipe on their website , which is delicious . i was informed that this beer has won more medals at the great american beer festival than any other beer , quite an accomplishment .

its not very good in the smelling department . its not very good in the tasting department .  theyre rumored to be in yakima now but no information is forthcoming and their system wont accept my email inquiries . the brew was deep crimson with fine sediment adrift throughout . this is ( was ) a regal , dignified ale that was oh so easy to drink . though neither the bottle nor the bear creek website mentions the abv , bearly barley wine didnt come across as overpowering or excessively strong .  m : smooth and medium bodied .

s : sour aroma with apple , citrus , and raisin notes . d : this brew looked and smelled good but is way off the mark on taste .  it pretty much looks like muddy pond water , but this look in a beer is actually sort of exciting , because it signals me that i am in for an interesting experience .  it is bubbly on the tongue and does leave you dry . it 's smooth , but just kind of basic . it 's a very approachable stout .

s : the red ale has plenty of caramel to go around , a sweet aroma with plenty of strength . too bad too , because the nose has a really nice aroma .  this score might be a bit lower than appropriate , as i drank the beer in an opaque vessel , and in a dark room -- did n't get much of a look , so i just gave it a middle of the road score on appearance .  it is quite nice on the mouthfeel , almost enough to disguise the heavy-handed corn influence .

the smell was also very nice and seemed like it would taste good .  courtesy of raindog , thanks sir body is dark brown and initially wears a tan head that fast becomes one of the quickest dissipating festival of bubbles i 've ever seen .  mouthfeel was good and very drinkable ; however , it was slightly bitter ... something i was n't expecting this to have considering the malts .

sweet marzipan-like smell reminds me of candied cake bread .  the beer pours a very deep brown , forming a thin 1/8 inch head .  the drink is carbonated a little more than average as well . mf- very crisp beer with little or no after taste . one of the smoother beers around .

a nice hoppy aroma .  pours a pale straw yellow color with a decent looking body and about two fingers of nearly pure white head . ample carbonation and the head is very fizzy , and as such it recedes quickly and leaves not a lick of stick or a trace of lace .  mouthfeel is fine . medium bodied with the right amount of carbonation .

nose is spicy , vanilla , wintergreen , sweet malt , molasses , and a few other thinks , not bad mind you , certainly different , start is sweet with a sudden rush of bitterness , light grain profile , and top light in feel .  fluffy head features large bubbles quickly thins , leaving only a very thin top .  mouthfeel is medium to full . there 's a nice level of carbonation .
the smell was oats and a fruitiness to it .  pours a caramel with a light tan froth , good retention , & average lacing .  mouthfeel : crisp and refreshing .

smell : sweet in it caramel and rum raisin like scent .  the beer 's appearance was a little bit of a letdown , there was almost no head at all even with an aggressive pour . below the beltline everything was all right , the beer was pale yellow and hazy , almost looked like a wit .  it as a quite full mouthfeel similar to a very sweet red wine , almost syrupy . it gives a good warming feeling .

hazelnut & coffee dominate the nose but there are roasted malt & faint hop scents in there , too . so far so good . nope .  the beer pours a dark copper , forming a 1/4 inch tan head . light spots of lace on the glass .  mouthfeel is nice , actually - light bodied , spritzy carbonation .

it smells pretty good , too .  ( a ) - pours a very thick cloudy caramel color .  the mouthfeel is good ; slightly thick and very smooth . however , it is a little bubble and will sting the recesses of your mouth .

it has a deep coppery crystal appearance and an invitingly crisp , sweet , floral scent .  an initial pleasantly sweet light malt aroma moves to phenol and other spiciness , finally settling with that mix . fizzy smallish head that leaves . richness to mouthfeel lends to the sense of fullness and a hefty carbonation helps too . contrary to crispness for style this has a very good ale smoothness .  taste is a very light malt sweetness upfront with a moderately bitter finish of good length and crispness . a pretty uncomplicated beer , good for the style , a good lawnmower beer .

odd , but oddly good . taste follow suit and starts out good , but a pretty strong metallic aftertaste ruins this beer .  pours a slighlty hazy amber with a pretty average head .  body is on the full side of medium . moderate carbonation .

2010 vintage thanks to j47paco look : pitch black and totally opaque with a 1/4 inch tan head and no real retention smell : hints of dark chocolate molasses and fudge taste : i am not sure why everyone praises the flavor of this beer because the beer is a sweet sugary mess .  this beer pours a mirky brown with a sizeable light tan head .  highly carbonated .
s - nice hop aroma with a few floral notes .  minimal head with an aggressive pour . minimal to no lacing at all .  mouthfeel : the bottle conditioning makes for a very smooth ride .

aroma disappointing , a bit of a rusty/copper aroma . hop aroma disappoints , and ibu fiends probably will be disappointed with it .  a hazy orangeish brown with a small head which quickly receded and left minimal lacing .  light and creamy mouth feel with obviously knocked down carbonation .

taste : something about the taste does n't quite live up to the smell . the taste is a weakened version of the caramel malts in the smell leading into a dark fruit plumlike aftertaste .  good bubbly , head . the variance in size of bubbles making up the head , almost give it a lumpy appearance .  good carbonation .

smells surprisingly thick : notes of chocolate on apricot and hops .  the pour was not what i would consider , um great . light amber in color , nearly golden with a very , very clear body to it . lots of carbonation could be seen streaming up towards the top of the glass which coalesced into a thin , but firm white cap at about a quarter of an inch , but this really did not stay long , fading with no real side glass lacing .  mouthfeel is very light and well carbonated .

aroma - a boozy chocolate smell , some light whiskey/peat supporting it .  cola-like brown in appearance . carbonation is a bit high on this very fresh bottle , but i 'm sure aging a few of these will mellow that , in addition to allowing the flavors to meld and blend together . quite nice fresh though .  m - low carbonation , tiny bubbles , overall feels pretty good .

i also get a sort of hospital sanitation aroma . i always think sahti smells very interesting and inviting as well as completely authentic . t - quite mild .  pours a cloudy amber topped with a two finger foamy tan head . a little too dark and too cloudy for the style - unless those are hop particles clouding it up , but as long as it tastes good i can look past it .  mouthfeel is medium , clean with a bitter hop aftertaste .

looks like honey , smells like honey , very sweet , almost no head in either pour out of a 22 oz .  very small tan head with minimal retention and lacing .  good , solid creamy feel with enough dryness to get you through .

aroma of sour cherries jumps out while being poured .  a : a murky , iced tea colour ... not much head at all , and whatever was there did n't stick around long .  if there is , then this ska brew is a prime example ... this is the second time i tasted a bottle of this brew . this is an extremely clean tasting brew which is a great quality i enjoy , but where are the hops ? the malt and ( not overwhelming ) bitterness serve as great supporting backbones to what should be a wonderful hoppy aroma and flavor . as it stands , this brew is severely lacking in hop flavor/aroma and comes across as a brew which should be named `` delicate '' rather than `` decadent '' imperial ipa .

i had this beer tried next to or , poured from a bottle into a pint glass ... a : a pitch black color , very tiny white thin ring of a head , pretty poor looking ... s : smell is awesome . tons of hoppy citric and grapefruit notes , with some sweet honey and vanilla ... t : wow . a bit of a letdown very little hop bitterness and a strong cloyingly sweet flavor with little complexity ... m : smooth , could use more carb ... d : a decent enough beer , but its the worst between either and or !  a- pale yellow and cloudy .  medium bodied and smooth .

s - instantly linseed and lemon peel smells entered the room when the cap was popped . some honey-comb sweet waxy smells and a bit of powdered sugar .  a : cloudy yellow/orange color with some suspended solids . broken , thin lacing ; none near the end .  nice mouthfeel .

interesting aroma . very floral with slight hints of spice and citrus .  but i was in a pils-y mood today and picked up some budweiser ( the real budweiser ) today and drank it before this guy , so i was worried about how it would hold up to that greatness . but it really is like comparing apples to oranges . troegs is a very faint , almost macro-lager yellow , almost definately not decoction mashed . like biting into an apple on a summer 's day . it does n't taste like an apple at all , but that is what it makes me think of . the mouthfeel is good for a pils . it 's a well made pils man .  mouthfeel is sticky and sweet with a nice roundness and full character .

s-chocolate milk mix , rich , earthy cigar tobacco , nutty malts .  their saison pours a bright , rich , cloudy golden hue with a milky white , effervescent head . the pearly cap of foam recedes fairly quickly and leaves little or no lacing .  m : about the same consistency as the boston lager .

s : a nice aroma of fruit , yeast , and malt . t : tasted of apples and yeast up front , with a malty finish .  poured from a 12oz bottled in 2009 a : pours a deep red orange color with a small white head that dissipates quickly .  mouthfeel : medium-plus body . medium carbonation . some oily viscosity to the mouthfeel .

smell is milk chocolate sweet and it also has traces of black fruit .  some sediment and good lacing .  as is the case in many of the wilder beers out there it 's not as wacky on the palate as it is on the nose . even for a lover of brett and funk this is n't a highly drinkable beer . if the goal was just to see how far they could crank up the volume on the brett funk then they succeeded but if they were looking to brew something that tasted great i 'll have to say they fell a little short .

smells nice .  a hazy dark yellow color with a head that i missed since i looked in another direction ( for 3 seconds ) while rvdoorn poured the beer .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied with a velvety texture , and appropriately low carbonation .

a hint of cinnamon mixes in there that is a bit unique fir the style t - taste is banana with a hint of bubblegum ; bit of malty sweetness dominates the flavor with a hint of oak of the end ; bit sweet for my taste and much sweeter than the noise led on to mf - bit thick with a hint of syrup ; light carbonation on the back end that attempts to break down some of the sweet , stickiness of the beer but fails d - happy this was a one off since that is about the only time i would drink it .  clear gold with a small bubbling white head . very balanced and enjoyable ... perfect for sessioning anytime .  mouthfeel : light bodied beer . moderate carbonation .

nose shows loads of treacle fudge and brown sugar with cloves showing in the background .  appearance is rather uninspiring , dark , little to no lace or head , no apparent carbonation .  the mouthfeel is medium to full bodied with smooth carbonation .
the smell was probably what i liked most about this olde style ale .  color is a nice golden orange , much like an iced tea .  fairly thick body .

smell is sweet and quite hoppy , smells a lot like raw carrot . sweet chocolate and coffee aromas that are heavier .  poured into my guinness 20 oz glass , no idea when this was bottled ... there is no date listed on the bottle a-pale orange color with a small inch head s- sweet pale malt , flowery and fruity ( citrus ) hops t- very flowery , earthy , oily hops with a subtle citrus fruit taste .  light body with good carbonation .

can into pint glass a - big 2 finger eggshell head , slightly hazy medium orange/brown coloring on the beer , relatively large bubbles s - quite robust hops and citrus control the doughy scent , surprisingly bold smell t - bready start transforms smoothly to a citrus to a bitter and a slightly sour finish .  a very cloudy orange color .  very smooth without being too full bodied .

syrupy with about 1 finger of dark brown head . s - vanilla cookies , some brown sugar and chocolate , but it 's alright .  pours a deep amber with very little carbonation . no head in trappist glass , just thin ring of white bubbles clinging to the sides for dear life .  taste is thin and adjuncty . mouthfeel is good , thick and creamy .

nose is sweet milk chocolate , cookie dough , and roasted malt with hints of vanilla and black cherry in the background . this is a fairly enjoyable brew , but i could n't see drinking more than a couple without wanting to go onto something else with a bit more complexity in flavor . perhaps with a little more carbonation the rich flavors hinted at in the nose could really come through .  a - pours a semi-translucent deep brown hue , and is capped with a smallish bubbly head .  m- very little carbonation . very full syrupy body .

i like it . t : bitter pine hop flavor hits first with a little bit of relief from the malt , but it never really helps balance the beer altogether .  eye candy : pours a transparent amber . plenty of rising carbonation . fizzy thin head , klacing lasted throughout session . otherwise , autumn is perfect for the fall , drinkable from early sept untill the snow starts a flying .  for a big mouthfeel , this simply does n't have a flavor to match . very nice mouthfeel , good bite up front , a bit of carbonation in middle that emphasises the rye flavors , and a crisp finish that is actual slightly ruined by the lingers smoked flavor .
an aroma of banana , cloves , spices and hops .  presentation : on tap . appearance : hazy amberish brown .  there 's moderate carbonation to it as well .

smell : lots and lots of blueberries .  22oz bottle a- pours an orangish amber color with a thin and fizzy off-white head that quickly disappears .  boiled pasta water finish . good carbonation . twinge of acid is perfect .

appearance -- pours dark brown with a slim smell -- the nose is inviting : cocoa , dark fruit , toasted coconut , whiskey , vanillin wood sugars , and dry oak planks . the mellow oak and coconut so strong in the nose have vanished .  12oz brown bottle with a bottle code that i ca n't decipher . thin layer of tan head holds its own and leaves some lacing on the glass . opaque brown with amber hues when brought up to the light . coffee flavors comes in slow but becomes a dominant flavor middle to end .  creamy mouthfeel with moderate carbonation .

amber color with a huge orangey , frothy head that leaves crusty peaks like meringue as it dissipates . aroma is of hop , citrus , and pine .  big head with big bubbles like one , too . head dissipates fast to nothingness .  it has a very soft mouthfeel , a little like soda to be honest and you can barely notice the alcohol .

love the idea of a beer from utah being called polygamy anything , although i 'm not sure how the people who run that state would feel . anyway , at first glance this is a beautiful dark red porter in the glass with a nice chocolate milk head that did dissapate a little quick . the taste of chocolate malt is very mild , if fact you have to wait 5-6 seconds after you swallow to really taste anything . i could drink this porter but for a purist , this would not hold up . a nice try , and not a bad brew , but not worth any extra effort either .  they get me all strung out on what becomes my go-to session beer -- like they did with the long-lamented cinder cone red -- and then like lucy van pelt , they snatch it away at the last second , leaving me flat on my back and yelling , `` aauugh ! '' red chair nwpa is a copper-colored pour with a sturdy , vanilla-tinted head that throws a nose of nice fragrant hops ; floral and citrus notes add some complexity to the usual pine/grapefruit assault . at around 55 ibus , red chair was the more balanced sibling of the more flamboyant bond street sisters . personally , i do n't care what they call it , it is a much better seasonal replacement for cinder cone than the buzzsaw brown was , and if they get it in their heads to make it year around , well , so much the better .  mouthfeel is medium with good level of carbonation .

the initial aroma is promising- delivering a crisp maltiness , low-lying sweetness , and a good helping of cascade hops for a grapefruity , lightly piney aroma . fair and balanced throughout the nose . flavors is where the beer begins to give way .  painted 12oz purchased at merchant 's and poured into a tulip . dark chestnut with a bubbly head of light tan that dissipates to a ring of large bubbles .  m : nice and thick d : not something ill try again .

the smell lacks any character . it 's hard to distinguish anything from the nose .  dark , almost black with no head yet nice lacing .  dark brown/amber body . it is a very smooth and a sweet sipper . some hops , caramel , candy sugar and oak . not much bourbon . i was way excited to try this and actually find it to be rather average .

s : smell of yeast and coriander that gives way to banana . t : taste not as complex as the smell , but still pleasing .  first off , i thought this beer was very delicious ... and i will certainly buy another ! i do n't know if i poured mine incorrectly , but it was very cloudy ... which i thought oktoberfests are supposed to be clear ( i 'm thinking about spaten , sam adams , and the like ) . in fact , i loved it !  medium mouhfeel with some carbonation . smooth and buttery feel . pretty dry finish .

the aroma is pleasing with a dominant smell of overripe peaches backed by toasty malt and pecans .  pours a hazy straw yellow with a half finger head that fades somewhat quickly . not too impressive .  feels very creamy but that does n't make the beer more drinkable to me .

smell - pumpkin with some nutmeg maybe a bit of brown sugar and cinnamon . overall - i just wish that this beer tasted more like it smells but that might just be me being a fan of spicy beers .  poured into a pint glass to give a nice clear golden ting witha 1/2 inch of white head thatlingered for a while but eventually dissipated to a thin film atop the beer .  mouthfeel : light-bodied but not watery . it had a nice feel to it .

nice . malty small hops in the nose .  but it was a good spiritual experience anyway . the color was a bit darker than i expected , but i am not a bjcp judge , so screw it .  there 's also just a hint of citrus from the orange peel ( or orange oil extract ) the smooth mouthfeel and moderate body is not unlike that of a german hefeweizen .

the aroma is very floral , scented and hoppy . the finish is very bitter , almost astringent . overall it is a nice pilsener , complex and interesting .  a- cloudy golden tan topped with an off white head . the head fades quickly to a ring and leaves a little spotty lace on the glass .  this is my first review and hope it looks well , even if not my favorite beer . leaves a malt taste on the roof and tongue . this is the first scottish ale i 've tried . for comparison , i love dark ales , like ommegang abbey belgium ale and founders breakfast stout . bottle serving .

s : a pleasant aroma of sweet candy sugar , soft raspberries , and maybe a bit of honey . very straight forward . t : first sip : i thought this is sorta nice .  a - reddish brown brew with a big head and a little bit of scattered lacing .  maybe i could not taste the `` rare '' but this really sucked compared to the 2008 classic gueuze which is a fantastic gueuze .

reviewed from notes : appearance : orange copper with a 1 finger head smell : bourbon , vanilla , fruity taste : sour fruit , something went wrong in this bottle mouthfeel : mild carbonation , medium body , overall : i think i 'm going to need to try it again .  hazy apricot-looking color , left a creamy light tan coating after the clean-up of the initial opening of the beer , left some spotty lacing and some slight traces of carbination .  m - great carbonation , finishes well .
had a very hoppy aroma upon first sniff . second whiff hints at fruity aromas that almost smell like a fruit salad .  a lot of particles .  m - medium body and low carbonation .

fresh aroma , fruity , with notes of peach , nectarine , citrus . once a favorite , before i discovered what the revivalists among american craftbrewers have been doing with this style . apparently , the american version , bottled and draft , is weakened some for `` our '' taste , and i 'm profoundly disappointed .  appearance- pours out a muddy brown color with a small off white head . a good amount of particles floating around .  mouthfeel is crisp , the whole drink is refreshing due to the good carbonation .

s - a delightful aroma typical of a oud bruin - sour cherries , with some faint mulling spice and faint caramel malt .  into a tulip , pours a decent head initially , with little lacing and no legs .  pleasantly carbonated on the palate , with a dry finish .

the aroma is very subtle but you can pick up on the yeasts used , and sweet grain .  kind of cloudy hazy light golden color .  being of fan of bocks , i was fully prepared to love this ubiquitous doppelbock . it was kind of sweet and malty , smelled great , felt nice going down -- quite satisfying . there was a slightly funky smell to it , and an even funkier taste . i thought that was more common in highly hopped beers . at $ 10 for the four pack , i hate to try it again for fear of wasting my hard-earned beer money .

pours dark brown with a large head s. lots of dried fruit , typical to a belgian brown t. something off here , metallic and strangely bitter along with the sweet dried fruit flavor . d. overall i was n't too impressed , it starts out pretty good but not what i expected .  another great offering from this great brewery . this is a great lambic . there is no mistaking it is a peach lambic . the peach is moderate to strong in flavor , somewhat sweet , a bit tart , but it balances well . again not all fruit beers are bad , were not talking about smirnoff or bacardi crap here , this isnt something sweet just to chug and get wasted , this is a beer to drink fo rthe enjoyment of drinking it , not just the buzz .  m- moderate/high carbonation , medium body , lager clean . crisp enough leaving a refreshing feel .

nose is weak chocolate , figs , and roasted barley .  clear , pale golden with a quickly thinning white head with ok retention and alcing .  medium-full body and medium carbonation with good smoothness .

s : ton of grapefruit , citrus , lemon , pine in the background , smells sweet t : there 's something that just tastes off and soapy . there 's almost a cloying sweetness that adds to the off-taste .  golden-orange color , almost transparent and practically no head .  very creamy and full . very dry .

head is almost tan , but too white to deserve the label . aroma is like a 60-minute ipa that 's gone off its meds . a blast of hops juice . but , i could not drink your 120 minute ipa .  served in a hill farmstead tulip glass . a - minimal carbonation . thin-late rising wisp of bubbles that linger on top . not much of a looker here .  mouthfeel is about right for style , perhaps a touch undercarbed , but all else is acceptable , though it showcases a flavor profile best left behind the curtain .

it was very hoppy but it lacked a lot of body , deep malt and maturation . drinkability is good but i rated it low as a barleywine because this is not a barleywine in my book , sorry guys . it did smell good..like imeprial ipa though..just because you hopped it to hell and it is a 100ibu does not make it a barleywine .  it pours a lovely clear caramel brown with red highlights . very little head sits on top , and what little there is disappears almost immediately .  - well carbonated , dries the mouth a bit . nice smooth body , probably this beers highlight is the mouthfeel .

there is a nice aroma of oats .  ayinger bru weisse pours a light golden color into my glass ; it has a perfect hefe haziness to it . moderate carbonation , no lacing . i was slightly disappointed by its initial appearance , but the taste is fantastic .  mouthfeel is light with a good spike of carbonation .

good hops and sourdough bread on the nose , some citrus , nice complexity and pleasant tone .  this one pours very clear and almost `` light '' looking for an ipa , it 's a rather light amber with a puny head .  very light body , and highly carbonated and fuzzy .

dark fruit aroma with pineapple and apricots as the main smells coming through .  finally got some last night on tap at mad mex . looks average , served in a snifter , no head , mild lacing .  it was somewhat thick with some carbonation , and had a hot aftertaste .

a- deep brown with mahogany hues , 1/4 '' tan head with little retention and films of lacing s- coffee , roasted malts , rich , alcohol , strong scents t- sweet caramel and buttery malts flavor but balanced by strong burnt astringencies , alcohol evident throughout , strong at finish , some chocolate m- somewhat creamy , stiff carbonation with ho alcohol at finish and in after d- complex malt flavor but alcohol is to strong and carbonation comes off as awkward .  this poured a clear medium golden , white foam head , that left broken lace all the way through , taste was nice , rather bold hops , up front , then mellows , to a bit of a sweet aftertaste , citrusy notes , fruit and hop nose , bit of apple , and lemon . mouthfeel was a little chewy , but fairly rich and full , drinkability is very good , nice summer brew !  a - opaque black color with a small head that disappears quickly s - rich chocolate-like aroma , mild yeast esters , some smokiness , no hop perceived t - roasted malt flavor dominates , some yeasty esters and mild hop flavors take a secondary role , very gentle mild hop finish with some lingering smokiness m - smooth creamy medium body with moderately low carbonation d - this is a decent enough oatmeal stout . the head and retention is disappointing , but the smell , taste and mouthfeel are acceptable .

has a unique floral-like almost medicinal band-aid brett character to it . a different aroma , but an intriguing one . ( t ) - very different from the smell . very dry and bitter with tons of clay . a bit disjointed and surprisingly thin even for the style .  poures a slightly hazy ... well hay/straw color with a white one finger head that leaves pretty quickly leaving no lace behind , nice lemony aroma very effervescent with just a light wheaty undertone.wow this beer suprises me a little not just a run of the mill american wheat ale here nice big wheat malt profile very sturdy but not heavy in the mouth , soft lemony tones round this out very nicely just enough to make you not think about the `` dreaded '' lemon wedge.could be one of the better american wheat beers out there wich might not be saying much but this is very good .  the mouthfeel is thick and oily with a mild burn going down . have a bottle of this is all i can handle , which is good because the full bottle would have me a little too buzzed .

my prominent reaction was one of disappointment ; this beer has some nice qualities , most notably a pleasant smell , but lacks much else and has a very flat mouthfeel which really detracted from my enjoyment of this beer and would lead me to not recommend it . aroma is a pleasant sweet coffee smell .  it pours a dark beer with little head .  light-medium caramel malt sweetness up front , continued in the middle with a hint of earthy hop bitterness , finishing with a more of the same . medium mouthfeel .

s - coffee ( duh ) , cocoa powder , and a mild pleasant sweetness t - initially hoppy followed briefly by mocha .  a pour down the center gave an initial 2 fingers of tan head , which diminished rapidly to a little foam around the edges ... a little disappointing . the dark color is n't opaque , if held to a back light . dark hues of deep red/garnet highlight the edges . no lacing either ( also disappointing ) .  i 'm not sure what a `` baltic '' porter is supposed to taste like ; but this one is quite different from most porters i 've had . sweet molasses aroma that is greater than any chocolate or mocha that might be found . a strong level of metal present also . sweet , almost like brandy . reminds me far more of a double bock than a porter . i can not detect any hops at all . too sweet for me , making it more one-dimensional without any complexity .

smell is of butterscotch and very pleasing . like you are about to have a delicious dessert .  a - pours cloudy dark amber with medium head . my glass had some dark particles in it .  it 's still fairly sturdy though , and carbonation is low but solid .

smell : ah , now we 're getting somewhere . super saturated bock aroma , fusels , brown sugar , surprisingly sharp citrus notes . as it opens up , cherry and vanilla become more assertive .  a - its a real muddy brown with a light tan head and massive bubbles .  m : thick , chewy..medium carb .

hopscent is sweet/floral with a good bit of sugary malt aroma as well . so much for the good will built up by the appearance and smell . the finish is so astringent and gummy that it almost completely takes away from any positives achieved by the consistency and carbonation of the drink .  nice deep amber/copper color was topped by a thin head that left zero lacing .  good mouthfeel for this light body but the hops balance the feel .

pours q light clear bmc ylliw . nose is plain of rice and malt . light and malty it 's very and bad worth skippng and bland skip it !  poured from 750ml bottle into tulip glass . a : dark copper , head is generous and frothing but does n't live very long and leaves almost no lacing .  mouthfeel : good carbonation , nice medium body .
s - big caramel malt nose with some fruity hops .  served a crisp yellow with a thin diminishing head .  could be a bit less carbonated .

not much smell , quite light on the hops , but still has a nice floral character .  glass with no head whatsoever .  m - full bodied and chewy with a moderately dry finish with some alcohol noticeable .

aromas of bread ( it looks like he is grilled ) and cinnamon sweet very pleasant .  a : crystal clear golden color with an appropriate sized head . i was expecting something a little more cloudy .  mouthfeel was nice smooth and easy to drink as far as body goes .

smells really good for a belgian strong dark so i 'll give it that , but the brett and sour cherry components were just not there as i thought they would be . could have been but the aroma was n't bad so i have my doubts .  brown color with tons of yeast floaters . very thin tan head . nothing special to look at but not terribly out of character for the style .  m : crisp and clean , moderate levels of carbonation and warmth . medium body .

the sweet smelling belgian malts are very nice . the flavor starts out very well .  appearance : dark orange-copper color ; a little hazy ; very small head on the pour smell : a pleasant hoppy smell taste : excellent : fairly balanced ; mild hoppiness with a nice sweet malt flavor to balance ; very tasty ( not watered down at all ) mouthfeel : medium bodied ( im really surprised this is on 4.87 % alcohol ) ; its a lot thicker than other 4.87 % beers ; this must a have a lot of unfermentables in it drinkability : good flavor ; good body , so its going down pretty quick overall , an excellent beer .  mouthfeel was nice and thick ; you know you 're drinking a dipa .

the smell is quite good , with typical bourbon notes of vanilla , oak , and toffee , with a touch of alcohol .  pours - nothing spectacular here . moderate carbonation , moderate head - coarse , and fades rapidly , leaving some lace . looks thick - the bubbles seem pretty leisurely on the way up .  m - surprising carbonation fight with a medium bodied beer .

sweet and fruity aroma with cloves and a little bit of funk .  appearance : medium carbonation , 1 inch head , dark brown smell : malt , chocolate syrup -- like bosco , and cream taste : chocolate , burnt malt , nut , and cream mouthfeel : sweet , medium bodied , smooth drinkability : this is a surprisingly sessionable stout .  mouthfeel was good , with plenty of carbonation and a nice smoothness to it .

but since it 's summertime , i 've been drinking more beer and have been quite impressed with the quality of crafty beers out there ( if only i did n't live on the upper east side of nyc , where you do n't get much of a beer selection at the supermarkets and delis ) . i was not a big fan of this beer - i enjoy ipa 's , but this one seemed all hops and nothing else .  small craft warning is a hazy golden lager with a somewhat diminishing , soft and splotchy , white head .  a little sticky and a very bitter aftertaste .

s : sweet and fruity , raisiny , red wine-iness comes through , though this is definitely beer as it has a strong malt character , roastiness and spicy hops . t : a sweet flavor up front with an off , flavor blocking presence in the center of my tongue ( wacky and tannic ) .  rich antique golden ale , with a one finger head that gives way pretty quickly .  smells of raisins , a hint of semi-sweet choc ? mouthfeel is nice , thick , syrupy & smooth ... the way i want a barleywine .

smell = lots of alcohol and zest . a candy like sweetness , smell almost exaclty like strawberry twizzlers . intesesting scent . taste = too sweet and syrupy with the alcohol packing quite a punch to boot .  33cl bottle poured into my gordons thistle glass a- 1 finger head post pour and reducing to non existancy immediately . held to the light , a hint of light gets through to show a very dark dark dark dark ruby body .  mouthfeel - medium bodied and smooth with a good carbonation level .

not much else and not too complex , but it had nice depth and smelled good . mouthfeel : medium-bodied , getting close to edging towards full bodied .  nice light golden straw color with a slight haze appropriate for the style . head dissapears quickly to a light spotty blanket .  pleasantly effervescent mouthfeel .

smell is sweetly malty , definite dark fruit edges ... quite appealing .  the crystal clear mahogany red color was nice , but it only produced a -finger of beige head that dissipated quickly , and it left no lacing whatsoever .  mouthfeel is pretty good , goes well with the style of light and highly carbonated .

smell figs , sweet molasses alcohol .  a pretty dull looking beer , but on the nose , there is a huge oatmeal presence that lays on top of the roasted coffee and bitter cocoa nubs .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied and carbonation is moderate .

nose is dark malt with some nice subtle estery notes of banana , raisin and pear .  12 oz bottle a : deep amber under a small tan head . no lace , no retention .  the carbonation and mouthfeel were appropriate for this style .
very pungent and filling . however , it 's surprisingly malty , more than both ramnuts and i cared for .  deep dark brown color , little head and no lace .  thick and smooth mouthfeel .

smell : dry , musty and earthy , with clove , banana and black pepper .  pours an opaque orange/brown , thin tan head forms , disappears to a thin ring really fast , some lace spots .  m & d - this beer is great on its own , too light and carbonated and malty for me , but suits a nice dinner perfectly , goes well with food and that was its intention so i must review it within its intentions and the style , for which it is very good

the aroma is similar to homebrewing wort with hints of cereal grains and corn syrup . it smells good but its way to sweet for my taste .  pours a clear golden color with a big white head that diminishes quite quickly .  mouthfeel : nicely carbonated , and nice and creamy . feels good on the tongue .

( s ) - smells seriously fruity ! raspberry , strawberry , cherry , and blueberrry . ( t ) - the massive fruits from the smell become really subdued in the taste . ( m ) - kinda lackluster in all categories besides smell .  appearence : poured a simple golden yellow without no head , smell : the smell is of grapes and some hints of spices .  this beer has noticeable viscosity and a big thick feel . minimal carbonation .

smell is really spicy and slightly malty .  it is cold and looks refreshing . the beer is a hazy gold pour with only a small white edge layer of head . hmm . was hoping for a little more froth . besides the lack of substantial head a good example of the style i think .  crisp , clean mouthfeel with flavors of dry , pale malt . at first , i found myself wanting more flavor , a la boston lager , but the mouthfeel and resulting drinkability really brought things back up for me in the end .

the taste though is a contradiction of the nose , as the brooding and seriously backward bitterness assault the mouth . this is a very weighted and saturated product that may be more of a showpiece of inventive beer making rather than a true beverage of pleasure .  pours a brown amber color with a fairly weak head and very few lacings but does keep a nice brown film on top .  m : pretty creamy and lightly carbonated . easy to swallow a mouthful .

appearance : dark brown , not ebony , slight retention , no lacing smell : some roasted and coffee aroma taste : flat , low on taste , just not much there .  pours a clear yellow with a light head on top .  m - lighter side of heavy , pretty smooth .

s - pretty good aroma . chocolate and coffee are both strong but not overpowering .  it was bottled in april 2010 , so i think i 'm good ... duped by the standard brown longneck bottle , i poured this into a standard american pint glass , and it appears a cloudy dark iced-tea colour , with a bit of swirling sediment , and a half finger of soapy pale beige head , which disappears quickly , leaving some sparse spidery lace around the glass .  m : medium in both body and carbonation .

yellow with full head , freshly aromatic of herbs , grass , and mint . unappealing .  a- clear yellow gold color with a small head that stick and laces .  light mouthfeel with a good amount of carbonation when you drink it .

smells of tons of citrus and pine , with a hint of kitchen cleaner and hardwood resin . very resinous taste win a lingering bitterness and faint light caramel .  brown bottle into a sam adams glass . the body was golden brown/amber with a pocked , off-white head .  m : light-bodied , crisp , very clean , refreshing .
the smell is good , and in fact is the strongest attribute in my opinion .  pours a clear , medium copper , very much like apple juice .  thick body is very good . it 's just passable for now .

pours clear yellow with a 2 inch cloudy white head ; smells of malt and yeast , with the malt odor dominating , but still very faint overall .  no problem though , taste is fine , colour is nice and although there is no head and very little in the way of lacings , the body is pretty nice .  mouthfeel : bitter . nice carbonation .

the smell was good and true to form : clear , crisp , and clean , plenty of wheat and yeast , nice and spicey , and cirtusy-sweet too .  the bottle looks very picturesque and i love it . it pours a cloudy , hazy wheaty yellow color with a tint or orange . only a half finger lace of head rises to the top . it doesnt have too much staying power and is gone within seconds .  i felt that the mouthfeel was the best part of this brew .

smells of citrus and ginger , very faint cloves & cinnamon there as well , very nice . the taste is very clean .  pours a clear light amber color with a thin white head that dissipates quickly with no lacing .  mouthfeel is good , soft and tingly .
smells of roasted hopps with mild hints of chocolate .  appearance was n't much . dark gold , big bubbles in the head , retained some , but not great lace .  mouthfeel - nice body , pretty crisp .

all things considered the aroma is pretty decent , but not outstanding .  appearance : lightly hazed pale golden straw . very volatile , fleeting white head .  it 's very creamy and goes down easy . i 'm really disappointed with this .

smells very nice , with strong citrus/lemon/fruitiness , and a good dose of floral .  7.5 % abv bottle into my slender & top heavy rare vos glass . big powdery head , though quite faint & not big on sticking around . body is a glittery caramel amber with lots of floaties .  mouthfeel was smooth , light , though i do n't know i 'd go as far as crisp .

the description lists this a russian imperial stout finished with 101 pounds of locally roasted coffee ... the beer pours dark brown with a light tan head , not much to look at ... the aroma is pretty nice roasted coffee dominates as you can imagine but this is fairly bounced some bitter chocolate and a little coffee ... the taste does n't translate the balance as it is totally dominated by the roasted coffee .  it is a dark brown color with a brown head .  i like the thick , syrupy mouthfeel as it 's quite comforting but the taste gets old fast and just is n't complex .

( s ) - a dry oaky profile with caramel and bourbon notes . ( t ) - nice vanilla notes with wet cardboard and sawdust aspects .  it is a medium brown brew with an ivory head .  medium bodied ; good amount of carbonation .

the smell was very promising with wonderful aromas of sweet , bready malt with banana , clove , and a banana bread finish .  slight amounts of sediment adds to the mild haziness . no lacing , and just about no head , but there is a slight cloud of head floating around . m- full and very smooth .  mouthfeel was really good for a light beer . liked the carbonation , and felt richer than it tasted .

super cru appears like it should , starting out with a leather-mahogany color , frothy head . does n't smell too bad either ; nice belgian yeasty notes and the added pear .  bottle poured into a tulip a : pours a translucent amber color with an eggshell hued , fizzy thin head . the fact that it 's considered an american amber is truly an insult . it has the appearance of an amber , but the aroma of a belgian and the flavor of a porter .  the body and carbonation levels are appropriate .

aroma- very hoppy and hints of sweet fruit taste a light citrus hop flavor , a little bitter as well , but in a refreshing way mouthfeel good carbonation , in fact maybe a bit too much .  a- pours and looks more like a porter than an imperial stout . dark see-through brown with a quickly fading tan head .  the mouthfeel is very nice , it 's very carbonated which works with the ginger presence , and the mouthfeel is at about a medium thickness .

smell is actually quite strong , a blast of medicinal malts , along with hops .  a & # 8211 ; it pours like a foamy glass of iced tea , with large soapy bubbles but not a huge head .  mouthfeel is heavier than i 'd anticipate . i wish i liked the flavor of this because its heaviness is spot on .

smells absolutely inviting . flavor falls woefully short of the aroma .  the aroma is mostly floral malty with some grassy hops and barely distinguishable yeast . taste is quite similar - soft and sweet maltiness in the beginning , maybe some caramel additionaly and nice bitter finish . pretty good beer , i will definitely buy some more of them  mouthfeel : light/medium with a tart , crisp finish drinkability : i really do n't crave another of these ; this certainly would n't be a lawnmower beer for me conclusion : just kind of unsorted ( also kind of an odd bitterness on the finish ) ... i tried this a year or two ago and was n't a huge fan ... now that i 'm reviewing it ... i 'm still not .

im disappointed by the lack of aroma .  whenever i drink magic hat # 9 i always have a happy buzz . it is great to get a fruit beer that tastes like beer and not so much a fruit stand in your mouth .  mouthfeel : full-bodied with a strong , expressive carbonation .
s : a very inviting sweet smell of hops and oranges .  this one pours a dark and murky , dirty gold in color .  the body was definitely heavy on this one . heavy for a dipa especially of this size .

the beer smells mostly of semi-sweet dark chocolate and is quite nice .  i 'm reviewing this one as i sit at the desk drinking it . i 'm weary of drinking something from a clear bottle , but i 'll get through it . the beer itself poured a rich mahogany or chestnut color . the head was fizzy and dissipated right after pouring . the initial flavor was a caramel nuttiness and molasses .  mouthfeel is of alcohol . the brew itself is medium-heavy bodied , with a very clean finish . this beer is clean as far as mouth feel goes , but is not as forgiving to the throat on the way down .

overall really nice aroma . first sip is a mix of caramel and toasted malts with a touch of fruitiness .  appearance - this is peculiarly shiny and clear , almost a bright orange , with little head .  good carbonation .

s - berry and more berry t - strong raspberry flavor , but very little beer flavor . it reminds me of ab wildblue m - thin and watery , nothing particularly special i 'm conflicted on many of my ratings for this beer because on the one hand , many of the attributes of this beer are on purpose ( like the pink color ) but at the same time , it 's not a beer i would pick up again .  2006 vintage . no head on the pour .  the mouthfeel is about right for a stout , a bit thick with low carbonation .

color seemed consistent with other ipa 's of the high alcohol content variety , and it had a pleasant , slightly fruity smell . regarding taste , you initially get hit with a flavorful mild fruit taste , but it fades into a musty bite that reminds me of the aftertaste of the awful four horsemen .  i was glad to see brew kettle still serving a pumpkin beer during my visit in late december ... seems like a lot of brewers plan to sell out of pumpkin beer by thanksgiving , and to me the flavor is appropriate through the new year . appearance-wise , it looked a great deal like the chief 's rye - not quite colorful enough in the amber body , and with a medium amount of head .  the mouthfeel is the most appealing part of this brew , unfortunately i just ca n't escape the sour flavour .

laces well throughout process s-smells like a coffee stout ( what a shocker ) . smell the roasted coffee up front with a slight chocolate malt i think t/m-eh , it does its job well , it tastes like it should .  somewhat murky , reddish and garnet in color . big hoppy and grassy aroma sort of `` locker room '' sweat which doesnt mean a bad thing . serious hop levels .  mouthfeel is light body , medium carbonation . fairly nice .

the aroma is very belgian with lots of sour fruit lacto , weaker raspberries and cherries , dusty basement .  12oz bottle into pint glass pours a deep gold color , one finger off-white head , with a decent amount of chunky particulates .  golden in color , slight haze ( nothing wrong with that ) , definite aromas of honey sweetness . lingering sweetness in the palate with a slight funk . interesting beer and something that one might only need to consume once .

s : lots of oak and bourbon . big bourbon smell really dominates . it 's followed nicely by a big chocolately middle , and a dry coffee finish .  poured and hazy copper/orange color with very little head .  velvety . good amount of carbonation .

usa says , `` batch # 56 '' this looked and smelled quite nicely , but everything else was rather ho-hum . the smell was nice , as well , consisting of caramel and roasted grains , but no really discernable , specific profile .  a : pours a light golden color with a big white head that does not quickly dissipate .  mouthfeel is nice and thick and well carbonated . the best part of the beer .

smell is very strong , like a clove-orange christmas pomander . really spicey and orange-peely , with coriander , grass and soap . if this thing tastes as good as it smells , i 'm gon na love it . the taste is dominated by the clove , soap and cookie-dough malt . it tastes good , but not as good or as complex as it smells . alcohol is notable from the warm burn in the aftertaste . all around , a very interesting beer .  upon pouring into my mirror mirror tulip , rock art 's golden tripple is a attractive hazy deep golden color , topped with a weak fine white head .  the mouth is thick and malty . as far as drinkability , i have to say that i would be really happy to have one of these if i was alive 4000 years ago but for now i 'm going to have to go for something else .

color is a brilliant ruby/amber with minimal haziness , smells of honeyed ginger and spice exactly as promised on the label , flavors of gingerbread and spiced christmas cookies come through cleanly just as promised by the nose , fresh , sharp , and clean flavors overall that really make me feel like the holidays ... if only there was carbonation , it could have been something stellar .  the beer poured a hazy burnished amber with next to nothing of a head .  m : medium-light body ; moderate carbonation ; smooth and clean mouthfeel .
smell is the best feature , chocolate chip cookies , booze and coffee.. it is flat .  nice gold ... almost no head .  meidum bodied and relatively smooth .

nose is dominated by whiskey . then there is some oak and toffee .  drink a few of these on a cold winter 's day and you 'll be feeling like you 're sitting by the fire ! very sweet , with lots of caramel . good stuff . gon na be buying this one a lot this winter .  mouthfeel is light and refreshing making the beer overall a decent session beer .

smell is malty and there are some woody hop essences . all the smells are present on the tongue too but when you compare this against a robert the bruce as an example , there is no comparison .  a ) amber in color , about 1/2 inch of head , which was gone before i could get my nose into the pint . no lacing . the smell is like pumpkin pie . in fact , i said to my wife , this smells like pumpkin pie .  smooth with a creamy but dry finish . i walked away thinking that the `` smoked vanilla , coffee , and birch '' was meant to be flavor descriptors rather than actual ingrediants . all of these elemtns were way too weak to be appreciated for what other beers can do with them . call it a single , nix the mention of the adjuncts , and this beer would be alright .

aromas are nice , sweet raspberry and syrup .  lovely little bottle , but i will say it looks much bigger in photographs . the head fades quickly and no head retention to be seen .  really nice body all around ... overall - i would really enjoy this beer if it were n't for the bubblegum flavor , it 's really off putting and not very pleasant .

sharp grapefruit-like hops aromas dominate , with only hints of grain in the background .  a- medium amber with a quarter inch white head that disappears very quickly , an inviting unfiltered cloud lingers as you continue to sip .  mouthfeel is fairly creamy , with a lighter , dry body .

looks like maple syrup i think . some grape , plums , burnt caremel perhaps . taste- not like the smell at all . sour at first .  deep gold/pale amber in colour . thin , foamy tan head fades to a respectable layer of foam . chill haze is very evident .  mouthfeel- medium mouthfeel ( for the style ) . carbonation level was perfect for bringing out the bittering hops .

smells rich and butterscotchy .  a - hazy , pale straw yellow color with less than a one finger white head . leaves little to no lacing . color is right on for a pilsener but the head/lacing is disappointing .  m & d : very good , sits well and fairly easy to drink once you get the first one down

s : smells tangy - slightly stings the nostrils , in a good way . ginger simple syrup , orange peel , graham cracker crust , peaches ? something a tad off lurks , almost like a liqueur . tastes like it was once great though .  i got a growler to go to assess . pour is a slightly hazy darker golden color . nice carbonation nose is alot of spice with a hint of citrus . i 'm a big dopplebock fan , but i liked this more than their dopplebock , it 's that good .  m - oily , medium body with a fantastic amount of carbonation .

the first smell was of licquorice , then coffee , then dark chocolate . the flavours in the taste followed very closely to the aromas , but a whole lot sweeter .  a : pours amberish color with little head s : piney and citrus hops with a touch of sweetness t : there 's a decent amount of bitterness from the hops but a good amount .  the feel was pleasantly smooth , but was unimpressed with the drinkability as seemed to reform a head with every drink .

while i am a huge barleywine fan , i just do not like this beer at all . smell is that of apricot an fruit .  minor head retained nicely , decent lacing .  the flavor that by far took the lead was chocolate ! there 's an overpowering ( and for me , disappointing ) chocolate aftertaste in this beer . mouthfeel- smooth , no complaints here . drinkability- well , the bottle looks cool as you drink from it !

pleasant citrus aroma , but also a pronounced herbal presence , which was a little bit jarring .  pours a hazy amber with fine carbonation ; not much of a head .  taste : slick and creamy mouth feel with a sharp biting carbonation , malt sweetness almost goes over the top .

this is a beer that , while not having a particularly outstanding taste , does offer a unique , fruity smell . i consider it a light tasting beer with the same alcohol content as a regular lager .  minimal head , that quickly dissipates . decent lacing .  mouthfeel is medium-light bodied , a nice creaminess to the carbonation .

s - smells actually quite nice , a toasty bready malt , chocolate , and some curry power .  a - completely opaque black , lets no light through . head is a very light brown that settles at a film . lacing is average .  m : creamy and nice . decent carbonation keeps it from sticking to you .

the aroma instantly improved my mood . wonderful complexity . dark fruit , alcohol , plum , rich malts , yeast , a little tawny port , some light diacetyl , and little bit of cola . again , nice nose , but overall this was a huge disappointment .  a - poured out a clear , orange color with golden highlights . it had a very small , white head of bubbly foam .  feel is good - light , crisp , medium bodied .

smells surprisingly good . the berry aroma really stands out here and is not what i would call subtle like the label implies . i was really pleased with the aroma , but this is just way too much .  a thin white head disappears before you can say royersford pennsylvania . lacing was good for the style .  has a nice medium to full body with light carbonation .

i 'll disagree with the majority of reviewers and say it actually smelled pretty nice .  since i have said it for all of the other beers i 've reviewed in this category , i will say it for this one as well : pours a clear , piss-yellow color with a small white head . head disappears quickly and leaves no lacing whatsoever . it 's my first asian beer , but when comparing with any of the american and mexican macros and even a lot of the europeans , this is top class .  but it does n't make me puke ( and it tastes better than bmc by a sconch ) mouthfeel is nice . kinda creamy mixed with crisp .

smell is nice , slightly sweet malt . right on par .  has an okay color , but is not cloudy enough . i was hoping for something close to opaque , but it is just mildly cloudy . i 'd buy a sixer of this over a lot of sa 's beers , and it 's easily the best thing in the harvest pack ( even if the mediocre appearance is going to knock the score down a bit ) .  m : medium body and very good amount of carbonation in my opinion .

poured from a real 16 ounce bottle , perfect pint ! aroma is pretty lacking as for the hops , i pick up faint pine , but its a dissapointment for aroma off a double ipa .  pours a transparent , clean looking amber with no head , even after an aggressive pour .  mouthfeel is light bodied with good carbonation .

aromas are surprisingly floral , nectar-like , and a bit perfumy from the boquet of aromatic hops . these compliment the softer pilsner malt aromas and mask the grainy-sharp sensation in the nose that usually accompany pilsner grains .  appearance : crystal clear pale straw color with thin bone-white head .  full bodied with a smoothy , creamy mouthfeel .

smell : sweet , nutty , roasted malts and some vanilla with a fruity hop aroma .  a fizzy white head forms on top and quickly dissolves back to the beer leaving only a few spots of lace on the glass . floating above the beer is a strong aroma of honey , ginger , and white grapes .  m : a nice , medium body .
the smell was good .  appears clear copper with small wispy head .  m- really good carbonation , low abv and the nearly great sweet/tart balance make it actually react quite nicely with the mouth .

aroma was appropriate for the style - hoppy , not much malt .  this brew arrived at my table essentially headless . lacing was very sparse .  mouthfeel is medium , carbonation average-high with some pleasant warming feel .
i get a nice dose of floral and citrus hops .  got ta love the english pint bottle , looks regal imo .  m - good . a little sticky .

the aroma is almost non-existent ; i could not pick up any distinct flavors in the nose at all . the taste , however , is sweet at the front of the tongue with hints of very floral hops ( almost flowery ) with a lingering bitterness at the back of the throat to remind you that this beer is an ipa .  750 ml bottle , a : pours a dark amber with a soft white head , average retention , no lace .  mouthfeel : nice feeling on the tongue and also a good consistencty .

i was expecting this ... s- very oaky smelling with a copious amount of bourbon presence t- bourbon is overwhelming vs the sweet malts of the flat beer .  appearance : pours a crystal clear golden color . i notice lots of suspeneded sediment in my glass .  the mouthfeel is fine . it is a low/medium bodied beer with good carbonation .

aroma is cloves , bananas , grainy malt and a bit of bubblegum . mouthfeel/body is light/medium , it 's very spritzy and has way too much carbonation .  a : pitch black with a one-finger head . poor head retention and no lacing . it looks like others have had a better looking pour ... perhaps i have this beer a little too much tlc .  m - good mouth feel . somewhat unique in feel .

woody roast malt aroma with wet earth , chocolate and other goodies .  i poured it into a glass and it had a small white head that disappered quick . it poured a very light golden color . while the beer was sitting on the table i looked down at it , the bottom of the glass was almost clear as water . it was n't intense .  mouthfeel is spot on for the style , light and crisp and a bit dry .

the aroma is a let down , though , as there is barely anything perceptible ( although that also means there is nothing unpleasant in the aroma either ) . as a result , this beer is an improvement over many of the other options available at most mexican eateries , but it still did a fine job cutting through the savory spice of the food .  had this at mcnellies in tulsa pours a semi-hazed amber with a finger of cream colored head . some head retention & lacing , lacing held up pretty good s : apple peels , breadyness , & orchard fruit t : apple peels , breadyness & booze presence up front , plus a touch of lemon hops .  m - pretty good .

aroma is a decadent mocha and milk chocolate , but the taste does n't quite live up to it .  a-pours a mostly clear yellow-gold w/just a touch of haze . white head with average retention .  the mouth is smooth and light .

this beer smells incredible . a strong aroma of hops and malts immediately made itself known as soon as the bottle was cracked . excellent lacing .  pours a pale golden , with not much of a head . it quickly dissipates , leaving basically nothing in terms of lacing .  m : medium-bodied with low and sightly creamy carbonation . there is a slight sticky feel and syrupy feel .

4.0 s : surprisingly grainy , which i like . roastiness , some toffee , and a touch of coffee . fairly simple , but pleasant nonetheless .  pours a very effervescent amber with 3+ fingers of rocky tan head . average lacing & head retention s : herbal hops , breadyness , a slight nuttyness .  decent carbonation , neither too intrusive nor too laid back .

the smell was nice . tobacco , chocolate , caramel , molasses , dried plums , brown sugar , and a hint of soy sauce .  like most traditional gueuze and like most drie fonteinen , this is pretty damn good stuff but compared to drie fonteinens 50th anniversary gueuze , which was consumed earlier in the day , it was clearly obvious that this was the lesser of the two . hazy nectarine . a good gueuze .  crisp , good body overall .

smells great with a nice faint aroma of hazelnuts .  bruges glass , unknown freshness , $ 2.75/bottle nh pour-light fizzy head that pours large but recedes very quickly to barely a ring of bubbles , red-orange light brown , mostly clear , essentially no lacing .  smooth in the mouth with nice , crisp carbonation . nice feel , but flavor is not there .

this one was aged in jd barrels and there is a definite whiskey note on the nose . quite a bit of oak and vanilla .  i was surprised when the beer poured a clear gold .  m- decent carbonation , light and airy .

s- it had a really nice aroma . it was big in both sweet-bread malt and pine-citrus hop scents .  pours a dark reddish-brown colour . the head very quickly disappears and very little lacing .  the mouthfeel is very smooth , with fine/sharp bubbles .

has an interesting unique look , very cloudy with a hint of ruby color , alot like cranberry juice ( duh ) smell is good , has a classic belgian wit aroma , spicy yeast dominates taste is ok , easy to drink , but the fruit really ruins the beer in imo just an unnecessary addition  nice oily sheen to this , along with some head retention & lacing s : chocolate , dark fruit , & some oakyness t : dark chocolate , oaky , a bit of iron & much dark fruit up front .  mouthfeel is quite decent .

smell : sweet roasted malt , vanilla and french oak .  pours a nice golden/dark straw color , with no head and almost no lacing ; a bit of carbonation and it appears to be filtered .  hoping it 's one of those better in a bottle beers i 'm returning to give it another try . so far so good . maybe , and i 'm stretching , some neutral hop spice . this beer makes me try too hard . these hops should be hops should be ashamed of themselves . good malt base to support hops , were they present . bottle is equally bland as on tap .

smell is sweet molases , carmel , and the like . the taste is ... meh .  poured a dark orange . the head was nice at first . then it turned minute and the lace ( everything ) was eliminated .  m : medium body and moderate carbonation .

yes the smell in particular is very banana bread , the flavor less so , plus there 's a nutty bitterness which a bit overwhelms the banana .  the beer is n't as hazy or cloudy as i remember , which is too bad .  mouthfeel is smooth , for sure , with mellowed out carbonation and a surprising absence of slickness , considering the alcohol .

the aroma was very sweet and promising with caramel malts being the forerunner .  hmm organic and spelt so this is a no wheat wit . very pale with a light fluffy head and lots of carbonation going on . a touch of lace but not much . notes of lemon and wheat like twang . excellent thirst quencher and it goes down like your favorite cold soda on a 100 degree day .  decently carbonated mouthfeel , and medium-bodied .

fresh grassy hop aromas with a lemony type backbone and biscuity malt presence .  750ml into a tulip . pours a dull dark dirty dishwater amber , minor mocha colored head subsided fairly quickly , minor lacing .  full bodied , moderate carbonation .

no lacing , but this beer is blacker than the ace of spades . a good strong burgundy wine . then when you raise the glass the fruitiness gives way to a sharp alcohholic smell , sherry , molases , and soy sauce ... somewhat remniscent of the polish porters i have had .  i was unaware this was an unfiltered beer , so i got lots of yeasties in the beer which made it cloudy and sort of foreign looking . i dont really mind it , but it doesnt look good and could serve as a detractor for some . nice white head and some decent lacing .  surprisingly , the sediment was n't hard and i did n't feel a corporeal presence in my mouth . coopers best extra stout was nice on the palate ; softly carbonated and creamy . to tell you the truth , i was a bit disappointed .

s : raisin , fig , brown sugar , classic `` american '' quad . nice smelling beer . t : big brown sugar , dark fruit , some molasses , very similar to the nose , though the agave comes out a lot more than in the smell .  pours a bright clear straw-yellow color with a good inch of soft whitish head .  the mouthfeel is medium to full bodied with smooth carbonation .
there isnt much of a smell at all .  pours a fairly clear dark straw with just a wisp of white head .  m : very fizzy , light on body , about right for the style .

s - cherries , duh ? but what smelled like very sweet cherries .  a - a pale gold color with a very small head that dissipates quickly and leaves no lacing .  orange , darkish color , looks a lot like the two previous hop project beers i had . the flavor also left a lot to be desired . the last hop project beers i had were both quite intriguing and sadly this was just boring as far as the hops were concerned . oh , well , hopefully i get to try more of this crazy series .
the smell included subtle notes of nutmeg/pumpkin .  it is the cheap drunk heaven send of beer .  m - good mouthfeel . a little heavier thanks to the lack of filtration .

restrained aroma of toasted coconut and rich cocoa .  i good beer for a good price , and with the exception of a few flaws , a fine example of a dopple bock . poured into a pilsner glass the beer produces no head , no carbonation to speak of , and no lacing .  this is a medium bodied , well carbonated beer .

good rich smell , malts and something unidentifiable .  poured into a pint glass ok was a little taken by the appearnce , its a chocolate ale and its dark amber with a fizzy head like a soda , about 1 finger high and disapates much like a soda as well smells of wheat and sweet chocolate notes with some semi-sweet malt , almost candy sweetness .  mouthfeel is full with tiny carbonation and a faint alcohol burn as you swallow .

a : pours a hazy orange color , good sized head with nice lacing down the glass s : smell is of sweet ripe citrus fruits .  appearance : kind of a pale yellow to cold and a little cloudy . thick white cloudlike head made of small bubbles ... some lacing , but poor retention ... just disappears on me smell : banana or wet bread like smell .  the mouthfeel is slightly creamy and very enjoyable . this drinks nicely . there is a lot going for this though , the mouthfeel in particular .

it smells fruity and hoppy , but the flavor seemed to be actually sweet with a tad bit of hops .  this beer was watery and did not have much taste to it in my opinion . the hue of this beer was yellow .  mouthfeel is pretty good .
