the aroma is of cocoa and grapefruit , orange and floral notes .  12 oz bottle poured into a pint glass a- cloudy dirty brown color s- faint sweetness , i assume is supposed to be cherry t- very weak ( if any ) cherry flavor , like a severely water down juice m- very little carbonation , feels like a soda that went flat d- fortanetly , i got this with a mix and match .  this brew reminds me very much of delirium , and is still a taste that i can not seem to thoroughly enjoy . very malty , and the alcohol is quite present with some mild chocolate and serious bitterness . very strong warming effect as well , which is enjoyable and will be one of the few things that helps me finish this brew off . as far as my beer palate is concerned , this type of ale is one of the few obstacles i have left to conquer .

a : pours a slightly cloudy light brown , no head to speak of , appears rather lifeless in the glass s : nose features healthy dose of roasted malts , mild caramel notes , no hops t : taste is nothing like the nose promised , very thin and watery up front , muted ashy malts , bad balance , not quite as enjoyable as i had hoped mf : very light body , mild carbonation o : the nose is quite nice with this brew , but that 's where it ends .  live review a- clear straw yellow . very cabonated , foams up big but dissaptes fast to have no head whatsoever s- strong scent , sweet , malty t- clean taste , sweet malts , grassy , surpisingly a yeasty afternote m- watery and very light d- not the tastest of beers , but one that can lead to very adventrous nights  m- good mouthfeel , just the right carbonation .

i wish hotd would start holding onto their bottles to give then a chance to carb up , if i was brewing , i wouldnt want to send out uncarbed bottles . the flavors are very interesting , the cherry does come through rather prominantly and has a large amount of sweetness behind it , and i think this is why the alcohol is hidden rather well , it is detectable only in some flavors and not so much in heat . the barrels come through with some oak too much not substantially so . there are alot of comparisons to a wine i could make with this actually , but i am not tomme . think of brandy angles share and decide .  has a very pale yellow color with a 1/2 inch head .  mouthfeel - some good body , oily smoothness per the style . carbonation is moderate .

aroma was very pleasant , with yeast/bread , melon , a light orange , honey and some spice .  a - nothing special . pale straw colour . looks like a typical pale lager : canadian , budweiser , etc .  long , earthy , dry finish . interesting , somewhat unusual brew .

the aroma seems to be pretty good , nice strong malt scent that gives off the idea of caramel also giving a sweet smell .  have n't seen the light version of pbr around to often but it showed up at a party i was at . tastes very similar to pbr regular , which is good because i find that better than the usual bud/coors/miller . it 's easy to drink , cheap , and not awful tasting.. what else can you want when its $ 12 a 30 ?  i 'm thinking of a breakfast bed . the beer was thick and the foam was velvety . the drinkitbility was okay for its thickness . however , the taste was terrible . a quick slam of semi-sweet citrus that is too heavy on the lemon . the beer ends with an unbalanced bitterness for more than half of the drink .

strong coffee aroma has me salivating , it is mixed with a lighter chocolate aroma , this beer smells rich with hints of bourbony alcohol . the taste is where i was thrown , there is an extremely lemony tartness in the flavor which may be fine in another style , but not what i was expecting here , especially after the inviting aromas . i 'm not sure if the tartness is a result of roasting the malts and the tangy acidity that follows or something else , but it masked most of the flavors and was very prevalent .  pale yellow with almost no head at all .  m - effervescent with a full body and a very yeasty finish .

the aroma is good . it has a solid malt bill of pale and carapils malts ; even some light crystal/bisquit as well .  poured into a pint glass it looks about the same as coors light , except slightly cloudy ( and i mean ever so slightly ) . the head is almost non-existant and fades leaving zero lacing in my glass .  m- mouthfeel is nice . medium body with a good amount of carbonation .

the aroma is pretty nice , and only improved as the beer and glass warmed . very piney and grassy , with a good citrus kick underneath . smells very clean , fresh .  looked like a bottle of budweiser when poured . no head to speak of , minimal lacing , some fizz .  mouth feel is completely crisp , refreshing , and clean .

smell is fruity with a nice yeast kick at the end .  poured a smallish head with no retention . color was a pale yet golden sunshine color . the lacing was defiently subpar with any average wheat beer .  body is right- light , lively carbonation , not cloying or excessively dry .

smells `` fresh '' , and lightly hoppy .  simply put , i 'm stunned that i got nothing ! zero head on this . the body is a hazy straw color that just looks dull and mucky .  the mouth feel was very nice however i really struggled to drink the whole bottle .

aroma was my favorite part of the brew . mostly sweet malt balanced with toasty grains , with just a hint of grass and spice . flavor was balanced roastiness , a little malt sweetness and appropriate bitterness - a nice stab at style .  appearance - for a `` strawberry blonde '' it poured pretty pale ... smell - smelled alright .  body was medium , and the liquid was fairly smooth overall . 3.03 rdev -19.5 % look : 3.5 | smell : 3 | taste : 3 | feel : 4 | overall : 2.5 1366

the nose delivers good fruity smells . banana and cloves are evident , but subdued .  the beer is a hazy deep golden color . pours a medium head with no retention .  soft prickly carbonation does cleans the pallet , of this light to medium body beer with moderate astringency and warming alcohol .
the aroma was pleasant , light and floral .  a - clear and very pale yellow .  mouthfeel is pretty good , it has a nice full body , and a good finish .
smell is pleasantly malty and sweet .  the beer poured a very pale yellow with a small white head .  good carbonation .

very malted , to hide the spices ? very corriander , hoppy , and yeast with a bananna aroma and taste , and all of this adding to mouthfeel .  pours a small amount of bubbles on the surface . not carbonation foam , bubbles like you could get from water . smells carry brandy and bourbon ( my wife says it smells metallic ) .  honestly as this has warmed it has become slightly undrinkable due to the sweetness m - medium bodied with a a good amount of carbonation . a slightly sticky mouthfeel as well .

s : strong notes of malt and caramel , sugary smell .  appearance : pours a light-golden yellow hue , with a half-finger head that quickly dissipates into nothingness . not impressed . while this beer pours out looking horrible , and smelling average , the taste and overall refreshment factor makes it a very nice beer .  taste/mouthfeel : mostly hops . heavily malted finish . drinkability : a bit heavy and not quite as good as other european lagers . overall : probably the best gateway to this style .

s : dominated by citrus , get a lot of tangerine , citrus , pineapple , and an earthy belgian yeast kick , light pepper .  pours a medium off colored copper , with very thin head and lacing . very low carbonation level .  the aroma contained notes of malt , hops and a discernable alcohol content of medium strength . it had a stong alcohol flavor that was very over powering the other flavors . it was smooth yet burned as it went down . truely a devilish brew !

nose is delicate like a bouquet of spring flowers , freesia and tea rose .  served on-tap in a 16oz pint glass appearance : bright yellow with thin head and minimal lacing ; i can read the paper through it smell : straight grain taste : grainy , corn flavor that is full for a light lager mouthfeel : relatively smooth and crisp that could quench after mowing the lawn on a hot day drinkability : good social beer that can definitely be repeated , but is n't the extra 5 bucks worth it ?  the mouthfeel is the pinnacle of this brew . full-bodied with a dry crisp feel .

piny , a bit fruity , very pungent .  a - pours a crystal clear honey hue with a fizzy light head that fades quickly to leave no retention and lacing .  a bitter spicy bite from the hops hit first . the light body and good crispness contrast the flavor pretty well .

s : cocoa at first , some coffee , diarrhea ( off putting to say the least ) , chalk dust .  it came served flat with no head or lace in a shade of yellow-gray .  mouthfeel - it does have a pleasant rich/buttery mouthfeel .

i smell sugar and berries , maybe some banana and a hint of wheat .  decent for a macro . kinda dark for a fizzy yellow american lager . taste is clean with noticable corn adjunct .  this beer tastes like sheep shit . this may appeal to some people , but it 's definitely a very unusual belgian ale . i enjoyed drinking half of this beer for the experience . it 's so pungent i laughed out loud . it 's always fun to be exposed to a radically different flavor profile than you 're used to .

the smell is fresh , bitter and hoppy with some notes of apricots , pineapples and a hint of tobacco .  poured very little head , less than 1/2 inch that disappeared almost instantly and left no lacing . taste was very watered down , similar to most american light beers but slightly better .  the mouthfeel is pretty good its not watery at all like you get with some lagers .

s - a little barley and some tangy fruits like orange/pear/apricot t - starts off with that specific fruity flavor that came from the nose and leads into a good amount of alcohol and finishes with a sweetness and very little hops .  poured a slightly cloudy golden color with almost no head or lacing .  mouthfeel is good - medium-bodied , good carbonation , smooth .

smell is impressive relative to low expectations - i 'm skeptical of hop-forward beers that are n't locally made and consumed fresh , but this one still has a resiny punch in spite of it 's journey from scandinavia , with a little oxidized biscuit malt as well .  pours a very light and clear stale orange color with lots of carbonation and no head .  m - the brew is wet at the lips but finishes quite dry . impressive . ~ unfortunately i 'm going to struggle finishing this because of the flavor .

o : the beer smells great , but pales in other categories , especially taste , which is a terrible place to have the weakest link .  amber , reddy/orange in colour , clear but no head , not even a collar . looked like a glass of fizzy pop . too sweet and the lack of a head , un-beery look along with its fruity smell does n't do it any favours and the 11 % just masks its shortcomings .  nice crisp carbonation to keep it refreshing .
smell is really good . very sweet and carmelly with some spices in there .  very light yellow with no head to speak of- apple juice .  mf : smooth and wet . complements the flavours of the body .

smell is of apricots and other dried fruit , not a strong scent but definately a scent . mouth is light and crisp but a surprising bitterness to it which is enjoyable . taste is a bit grassy and still some apricot to it but not much .  looks like white grape juice . i hate it when no head is erected .  m - full bodied , medium carbonation , really smooth . seems appropriate .

well balanced aroma . t/m - medium bodied , plenty of carbonation .  the head is initially one finger before settling down to a thin cap and a fatter collar . no real lace or anything . sort of bland looking .  m - good carbonation and a nice balance .

the smell reminds me of peaches in a can with syrup and is slightly interesting . the taste is oily hops on top of a decent amount of malts but is just not very good .  a : it pours pitch black with no head whatsoever . it looks like a flat coke .  lovely thick aromas of blackstrap molasses , dark bitter chocolate , strong coffee and deep roasted malts ... awesome aromas to this one ... lazy and flat tasting ... strange bitter almost sour taste present ... . not much in common with the aromas ... thick oily mouthfeel is great but i ca n't get by the taste of this one ... drain poured this one ... maybe a bad bottle but as is , a big disappointment ...

a- 3 very light blonde color reminiscent of a cider , with a minimal white head which dissipates to practically nothing quickly . s- 4 the aroma of this is more like white grapes to me , similar to a wine , but the peach is definitely there in the background . it smells as if it will be refreshing ... t- 3 it is hard for me to get past the tartness of this brew .  it looked like coke .  mouthfeel : good .

s : lots of sweet dark fruit , candi sugar , and some sweet lighter fruits as well . t : prunes , figs , candi sugar , cinammon , and a little lurking booziness .  pours a very dark brown that is pretty thin and has a reddish hue when held to the light . head is very thin and disappears rapidly and leaves no head and no lacing .  2.5 t & m : mouthfeel is fairly viscous and silky .

quite pleasant on the nose without being much on the side of complex .  coppery color , with a pinky 's head that dissolved in 15 seconds and no lacing . disappointing appearance .  after smelling , i picked up on a semi-complex mix of belgium candy , malts , cherries and alcohol . it sat heavy on me and did not taste refreshing to me . i enjoyed this beer and can tell there was definitely quality & craftsmanship involved in it 's making ; but it 's not the best tripel i have ever had .
the smells consists of sweet malt with hints of roastiness and dark fruit .  pours a dark brown with almost no head .  the mouthfeel was full and sweet .

aroma is quite citrusy with plenty of zesty grapefruit and a hint of pine . it also has a tiny bit of tropical character and some sweet non-descript malt . this beer smells very nice and has a nice hop flavor , but it seems a bit out of whack . much better than the dreadful ipa my friend ordered , but overall a pretty forgettable beer .  a - does n't look very good . completely clear , extremely light body with a finger or two of poofy white head , basically no lace . looks like a bmc adjunct lager , honestly .  the mouthfeel is decently crisp while not out-of-control with carbonation .

smell is sweet and chocolatey , nice java presence .  dogfish head is really pushing it these days . they seem to be doing the avery thing ... trying to make one beer in every concievable style that will make people say , '' you ca n't even taste the alcohol ! it gets me drunk and it tastes like fruit ! what the hell ? it pours out the color of a cran-apple fruitopia . smells like berris and cheap nikolai vodka out of a plastic bottle . drinkable , sure , if you just want tog et drunk , but this is nothing special , and it is way overpriced .  the aftertaste lingers nicely , and the mouthfeel is firm . full bodied and smooth , but lacking an extra punch .

a : pours dark brown with purple hue , has a cloudy appearance ... similar to dark chocolate milk . s : nose features rich roasted malta along with candied red grapes .  semi-cloudy caramel , forming a small white head with no retention or lacing .  reminds me of a lager ... mouthfeel is nice and crisp which aids drinkability . everything about this tells me this is a lager . it 's a good thirst-quencher .

aroma is very nice , surprisingly fruity , almost like a belgian pale .  2002 this is one ugly beer . its a decent color , dark red brownish hue , but so freakin ' murky and flat . it looks like it could be the dregs from my garbage disposal .  the carbonation is considerable , quickening the mouth , and the hops are noticeable , but not significant .

overly sweet at times , but still nice . if it was n't for the mild astringent smell i 'd give it a 5 .  poured into a pint glass from the freezer , it had a sizeable head , which quickly calmed down to almost nothing . after looking at the color , noticed that the can said `` caramel coloring added , '' so nothing real to go by there . i pick up the regular if it 's on special , but for a real bitter , this ai n't it .  m : full body with mild carbonation ; slightly clinging .

nose smells like yummy cherries , the kind of nose you get from a cherry infused cider .  high clarity gold , very few bubbles and absolutely no head . there was a carpet of little co2 bubbles stuck to the bottom , but the beer itself felt flat .  big body , low carbonation .

smells fig , chocolate pudding , pears , brown sugar , candi-sugar , floral , clean alcohol , and a waft of spicy zip . nice candi-sugar adds depth , as does a spicy belgian yeast zip .  ) its appearance is typical of a lager , especially in the style of major domestic lagers such as budweiser , etc . it was yellow and fizzy . the smell reminded me of the corn that was in it , very mediocre . i drank it quickly , wanting nothing more then to get it out of the glass so i could poor a sweetwater ipa .  m - thick , syrupy , smooth , a bit refreshing .

the aroma is wonderful . it is dark and roasty , yet with a sweet chocolaty undertone , along with a slight hint of anise . the alcohol is n't quite as well masked as the aroma indicated , and there is some decent hop bitterness throughout .  review based on notes poured caramel with 2 fingers of tan head . zero head retention & lacing s : much bourbon , fruittyness & then leafy hops as this warms t : sour mash , toffee & a bit of vanilla up front .  the mouthfeel is nicely carbonated and almost creamy .

s : aromas of piney hops , almost like an ipa .  pours a hazy brown/black with a very quickly disappearing head .  mouthfeel is good bordering on to thick .

aroma is hard to detect , very mild malt/hops and paper .  pours a brown + red beer with minimal viscosity and head to it . carbonation appeared to be lacking at this point .  mouthfeel is good , slightly thick .

a-black , thin light tan head s-surprisingly i 'm not picking up not much more than a light hint of sweet potato , and possibly some cream . very very unique for stout t-i 'm getting some coffee notes with a sweet potato after-taste but more than anything this beer is just watery . it is absolutely a terrible stout .  soda pop head that dies to nearly no bubbles . very thin and spotty lace that does not last .  mouthfeel is decent medium bodied and goes down smooth .

the best way for me to try and describe this beer is if you would take a blueberry muffin , ferment it , and then bottle it .  *did not mind would not buy* app : kinda bland and yucky colored yellow , white head that was here and then suds .  we 're okay though , as next time we get a samuel adams winter sampler pack , i 'll give her my cranberry , and i 'll have her boston lager . it 's not a bad beer , it 's just not to my liking . i ca n't even really say why . a bit sweeter than i 'd like , and just nothing that stands out and says `` i 'm great '' .

looked nice and had a nice aroma to it , but i just never got into it .  pours a really pale piss yellow .  the feel was light , clean and crisp . damn , and after smelling this hefe , it had so much promise .

taste s not as rich as the aroma , but still excellent . slightly warming alcohol if felt but not tasted .  pours a very pale , slightly golden color , with a head that shows minimal retention .  it had a smooth mouthfeel with a little carbonation .

good ! taste is similar to smell but a bit strong for my tastes .  | 3.9 % abv | 2010 brewer : kiuchi brewery style : milk / sweet stout glass : pint appearance : dark cola brown with virtually no head or lacing .  body is pleasantly creamy , almost akin to that of an esb or pub ale .

the smell was firm and earthy ; wet straw , burnt malt and tomato paste fragrances mingled together .  appearence ... slight haze ( no big deal ) but the color is way off . looks like an amber .  first off , i can tell that this one is slightly skunked , but i ca n't really blame the brewer for this one as i am also able to pull out some nice mellow caramel malts and a touch of biscuity-bready goodness as well . nice mellow malts , not too sweet , but the hops come through for a bit too much bite from what i look for and love about english pales . the hops come on a little too strong and linger too long , not really allowing me the chance to savour the mellow malts as much as i would like . there is a slight sweetness about it that reminds me of fresh apples although not the biting green apple off taste . this is different , and nice , but not my first choice for an english pale .

s : has a sweet smell of caramel .  this beer has the typical huber metallic , sulfury , antiseptic taste . a high amount of carbonation that quickly fades and no head develops when poured .  the mouthfeel is good - smooth with a right amount of carbonation .

very earthy aroma with a strong pine needle character along with some floral and citrus hop notes . strong tongue-coating pine flavor that overpowers the other notes that te nose hinted at .  this is an awesome , cheap , f**k you up-type beer . yellow , smells like alcohol and corn . sometimes you just want a crappy beer , and this is it .  m : very nicely carbonated for this type of beer .

a very simple aroma , all in all , that strikes me as unimposing . flavor does n't even do as well as smell unfortunately ... roasted barley mirrors in the flavor but then comes a touch of tannin astringency that grows .  a - poured a blackish red colour with no head but a ring around the top , leaving no lacing .  '' the mouthfeel is good . its quite smooth and slightly creamy .

smells of very sweet caramel malts , black licorice , taffy and pine .  white almost non-existent head pale straw , clear body .  body and mouthfeel is more or less where it should be for the style , with a heavy weight and restrained carbonation .

once the cork came out on this one it shot foam everywhere , had to have a glass handy to start pouring . smelled very fruite , a lot of raspberry and a little bit of sourness .  hazy dirty looking copper tone . overall , kind of a dirty looking beer . not good for a pilsner .  m : very viscous , pretty smooth .

nice bitter chocolate and roast malt aroma , some earthy hop spiciness taste was black and roasted malt with loads of caramel to smooth a touch of pnw hops for balance but somewhat soapy in the swallow ?  this beer reminded me of a red bud light without hops not very good . poured it into a glass and the head was great ... for 10 seconds then there was no head at all .  very thick and coating , with very little carbonation .

a - clear yellowish orange , very thin head that dissapates almost immediately s - lots of bright apple and spice , by far the best facet of this one . t - not really sweet , but possessing a lot of apple and spice . not very endearing . d - very drinkable , if not the the disappointing taste .  appearance : light amber ... similar to an american lager but with more carbonation smell : like a cross between a budweiser and heineken .  medium bodied with lively fine carbonation .

nice chocolate and coffee in the nose , surprisingly good when compared to the last pioneer brew i had .  pours golden yellow with one finger white head when poured aggressively that subsides to none almost instantly .  the mouthfeel is surprisingly creamy and not too heavy . the drinkablity is pretty low , not from the booze , but extreme bitterness , which overwhelms the decent , but not exceptional malt .

aroma is good - coriander , peaches , a bit of pipe smoke - but a bit harsh .  a- golden yellow little no white lace / head s- a slight skunky smell to it light hop odor t- tasted like your average heineken , nothing to really stand out m- went down smooth , slight aftertaste the beer skunk after taste very thin d- not bad would have been better on a hot day , not one i would run out and get again but might have it if i were out for italian .  char davies , the artist in 1998 , made a fully interactive immersive visual/aural virtual artwork called ephemere , which furthers the work begun in osmose started in 1995 and displayed in the national gallery of canada in ottawa on june 26 , 1998. who cares ? this beer is almost close to a champaign ( and i would think that the yeast probably is champaign ) . also there is bitterness , which is nice to know that at least there are some hops to the so called beer . it is not advisable to use apples with fermenting , as the yeast creates funky flavors from apples , but this is much better than expected . although i would not want to drink this beer on a regular bases , thus low score on drinkability , i think it has a great taste like a grandsmith apples i use to eat as a kid .

it has a metallic aroma with a soft sweetness and a toasted note and ... something medicinal . there 's nothing stand-out here but it 's very drinkable .  this looks very strange when poured : it looks like small ice crystals in the liquid floating around for a short while ( the beer is chilled to round 6 c/42 f ) .  m- medium in body and good carbonation .

aromas of black current , butter , black coffee , some malted milk and alcohol.first thing i notice about this beer is the fact that it is a bit too carbonated for the style . there are way better brews out there .  a : pours a dark honey amber with a touch of fizzy head that quickly vanished into nothing . no head , no lace .  m- a good body to it . good weight and smooth carbonation . there is a strange foamy texture in the finish though .

s : sugary citrus smell . fruity smell overall . hops give it a slight floral smell .  this poured a standard macro lager yellow with a boring head that quickly dissipated .  very tame malt , very little hops , and weak alcohol that 's more like aftershave . definitely not over-carbonated , the texture fits the style . actually the best element of this beer .

highly aromatic nose of fruity , herbal resiny hops .  very pale straw gold in colour . thin head does n't stick around for very long , and does n't lace .  the body is somewhere between medium and full , with a creamy mouthfeel .

disappointed , as i am an avid stone fan and this being my first opportunity with the levitation ale . while the prose was sweet as ever , the brew itself was exceedingly oppressive , strongly hopped -- i would hands down prefer ruination to levitation when it comes to high hops from stone .  pours a crystal clear pale yellow . fluffy head fades fast ; no lace sticks . looks like a pilsner .  m : good , not too thin or thick .

smelled pleasant . fruity with nice hop smell .  i 'll tell ya in college , if your drinking bud light that is a good night . it looks like your typical goldish yellow and smells like . . . well like bud light , im sure if your reading this you have had it so there isnt much to compare it to .  the mouthfeel at the start was mildly crisp and finished dry and smooth . the unbalanced flavors knock down the drinkability for me .

nice and warming . slight roasted malt flavor to it as well , but overall pretty sweet aroma .  murky cola brown body with an exceedingly brief wisp of bubbles and a short-lived ring of bubbles providing the only signs of life . not too impressive looking , but things get better soon enough .  no complaints as the the mouthfeel , medium bodied with a pretty sharp carbonation .

very sweet and strong . this is definitely this brew 's biggest flaw , a total nose dive halfway through the palate that leaves me less than tempted for another swig .  hazy golden color with no head and no lacing . it is not completely flat but nothing formed during the pour .  medium mouthfeel .

uh huh , this smells like a chocolate stout . another one of trader joe 's deals here . aroma is better than flavor .  a : pale straw color , looks like a macro . the carbonation looks weak but feels good on the tongue .  the mouthfeel was decent , medium with adequate carbonation .

smell is rich caramel and roasted maltiness with a distinct dairy sweetness .  no carbonation really to speak of . no head forms at all , and therefore no lacing .  i like the feel with some prickly carbonation and moderately light feel and some creaminess from the head .

aromas are medium bodied , and fill the nose with cherries , roasted malt , and wood elements .  i knocked back a few of these at a restaurant the other night because all they had on tap was miller and bud products . appearance : poured slightly darker than a budweiser , but i could only tell when i held it right next to a bud . had no head but that 's no doubt the bartender 's fault .  the mouthfeel is crisp overall .

from tap into a pitcher , then into a frosty 16 ounce mug at brick house pizza in west richland , wa . s- dark malts . t- nice rollercoaster in the mouth : started only slightly sweet , built to a robust dark malts , maybe a hint of charring , then dissolved with a touch of hop bitters . finished nice and clean with the alcohol completely concealed .  pours a clear gold color with a thin white head . no real lacing to speak of and the head was short-lived .  mouthfeel is thick and smooth , no watery sensation at all .

a bit muted , but in a nice direction . t : low hop bitterness , low hop flavor for style .  it 's appearance is a fizzy , yellow colored average looking beer . thats this beer 's only huge upside .  m : medium-bodied and creamy ; high carbonation ; mouthfeel is this beer 's strongest attribute , in my opinion .

aroma of chocolaty mocha and alcohol .  not terribly impressed however . and i think the green bottle adds to a slight skunking of the beer . tasted like a typical american macro lager , not much now to add . i think i 'd order a bud over this in the future though .  mouthfeel : smooth and medium thick , low carbonation .

very odd look for a dipa s : lots of citrus on the nose . grapefruit , orange and banana .  a clear pinkish color , almost like cherry 7-up mixed with pale ale . no head to speak of .  nice creamy mouthfeel .

smells mainly vinous , sauternes with raisins and sherry . a bit uneven , and demanding , possibly with dark chocolate or strong cheese .  poured the carta blanca from a bottle to a pint glass . very , very thin looking .  medium carbonation .

i can taste all the spices and pumpkin , but for whatever reason the taste does n't live up to what this brew smells like . it 's a lot weaker tasting than i thought it would be , at least compared to the aroma anyway .  has a very pale yellow color with a 1/2 inch head .  light to medium bodied , with a very smooth mouthfeel .
nice . the liberator is n't quite my bag of tea .  pours yellow , clear , small white head .  m : creamy and spot-on carbonation .

beer smelled like fresh bread with a fruity apricote kinda taste .  pours an amber color with reddish hues , looks more like a red ale than anything else , not much of a head and what there is fades fast , no lacing on the glass .  m - good mouthfeel , coats a bit like oil but smooth .

appearance - pale yellow smell- i enjoy the smell of this beer . a scent of hops , slightly fruity . this beer is a good one to wash down some jerk pork mouthfeel- not great but not bad either .  1995 lambic bottled in 2000 and drank in 2004 . poured a pale hazy yellow beer with almost no carbonation , which was to be expected .  mouthfeel : medium body , medium carbonation overall : this beer has almost no taste , pity

smells heavily of booze dipped dark fruit and straight up alcohol , but not much burn .  good thing they told me this was a hefeweizen on the label , because otherwise i would n't have been able to tell . golden yellow color with an awful lot of clarity for a hefe . do n't think i 've ever seen a hefeweizen that 'd been filtered this much .  but , also an odd smell kind of like salami . this must be some nasty phenol created by the yeast . a bad yeast flavor here and a lot of it . i usually love unibroue brews for that complex yeasty quality but for some reason this one tastes a little off . that lunchmeat aroma and now this bad oily yeasty taste make this beer almost undrinkable . i doubt it considering it 's called edition 2004 , we 're in 2005 , and it 's 10.5 abv .

i just about busted a nut getting the # $ # cork off in one piece..ahh make that several pieces that did n't fall back into the bottle ... but after a long and arduos process the cork was successfully removed.. poured a dark brown ... relatively clear..absolutely no head ... mouthfeel is very uncarbonated..i love the nose ... molasses ... .brown sugar ... .dark fruits ( plums , dates , even burgandy cherries ) ..a bit of oak ... just an awesome smelling beer.. the flavors are similar to the nose but much more tame ... .dark fruits ... molasses ... oak ... good taste to this ... my biggest complaint is the loose mothfeel ... very uncabonated which gives it almost a watery texture ... seems almost thin ... overall , the nose is great and the taste is very good but the body leaves something to be desired..definitely worth trying ... i wo n't be buying any more though ... .  a - pours a clear orange color with decent carbonation . the head fizzled out before i could even look at it long enough to see what color it was . obviously no lacing here .  mouthfeel is fine for the style .

s- lots of coffee , and *tons* of that smoky flavor you 'd expect from the title . i actually ... do n't like the way they jive as much as i thought i would , but it 's still nice . t- this is actually ... kind of disgusting . very nice d- not a fan .  sprecher 's version uses real bananas . orange hazed brew is nearly cloudy . fizzy at pour and fizzy from the head , which drops down to a minimal ring around the glass .  the mouthfeel was quite good , though . well carbonated and it felt good going down .

nice notes on the nose - lots of toffee and caramel with a pleasant citric fruit character piping through , perhaps a little pineapple which stops the rich malt and caramel from becoming overpowering .  pour was boring , even for the style , as the beer had little head that vanished quickly and left not lacing on the glass as it was being consumed . color and body are yellow and looks fairly thin . as for budweiser , i would advise ab to make sure they keep the flavor in bud , and leave it to bud light to cater to the people that do n't like the taste of real beer .  this beer feels almost delicate .

spicey , fruity , and perfumey nose .  for a white ale , this is pretty translucent . not terribly impressed -- looks somewhat like a cloudy average big brew ale .  the mouthfeel is smooth and oily and the carbonation is alright .

s- lots of roasty malt smell , some cocoa t- notes of acrid coffee , black patent , mild hops .  but today , i finally decided to try it , and though its appearance is not good , it 's got a strong taste .  it is medium bodied and smooth in the mouth .

nose : notes of coffee , chocolate and wood . roasted malt smells come through strongly . taste : tastes of roasted and chocolate malt , coffee and tangy flavors come through as well .  a-pours with no head , no carbonation , and just some white bubbles around the rim .  pretty refreshing , not overwhelmed with carbonation .

i do n't believe that i 've been unduly influenced by the cranberry and white label or the color of the beer , but i smell dark berries .  well the appearance is rather limp .  the palates leads with a thick , malty mouthfeel up front and a sticky , resiny bitterness in the back .

to me the smell was of roasted and chocolate malt , but was rather faint .  appearance : light , clear straw color with a medium sized white head that dissipates very quickly and leaves no lacing behind .  m : mouthfeel is crisp , light-medium bodied and pretty dry .

the aroma is of dark chocolate and malty with a hint of coffee lurking in the shadows .  a painfully flat and lackluster appearance .  still for such a big beer it had a great body , just not sure if i would want more , until it got about 5 years on it .

the smell is of dark fruits . plums , grapes , raisins , and cherries . i tried a `` lift your kilt scottish ale '' from cottonwood at the brewgrass festival and was wondering if this is the same thing .  12 oz bottle into a rare vos 3/4 pint glass appears murky and super-light in the glass . not much head but alot of slow-moving crazy carbonation .  mouthfeel : soft creaminess , light to medium carbonation , with a medium to full body .

the nose comprises chocolate syrup , roasted malts , dark chocolate powder , molasses , and a touch of vanilla bean . the taste holds notes of darkly-roasted malts , very bitter dark chocolate ( the kind you 'd bake with , rather than eat straight-up ) , vinyl , anise , rubbing alcohol , charcoal , and molasses .  it is a light straw colour with little to no aroma . there is yeast floaties which adds to the ugliness of the beer .  pours a cloudy , almost 'chunky ' looking way -- looks a bit similar to an apple cider ( non alcoholic kind ) . caramelly sweet too . vanilla . taste is what kind of throws me - again , both the oak ( taste of whisky barrel ) and smokiness are there . i like both of those favors in my beers , but combined , my jury is still out : like they are competing for my affection . alcohol is quite present too , which seems to go well with the aforementioned whisky oak . a lot going on in this brew .
well , it smells pretty good at least .  pours fizzy yellow gold with alot of pbr type nose .  mouthfeel is good and thick , finish is dry with a moderate dose of alcohol present .

s- smell is sour , raspberries , slight peach .  litle head and a amberbrown beercolor with white haze and big flocks floating .  aroma : hops . the crystal hops dominate the aroma . the malt is there , but overpowered by hops . but i do n't taste the balance that an esb should have . the hops weigh far more than the malt in this beer . notes : this tasted like a very good ipa , but did not have the balance i was expecting , for an esb . a great beer , but did n't fit the style as well as i would have liked .

lovely , bright cherry red color ... head is large at first , simmers down quickly ... aroma : mmmmm ... .complex ! quite a rich and invigorating aroma , i postpone consumption to prolong my time drinking it deep into the nose ... really nice !  pours a clear darkish iced tea color with a fizzy 1 inch beige head that fades to nothing . no lacing whatsoever either . i was expecting something disgustingly gross but i actually really enjoy drinking this one .  oily mouthfeel with next to no carbonation . quite thick and heavy , coating every area of the mouth .

good smell , spicy and hoppy .  lots of bubbles . no head what-so-ever , no lacing either . looks like sparkling lemon koolaid .  everything about this beer was pretty light - light , crisp malt scent ; light fruity taste ; light body . feel - 4.0/5.0 - refreshing , which was really nice .

the beer has a very spicy odor , maybe a hint of cloves or something similar in the nose .  pours a lot like the american macros - pale yellow and a very small head that disappears quickly .  smells sour , big nodes of orange and very tart lemon juice . there 's a bit of a funky hop in there , as well . no real spice of which to speak , nor any hint of wheat . very sour , almost cidery . starts more tart , like lemon juice , moves into a dryer , white wine middle , and ending on a more of a light , semi-sweet orange sour . a unique beer , to say the least . could benefit from a bit of something at the end , but is drinkable enough as it is .

s - musty leather , peaches . t - sweet caramelised peaches .  now i am stuck with with the remaining 5 bottles with no one to try and pawn them off on . this beer was a terrible dissapointment and had really no pumpkin flavor at all to it . it had quite a bit of cinnamon to it but no pumpkin flavors .  mouthfeel is nice & creamy .

s - tart cherries right away with maybe just a tad of artificial cherry candy smell , and some dark chocolate . i like it . i wanted to like this because it looked and smelled very good but just took a bad turn after that .  a - pours just the lightest clear gold with a thin white head that dissipates quickly , leaving nothing but a steady stream of carbonation bubbles . a bit better then your average adjunct , but an adjunct nonetheless .  m : fuller side of medium-bodied with moderate carbonation that tickles the tongue and throat . this aspect of the beer is really nice .

s- smell is absolutely perfect . sweet , floral tones with a huge aromatic pineyness . t- taste is milder than expected from the ipaesque nose but good none the less .  a : pours light golden with a white soapy head that dissapears quckliy with a sizziling sound . no lace . d : a rather uneven beer ; looks crappy and smells below average but tastes ok and has a really nice aftertaste .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied , with a soft prickly creaminess , along with some easy slickness in the body that helps that raw feeling finish go down . just a smidge of alcohol is felt but it is n't overly noticeable .

looks a lot more like a lager than an ipa ... there is some wispy retention on the glass . smells appetizing -- i get mango from the esters and citrusy hops . i like the way the fruit aromas mix with the graininess of this beer in the nose , but less so on the tongue . as a grad student on a budget , i 'll continue to buy it as long as it 's on sale , though i should really just make 10 gallons of true ipa and stop supporting mediocre `` craft '' brewing ...  this beer simply looks awful . i try not to judge beer by its outward appearances but since the ba ratings system includes a weighted 20 % value based on visual appearances , ill just play along and call em like i see em . and this beer looks awful . ) in fact , this beer is hideous to look at , but delightful to drink . it has a very active measure of carbonation , a bright honey-apricot color , and a strong aroma that is distinctly belgian and musty .  m - nice and creamy in the mouth , goes down smooth .

everything from the nose is lost to sweetness , very disappointing .  undated bottle , but these just arrived on the shelf at a street wines , so it shouldnt be too old . head is small , rapidly fizzling to a ring of bubbles , beer is copper to very light auburn-amber and though the bottle has no sediment left in it whatsoever , the beer does have a decent chill haze . no lacing on the glass , head is off-white .  the mouthfeel of this beer ( outside of taste ) was great . great carbonation , bitter hop aftertaste , medium bodied .

s : very tart , almost of a peach mixed with lemon . t : just ok . extremely peachy , but in a sour/tart sort of way .  with the 5.9 abv , this is equivalent to putting down around 9-10 macro lights , like coors or bud light .  mouthfeel - good smoothness , a medium body on par with the style , crisply carbonated .

s : a nice roasty bitter chocolate scent upfront followed by some hints of vanilla and raisin . a nice cocoa on the backend . good .  black color turning to a yellow gold around the top . once again it looks very thin and watery . low marks are in order here .  mouthfeel is quite nice and full .

back in the aroma i am digging the rich toasty bready stuff . there is a bit of the aroma 's promise for maybe a quarter second , then , `` wham ! i would imagine that if the flavor held to the aroma this would be a nice red ale that i could drink a ton of , but this one just is n't right .  appearance is wholly lacking in any kind of head - so obviously no retention or lacing .  m- felt just about right on not too thick .

a - looked good s - smelled good t - this beer has an aftertaste similar to when you chew on a fir tree limb .  soft white to off white head begins at two and three quarters inches falling to one quarter of an inch within five minutes leaving no lace on the glass . hazy dirty gold in color . large quantity of sediment entered glass despite careful pouring efforts .  m - good carbonation and it finishes clean . good light to medium mouthfeel .

good clean , refreshing scent . taste = good taste upfront but too much sourness comes through .  poured a typical macro pee-yellow .  m : easy drinking with medium-body and low-moderate carbonation .

the smell is apples , vanilla , peppers , and caramel . it has some almost witbeer-like characteristics .  zero lacing . color was very dark brown , almost black .  as i drink more my palate adjusts but it does n't ever really get over the off flavors m - pretty thick , not too carbonated , nice mouth coating qualities d - burnt coffee does not go down very well , plust the thickness of the beer limits my ability to quaff this completely i like coffee , i like stouts , and i like a lot of coffee stouts ( new glarus and founders breakfast stout for instance ) .

the aroma was gingerbread spice and cinnamon spice with some light caramel maltiness . almost the aroma of allspice one finds in a pumpkin beer .  clear piss/apple juice color with a bit of chill haze . thin fizzy white head that fades to a sickly smattering of froth .  m : moderate carbonation with a decently viscous mouthfeel .

slight hint of coffee at first in the aroma that 's followed by a dark fruitiness ; some sweetness ; not really all that roasted , but nice . the flavor has a sharp coffee character that moves really quickly into a sourishness , almost like eating a raw cranberry without the berriness ; some hint of that fruit comes in , not sure what 's going on here , but it 's all over the place and not very pleasant .  pours out of the bottle with just a thing layer of foam that disappears almost immediately . the body is really a dull amber body with not much going on .  finish is very grainy and `` off '' lol mouthfeel : full-medium , creamy body with moderate carbonation .

very pleasant t - kind of like a apple jolly rancher diluted into water .  clear yellow filtration victim of a beer screams anything but quad . first sip reveals corn syrup and chardonnay .  mouth feel is more medium bodied than the wheats i 'm used to , a nice change and the full blast carbonation leaves one a happy advocate overall it is lacking smell , good in flavor , great in feel .

s ) roasted grain . coffee bean . earthy - dirt .  on tap brigantine seafood restaurant poway , ca pale straw yellow with a pitiful white head that dissipates almost immediately .  m : lots of carbonation , but a pretty smooth medium body nonetheless .

has a decent enough aroma , all malty and caramely with some raisin coming out as it warms and some grassy hops .  a hard pour produced nothing ! very interesting color .  mouthfeel : medium body with smooth carbonation and a dry finish .

very nice .  still feel this is easily the best us macro-brewed light beer . this is my go to beer if i 'm out tailgating or watching sports and need something cold , refreshing and in a quantity that wo n't have me draining the wallet . i will take this over bud or coors , everytime .  m : creamy to a crisp finish with a good carbonation throughout .

pours a deep ruby as relatively low carbonation pushes up a meagre white head with rather horrendous retention - not bsda-appropriate at all ... '' ruby '' carries through as a concept in the aroma with some nice plum & cherry-type scents wafting up . simple , overall , but i like the way this stuff smells .  appearance low head . looks uninviting .  i did n't want to buy this because i do n't trust twisted pine to sell me a good beer . since i am a sucker and i love hoppy beers i bought it anyway . the smell was very hoppy citrus , pine and something off i could n't place until i tasted it , butter . this beer was quite disappointing and i poured out the remaining 13 or so ounces after i finished my first glass .

smells awful , but turns out to be half decent .  pours a hazy 24 karat gold color , with considerable amounts of chunkiness floating in it , despite a very slow pour . protein flakes everywhere in the beer , makes this truly disgusting to look at . no head and no lacing to speak of .  fine mouthfeel , nothing objectionable , but it 's not a stand-out lager either .

there is a very nice fruity sweet character along with an inviting spiceyness in the aroma . the flavor is sour , dry and reminds me of fruit going bad .  appearance : orange-amber color , clear . little to no head , no lacing .  mouthfeel -- nice , an initial carbonate bite followed by a foamy smoothness . , molasses , pepper/spice .

s : hops , herbs , tangerine , yeast t : toffee , bread , flowers , lemon peel . this disappointed me a bit .  mother lager- magic hat `` you 're never alone with a bone '' mother lager poured a light yellow with no head .  mouthfeel - some creamy smoothnes , well-carbonated .

aroma is interesting and pleasant , a blend of sweet tropical fruits and sugars with a musty , earthy belgian yeast and estery typical saison base .  a - pours pink with half an inch of white foam and soda-like carbonation . looks an awful lot like some kind of fanta .  lighter body and a nice lively carbonation .

s : not nearly as impressed here , it smells mainly of bitters . too hard to distinguish much else , and its a bit too imposing .  poured into a .2l stange , this brew is a clear gold with a negligible white head . no retention or lacing .  mouthfeel is nice and light , with adequate carbonation for the style .

s - smells malty with a small sweet scent ... smells like most of flying dog 's beers ... t - very thick and extremely malty m - strong and bitter d - extremely bitter and filling ... .i would probably only be able to drink a couple before feeling full . im not a porter guy and this was my first one so i can really say it does porters justice ... its very bitter and reminds me of a stout being so dark and filling .  i am a little concerned about the complete and total lack of head on this one . there is no head , no carbonation and no body .  m : smooth and round .

s : pinot barrel with some dark fruit riding a wave bringing a boatload of vanilla and whiskey .  this beer being a macro lager , still is a very good beer , is nothing to be impress about , this beer have a light gold color with a little bit of head.very easy to drink , not a hard taste or a hard feeling on the mouth .  creamy mouthfeel with the addition of oatmeal in the mix .

nose : unremarkable , yet clean and appetizing . osh is only lackingif one would say thatin the category of smell , which is at worst routine and at best bracing . i very much like this ale .  pours a pale straw yellow with a soda like head that recedes fairly quickly . mouthfeel and drinkability make this beer , like most macros .  mouthfeel is medium bodied and crisp . good carbonation , but the overall trainwreck of flavor in the brew makes this one hard to take down .

the smell is also decent . there 's a decent sweetness from the malt , and this almost smells like a fruit candy cane . very unique . things fall completely apart when we get to the taste .  it poured a murky , yellow-white color . very hard to describe . it also was corn .  mouthfeel is medium , well carbed , nice on all fronts but where it needs to be . big failure , in my opinion .

s - coffee with with a hint of sweetness . t - a solid coffee taste in the beginning ... and that is where it left off .  a good hot weather outdoors session beer , can only get in a bottle , not available in a keg for my kegerator , a shame , need to add a lime and lots of salt , that way i can not taste the actual beer . this is a light beer but not as watery tasting as american light beers and the lime and salt make it something a little special .  the body is nice and thick , with a flavorful malt profile : sweet medium caramel malts with a bit of roast character . hops , by the way , are almost nonexistent , which would n't be bad if not for the oxidation , which makes the faint floral flavor seem dull . overall not bad , but has the same type of oxidized or maybe just oversparged flavor common to other corporate breweries like gordon-biersch .

a : straw lager coloring , half finger head with nice lacing . s : not much on the nose at all , nothing negative but nothing really positive to say either . d : very drinkable , i wish i had tried this brew before and will definitely be having again to support my local brewery .  it 's all over the place in canada , but i 've never seen it here ... very light yellow , clear body with half inch offwhite head . similar to a macro lager . i 'd drink this again .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied and watery with almost no carbonation .

the aroma , however , was weak and suggested skunky cardboard to me . not inviting .  poured chilled in scotch glass ( all that was handy ) a : cloudy , dark orange ; thin-to-no head ; dead carbonation ; no lacing s : sweet , malty , savory spicing t : very well spiced ale ( to push the amber/red into october ) ; complex ; moderately hopped m : carbonation should be better one of the better october brews i 've had .  medium body , almost non existent carbonation , sweet sticky syrupy mouthfeel . i think the lack of carbonation ruins the mouthfeel and makes this taste and smell overly sweet .

the smell is very strong of hops . very floral and powerful . the taste it really dominated by hops and the bitterness at the end is quite nice .  poured from the bottle into a pint glass , beer is a slightly hazy , straw color with a pure white , fizzy head . other than the small bits of sediment actively swimming around throughout the glass , looks like a macro lager .  overall , feels unbalanced , too much carbonation and a little too dull .

it appears average , smells bad , and needs a lime but it would be blasphemy for me to give it anything less than a c. i grew up with this beer , in fact this was the first beer i ever had . s : smells of strong yeast , and potent grain malts . also faint skunk smell .  i poured my first bottle and poured it out because there were lots of floaties . poured a second glass and still lots of floaties . the color was a sick orange , with a thin head that receded to the edges .  flavor is rather plain , roasty , sweet , a bit of coffee and coco , the hops seem to be hiding somewhere , i detect little to none , little carbonation , short finish , with a bit of dark bread , and rasins , very thin body.drinkable but not very memoriable .

it looks like watered-down , carbonated honey , but tastes nothing like that . it 's nothing to get excited about , unless you 're looking to get out of hand .  if you pour it good you can get absolutely no head on it , looks like apple juice when you do .  m : this was the most dissapointing . aside from the lingering dry finish this was a very thin porter .

a nice alternative to the big three 's light beers . it 's better overall than hamm 's , blatz 's , and even leinenkugel 's .  appearance- cloudy , absolutely no head , and no lacing .  mouthfeel was poor .

s - has a metallic caramel aroma ( pretty weird ) , crackery malt ... there 's barely any aroma to this beer !  12oz bottle a- pours a clear golden yellow color with a fizzy white head that quickly disappears .  body is depressingly light . very nonexistent in the finish . taking bigger an bigger sips just to capture some flavor . smooth , but light . bitterness in the aftertaste follows a big gulp .

the first thing i noticed about this brew was the skunky odour the second it was popped ... .it poured very nicely with a thick crown which quickly disapated ... the body is medium and the taste is that of thin hops with a hint of carmel ... i liked the `` stubby '' .an ok offering at best .  magic hat # 9 was left at my house after a party . # 9 pours a very clear yellow with tons of bubbles , but only a very slight head that soon reduces to nothing . the maltiness does come out a bit more in the taste , but unfortunately , it is drowned out by the overbearing fruit .  the mouthfeel is disappointing with absolutely no carbonation and mild flavors lingering around . overall , i could have possibly gotten a flat beer but this beer had potential ( when carbonated ) but it didnt come through in my bottle .
nose is grainy - pretty faint .  a : the beer is clear pale yellow in color and has no visible signs of carbonation .  mouth is thin and watery . too simple and too one dimensional and thin .
nose : very slight nose .  i poured this strange brew into my tumbler at 50 degrees . the beer ? had no head whatssoever . it looked like beer other than that .  mouthfeel is thin for the style .

pours a straw yellow with a one finger head . no lacing on the glass aroma is light hops , yeast , sweet taste is good dose of hops , citrusy lemon , the bitterness is sour . pretty bland , not enough hop bitterness for me to really wash down some spicey indian food .  a - straw yellow , clear with no head .  2.5 m very light , i am not impressed . it is very close to water in feel .

there is an obvious orange peel smell coupled with spice and something that resembles dirty socks . the body is somewhat thin and dry , lacking in richness and the taste is pretty much the same as the smell . orange peel , some spice and not much more .  three of some of the great brewers together to produce a lovely , artistic bottle with minute text on the back outlining the mikkeller history from loving the pale yellow american macro-beers of the past . the first thing noticed was that it poured much like the `` fizzy yellow '' macro-beers mentioned ; but this soon darkened a bit with a 1-2 finger white head that soon disappeared without a lace !  the mouthfeel is syrupy and shows none of the carbonation that the pour hinted at .

i think this is the first time i 've ever written this , but the aroma seriously reminds me of urine .  not very beer like . more like a sparkling apple juice . color is a somewhat dull gold . no head .  aside from that , the taste , like the smell , is unremarkable mouthfeel is borderline watery .

the smell is very mild with some weak notes of fresh hops . there are lots and lots of small bubbles ; the carbon dioxide is petty strong .  has a very pale yellow color with a 1/2 inch head .  the mouhfeel is weak , watery , thin .

smell is subtle at first and different than any beer i 've smelld before .  a : pours a deep brown with a soda-like head that quickly fizzes away to nothing . zero lacing .  taste is weak , almost watery , has to be drank ice cold or has a taste like vomit . bottom line is compared to other cheap beers pbr excels in taste , quality , and conveniently the price , 7 bucks a 12 pack .

i did not use a lime , if you need fruit with your beer perhaps you should look for another type of beer . there is no smell of hops , but the taste is crisp , and this beer is super easy to drink .  the appearance was an opaque golden yellow that left a thin white head that dissipated quickly . obviously , little of the head was left clinging to the glass . on the second pour in the same glass , there was more of a head , and more apparent carbonation , but still was not impressive .  smells basically like apple juice . watery . also , the carbonation that was so present during the pour now seems dulled . for all its faults , in the end rogue makes a malt liquor that achieves what you usually want out of the style .

s- smells a little too sweet , maybe it 's just me . t- above average for a beer this cheap . lightly grainy , sweeter than average , corn with trace hops detectable .  on tap , looks unimpressive , same with smell .  m - thin , watery , overly carbonated .

at first notice the smell is like any other beer just with a sweet hint . also believe it or not it went well with mexican food .  very pale yellow and not much head . minimal bubbles floating to the top .  mf : it 's medium-bodied at best despite the label 's claims of `` full bodied . '' speaking of which , it has a soda watery type carbonation , not at all the `` luxuriously smooth '' of the label . i have to say that they could get the mouthfeel under control ( i 'd imagine this is less of an issue on tap ) , it would be hands-down my favorite irish stout .

no aroma . for as cold as it is , it actually still has a lot of flavor .  it appearance is awfully light in color to have blueberry flavors .  mouthfeel is thin and weak .

not a lot of aroma though , more of a faint `` beer-stink '' smell ... certainly not that impressive .  pours a peachy , almost lemonade in color and fizzy clarity .  the mouthfeel was thin and not terribly hoppy on the palate .

aroma is non-present except for the german munich malt aroma .  the weakest 'imperial ' anything ___ a : deep , dingy clear ruby body with essentially no head .  maybe a little dusty , but i probably dislike the low carbonation & tackiness more . my tongue feels like i just drank a pot of black tea .

smells like bad tequila or bad beer , take your pick .  the wife wanted to try a fun fruit beer , my choices were limited , so i grabbed a sixer of this ... neat 12 ounce bottle with silly dog cartoon thingy on the label . let 's see how `` wild '' this blueberry beer is ... a : poured in traditional pint glass at 40 degrees . holy fruit beer , batman , this one 's a clear , purplish red with a light purple fizzy head that fades quickly leaving no lacing and a small purple/off-white collar .  very light bodied , an ok mouthfeel.. just way too watery and thin , not much for taste , just some lemon zest on the after taste .

i could hardly get any smell from this beer , so not much to be impressed with . the taste starts out with some corn and sweet malts and later get some hops that nicely balance the malts out . a good beer to drink when low on money and in need of one .  yellow-brown beer with a fizzy head that dissolves right away .  on top of that , the beer tasted a bit flat and felt thin .

slightly sweet aroma . light , sweet malt , bit of corn . no hops . immensely drinkable . i 'm still convinced that corn is a much more acceptable adjunct than rice .  had one the other night , but this actually tastes better on a fresh set of taste buds imo ... pours an effervescent ebony with a finger+ of brown/chestnut colored head . zero head retention & lacing s : chocolate , coffee & iron t : coffee , dark chocolate , & iron up front .  the feel is fizzy and watery thin .

citrus/orange aroma ; really need to get the nose in there to detect much of the hops .  poured out a darker yellow with maybe a half pinky head that dissapeared immediately .  thin to medium mouthfeel with zero carbonation -- lifeless .

attractive silver label with a moon and rays behind a mountain . pours a light straw yellow with a snow white head . very faint grainy smell .  there is absolutely no head to be found on this beer when i receive it .  smell is not overwealming , but seems sweet with hints of yeast and hop . watery , yeasty , sweet ... more corn than i thought there would be ... taste relatively one-dimensional , unfortunately . fairly drinkable though ... inoffensive and cheap ...

s - not much smell at all . again , there 's a fruitiness that i ca n't put my finger on .  a- hazey pale orange . if i ignored the small foamy cap i 'd swear it was some sort of orange soda made with juice . i would n't buy a 6-pack , and if i had a choice of this macro and blue moon i 'd choose blue moon .  in body and taste , this is so akin to water that i find it very drinkable .

i found this beer to have an interesting , complex aftertaste . i had another dark beer ( ca n't remember the name , and it 's not listed on-tap on their website anymore ) at brewery creek that did n't have any flavor at all . so i am pleased that this had a lot of flavor . it just was n't my cup of tea .  a : pours a clear weak yellow with a thin white head which does not last long at all .  it actually smells more like a belgian dubbel . it does n't have much complexity and it drinks very watery . this is by far the thinnest quad i 've ever come across .

i could n't smell much of anything other than some light hops on the nose . remarkably ordinary lager that impersonates a pilsner on occasion .  near zero head . not an attractive beer . it looks dead .  although the mouthfeel is thin for a stout , the flavor is pretty good .

s - i get a bit of sweet pilsner dry malt scents - no rye . i was hoping for something more direct than this .  very small head , particularly for a wheat . it dies to literally no bubbles and therefore no lace . the finish is milky and short lived .  very little mouthfeel , this beer is meant to be drank ice cold as implied with the cold indicator on the can unlike most beers that i drink .

the aroma was dominated by an earthy/mossy funk that seems to by mostly hops and mild overall .  a : pours a copper body with a very small off-white head with extremely poor retention and no lacing .  very thin , and watery . lower carbonation .

nose is fairly lager-like with some light frutiness .  appearance : very cloudy , much more so than an average wheat beer . the head was almost nonexistent , but had decent lacing for whatever was there .  color very pale green or lemon odor , which suggests more concentrated lemon juice only freshly cut lemon slices , but preserving a small mouth , perhaps a bit too much . the lager that is the basis must be extremely low in taste because the body is still very watery , just a few hints of lemon , no sugar but not bitter unfortunately .

definitely pale . the nose on this beer is not very entertaining . it 's lightly fruity , but weak in the malt department . not its finest quality , the aroma . the taste is rather pungent , but otherwise underwhelming .  a - this beer was light . almost transparent . a clear as sprite , but less bubbly . s - corn , mild hops , mild algae smells , a bit sweet . mostly because the pilzner hops are cut back and other flavors of the corn barley and local water come out .  m : water thin , light side of champagne-like carbonation .

smell is not impressive with watery dark malt and stale coffee .  alright , enough flack from all you real men who dont drink light beer . sometimes drinking 5 imperials of barley wine and washing it down with 10 plates of nachos is a little overkill . theres nothing wrong with enjoying a light beer every now and then . im not in love with it , but hey , i dont like soda and this is a good pick for lunch or after the gym when you dont really need the full impact of a heavyweight brew but need a little refresher . it is somewhat enjoyable , a lil funky and it tastes better than the usual na beer . so all in all , i think its a decent stab at a low cal/alch .  its rather thin in the mouth , and doesnt ready leave me wanting more drinkabilty - with its high alcohol , and bitter mocha overload , this beer doesnt do it for me .

'' the aroma was not very strong , however . there was a slight hint of hops but the overall taste was not very strong . it left very little aftertaste and was very easy to drink . this beer was very drinkable .  pretty plain-jane . very light color a real pale yellow .  feel is thin , dribbly and loose .

there lacked a adequate smell here . there was a malty smell , but very slight .  this was always my emergency beer ; the cheapest sixer at the one place that stayed open latest . tastes pretty cheap and watery and best served ice-cold-as-possible .  mouthfeel is painfully carbonated . light bodied , way way to much carbonation .

but perhaps i 've been drinking too much ipa lately to truly judge my recent first sips of this from tap . it was difficult to detect anything revelatory on my initial smell and mouthfeel but i was impressed with its good drinkability and uncharacteristic load of hops . this is a very refreshing lager and my preferred choice over most .  served in a nonic pint glass , the beer pours a hazy gold color with about a 1/4 inch white head that went away pretty quickly . no lacing whatsoever .  the mouthfeel needs work . it is n't creamy at all , it is just really watery and lacking carbonation .

a sour and somewhat bitter smell to start off , contrary to what others have said . the usual appearance for this style , and the taste improved as it warmed .  only a tiny bit of apple juice yellow color . corn and rice but slightly malty m - it 's surprisingly viscous for this type of cheap canned adjunct .  for a russian imperial this is even for 9.7 incredibly weak and watery it 's the first thing i notice . the mouthfeel on this is not good , it 's even weaker than most american stouts i 've had .

probably more of the latter , but still ... this is my go-to beer when i 'm reaching for an ice-cold 40 ... they 're cheap at the local bodega ( about $ 2.50 for a 40 or a dollar or two for the smaller cans ) and pleasantly skunky enough to please your average `` ale '' lover 's palate , especially if you 're just looking for something tasty , cold , cheap and readily available on a hot summer day .  pours out a light , pale yellow that gives the impression of a basic beer . almost no head , even from the tap .  very light in body with a slick mouthfeel at first that becomes almost slimy .

does n't smell like much . i get some malt , maybe some peach fuzz .  almost no head , carbonation or lacing observed .  medium bodied , but watery .

an uninspiring golden hued beer lowers itself into my glassware with a small flurry of fizzy pop-like bubbles that fizzle out just as quickly . when i lean in to enjoy the aroma i find myself confused . did i somehow imagine pouring a beer into my glass , only to find myself sniffing empty space ? nothing that makes me think `` mmm , now this is a hefe-weizen '' .  with fairly aggressive pouring i got a small to medium sized off white head that quickly faded to almost nil and no lace .  still has some things that i 'd consider defects that define budweiser 's trademarks ; it 's got plenty of personality but not enough charm . overall seltzer water vibe , which shoots beer right up your nose like soda pop . do n't pass it up if you 're at the brewery , simply because it 's not too shabby when it 's this fresh .

serving type : bottle appearance : a straw like yellow that started w/ a 2 finger head that quickly dissipated to nothing smell : grains and some sort of skunky smell .  if you cant drink beer out of a mug its not a beer ! appearance- pale clear yellow smell - not much more than a hint of beer odor taste- clean . very light and clean . drinkability- easy to drink .  the mouthfeel is thin , with excessive carbonation that gives it a slight harsh feeling on the tongue .

s : a definite harshness to the nose . t : the flavor is pretty bitter , which is nice enough , along with citrus peel in terms of the hops . at least the flavor was an improvement over the nose .  i think on the right day with the right food it 'd be a fair beer - like a hot summer day doing some yard work . the beer seemed lighter than miller or bud light to me . smells piney and malted .  poured a very light gold colour that was extremely transparent . it looks thin , if that 's possible .  the mouthfeel was a bit thin and watery .

the aroma set the tone for me . maybe a little hop aroma would have pushed it higher for me .  with the last `` porterish '' day before summer actually kicks in upon me , i rate this from a 12-pack sampler ... chocolate-vanilla notes adorn a mocha-soda tint with flatlining head and zero lacing ... like experiencing a cologne bottle ... malty punch ... obtrusive , almost as `` no shit '' as flying dog provokes on its label ... a too smooth ( oily ?  m : very overly carbonated to the point where it was difficult to drink early on , mild acidity , medium-bodied .
scent - almost also non-existent . a faint carmel aroma .  a - poured out a straw yellow color with a bubbly , white , two-finger head .  3.0 m thin .

s : malty smell , but not much really . t : a bit fruity with very small hints of fruits .  very pale yellow colour with surprisingly thick head .  way too carbonated here , which hurts the mouthfeel quite a bit .

s : light and thin , with some malt and alcohol notes . t : tastes pretty much of malt and corn , no hops to speak of . m : medium-bodied for a macro , light overall , a bit medicinal and solventy from the alcohol .  next time , i 'll have the server recommend some sake to try ... it seems asian macros are rather predictable . i like the bottle design , for what its worth ... beer poured a clear straw into the glass , which was provided ( kudos ) .  pretty nice . the body is as thin as water . that leads to a very drinkable beer , actually , since it goes down ... well , like water .

the smell was rather disapointing for an octoberfest and seemed somewhat bland with slight hops and malt evident with a spicy tinge .  i actually like this beer with a nice slice of lemon or lime . taste pretty good when it is ice cold but do n't let it warm down or the skunkiness comes through .  feel of almost flat carbonated water .

smell : aroma of herbal hops is very strong and almost totally dominates the malt . not what i expected at all . ) i found the huge hoppy aroma off-putting , but that 's my only major knock .  my father is a bartender . he works at an `` old man bar '' where the options are pretty limited and there is n't much to do but bs and drink and maybe watch some tv . heineken is not a pretty beer , but do n't let it 's asthetics get it the way of your enjoyment . i would never turn down a free heineken , but if i needed to pay for it i would likely select something else .  m- thin highly carbonated .
i could not get much out of the aroma with this one .  appearance - murky witbeer like appearance . not very presentable appearance at all .  the mouthfeel is very thin .

s : slightly vegetal and a bit disappointing in this respect , slightly sweet maltiness but nothing to pull it away from this bruised fruity/cooked vegetable aroma . appearance is boring , smell seems a bit off , flavor is n't bad and mouthfeel is adequate .  i see this currently ranks 202 out of 205 for the style ... no way this is that bad ... there are many macros worse ... with that said , i am not a big a-b fan ( used to work for a miller distributor ) ..this is at least as good as bud and cheaper ... it pours a light straw color ... .about a 1 inch head settles to virtunally nothing ... .no lacing evident ... .nose is cooked corn and cereal grains ... body is on the lighter side of medium but defnitely not watery or thin like some ... .slick ... not real charged up ... flavor is basically adjuncty sweet cereal grains and corn meal ... .relatively sweet for the style ... .no hop bite at all ... .  the body is light and really deters the taste .

smell : this one is all about that distinctive fruity grape note ( thinks welsh 's grape jelly filled grape bubblegum ) in the beginning that then gets washed over by a classic cantillon urine and yeast wave . truly unique and highly enjoyable . taste : same as the nose but more integrated and not as grape dominant as the nose .  cloudy golden color body topped by a thin white head that quickly fades . a hefe with a quick-fading head ?  the herbal hops will become medicinal with traces of alluminum and will become a bit less appealing as it goes from a zippy feel to rather stagnent . a flat and bitter hop flavor is the finish .

s - i found the nose to be very muted , very slight scent of roasted malts . t - luckily this tastes better than it smells .  the color is moderate golden . something is wrong with the color on this one . no head and no lacing on the glass .  the presence of tannin explains how , while quite watery , satan red is also quite drying .
