s : the smell is very balanced and i am loving it . mild fruity esters mix with sweet bourbon , vanilla , and coconut to form what is probably the best smelling beer ( non-ipa ) i 've had before . d : fantastic barrel aged barleywine . great job mayflower .  that taste mitigates after a while , leaving a more pleasant nose of dark coffee . in other words , a lagered stout . the waitress said it may be off because the batch was just tapped the day i can in .  the mouthfeel is way to under carbonated and watery for the style .

an irish dry stout arrived , looking much like guinness . very little to smell , sort of weak grain .  a : pours a dark golden yellow with a couple fingers worth of fairly oily looking bright white head that took its time fading into a thin film that left a pretty good layer of sticky lace down the glass .  i feel like i have now experienced the true port/lost abbey experience , this is the first one i 've had that is flat ... a : pours dark brown with caramel highlights , zero head even after stiff pour , some clarity s : nose is predominantly oak and vanilla , some char quality in there , stout base takes a back seat t : vanilla and bourbon again dominate , some ashy character in there along with light notes of leather and tobacco , a bit of of boozieness on the finish mf : low carbonation is an understatement , medium body o : good flavors here , the lack of carbonation takes away from the quality a bit , for the premium price tag , i would expect carbonation .

by pabst . you wo n't believe me but it kind of smells like a bar of soap . damn it . it tastes like nothing at first , then really sweet , then like boiled corn .  bottle into a pint glass pours black in color with a bit of red highlighting along the edges of the glass .  mouthfeel : way too carbonated .

the aroma is quite limited but offers some light malt and spicy hops , as well as some light sulfur ( which seems to be characteristic of the brewery ) . the maltiness has an odd , almost musty , bready note that 's fortunately overshadowed by a spicy , but indistinct , hop flavor .  it looks pretty enough , with its amber body and nice tan head , but the heavy mouthfeel did n't sit too well with me .  head falls into the liquid way too quickly and seems to look more like bubble bath suds that the typical beautiful belgian head . certainly is the high point of the beer . alcohol comes a little too strong on the palate and seems to take over the other flavors . flat on the tonque . outrageously overpriced and overrated .

smell : grainy with a cut grass smell when cold - and almost no smell at all when warm .  a : a strange deep red color with both pink and brownish hues .  thin and watery for a dark beer . little carbonation . needless to say , i was disapointed in this beer .

there is a slight hint of malt in aroma , not much else , but it smells like a bock . this is a decent bock with some spiciness .  kind of an odd lager ... pours a clear , good looking rich gold color ... 1/2 inch frothy head ... .nose is sweet ... .almost a hint of barley..body is light and lacks substance ... .taste is bland..there are macros with more flavor than this ... no hops to speak of and the malt profile borders on an adjunct style beer ... has a corny , adjunct like mouthfeel ... .  mouthfeel : a bit on the fizzy side - really scrubs the tongue .

it 's yellow . smell : it has an unusual smell . not skunky , but funky .  the beer has an overall nice appearance .  coppery colored amber with a sudsy froth top that subsides to a foam slick , no lacing , body is very thin and under-carbonated . perhaps as an effect of my bottle not being quite as fresh as it ought to be , i am detecting absolutely none of the fruity notes commonly perceived by other ba members ... .and this really hurts my overall impression quite a bit .

s : very mild citrus , not much else detected . unimpressive smell . t : much better than expected .  a - hazy ( for a pale lager ) yellow with a big frothy head that lingers .  body is thin and flat .

first off , i 've never had a beer that smelled this bad while tasting so good . it had a caramel scent , with very heavy undertones of wet dog .  it looks pretty nice .  the palate is thin .

ok malt scent , not an aromatic beer really . starts out mildly sweet with a decent herbal hop assault .  tastes extremely bitter , reminded me of chinook on steroids . grapefruit city . normally bitter beers i can deal with but not enough sweet malt to counter balance for me . one and done for taste buds .  m : taste was below average for me , but the mouthfeel is even worse . super thin . light carbonation and no body make this almost watery .

smell is , well , sauerkraut . it dominates the aroma and any sembelence of oakiness or caramel just get lost in the sauerkraut . needless to say , i do n't like sauerkraut . taste is significantly better than aroma , but still not all that amazing . definte caramel and burnt sugar flavors as well as lactic tartness and there 's that darn sauerkraut again .  slightly hazy amber , with a tan head that foams up and laces .  mouthfeel : very very thin .

nose is non existent . really nothing there at all .  appalachian trail blaze brown is a clear red ale with a thin beige head that fades and leaves nice lacing .  carbonation appears low . beer is thin and boring , not much there at all . mild sweetness very water like . bummer .

aroma is the green bottle skunked hops aroma that you get from some of these types of `` imports '' not necessarily bad , but very strong and overpowers the grain bill completely .  initial head that rises a half inch or so , then fades to a broken ring around the edge . mahogany color when poured , appears black in the glass .  the taste is similar , just a little sweeter , with more wateriness and less hops . i could n't get over how watery this beer tasted and felt . maybe i 'm rating it a little low because of that , but it has a lot of strikes against it : watery , bland , and definitely not a bargain .

pours a nice clear golden with an average head that dissapated before i took a drink smelled a bit skunky ( surprise surprise ) with some sweetness in there .  a - pours a one a half finger head with a hazy golden straw body . the head fades to a decent lace as time passes .  has a bit of a sweet maltiness and maple flavor does come out more as it warms m : very thin feel for a porter and leaves an odd buttery coating d : nothing really appauling , and nothing overpowering so it is drinkable , but i probably wo n't get another

it smells a bit yeasty and a tad skunky .  dark brown to black color with ruby red highlights and an inch of light beige head .  hard to slam the beer that got my through college but ... . the twelfth tasted like the first . not really whatt i consider beer anymore but my in-law says it is more of a beer than budweiser ? could there be a reason you can by `` cooler-packs '' in multiples of 6 !

the smell is exactly what you get when you open a can of corn kernels . not really true to style and not great at all . overall , you drink the beer for what you taste and smell predominately and this is below par on both .  the santa fe pale ale poured a copper-orange with an thick and creamy off-white head that laced the glass .  the mouthfeel is medium-light bodied with a watery texture , and a little too much carbonation .

somewhat skunky aroma , but that 's no surprise coming from a green bottle . the taste is above average for a macro lager .  pours a orange almost amber color with a less than finger head .  taste is malty to start , but very thin . the body leaves one wanting more . dry finish with an almost soda-like feel . despite the lack of body , this beer is rather drinkable .

very light smell of rice and malt .  looks like a nice beer .  m : light carbonation with a very light watery body .

the smell is not very noticeable ; slightly sweet and grainy . the flavor is fairly sweet as well , with definite fruit and vanilla notes .  this bell 's porter was dark brown and had a tan head which went away .  m : this feels fairly thin ; the flavors fall quickly off the tongue , resulting in a watery finish .

almost no aroma . creamy nitro texture .  poured from a 22oz bottle into a magners glass the beer pours a nice golden color with a slight amount of haziness to it . there is a big 1-2 inch head that falls back to about 1/4 inch and statys .  the taste is cloyingly sweet , viscous , the aromas transfer , and turn very bready on the finish , the middle has cherries candies , almost medicinal the mouth feel is vaguely reminiscent of cough syrup , but watered down . there is no bitterness and even less carbonation .

my wife smelled it and said `` yuck '' and said it reminded her of some makeup she wears . the smell did get a little better the longer i drank it , but initially - not good .  i really enjoy most st offerings a -- nice amber/copper color s -- very surprising nutty aroma .  mouthfeel was quite thin and highly over carbonated .

the smell while weak , does smell a bit offensive .  barnyard in a bottle . but uniquely so . if for no other reason than to go back to a differing style .  watery and flat in my mouth .

the label on the bottle i 'm drinking has a coat of arms , 2 cherries and says the abv is 6.8 % . the smell was the first thing that weirded me out ; maybe i was expecting more of a lambic-ness , but the smell had a funk that i found hard to place . what the hell was that smell ? dirty underwear ? the taste started okay with a tart , bitter cherry flavor but followed by a metallic nastiness that almost pressed down on the back of my tongue .  it poured a dark brown-copper color with a nice off-white head and good lacing .  the beer was entirely too light bodied for a stout , this really was one of the most disappointing elements of the beer .

smells sightly yeast , but there 's not much else there .  12 oz bottle poured into a pilsner - fridge - 2009 appearance : pours a transparent golden color with lots of flowing carbonation . the head is white and rises 1 '' tall , showing a good amount of foaminess and retention . a coating of lace remains behind . nice !  mouthfeel is thin and watery .

no smell whatsoever ... like , absolutely nothing .  pours a large white head with fair retention and some lace .  but it seemed way too flat and thin . the favor is there , but the body is not . unless you have a pathological obsession with oatmeal stouts , look elsewhere for your beer drinking needs

not betting much out of the nose , other than some faint caramel malts ... taste is very mild , some medium caramel and brown malts noted .  it is a nice amber color , much darker than most miller products .  taste is very light and mouthfeel is weak .

ok. s : very roasty , with dark chocolate , char , and just nasty burnt grass . i am not a fan at all .  a= the pour is a nice deep golden color with a crispy white head on it that holds some decent retention and lacing .  mouthfeel - watery .

s : really hard to pick anything up . all i can come up with is bready and , thanks to my brother , faintly reminiscent of grape jelly . t : hello barrel aging ! d : surprisingly easy to drink for a cask ale .  this beer pours a dark mahogany with a normal-ish 2 inch tan head that leaves just a bit of lacing .  m - watery . too thin , especially for a beer so strong , and meant to be malt-forward .

so with that in mind ... the taste was small and the aroma was microscopic . this one smelled of beer , and i am talking tat white beer can with black letters that was so wonderfully used in the film repo man .  poured a bright copper color with a large tan head that dissolved away quickly . looked nice .  unfortunately it takes on flat , syrupy , and warm qualities from the cask . it needs more carbonation to lift it .

slightly murky ( as i would expect of an unfiltered wheat ) s : kind of like bud light . not impressed or excited upon smelling it .  i do like the appearance , nice amber color .  mouthfeel is very flat .

s - little bit of a corn smell in the nose .  this is my second try with a high-alcohol beer ; the first time was at a party years ago and i was too drunk to remember whether or not i enjoyed whatever it was that i drank , i just remembered that it was really strong . this comes in an absolutely beautiful bottle and pours a thick , very dark red .  a - medium to dark amber ; almost no head , but what little bubbling there was at the edge of the glass managed to leave a slight bit of lacing s - there was nearly no aroma , and what was there was nothing distinctive t - good malt/hop balance with pleasantly surprising bitter finish m - far too thin and too little carbonation in this sample ; a bit of a sticky finish d - though it will not be mistaken for a world-class brew , this one is easy to suck down since it is thin and flavorful ; without the sticky finish , it would score a half-tick higher

s - no aroma to speak of . t - extremely restrained flavor .  pours out to a slightly hazy light amber with orange accents , forming a large light beige head after a vigorous pour . head is sea-foam in consistency and has ok retention with sparse lacing .  mouthfeel is flat but this is the only disappointment .

creamy frothy head at first and last throughout ... aroma - metallic bitter hops .  stroh 's in a can , why not let 's do this ... appears a golden clear bubbly quote , unquote beer look to it with large heavily carbonated bright white head floating above body dwindling at a moderate pace leaves some nice patches of sporadic lacing around my duvel chalice ... sorry duvel .  smells and tastes bland and grain like . almost stale . it is a good beer to party with if all your doin is playin beer pong or circle .

sure it 's crystal clear and pale straw yellow but the dense two-finger white head cakes the glass in beautiful , thick lace . s - grainy straw and a boat-load of sweet corn in the nose . while this is n't really offensive in the least , big flats does n't offer much in the way of aroma ... t - heavily grainy pale malt seems ber cheap as does the corn adjunct flavor and husky straw finish but really , this might be one of the better tasting beers of it 's style , which is how i 'm judging it .  pours a dark brown with ruby highlights . tan head that fades quickly .  m - very thin and watery with flat carbonation .

; ( the aroma was almost non existent - a major flaw in any ipa and what i could smell was mild butterscotch and a spritz of earthy hop . i swirled and stuck my face in - i got nuthin . a very mediocre beer , with bland and generic sort of flavor .  pours from the bottle a dark brown with a light tan head and settling quickly into a thin filmy froth .  the mouthfeel is very thin and highly carbonated , very reminiscent of your typical macro lager .

the aroma is not what i expect from an esb . it has a raisin character that is more common among belgian ales . the bitterness is much more prevalent and the raisin character is n't as strong , making the flavor much better than the aroma .  served in a stone vertical epic glass that can be described as stemless martini-like . pours a dark golden-copper color with a good white head and some lacing .  mouthfeel : medium-bodied . it took much diligence to see my way to the end of this beer , and , were it not for the runaway carbonation , it could 've been far better . one to revisit , provided they clear up the carbonation issue .

aroma : weird fruit , obvious guess would be peach , but alas it is not obvious .  drank from a bottle . i first had to rid myself of the expectations of guiness extra stout in a bottle ( what i 'm used to ) . chocolately and coffee-ish , appropriately bitter , no noticeable hops .  almost watery .

no aroma .  the pour was highly carbonated , with thick tan , lingering head .  the flavor was both too light and 'way too bitter for a pils . it was watery and lacking in aroma . not much foam - what there was disappeared quickly . the word i 'd use to describe this beer is `` insubstantial . ''

i't smells like a funky straw bale , some wet grassy notes as well .  in the glass the beer looks fine , amber in color .  it lacks a big full mouthfeel , and is actually very watery and disappointing .

even before the glass got in front of me the green apple aroma hit me in the face . it dominates right from the start and influences everything else . a medium body is again dominated by the tart green apple with a tang from the carbonation .  appearance is very good . a nice dark red brown but not black like so many american porters . clean and transparent . dirty socks maybe ? a cheap macro would do this for you .  mouth : enters the mouth with very light carbonation that flattens as it goes back . overall , it 's not a bad brew , it 's got a great hop flavor but not enough depth or balance , and the weak mouthfeel ruins the experience .

overall , nothing all that great here , especially with that odd smell . it goes down easy enough , but i really do n't wan na put too much more in me .  bad sign , but i ordered it anyway a - looked fine , medium golden , mildly hazy s - mild citric hop smell quickly hidden behind malty/bisquity sweet smell . can still smell the yeast on it as well , which makes me wonder if they filter at all .  mouthfeel is weak and watery .

purchased a 4-pack of nitro cans - a treat every stout lover must indulge in every once in a while . the cascading in the glass was also pretty impressive - got ta love that widget . personally i thought the smell was a mix between chalk dust and flat budweiser .  a= pours a nice cloudy golden copper hue , sits hazy golden orange in glass . a good foamy white head forms and lingers pretty well .  body is way too thick , sweet , and syrupy .

delectably hoppy smell . taste is not bad , but does n't live up to the smell . it tastes thinner than i 'd like .  poured a entirely opaque dark brown color that yielded nothing when held up to light . big , creamy tan head that required two pours . lots of lace on the sides of the glass .  but i felt i owed it to myself to see if smaller carbonation meant bigger taste .

smells earthy and muddyt . a bit too strong of an aroma but the negativity associated with the scent doesnt seem to get in the way of the taste .  pours a clear copper color with a mostly white with light tan head .  carbonation is way too strong .

effervescent smell : funky overcooked grain , corn husks , some kind of syrupy sweetness , not decipherable through the nose .  appearance : looks pretty good .  taste : largely dry ; bland notes of roast upfront and throughout ; slightly sour with a mildly bitter finish ; hints of chocolate ; somewhat light bodied ; thin mouthfeel .

a touch of hops and sweet malts in the nose , but there is an odd , vegetal aroma in there that is pretty offensive .  pours a light brass color with very active carbonation . the head has good retention and leaves sticky patches of lace behind .  i 'm going to have to go against the gimmick and with the style here , the mouthfeel just is n't there . i 'm not impressed at all , it 's like a half flat beer that you 've left on your desk whilst reviewing a beer and forgotten about it only to come back to it 30 mins later . the shining point of this beer is it 's drinkability .

s - some malt , but you need to inhale deeply . it also smells somewhat sweet to me , perhaps a bit corny .  a-cloudy gold , nice white head s-fairly gross smelling , like a very tangy orange with wheat t-orange and wheat upfront that quickly fades in to a tanginess . sam adams , thank you for changing the spring seasonal to the noble pils , you still should 've left this out of the winter package and never made this again .  mouthfeel/ drinkability : the carbonation isnt stinging and seems appropriate . the body of the beer seems far too thin .

nose is not there . hoppy after taste .  the pour was ok , nice hazy reddish amber color .  a nice chocolatey finish that lingers for a while on the palate is the best part about this beer . m : poor .

the aroma is pretty complex like any respectable barleywine , but definitely more on the malt side . brown sugar is obvious and is of pleasant company to figs , peaches , alcohol and an all-around complex fruitiness .  well , it looks good - coppery gold with plenty of creamy head .  nose : it 's aroma is a little bit malty , a little bit citrusy flavor : the taste has some lemon/citrus notes w/ some hints of maltiness , but the big thing that you notice is how fizzy this beer is . it 's far too fizzy for me .

s - this is an incredibly weak aroma for the style . they 're there but they 're almost undetectable .  a- has a nice amber color to it . nice and clear .  mouthfeel is kind of thin and not very pleasant as the carbonation dies down and leaves a sort of flat cola sensation , without the stickiness .

the smell is nothing special . had this one after the jupiler , and this beer is so much better for the style .  it pours a pale and perfectly clear straw-yellow . a two finger head rests on top , retaining nicely and leaving a bit of lacing behind .  d-a little rough on the palate with the huge carbonation and extremely grainy feel .

the smell is worty and fairly unappetizing , although strong .  i really want to like this local brewery but something about every beer i try ends up being below average . this beer , for a stout , is great looking but the taste is something very strange .  mouthfeel is boring and watery .

however , i detected no aroma at all .  the color was very appealing , but that was all . when i gathered the nerve to take a drink and really sink my teeth into this beer , it felt like i was drinking a beef jerky smoothie .  on first taste the mouthfeel seems a little thin . all in all tasty , but quite thin and seriously lacking in body .

yeasty aroma with the funk of rotten fruit and full kitchen garbage can.. nasal accents of strong commonly-belgian hops work their way in as well .  a- this one pours out of the bottle a glowing golden orange colored body with a small eggshell colored head on top .  medium body . nearly flat .

some nice elements in the nose ( a touch of smoke , apple , grapefruit , ) but it 's mostly very unpleasant , shows a lot of oxidation , dullness and even a light manure note .  a - pours a nice clear amber colour with a white large bubbled head that dies quickly to a film .  m - the body is vanishingly thin and i feel the carbonation is too high for an english porter .

very unimpressive .  the beer poured a clear medium gold color with a four finger fluffy white head that lasted awhile and left lots of lacing .  mouthfeel is overly fizzy , making an already light beer even fluffier . overall , this is an interesting beer that could be very refreshing if less carbonated .

not much for aroma , just a little grainy malt .  bottle poured into a tulip glass . appearance-pale to medium gold , with a slight cast of haze , and a moderate white frothy head with decent retention .  neither was the taste - a bit bitter , no real aftertaste , with a weak , watery mouth feel .

i really ca n't smell anything on this beer .  appearance-dark golden color , nice white head that dissapears slowly .  mouthfeel was thin like water , very little body .

nothing spectacular on the nose but for the typical belgian `` funk '' which was fine but i could distinguish nothing else . overall , a keeper , i just expected some more hop character to poke through but , then again , perhaps belgian darks are n't where we go for hop nirvana ?  but now , 2,500 miles from the source , and from it 's 25.4 oz oil can , i get the opportunity to try it again : poured into a stange , it 's golden color is attractive along with its well built head that does n't fizz .  m- spritzy , carbonation fills your mouth swelling your cheeks slightly . rough , bubbly and thin .
grainy aroma , corn flavored .  pours black with brownish edges , feeble foam rises and leaves a thin ring at the edge of the glass .  2/5 m : thin and watery with medium carbonation .

pours golden clear with good carbontaion that provides an intial froathy white head that dissapates quickly . the smell and taste are bolstered by grain with some hop in an effort to balance the beer .  served in a tulip . pours a light copper color with a single-finger white head and a bit of lacing as it slowly falls down my glass .  good for a lager , but way too much carbonation really throwing this beer off .

s-strangely sour with some euro skunk .  ca n't really knock this beer for it 's appearance , it looks pretty good .  was excited to see this one.. but again newcastle has let me down again ... on the bottle it says `` blood red ale '' .. it pours a reddish-brown color.. smells a little funky ... way too carbonated for my liking .

smell : sweet and pungent . horseblanket nose . spicy belgian funk is reminiscent of a gueuze .  it has good color , but beyond that that this ipa is not a pleasant one to drink .  really fizzy ( like coca-cola fizzy ) on the tongue , with a metallic finish , not really what i was hoping for , dissapointing .
